ssumes the output should be annual.", "options": [{"label": "Annual (returns are annual, periods are years) - DEFAULT", "value": "annual", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Monthly (returns are monthly, periods are months)", "value": "monthly", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "(1 + result) ** 12 - 1", "max_expr_nodes": 12, "invariant": "result_new == (1 + result_old) ** 12 - 1", "affected_inputs": []}}, {"label": "Daily (returns are daily, periods are days)", "value": "daily", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "(1 + result) ** 365 - 1", "max_expr_nodes": 12, "invariant": "result_new == (1 + result_old) ** 365 - 1", "affected_inputs": []}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Annual (no additional compounding factor applied beyond the explicit periods count)", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "returns", "type": "array[number]", "required": true, "description": "A list of periodic return rates (expressed as decimals, e.g., 0.05 for 5%).", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "periods", "type": "integer", "required": true, "description": "The total number of periods over which the returns are measured. This should match the number of elements in the 'returns' list.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "annualized_return", "type": "number", "unit": "None", "description": "The annualized total return rate, expressed as a decimal."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    returns = inputs['returns']\n    periods = inputs['periods']\n    compounded_growth = 1\n    for r in returns:\n        compounded_growth *= 1 + r\n    annualized_return = compounded_growth ** (1 / periods) - 1\n    return annualized_return", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "returns_input_type", "name": "Returns Input Must Be a List", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['returns'], list)", "applies_to": ["returns"], "description": "The 'returns' input must be a list of numbers representing periodic return rates."}, {"rule_id": "periods_input_type", "name": "Periods Input Must Be an Integer", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['periods'], int)", "applies_to": ["periods"], "description": "The 'periods' input must be an integer representing the total number of periods."}, {"rule_id": "periods_positive", "name": "Number of Periods Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "inputs['periods'] > 0", "applies_to": ["periods"], "description": "The total number of periods over which returns are measured must be greater than zero."}, {"rule_id": "returns_elements_numeric", "name": "All Returns Elements Must Be Numeric", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "all(isinstance(r, (int, float)) for r in inputs['returns'])", "applies_to": ["returns"], "description": "Each element in the 'returns' list must be a number (integer or float)."}, {"rule_id": "returns_periods_length_match", "name": "Number of Returns Must Match Periods", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "len(inputs['returns']) == inputs['periods']", "applies_to": ["returns", "periods"], "description": "The number of periodic returns provided must exactly match the total number of periods specified."}, {"rule_id": "returns_plausibility", "name": "Return Rates Must Be Plausible", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "all(-1.0 <= r < 10.0 for r in inputs['returns'])", "applies_to": ["returns"], "description": "Individual return rates should typically be between -1.0 (-100% loss) and 10.0 (1000% gain) to indicate plausible data entry."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    returns = inputs['returns']\n    periods = inputs['periods']\n    compounded_growth = 1\n    for r in returns:\n        compounded_growth *= 1 + r\n    annualized_return = compounded_growth ** (1 / periods) - 1\n    return annualized_return"}, "article_title": "Annualized Total Return", "article_doc_id": 4504, "article_content_excerpt": "# Annualized Total Return Formula and Calculation\n\n## What Is Annualized Total Return? \n\nAn annualized total return is the geometric average amount of money an investment earns each year over a given period. The annualized return formula is calculated as a geometric average to show what an investor would earn over some time if the annual return were compounded. \n\nAn annualized total return provides only a snapshot of an investment's performance and does not give investors any indication of its or price fluctuations. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * An annualized total return is the amount of money an investment earns each year over a given period.\n * The annualized return formula shows what an investor would earn over a period of time if the annual return were compounded.\n * Calculating the annualized rate of return needs only two variables: the returns for a given period and the time the investment was held.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/Annualized-Total-Return-FINAL-69a0de5921b84ad88984ae90ff4e3733.jpg)\n\nInvestopedia / Jiaqi Zhou\n\n## Understanding Annualized Total Return \n\nTo understand what annualized total return is, it helps to compare the hypothetical performances of two mutual funds. Below is the annualized rate of return over a five-year period for two funds: \n\n * Mutual Fund A Returns: 3%, 7%, 5%, 12%, and 1%\n * Mutual Fund B Returns: 4%, 6%, 5%, 6%, and 6.7%\n\nBoth mutual funds have an annualized rate of return of 5.5%, but Mutual Fund A is much more volatile. Its is 4.2%, while Mutual Fund B's standard deviation is only 1%. Even when analyzing an investment's annualized return, it is important to review risk statistics. \n\n## Annualized Return Formula and Calculation \n\nThe formula to calculate the annualized rate of return needs only two variables: the returns for a given period of time and the time the investment was held. The formula is:\n\n\\begin{aligned} \\text{Annualized Return} = &\\big ( (1 + r_1 ) \\times (1 + r_2) \\times (1 + r_3) \\times \\\\\\ &\\dots \\times (1 + r_n) \\big ) ^ \\frac{1}{n} - 1 \\\\\\ \\end{aligned}\n\nFor example, take the annual rates of returns of Mutual Fund A above. An analyst substitutes each \" r \" variable with the appropriate return and \"n\" with the number of years the investment was held. In this case, five years. The annualized return of Mutual Fund A is calculated as:\n\n\\begin{aligned} \\text{Annualized Return} &= \\big ( (1 + .03) \\times (1 + .07) \\times (1 + .05) \\times \\\\\\ &\\quad \\quad (1 + .12) \\times (1 + .01) \\big ) ^ \\frac{1}{5} -1 \\\\\\ &= 1.309 ^ {0.20} - 1 \\\\\\ &= 1.0553 - 1 \\\\\\ &= .0553, \\text{or } 5.53\\% \\\\\\ \\end{aligned}\n\nAn annualized return does not have to be limited to yearly returns. If an investor has a for a given period, even if it is a specific number of days, an annualized performance figure can be calculated; however, the annual return formula must be slightly adjusted to:\n\n\\begin{aligned} &\\text{Annualized Return} = ( 1 + \\text{Cumulative Return} ) ^ \\frac {365}{ \\text{Days Held} } - 1 \\\\\\ \\end{aligned}\n\nFor example, assume a mutual fund was held by an investor for 575 days and earned a cumulative return of 23.74%. The annualized rate of return would be:\n\n\\begin{aligned} \\text{Annualized Return} &= ( 1 + .2374) ^ \\frac{365}{575} - 1 \\\\\\ &= 1.145 - 1 \\\\\\ &= .145, \\text{or } 14.5\\% \\\\\\ \\end{aligned}\n\n## Difference Between Annualized Return and Average Return \n\nCalculations of simple averages only work when numbers are independent of each other. The annualized return is used because the amount of investment lost or gained in a given year is interdependent with the amount from the other years under consideration because of . \n\nFor example, if a mutual fund manager loses half of her client's money, she has to make a 100% return to break even. Using the more accurate annualized return also gives a clearer picture when comparing mutual funds or the return of stocks that have traded over different periods. \n\n## Reporting Annualized Return \n\nAccording to the —a set of standardized, industry\n...[truncated]"}
