 "expression": "inputs['investment_return'] < 0 or inputs['risk_free_rate'] < 0 or inputs['benchmark_return'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Investment return, risk-free rate, and benchmark return should generally be non-negative. Negative values may indicate unusual market conditions or data entry errors."}, {"rule_id": "positive_beta_or_reasonable_negative", "name": "Beta should be within a plausible range", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['beta'] < -1 or inputs['beta'] > 5", "applies_to": [], "description": "Beta coefficient typically falls within a range of -1 to 5. Values outside this range might indicate highly unusual assets or data errors and should be reviewed."}, {"rule_id": "risk_free_less_than_benchmark", "name": "Risk-free rate less than benchmark", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['risk_free_rate'] > inputs['benchmark_return']", "applies_to": [], "description": "For a rational market, the risk-free rate should be less than the expected market (benchmark) return, otherwise, there is no premium for taking market risk."}, {"rule_id": "plausible_alpha_range", "name": "Plausible Alpha Range", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not -100 <= compute(inputs) <= 100", "applies_to": ["jensens_alpha"], "description": "Jensen's alpha typically falls within a plausible range (e.g., -100% to 100% for percentage output). Extreme values may suggest input errors or highly atypical performance."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    investment_return = inputs['investment_return']\n    risk_free_rate = inputs['risk_free_rate']\n    benchmark_return = inputs['benchmark_return']\n    beta = inputs['beta']\n    expected_return = risk_free_rate + beta * (benchmark_return - risk_free_rate)\n    jensens_alpha = investment_return - expected_return\n    return jensens_alpha"}, "article_title": "Alpha", "article_doc_id": 4461, "article_content_excerpt": "# Alpha: Its Meaning in Investing, With Examples\n\n## What Is Alpha? \n\nAlpha (α) is a term used in investing to describe an investment strategy’s ability to beat the market, or its “edge.” Alpha is thus also often referred to as or the in relation to a benchmark, when adjusted for risk. \n\nAlpha is often used in conjunction with (the Greek letter β), which measures the broad market’s overall or risk, known as . \n\nAlpha is used in finance as a measure of , indicating when a strategy, trader, or portfolio manager has managed to beat the market return or other benchmark over some period. Alpha, often considered the on an investment, gauges the performance of an investment against a market index or benchmark that is considered to represent the market’s movement as a whole. \n\nThe excess return of an investment relative to the of a benchmark index is the investment’s alpha. Alpha may be positive or negative and is the result of active investing. Beta, on the other hand, can be earned through passive . \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Alpha refers to excess returns earned on an investment above the benchmark return when adjusted for risk.\n * Active portfolio managers seek to generate alpha in diversified portfolios, with diversification intended to eliminate unsystematic risk.\n * Because alpha represents the performance of a portfolio relative to a benchmark, it is often considered to represent the value that a portfolio manager adds to or subtracts from a fund’s return.\n * Jensen’s alpha takes into consideration the capital asset pricing model (CAPM) and includes a risk-adjusted component in its calculation.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/alpha_definition_v1-e2fc096b73fd4d15975d7406c84071cc.jpg)\n\nSydney Saporito / Investopedia\n\n## Understanding Alpha \n\nAlpha is one of five popular technical investment . The others are beta, , , and the . These are all statistical measurements used in . All of these indicators are intended to help investors determine the risk-return profile of an investment. \n\nActive portfolio managers seek to generate alpha in diversified portfolios, with intended to eliminate . Because alpha represents the performance of a relative to a benchmark, it is often considered to represent the value that a portfolio manager adds to or subtracts from a fund’s return. \n\nIn other words, alpha is the return on an investment that is not a result of a general movement in the greater market. As such, an alpha of zero would indicate that the portfolio or fund is tracking perfectly with the benchmark index and that the manager has not added or lost any additional value compared to the broad market. \n\n## Applying Alpha to Investing \n\nThe concept of alpha became more popular with the advent of index funds tied to indexes like the Standard & Poor’s 500 index and the Wilshire 5000 Total Market Index. These funds attempt to enhance the performance of a portfolio that tracks a targeted subset of the market. \n\nDespite the considerable desirability of alpha in a portfolio, many index benchmarks manage to beat asset managers the vast majority of the time. Due in part to a growing lack of faith in traditional financial advising brought about by this trend, more and more investors are switching to low-cost, online advisors (often called ​) who exclusively or almost exclusively invest clients’ capital into index-tracking funds, the rationale being that if they , they may as well join it. \n\nMoreover, because most traditional financial advisors charge a fee, when one manages a portfolio and nets an alpha of zero, it actually represents a slight for the investor. For example, suppose that Jim, a financial advisor, charges 1% of a portfolio’s value for his services and that during a 12-month period, Jim managed to produce an alpha of 0.75 for the portfolio of one of his clients, Frank. \n\nWhile Jim has indeed helped the performance of Frank’s portfolio, the fee that Jim charges is in excess of the alpha he has generated, so Frank’s portfolio has experie\n...[truncated]"}
