_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['income'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The income subject to taxation cannot be negative. A negative income is not meaningful in the context of calculating tax liability and would lead to an unrealistic result."}, {"rule_id": "brackets_sorted_and_non_negative", "name": "Bracket Thresholds Valid", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not all(b >= 0 for b in inputs['brackets']) or not (len(inputs['brackets']) <= 1 or all(inputs['brackets'][i] < inputs['brackets'][i+1] for i in range(len(inputs['brackets']) - 1)))", "applies_to": [], "description": "All income bracket thresholds must be non-negative and strictly increasing. Non-increasing or negative brackets indicate an improperly defined progressive tax system and would lead to incorrect or ambiguous tax calculations. An empty or single-element 'brackets' list is considered valid for sorting purposes, as there's no sequence to violate."}, {"rule_id": "rates_percentage_range", "name": "Rates Valid Percentage Range", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not all(0.0 <= r <= 1.0 for r in inputs['rates'])", "applies_to": [], "description": "All tax rates must be expressed as decimals between 0.0 and 1.0 (inclusive). Rates outside this range would represent illogical percentages (e.g., negative tax or over 100% tax). An empty 'rates' list is considered valid as it trivially satisfies the 'all' condition (no rates to violate)."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    income = inputs['income']\n    brackets = inputs['brackets']\n    rates = inputs['rates']\n    tax_liability = 0.0\n    previous_bracket_limit = 0.0\n    for i in range(len(brackets)):\n        bracket = brackets[i]\n        rate = rates[i]\n        if income > bracket:\n            tax_for_bracket = (bracket - previous_bracket_limit) * rate\n            tax_liability += tax_for_bracket\n            previous_bracket_limit = bracket\n        else:\n            tax_for_current_segment = (income - previous_bracket_limit) * rate\n            tax_liability += tax_for_current_segment\n            break\n    return tax_liability"}, "article_title": "Vertical Equity", "article_doc_id": 445, "article_content_excerpt": "# Vertical Equity: What It Is, How It Works, and Example\n\n## What Is Vertical Equity? \n\nVertical equity is a method of collecting in which the taxes paid increase with the amount of earned . The driving principle behind vertical equity is that those who have the ability to pay more taxes should contribute more than those who are not. \n\nThis can be contrasted with , whereby individuals with similar income and should pay the same amount in . \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Vertical equity is a method of income taxation whereby more taxes are paid as income increases.\n * Vertical equity is based on the principle of ability to pay through progressive tax rates or proportional taxation.\n * Vertical equity is often more achievable than horizontal equity, which can be undermined by loopholes and deductions.\n\n## Understanding Vertical Equity \n\nThe equity of a tax system speaks to whether the tax burden is distributed fairly among the population. The principle states that the amount of tax an individual pays should be dependent on the level of burden the tax will create relative to the of the individual. The gives rise to two notions of fairness and equity: vertical and horizontal equity. \n\nVertical equity drives the principle that people with higher incomes should pay more tax, through proportional or progressive tax rates. In , the amount of taxes paid increases directly with income. Everyone pays the same proportion of their income in tax since the effective average tax rate does not change with income. \n\n## Example of Vertical Equity \n\nFor an example of vertical equity, consider a who earns $100,000 per annum and another who earns $50,000 per annum. If the tax rate is flat and proportional at 15%, the higher income earner will pay $15,000 tax for the given , while the taxpayer with the lower income will have a of $7,500. With the same rate applied across all income amounts, the individuals with more resources or higher income levels will always pay more tax in dollars than lower earners. \n\n## Progressive Taxation \n\nProgressive taxation includes , in which people pay taxes based on the tax bracket that their income places them. Each tax bracket will have a different tax rate, with higher income brackets paying the highest percentages. \n\nUnder this taxation system, effective average tax rates increase with income, so that the rich pay a higher share of their income in taxes than people whose self-reported incomes were in the lowest income bracket. For example, in the United States, a single taxpayer who earns $100,000 has a top of 22%, as of 2024. Their tax liability would be $5,426 plus 22% of any excess over $100,000. The top marginal tax rate for a single taxpayer whose annual income is $50,000 is also 22%. In this case, this taxpayer would pay $5,426 plus 22% of any excess over $50,000. For 2025, the marginal tax rate remains 22%, but a single taxpayer who earns $100,000 or $50,000 would pay $5,578.50 plus 22% of any excess over $100,000 or $50,000, respectively.\n\nThe other yardstick that is used to measure equity in a taxation system is horizontal equity, which states that people with similar abilities to pay should contribute the same amount in taxes to the . The basis behind this notion is that people in the same income group are equal in their contribution capacity to society and, thus, should be treated the same by imposing the same level of income tax. \n\nFor example, if two taxpayers earn $50,000, they should both be taxed the same rate since they both have the same wealth or fall within the same income bracket. However, horizontal equity is hard to achieve in a tax system with , , and incentives, because the provision of any tax break means that similar individuals effectively do not pay the same rate. \n\n## Is Vertical Equity a Method of Income Taxation?\n\nYes. Vertical equity is a method of income taxation whereby more taxes are paid as income increases.\n\n## What Is Vertical Equity Based on?\n\nVertical equity is based on the princi\n...[truncated]"}
