EFAULT", "value": "decimal", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Percentage (e.g., 7) - interpret as decimal (7/100)", "value": "percentage_to_decimal", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "(principal + (result * (loan_term_years * 12) - principal) / 100.0) / (loan_term_years * 12)", "max_expr_nodes": 28, "invariant": "result_new == (principal + (result_old * (loan_term_years * 12) - principal) / 100.0) / (loan_term_years * 12)", "affected_inputs": ["principal", "loan_term_years"]}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "The annual interest rate is provided as a decimal.", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "principal", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The initial principal amount borrowed.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "annual_interest_rate", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The annual interest rate as a decimal (e.g., 0.08 for 8%).", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "loan_term_years", "type": "integer", "required": true, "description": "The term of the loan in years.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "monthly_payment", "type": "number", "unit": null, "description": "The calculated monthly payment for the add-on interest loan."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    principal = inputs['principal']\n    annual_interest_rate = inputs['annual_interest_rate']\n    loan_term_years = inputs['loan_term_years']\n    total_interest = principal * annual_interest_rate * loan_term_years\n    total_loan_amount = principal + total_interest\n    monthly_payments_total = loan_term_years * 12\n    monthly_payment = total_loan_amount / monthly_payments_total\n    return round(monthly_payment, 2)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "principal_positive", "name": "Principal must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['principal'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["principal"], "description": "The principal amount borrowed must be a positive number."}, {"rule_id": "annual_interest_rate_positive", "name": "Annual interest rate must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['annual_interest_rate'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["annual_interest_rate"], "description": "The annual interest rate must be a positive number."}, {"rule_id": "loan_term_positive", "name": "Loan term must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['loan_term_years'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["loan_term_years"], "description": "The loan term in years must be a positive number."}, {"rule_id": "loan_term_integer_type", "name": "Loan term must be an integer type", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not isinstance(inputs['loan_term_years'], int)", "applies_to": ["loan_term_years"], "description": "The loan term in years must be a whole number (integer type)."}, {"rule_id": "annual_interest_rate_plausibility", "name": "Annual interest rate plausibility check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['annual_interest_rate'] > 1.0", "applies_to": ["annual_interest_rate"], "description": "The annual interest rate appears to be greater than 100%. Please ensure it is entered as a decimal (e.g., 0.08 for 8%)."}, {"rule_id": "monthly_payments_non_zero", "name": "Total monthly payments must be non-zero", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['loan_term_years'] * 12 == 0", "applies_to": ["loan_term_years"], "description": "The total number of monthly payments (loan term in years * 12) cannot be zero."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    principal = inputs['principal']\n    annual_interest_rate = inputs['annual_interest_rate']\n    loan_term_years = inputs['loan_term_years']\n    total_interest = principal * annual_interest_rate * loan_term_years\n    total_loan_amount = principal + total_interest\n    monthly_payments_total = loan_term_years * 12\n    monthly_payment = total_loan_amount / monthly_payments_total\n    return round(monthly_payment, 2)"}, "article_title": "Add-On Interest", "article_doc_id": 4406, "article_content_excerpt": "# Add-On Interest: Definition, Formula, Cost vs. Simple Interest\n\nDefinition\n\nIf you're looking for a loan, finding the most affordable option is important. While interest rate is a big factor, the way the interest is calculated can be just as important. Add-on interest loans tend to favor the lender, resulting in more money paid, even if the loan is paid off early.\n\n## What Is Add-On Interest? \n\nAdd-on interest is a method of calculating the interest to be paid on a loan by combining the total principal amount borrowed and the total interest due over the life of the loan into a single figure. This combined amount is then divided by the number of monthly payments to be made. The result is a loan that combines the initial principal and total interest into one amount due, regardless of how much principal is repaid. \n\nThis method of calculating the payment on a loan is substantially more expensive for the borrower than the traditional calculation and is rarely used in . Most loans use simple interest, where the interest charged is based on the amount of principal that is owed after each payment is made. Add-on interest loans may occasionally be used in short-term installment loans and in loans to . \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Most loans are simple interest loans, where the interest is based on the amount owed on the remaining principal after each monthly payment is made.\n * Add-on interest loans combine principal and interest into one amount owed, to be paid off in equal installments. The result is a substantially higher cost to the borrower.\n * Add-on interest loans are typically used with short-term installment loans and for loans made to subprime borrowers.\n\n## Understanding Add-On Interest \n\nIn simple interest , where the charged is based on the amount of that's owed after each payment is made, the payments may be identical in size from month to month, but that's because the principal paid increases over time while the interest paid decreases. \n\nIf the consumer pays off a simple interest loan early, the savings can be substantial. The number of interest payments that would have been attached to future monthly payments has been effectively erased. \n\nBut in an add-on interest loan, the amount owed is calculated upfront as a total of the principal borrowed plus the total interest owed over the life of the loan. This combined figured is then divided by the number of months of payments due in order to arrive at a monthly payment figure. \n\nThis means that the interest owed each month remains constant throughout the life of the loan. The interest owed is much higher, and, even if the borrower pays off the loan early, the interest charged will be the same. \n\n## Example of an Add-On Interest Loan \n\nSay a borrower obtains a $25,000 loan at an 8% add-on interest rate that's to be repaid over four years. \n\n * The total loan amount is multiplied by the interest rate to give us $2,000 interest per year ($25,000 * 0.08).\n * The annual interest is multiplied by the term of four years to result in $8,000 total interest ($2,000 x 4 years).\n * The initial principal and total interest are combined to reach the loan total of $33,000 ($25,000 + $8,000).\n * To determine the monthly payment, the loan total is divided by the monthly term to reach roughly $687.50 ($33,000 / 48 months).\n\nUsing a simple interest loan , the same borrower with the same 8% interest rate on a $25,000 loan over four years would have required monthly payments of $610.32. The total interest due would be $4,295.51. \n\nThe borrower would pay $3,704.49 more for the add-on interest loan compared to the simple interest loan, assuming the borrower didn't pay off the latter early, reducing the total interest even more. \n\n## How Do I Know That I'm Being Charged Add-On Interest?\n\nYour loan agreement should disclose what interest calculating method is used. Read the fine print, and if you're still unsure, ask your loan officer directly.\n\n## Can I Save Money on an Add-On Interest Loan by Payi\n...[truncated]"}
