ts['market_excess_return'] <= 30.0)", "applies_to": ["market_excess_return"], "description": "The market excess return (in percentage points) is outside a typical annual plausible range (-20% to 30%). Consider if input should be a decimal or a different magnitude."}, {"rule_id": "e_002", "name": "SMB Premium Plausibility", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (-10.0 <= inputs['smb'] <= 20.0)", "applies_to": ["smb"], "description": "The SMB premium (in percentage points) is outside a typical annual plausible range (-10% to 20%). Consider if input should be a decimal or a different magnitude."}, {"rule_id": "e_003", "name": "HML Premium Plausibility", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (-10.0 <= inputs['hml'] <= 20.0)", "applies_to": ["hml"], "description": "The HML premium (in percentage points) is outside a typical annual plausible range (-10% to 20%). Consider if input should be a decimal or a different magnitude."}, {"rule_id": "e_004", "name": "Alpha Plausibility", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (-10.0 <= inputs['alpha'] <= 20.0)", "applies_to": ["alpha"], "description": "The alpha (in percentage points) is outside a typical annual plausible range (-10% to 20%). While alpha can vary, very extreme values may indicate input errors."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    alpha = inputs['alpha']\n    beta_market = inputs['beta_market']\n    market_excess_return = inputs['market_excess_return']\n    beta_size = inputs['beta_size']\n    smb = inputs['smb']\n    beta_value = inputs['beta_value']\n    hml = inputs['hml']\n    expected_excess_return = alpha + beta_market * market_excess_return + beta_size * smb + beta_value * hml\n    return expected_excess_return"}, "article_title": "Fama and French Three Factor Model", "article_doc_id": 942, "article_content_excerpt": "# Fama and French Three Factor Model Definition: Formula and Interpretation\n\n## What Is the Fama and French Three Factor Model? \n\nThe Fama and French Three-Factor Model (or the Fama French Model for short) is an asset pricing model developed in 1992 that expands on the capital asset pricing model (CAPM) by adding size risk and value risk factors to the market risk factor in CAPM. This model considers the fact that value and small-cap stocks outperform markets on a regular basis. By including these two additional factors, the model adjusts for this outperforming tendency, which is thought to make it a better tool for evaluating manager performance. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * The Fama French 3-factor model is an asset pricing model that expands on the capital asset pricing model by adding size risk and value risk factors to the market risk factors.\n * The model was developed by Nobel laureates Eugene Fama and his colleague Kenneth French in the 1990s.\n * The model is essentially the result of an econometric regression of historical stock prices.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/fama-4196653-b2f48bc85216461ab6f626e63818552c.jpg)\n\nInvestopedia / Joules Garcia\n\n## Understanding the Fama and French Three Factor Model \n\nNobel Laureate Eugene Fama and researcher Kenneth French, former professors at the University of Chicago Booth School of Business, attempted to better measure market returns and, through research, found that outperform growth stocks. Similarly, small-cap stocks tend to outperform As an evaluation tool, the performance of portfolios with a large number of small-cap or value stocks would be lower than the result, as the Three-Factor Model adjusts downward for observed small-cap and value stock outperformance. \n\nThe Fama and French model has three factors: the size of firms, book-to-market values, and excess return on the market. In other words, the three factors used are (SMB), (HML), and the portfolio's return less the risk-free rate of return. SMB accounts for publicly traded companies with small market caps that generate higher returns, while HML accounts for value stocks with high book-to-market ratios that generate higher returns in comparison to the market.\n\nThere is a lot of debate about whether the outperformance tendency is due to market efficiency or market inefficiency. In support of market efficiency, the outperformance is generally explained by the excess risk that value and small-cap stocks face as a result of their higher and greater business risk. In support of market inefficiency, the outperformance is explained by market participants incorrectly pricing the value of these companies, which provides the excess return in the long run as the value adjusts. Investors who subscribe to the body of evidence provided by the (EMH) are more likely to agree with the efficiency side. \n\nThe formula is: \n\n\\begin{aligned} &R_{it} - R_{ft} = \\alpha_{it} + \\beta_1 ( R_{Mt} - R_{ft} ) + \\beta_2SMB_t + \\beta_3HML_t + \\epsilon_{it} \\\\\\ &\\textbf{where:} \\\\\\ &R_{it} = \\text{total return of a stock or portfolio } i \\text{ at time } t \\\\\\ &R_{ft} = \\text{risk free rate of return at time } t \\\\\\ &R_{Mt} = \\text{total market portfolio return at time } t \\\\\\ &R_{it} - R_{ft} = \\text{expected excess return} \\\\\\ &R_{Mt} - R_{ft} = \\text{excess return on the market portfolio (index)} \\\\\\ &SMB_t = \\text{size premium (small minus big)} \\\\\\ &HML_t = \\text{value premium (high minus low)} \\\\\\ &\\beta_{1,2,3} = \\text{factor coefficients} \\\\\\ \\end{aligned}\n\nFama and French highlighted that investors must be able to ride out the extra volatility and periodic underperformance that could occur in a short time. Investors with a long-term time horizon of 15 years or more will be rewarded for losses suffered in the short term. Using thousands of random stock portfolios, Fama and French conducted studies to test their model and found that when size and value factors are combined with the beta factor, they could then explain as much as 95% of the r\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_2457", "name": "Weighted Average Loan Age (WALA)", "short_description": "Calculate the Weighted Average Loan Age (WALA) for a pool of mortgage-backed securities. This function computes the weighted average loan age (WALA), which measures the maturity of mortgages in a mortgage-backed security (MBS). The WALA is calculated using the initial nominal value of each mortgage and the number of months since the mortgage loan was originated.", "domain": "financial_markets", "topic": "mortgage_backed_securities", "topic_extension": true, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-2457", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-893", "question_id": "test-1007", "difficulty": 2.4849066497880004, "level": "medium", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "295fb46095d04069bafea9170f2a7093e1e3b827833bd204e5d09c1ca21e2499", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["WALA", "Weighted Average Loan Age", "mortgage-backed securities", "MBS", "loan maturity", "mortgage pool", "bond portfolio"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "output_vs_wam", "ambiguity_type": "inverse_metric", "trigger_signal": "mention of loan maturity or average maturity", "clarification_question": "Are you looking for Weighted Average Loan Age (WALA) or Weighted Average Maturity (WAM)?", "options": [{"label": "Weighted Average Loan Age (WALA) - DEFAULT", "value": "wala", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Weighted Average Maturity (WAM) (inverse of WALA)", "value": "wam", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "1.0 / result", "max_expr_nodes": 6, "invariant": "result_new * result_old == 1.0", "affected_inputs": []}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Weighted Average Loan Age (WALA)", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}, {"id": "output_unit_time", "ambiguity_type": "unit_scale", "trigger_signal": "time unit for loan age not explicitly specified or ambiguous", "clarification_question": "Should the result for loan age be expressed in months or years?", "options": [{"label": "Months - DEFAULT", "value": "months", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Years", "value": "years", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "result / 12.0", "max_expr_nodes": 6, "invariant": "result_new * 12.0 == result_old", "affected_inputs": []}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Months", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}, {"id": "weighting_basis", "ambiguity_type": "input_binding", "trigger_signal": "weighting basis for loans not explicitly specified", "clarification_question": "Should the loans be weighted by initial nominal value or remaining principal balance?", "options": [{"label": "Initial nominal value - DEFAULT", "value": "initial_nominal_value", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Remaining principal balance", "value": "remaining_principal_balance", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Initial nominal value", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}], "inputs": [{"name": "nominal_values", "type": "array[number]", "required": true, "description": "A list of the initial nominal values of each individual mortgage in the MBS pool.", "unit": null, "aliases": ["initial_values", "loan_amounts"]}, {"name": "months_since_origination", "type": "array[number]", "required": true, "description": "A list of the number of months since each mortgage was originated.", "unit": null, "aliases": ["loan_ages_in_months", "time_since_origination"]}], "output": {"name": "wala", "type": "number", "unit": "months", "description": "The weighted average loan age of the mortgages in the pool."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    nominal_values = inputs['nominal_values']\n    months_since_origination = inputs['months_since_origination']\n    if len(nominal_values) != len(months_since_origination):\n        raise ValueError('The length of nominal_values and months_since_origination must be the same.')\n    total_value = sum(nominal_values)\n    if total_value == 0:\n        raise ValueError('The total value of nominal values must be greater than zero.')\n    weighted_sum = sum((value * months for value, months in zip(nominal_values, months_since_origination)))\n    wala = weighted_sum / total_value\n    return wala", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "wala_dgn_001", "name": "Nominal Values Type and Structure Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['nominal_values'], list) and all(isinstance(x, (int, float)) for x in inputs['nominal_values'])", "applies_to": [], "description": "Ensures 'nominal_values' is a list of numbers."}, {"rule_id": "wala_dgn_002", "name": "Months Since Origination Type and Structure Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['months_since_origination'], list) and all(isinstance(x, (int, float)) for x in inputs['months_since_origination'])", "applies_to": [], "description": "Ensures 'months_since_origination' is a list of numbers."}, {"rule_id": "wala_dgn_003", "name": "Input List Length Consistency", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "len(inputs['nominal_values']) != len(inputs['months_since_origination'])", "applies_to": [], "description": "The lists 'nominal_values' and 'months_since_origination' must have the same length."}, {"rule_id": "wala_dgn_004", "name": "Non-Negative Nominal Values", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "any(val < 0 for val in inputs['nominal_values'])", "applies_to": [], "description": "All nominal values must be non-negative."}, {"rule_id": "wala_dgn_005", "name": "Non-Negative Months Since Origination", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "any(months < 0 for months in inputs['months_since_origination'])", "applies_to": [], "description": "All months since origination values must be non-negative."}, {"rule_id": "wala_dgn_006", "name": "Total Nominal Value Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "sum(inputs['nominal_values']) <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The sum of nominal values must be greater than zero to avoid division by zero."}, {"rule_id": "wala_dgn_007", "name": "Months Since Origination Are Integers", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "any(m % 1 != 0 for m in inputs['months_since_origination'])", "applies_to": [], "description": "It is generally expected that 'months_since_origination' values are whole numbers (integers)."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    nominal_values = inputs['nominal_values']\n    months_since_origination = inputs['months_since_origination']\n    if len(nominal_values) != len(months_since_origination):\n        raise ValueError('The length of nominal_values and months_since_origination must be the same.')\n    total_value = sum(nominal_values)\n    if total_value == 0:\n        raise ValueError('The total value of nominal values must be greater than zero.')\n    weighted_sum = sum((value * months for value, months in zip(nominal_values, months_since_origination)))\n    wala = weighted_sum / total_value\n    return wala"}, "article_title": "Weighted Average Loan Age (WALA)", "article_doc_id": 4848, "article_content_excerpt": "# Weighted Average Loan Age (WALA): Meaning, How it Works\n\n## What Is Weighted Average Loan Age (WALA)? \n\nThe weighted average loan age (WALA) measures the average age of the loans in a pool of (MBS). The weights are based on the dollar amount of each loan at each maturity in proportion to the aggregate total of the pool and can be weighted on the remaining principal balance dollar figure or the of the loan. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Weighted average loan age (WALA) is a measure of the maturity of the mortgages in a mortgage-backed security (MBS).\n * WALA is dollar-weighted based on mortgage size and time left until it matures (usually in months).\n * WALA is computed as the mathematical inverse of weighted average maturity (WAM), a more common estimation of MBS profitability.\n\n## How Weighted Average Loan Age Works \n\nWeighted average loan age is used by investors of mortgage-backed securities to estimate how long it will take for a pool of mortgage-backed securities to be repaid. The measure varies over time due to the fact that some mortgages get paid off faster than others. \n\nEssentially, a mortgage-backed security turns the bank into an intermediary between the homebuyer and the investment industry. A bank can grant mortgages to its customers and then sell them at a discount for inclusion in an MBS. The bank records the sale as a plus on its balance sheet and loses nothing if the homebuyer defaults sometime down the road. \n\nThe investor who buys a mortgage-backed security is essentially lending money to home buyers. An MBS can be bought and sold through a broker. The minimum investment varies between issuers. \n\nWALA is arrived at by multiplying the initial nominal value of each individual mortgage in the MBS pool by the number of months since the mortgage loan was originated. WALA and other measures of MBS maturity are used to estimate both profit potential and . Prepayment risk is the risk involved with the premature return of principal on a such as when a mortgage is refinanced or a house is sold and the mortgage paid off. When principal is returned early, future interest payments will not be paid on that part of the principal, meaning investors in associated fixed-income securities will not receive interest paid on the principal. \n\n## Weighted Average Loan Age vs. Weighted Average Maturity \n\n (WAM) and WALA are both used to estimate the likelihood of an investment in a mortgage-backed security being profitable. However, WAM tends to be a more broadly used measure for the maturity of pools of mortgage-backed securities. It measures the average time it takes for securities in a debt portfolio to mature, weighted in proportion to the dollar amount invested in the portfolio. Portfolios with higher weighted average maturities are more sensitive to interest rate changes. \n\nWALA is actually calculated as the inverse of WAM: WAM computes the percentage value of each mortgage or debt instrument in the portfolio. The number of months or years until the bond’s is multiplied by each percentage, and the sum of the subtotals equals the weighted average maturity of the bonds in the portfolio."}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_301", "name": "Variance Equation", "short_description": "Calculates the statistical variance of a numerical data set, differentiating between sample and population variance.", "domain": "risk_management", "topic": "risk_metrics", "topic_extension": false, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-301", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-290", "question_id": "test-1959", "difficulty": 4.007333185232471, "level": "medium", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "98237806e48b3193904f778b789befbdadfd57eb00784e82e0faded801a3709c", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["variance", "standard deviation", "spread", "dispersion", "risk measurement", "statistical analysis"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "sample_vs_population_basis", "ambiguity_type": "statistical_basis", "trigger_signal": "statistical variance calculation without explicit mention of sample or population", "clarification_question": "Should the variance be calculated for a sample (N-1 denominator) or the entire population (N denominator)?", "options": [{"label": "Sample (N-1 denominator) - DEFAULT", "value": "sample", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Population (N denominator)", "value": "population", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Sample variance (using n-1 in denominator)", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}, {"id": "output_scale", "ambiguity_type": "unit_scale", "trigger_signal": "output might be interpreted as decimal or percentage based on context", "clarification_question": "Should the variance output be expressed as a decimal (e.g., 0.0001) or a percentage (e.g., 0.01%)? The input data itself is assumed to be in percentage terms (e.g., 3.2 means 3.2%).", "options": [{"label": "Decimal - DEFAULT", "value": "decimal", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Percentage", "value": "percent", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "result * 100.0", "max_expr_nodes": 6, "invariant": "result_new == result_old * 100.0", "affected_inputs": []}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Decimal", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "data_set", "type": "array[number]", "required": true, "description": "A list of numerical values representing the data set.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "sample", "type": "boolean", "required": false, "description": "True if the data set represents a sample (using n-1 denominator), False if it represents the entire population (using n denominator). Defaults to True if not provided.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "variance", "type": "number", "unit": null, "description": "The calculated variance of the data set."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    data_set = inputs['data_set']\n    sample = inputs.get('sample', True)\n    if not isinstance(data_set, list):\n        raise TypeError('data_set must be a list.')\n    if len(data_set) < 2:\n        raise ValueError('Data set must contain at least two values for variance calculation.')\n    if not all((isinstance(x, (int, float)) for x in data_set)):\n        raise ValueError('All elements in data_set must be numerical.')\n    mean = sum(data_set) / len(data_set)\n    squared_diffs = [(x - mean) ** 2 for x in data_set]\n    divisor = len(data_set) - 1 if sample else len(data_set)\n    if divisor == 0:\n        raise ValueError('Cannot compute sample variance for a data set with only one value.')\n    variance = sum(squared_diffs) / divisor\n    return variance", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "data_set_not_list", "name": "Data Set Must Be a List", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not isinstance(inputs.get('data_set'), list)", "applies_to": ["data_set"], "description": "The 'data_set' input must be provided as a Python list."}, {"rule_id": "data_set_missing_or_empty", "name": "Data Set Missing or Empty", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not inputs.get('data_set') or len(inputs['data_set']) == 0", "applies_to": ["data_set"], "description": "The 'data_set' input is required and cannot be empty."}, {"rule_id": "data_set_too_few_elements", "name": "Data Set Must Have at Least Two Values", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "len(inputs['data_set']) < 2", "applies_to": ["data_set"], "description": "The data set must contain at least two values to calculate variance meaningfully (especially for sample variance with n-1 denominator)."}, {"rule_id": "data_set_non_numeric_elements", "name": "Data Set Elements Must Be Numeric", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "any(not isinstance(x, (int, float)) for x in inputs['data_set'])", "applies_to": ["data_set"], "description": "All elements in the 'data_set' list must be numerical (integers or floats)."}, {"rule_id": "sample_input_type_check", "name": "Sample Input Type Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "'sample' in inputs and not isinstance(inputs['sample'], bool)", "applies_to": ["sample"], "description": "If provided, the 'sample' input must be a boolean value (True or False)."}, {"rule_id": "variance_non_negative", "name": "Calculated variance must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "compute(inputs) < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Variance, as a measure of dispersion, cannot be negative. A negative result indicates a calculation error."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    data_set = inputs['data_set']\n    sample = inputs.get('sample', True)\n    if not isinstance(data_set, list):\n        raise TypeError('data_set must be a list.')\n    if len(data_set) < 2:\n        raise ValueError('Data set must contain at least two values for variance calculation.')\n    if not all((isinstance(x, (int, float)) for x in data_set)):\n        raise ValueError('All elements in data_set must be numerical.')\n    mean = sum(data_set) / len(data_set)\n    squared_diffs = [(x - mean) ** 2 for x in data_set]\n    divisor = len(data_set) - 1 if sample else len(data_set)\n    if divisor == 0:\n        raise ValueError('Cannot compute sample variance for a data set with only one value.')\n    variance = sum(squared_diffs) / divisor\n    return variance"}, "article_title": "Variance Equation", "article_doc_id": 419, "article_content_excerpt": "# What Is Variance in Statistics? Definition, Formula, and Example\n\nDefinition\n\nVariance is a measurement of how far each number in a data set is from the mean (average), and thus from every other number in the set.\n\n## What Is Variance? \n\nVariance is a statistical measurement of the spread between numbers in a data set. It measures how far each number in the set is from the (average), and thus from every other number in the set. Variance is often depicted by this symbol: σ2. It is used by both analysts and traders to determine and market stability. \n\nThe is the (SD or σ), which helps determine the consistency of an investment’s over time. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Variance is a measurement of the spread between numbers in a data set.\n * In particular, it measures the degree of dispersion of data around the sample's mean.\n * Investors use variance to see how much risk an investment carries and whether it will be profitable.\n * Variance is also used in finance to compare the relative performance of each asset in a portfolio to achieve the best asset allocation.\n * The square root of the variance is the standard deviation.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/Variance-TAERM-ADD-Source-464952914f77460a8139dbf20e14f0c0.jpg)\n\nInvestopedia / Alex Dos Diaz\n\n## Understanding Variance \n\nIn statistics, variance measures from the average or mean. It is calculated by taking the differences between each number in the data set and the mean, squaring the differences to make them positive, and then dividing the sum of the squares by the number of values in the data set. Software like .\n\nVariance is calculated by using the following formula:\n\n\\begin{aligned}&\\sigma^2 = \\frac { \\sum_{i = 1} ^ { n } \\big (x_i - \\overline { x } \\big ) ^ 2 }{ N } \\\\\\&\\textbf{where:} \\\\\\&x_i = \\text{Each value in the data set} \\\\\\&\\overline { x } = \\text{Mean of all values in the data set} \\\\\\&N = \\text{Number of values in the data set} \\\\\\\\\\end{aligned}\n\n### Tip: \n\nYou can also use the formula above to calculate the variance in areas other than investments and trading, with some slight alterations. For instance, when calculating a variance to estimate a variance, the denominator of the variance equation becomes N − 1 so that the estimation is unbiased and does not underestimate the population variance.\n\n## Advantages and Disadvantages of Using Variance \n\nLike any way of analyzing data, variance and benefits and limitations. \n\n### Pros \n\n * **Simplicity** : Variance is a straightforward measurement that statisticians can use to see how individual numbers relate to each other within a data set, rather than using broader mathematical techniques such as arranging numbers into quartiles. \n * **Treats all deviations the same** : The advantage of variance is that it treats all deviations from the mean as the same regardless of their direction. This allows analysts and investors to see the full range of risk and variability in a data set, rather than only those that are positive or negative. \n * **Avoids appearance of no variability** : The squared deviations cannot sum to zero and give the appearance of no variability at all in the data. This can avoid some misinterpretations of the data.\n\n### Cons \n\n * **Added weight to outliers** : Outliers are the numbers far from the mean. Squaring these numbers gives them more weight, which can the data. \n * **Not often used alone** : Variance is often used as a stepping stone to finding the of a dataset, rather than a measurement on its own. Investors can use standard deviation, which is the square root of variance, to assess how consistent returns are over time.\n\nPros\n\n * Simplicity\n\n * Treats all deviations the same\n\n * Avoids appearance of no variability\n\nCons\n\n * Added weight to outliers\n\n * Not often used alone\n\n### Important: \n\nIn some cases, risk or volatility may be expressed as a standard deviation rather than a variance because the former is often more easily interpreted.\n\n## Example of Variance in Finance \n\nIf returns for s\n...[truncated]"}
