hould be at least equal to the 'days' parameter.\")\n    if days <= 0:\n        raise ValueError(\"'days' parameter must be positive.\")\n    if smoothing <= 0:\n        raise ValueError(\"'smoothing' parameter must be positive.\")\n    multiplier = smoothing / (1 + days)\n    sma = sum(prices[:days]) / days\n    ema_values = [None] * (days - 1)\n    ema_values.append(sma)\n    for price in prices[days:]:\n        new_ema = (price - ema_values[-1]) * multiplier + ema_values[-1]\n        ema_values.append(new_ema)\n    return ema_values[-1]", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "prices_is_list", "name": "Prices Input Type Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('prices'), list)", "applies_to": ["prices"], "description": "The 'prices' input must be a list."}, {"rule_id": "prices_elements_numeric", "name": "Prices List Elements Numeric Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "all(isinstance(p, (int, float)) for p in inputs.get('prices', []))", "applies_to": ["prices"], "description": "All elements in the 'prices' list must be numeric (integers or floats)."}, {"rule_id": "days_is_integer", "name": "Days Input Type Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('days', 20), int)", "applies_to": ["days"], "description": "The 'days' input must be an integer."}, {"rule_id": "smoothing_is_numeric", "name": "Smoothing Input Type Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('smoothing', 2), (int, float))", "applies_to": ["smoothing"], "description": "The 'smoothing' input must be numeric (integer or float)."}, {"rule_id": "prices_length_sufficient", "name": "Minimum Prices Length Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "len(inputs['prices']) >= inputs['days']", "applies_to": ["prices", "days"], "description": "The number of prices must be at least equal to the 'days' parameter to calculate EMA."}, {"rule_id": "days_must_be_positive", "name": "Days Positive Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "inputs['days'] > 0", "applies_to": ["days"], "description": "The 'days' parameter must be a positive integer."}, {"rule_id": "smoothing_must_be_positive", "name": "Smoothing Factor Positive Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "inputs['smoothing'] > 0", "applies_to": ["smoothing"], "description": "The 'smoothing' factor must be a positive number."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    prices = inputs['prices']\n    smoothing = inputs.get('smoothing', 2)\n    days = inputs.get('days', 20)\n    if len(prices) < days:\n        raise ValueError(\"Number of prices should be at least equal to the 'days' parameter.\")\n    if days <= 0:\n        raise ValueError(\"'days' parameter must be positive.\")\n    if smoothing <= 0:\n        raise ValueError(\"'smoothing' parameter must be positive.\")\n    multiplier = smoothing / (1 + days)\n    sma = sum(prices[:days]) / days\n    ema_values = [None] * (days - 1)\n    ema_values.append(sma)\n    for price in prices[days:]:\n        new_ema = (price - ema_values[-1]) * multiplier + ema_values[-1]\n        ema_values.append(new_ema)\n    return ema_values[-1]"}, "article_title": "Exponential Moving Average (EMA)", "article_doc_id": 5705, "article_content_excerpt": "# What is EMA? How to Use Exponential Moving Average With Formula\n\n## What Is an Exponential Moving Average (EMA)? \n\nAn exponential moving average (EMA) is a type of that places a greater weight and significance on the most recent data points. The exponential moving average is also referred to as the exponentially moving average. An exponentially weighted moving average reacts more significantly to recent price changes than a simple moving average , which applies an equal weight to all observations in the period. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * The EMA is a moving average that places a greater weight and significance on the most recent data points.\n * Like all moving averages, this technical indicator is used to produce buy and sell signals based on crossovers and divergences from the historical average.\n * Traders often use several different EMA lengths, such as 10-day, 50-day, and 200-day moving averages.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/Exponential-Moving-Average-eb1cb1860f3f4768892091ddcfec5b34.png)\n\nInvestopedia / Daniel Fishel\n\n## Formula for Exponential Moving Average (EMA) \n\n﻿\\begin{aligned} &\\begin{aligned} EMA_{\\text{Today}}=&\\left(\\text{Value}_{\\text{Today}}\\ast\\left(\\frac{\\text{Smoothing}}{1+\\text{Days}}\\right)\\right)\\\\\\ &+EMA_{\\text{Yesterday}}\\ast\\left(1-\\left(\\frac{\\text{Smoothing}}{1+\\text{Days}}\\right)\\right)\\end{aligned}\\\\\\ &\\textbf{where:}\\\\\\ &EMA=\\text{Exponential moving average} \\end{aligned}﻿ \n\nWhile there are many possible choices for the smoothing factor, the most common choice is: \n\n * Smoothing = 2\n\nThat gives the most recent observation more weight. If the smoothing factor is increased, more recent observations have more influence on the EMA. \n\n## Calculating the EMA \n\n requires one more observation than the SMA. Suppose that you want to use 20 days as the number of observations for the EMA. Then, you must wait until the 20th day to obtain the SMA. On the 21st day, you can then use the SMA from the previous day as the first EMA for yesterday. \n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/EMA-5c535d5a46e0fb000181fa56.png)\n\nTradingView.\n\nThe calculation for the SMA is straightforward. It is simply the sum of the stock's closing prices during a time period, divided by the number of observations for that period. For example, a 20-day SMA is just the sum of the closing prices for the past 20 trading days, divided by 20.\n\nNext, you must calculate the multiplier for smoothing (weighting) the EMA, which typically follows the formula: [2 ÷ (number of observations + 1)]. For a 20-day moving average, the multiplier would be [2/(20+1)]= 0.0952. \n\nFinally, the following formula is used to calculate the current EMA:\n\n * EMA = Closing price x multiplier + EMA (previous day) x (1-multiplier)\n\nThe EMA gives a higher weight to recent prices, while the SMA assigns equal weight to all values. The weighting given to the most recent price is greater for a shorter-period EMA than for a longer-period EMA. For example, an 18.18% multiplier is applied to the most recent price data for a 10-period EMA, while the weight is only 9.52% for a 20-period EMA. \n\nThere are also slight variations of the EMA arrived at by using the open, high, low, or median price instead of using the closing price. \n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/dotdash_Final_Exponential_Moving_Average_EMA_Aug_2020-01-3bacd080c9ac450595fe7daa9148a65b.jpg)\n\nImage by Sabrina Jiang © Investopedia 2020\n\n## What Does the EMA Tell You? \n\nThe 12- and 26-day exponential moving averages (EMAs) are often the most quoted and analyzed short-term averages. The 12- and 26-day are used to create indicators like the and the . In general, the 50- and 200-day EMAs are used as indicators for long-term trends. When a stock price crosses its 200-day moving average, it is a technical signal that a has occurred. \n\nTraders who employ find moving averages very useful and insightful when applied correctly. However, they also realize that these signals can create havoc when used improperly or misinterpr\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_898", "name": "McClellan Oscillator", "short_description": "Calculates the Adjusted McClellan Oscillator, a market breadth indicator, using Adjusted Net Advances (ANA) and prior Exponential Moving Averages (EMAs) to account for changes in listed stocks, offering a more reliable long-term indicator.", "domain": "financial_markets", "topic": "stock_market_analysis", "topic_extension": false, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-898", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-194", "question_id": "test-2075", "difficulty": 4.499809670330265, "level": "hard", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "2ff9bf67c16374b47b39fbc774f98baa191e510c59aa3e4271cf15d5f84a95e9", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["McClellan Oscillator", "Adjusted Net Advances", "ANA", "market breadth", "technical analysis", "EMA", "stock market indicator", "momentum indicator"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "oscillator_type", "ambiguity_type": "formula_variant", "trigger_signal": "User refers to 'McClellan Oscillator' without specifying 'Adjusted' or 'Standard' type.", "clarification_question": "Are you referring to the standard McClellan Oscillator (based on raw Advances minus Declines) or the Adjusted McClellan Oscillator (which normalizes Advances minus Declines by total issues)? This function implements the Adjusted version.", "options": [{"label": "Adjusted McClellan Oscillator (normalized, current calculation) - DEFAULT", "value": "adjusted", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Standard McClellan Oscillator (raw Advances - Declines)", "value": "standard", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "hard", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Adjusted McClellan Oscillator is assumed as per the function's implementation.", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "ana", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "Adjusted Net Advances, representing the difference between advancing and declining issues, potentially normalized depending on the specific implementation.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "prior_19_day_ema", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The previous day's 19-day Exponential Moving Average (EMA) of the Adjusted Net Advances.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "prior_39_day_ema", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The previous day's 39-day Exponential Moving Average (EMA) of the Adjusted Net Advances.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "adjusted_mcclellan_oscillator", "type": "number", "unit": null, "description": "The calculated value of the Adjusted McClellan Oscillator."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    ana = inputs['ana']\n    prior_19_day_ema = inputs['prior_19_day_ema']\n    prior_39_day_ema = inputs['prior_39_day_ema']\n    ema_19_day = ana * 0.1 + prior_19_day_ema * (1 - 0.1)\n    ema_39_day = ana * 0.05 + prior_39_day_ema * (1 - 0.05)\n    adjusted_mcclellan_oscillator = ema_19_day - ema_39_day\n    return round(adjusted_mcclellan_oscillator, 2)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "ana_magnitude_check", "name": "Adjusted Net Advances Plausibility Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (-10000 <= inputs['ana'] <= 10000)", "applies_to": [], "description": "Adjusted Net Advances (ANA) should be within a reasonable magnitude, typically not exceeding +/- 10,000 for standard exchanges. Values outside this range may indicate a data error."}, {"rule_id": "prior_19_day_ema_magnitude_check", "name": "Prior 19-day EMA Plausibility Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (-10000 <= inputs['prior_19_day_ema'] <= 10000)", "applies_to": [], "description": "The prior 19-day EMA of ANA should be within a reasonable magnitude, typically not exceeding +/- 10,000. Values outside this range may indicate a data error or miscalculation."}, {"rule_id": "prior_39_day_ema_magnitude_check", "name": "Prior 39-day EMA Plausibility Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (-10000 <= inputs['prior_39_day_ema'] <= 10000)", "applies_to": [], "description": "The prior 39-day EMA of ANA should be within a reasonable magnitude, typically not exceeding +/- 10,000. Values outside this range may indicate a data error or miscalculation."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    ana = inputs['ana']\n    prior_19_day_ema = inputs['prior_19_day_ema']\n    prior_39_day_ema = inputs['prior_39_day_ema']\n    ema_19_day = ana * 0.1 + prior_19_day_ema * (1 - 0.1)\n    ema_39_day = ana * 0.05 + prior_39_day_ema * (1 - 0.05)\n    adjusted_mcclellan_oscillator = ema_19_day - ema_39_day\n    return round(adjusted_mcclellan_oscillator, 2)"}, "article_title": "McClellan Oscillator", "article_doc_id": 1650, "article_content_excerpt": "# McClellan Oscillator: Definition, Uses, and What It Indicates\n\n## What Is the McClellan Oscillator? \n\nThe McClellan Oscillator is a indicator that is based on the difference between the number of advancing and declining issues on a stock exchange, such as the New York Stock Exchange (NYSE) or NASDAQ.\n\nThe indicator is used to show strong shifts in sentiment in the indexes, called breadth thrusts. It also helps in analyzing the strength of an index trend via or confirmation. \n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/McClellanOscillator-5c8bf43b46e0fb00016ee083.png)\n\nTradingView.\n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * The McClellan Oscillator formula can be applied to any stock exchange or group of stocks.\n * A reading above zero helps confirm a rise in the index, while readings below zero confirm a decline in the index.\n * When the index is rising but the oscillator is falling, that warns that the index could start declining too. When the index is falling and the oscillator is rising, that indicates the index could start rising soon. This is called divergence.\n * A significant change, such as moving 100 points or more, from a negative reading to a positive reading is called a breadth thrust. It may indicate a strong from downtrend to uptrend is underway on the stock exchange.\n\n## The Formula for the McClellan Oscillator is \n\nThere are two formulas for the McClellan oscillator. The original formula, and one that adjusts for changes in the number of stocks listed on the stock exchange. The adjusted formula allows for a better comparison of values over longer periods of time.\n\n\\begin{aligned} \\text{McClellan Oscillator} =& ( \\text{19-day EMA of Advances} - \\\\\\ &\\text{Declines} ) - ( \\text{39-day EMA} \\\\\\ &\\text{of Advances} - \\text{Declines} ) \\\\\\ \\text{19-day EMA} =& ( \\text{Current Day Advances} - \\\\\\ &\\text{Declines} ) * 0.10 + \\\\\\ &\\text{Prior Day EMA} \\\\\\ \\text{39-day EMA} =& ( \\text{Current Day Advances} - \\\\\\ &\\text{Declines} ) *0.05 + \\\\\\ &\\text{Prior Day EMA} \\\\\\ \\\\\\ \\text{Adj. McClellan Oscillator} =& ( \\text{19-Day EMA of ANA} ) - \\\\\\ &( \\text{39-Day EMA of ANA} ) \\\\\\ \\text{Adj. Net Advances (ANA)} =& \\frac{\\text{Advances} - \\text{Declines}}{\\text{Advances} + \\text{Declines}}\\\\\\ \\text{19-day EMA} =& ( \\text{Current Day ANA} - \\\\\\ &\\text{Prior Day EMA} * 0.10 \\\\\\ &\\+ \\text{Prior Day EMA} \\\\\\ \\text{39-day EMA} =& ( \\text{Current Day ANA} - \\\\\\ &\\text{Prior Day EMA} ) * 0.05 \\\\\\ &\\+ \\text{Prior Day EMA} \\\\\\ \\end{aligned}\n\n\\begin{aligned} &\\textbf{where:} \\\\\\ &\\text{EMA} = \\text{Exponential moving average} \\\\\\ &\\text{Advances} = \\text{Number of stocks trading above their} \\\\\\ &\\text{previous day's close} \\\\\\ &\\text{Declines} = \\text{Number of stocks trading below their} \\\\\\ &\\text{previous day's close} \\\\\\ \\end{aligned}\n\n### How to Calculate the McClellan Oscillator \n\n 1. To get the calculation started, track Advances - Declines on a stock exchange for 19 and 39 days. Calculate a for these, not (EMA).\n 2. Use these simple values as the Prior Day EMA values in the 19- and 39-day EMA formulas.\n 3. Calculate the 19- and 39-day EMAs.\n 4. Calculate the McClellan Oscillator value.\n 5. Now that the value has been calculated, on the next calculation use this value for the Prior Day EMA. Start for the formula instead of simple averages.\n 6. If using the adjusted formula, the steps are the same, except use ANA instead of using Advances - Declines.\n\n## What Does the McClellan Oscillator Tell You? \n\nThe McClellan Oscillator is an indicator based on market breadth which can use in conjunction with other technical tools to determine the overall state of the stock market and assess the strength of its current trend.\n\nSince the indicator is based on all the stocks in an exchange, it is compared to the price movements of indexes that reflect that exchange, or compared to major indexes such as the . \n\nPositive and negative values indicate whether more stocks, on average, are advancing or declining. The indicator is positive when the 19-day EMA is above the 39-\n...[truncated]"}
