ax value, or is tax irrelevant for this allocation?", "options": [{"label": "Tax is irrelevant to the allocation (default)", "value": "tax_irrelevant", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Pre-tax expense", "value": "pre_tax", "is_default": false}, {"label": "Post-tax expense", "value": "post_tax", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Tax considerations are not relevant to the allocation", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "total_expense", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The total administrative expense to be allocated (e.g., an electricity bill).", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "department_square_footages", "type": "dict[string,number]", "required": true, "description": "A JSON object/dictionary where keys are department names and values are their respective square footage.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "target_department_name", "type": "string", "required": true, "description": "The name of the department whose allocated expense should be returned.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "allocated_expense", "type": "number", "unit": "dollar", "description": "The portion of the total administrative expense allocated to the target department."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    total_expense = inputs['total_expense']\n    department_square_footages = inputs['department_square_footages']\n    target_department_name = inputs['target_department_name']\n    total_square_footage = sum(department_square_footages.values())\n    if total_square_footage <= 0:\n        raise ValueError('Total square footage must be greater than zero to allocate expenses.')\n    if target_department_name not in department_square_footages:\n        raise ValueError(f\"Target department '{target_department_name}' not found in the provided square footages.\")\n    target_dept_sq_ft = department_square_footages[target_department_name]\n    allocation = target_dept_sq_ft / total_square_footage * total_expense\n    return allocation", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "total_expense_type_check", "name": "Total Expense Type Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('total_expense'), (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'total_expense' input must be a numerical value (integer or float)."}, {"rule_id": "total_expense_positivity_check", "name": "Total Expense Positivity Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['total_expense'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'total_expense' cannot be a negative value."}, {"rule_id": "department_square_footages_type_check", "name": "Department Square Footages Type Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('department_square_footages'), dict)", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'department_square_footages' input must be a dictionary."}, {"rule_id": "department_sq_ft_values_check", "name": "Department Square Footage Values Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not all(isinstance(v, (int, float)) and v >= 0 for v in inputs['department_square_footages'].values())", "applies_to": [], "description": "All square footage values within 'department_square_footages' must be non-negative numbers."}, {"rule_id": "total_square_footage_positive_check", "name": "Total Square Footage Positive Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "sum(inputs['department_square_footages'].values()) <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The sum of all department square footages must be greater than zero to enable allocation."}, {"rule_id": "target_department_name_type_check", "name": "Target Department Name Type Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('target_department_name'), str)", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'target_department_name' input must be a string."}, {"rule_id": "target_department_exists_check", "name": "Target Department Exists Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['target_department_name'] not in inputs['department_square_footages']", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'target_department_name' must correspond to a department key present in the 'department_square_footages' dictionary."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    total_expense = inputs['total_expense']\n    department_square_footages = inputs['department_square_footages']\n    target_department_name = inputs['target_department_name']\n    total_square_footage = sum(department_square_footages.values())\n    if total_square_footage <= 0:\n        raise ValueError('Total square footage must be greater than zero to allocate expenses.')\n    if target_department_name not in department_square_footages:\n        raise ValueError(f\"Target department '{target_department_name}' not found in the provided square footages.\")\n    target_dept_sq_ft = department_square_footages[target_department_name]\n    allocation = target_dept_sq_ft / total_square_footage * total_expense\n    return allocation"}, "article_title": "Administrative Expenses", "article_doc_id": 4420, "article_content_excerpt": "# What Are Administrative Expenses and What Are Some Examples?\n\n## What Are Administrative Expenses? \n\nAdministrative expenses are expenses incurred by an organization that are not directly tied to a specific core function such as manufacturing, production, or sales. These are related to the organization as a whole rather than to individual departments or business units. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Administrative expenses are costs incurred to support the functioning of a business but that aren't directly related to the production of a specific product or service.\n * Some level of administrative expenses will always be incurred as a necessary part of operations.\n * Administrative expenses are often among the first identified for budget cuts because they don't directly impact a company's main business functions.\n * Management may allocate administrative expenses to its business units based on a percentage of revenue, expenses, or other measures.\n\n## Understanding Administrative Expenses \n\nAdministrative expenses may include the salaries of senior management and the costs associated with general services or supplies, such as legal, accounting, clerical work, and information technology. These costs generally aren't directly related to the production of goods or services and are usually excluded from . \n\nCompanies incur administrative expenses to perform basic operations such as administering payroll or healthcare benefits. They incur them to increase oversight and efficiency and/or to comply with laws and regulations. Administrative expenses appear below (COGS) on the and they may be shown as an aggregate with such as general or selling expenses. \n\nSome administrative expenses are in nature because they're incurred as part of the foundation of business operations. They would exist regardless of the level of production or sales that occur. Other administrative expenses are . A business will always use some minimum level of electricity to keep the lights on. It can take measures to reduce its electric bill beyond that point. \n\nA business can eliminate administrative expenses without a direct impact on the product it sells or produces so these costs are typically first in line for budget cuts. Management is strongly motivated to maintain low administrative expenses relative to other costs because this allows a business to use more effectively. The sales-to-administrative expense ratio helps companies measure how much sales revenue is being portioned to cover administrative costs. \n\nCompanies can deduct administrative expenses that are reasonable, ordinary, and necessary for business operations on their tax returns. These expenses must be incurred during the usual course of business and deducted in the year they're incurred.\n\n## Other Types of Administrative Expenses \n\nWages and benefits to certain employees such as accounting and IT staff are considered to be administrative expenses. All executive compensation and benefits are considered to be administrative expenses. Building leases, insurance, subscriptions, utilities, and office supplies may be classified as . \n\n expenses may be classified as general, administrative, or selling (marketing) expenses depending on the asset being depreciated. Organizations may choose to include consulting and legal fees as administrative expenses as well but (R&D) costs aren't considered to be administrative expenses. \n\n### Important: \n\nA company may allocate administrative expenses to each of its departments based on a percentage of revenue, expenses, square footage, or other measures. This allows management to make decisions internally about expanding or reducing individual business units.\n\n## Example of Administrative Expenses \n\nXYZ Company might allocate the cost according to the square footage each department occupies if it spends $4,000 monthly on electricity and records this as an administrative expense. Assume: \n\n * The production facility is 2,000 square feet\n * The manufacturing facility is 1,\n...[truncated]"}
