, "description": "The total gain from call options due to appreciation in the underlying equity.", "unit": "currency", "aliases": []}, {"name": "participation_rate", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The participation rate as a decimal, representing the proportion of the equity gain the investor participates in (e.g., 1 for 100%, 0.75 for 75%).", "unit": "decimal_ratio", "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "eln_payout", "type": "number", "unit": "currency", "description": "The total payout of the ELN at maturity, including the initial principal and any gains."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    initial_investment = inputs['initial_investment']\n    bond_yield = inputs['bond_yield']\n    call_options_gain = inputs['call_options_gain']\n    participation_rate = inputs['participation_rate']\n    principal_protection = initial_investment * (1 + bond_yield)\n    equity_gain = call_options_gain * participation_rate\n    eln_payout = principal_protection + equity_gain\n    return round(eln_payout)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "eln_payout_001", "name": "Positive Initial Investment", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['initial_investment'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["initial_investment"], "description": "The initial investment for an ELN must be a positive value."}, {"rule_id": "eln_payout_002", "name": "Valid Bond Yield Range", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (0 <= inputs['bond_yield'] <= 0.30)", "applies_to": ["bond_yield"], "description": "The bond yield must be a non-negative value and typically not exceed 30% (0.30) to be realistic."}, {"rule_id": "eln_payout_003", "name": "Non-negative Call Options Gain", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['call_options_gain'] < 0", "applies_to": ["call_options_gain"], "description": "The total gain from call options cannot be negative. If options expire worthless, the gain is zero."}, {"rule_id": "eln_payout_004", "name": "Valid Participation Rate Range (Decimal)", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (0 <= inputs['participation_rate'] <= 1)", "applies_to": ["participation_rate"], "description": "The participation rate, as a decimal, must be between 0 and 1 (inclusive)."}, {"rule_id": "eln_payout_005", "name": "Principal Protection Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "compute(inputs) < inputs['initial_investment']", "applies_to": ["initial_investment", "bond_yield", "call_options_gain", "participation_rate"], "description": "In most ELN structures, the principal is protected, meaning the total payout should not be less than the initial investment. This check might indicate an unusual ELN structure or an incorrect input."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    initial_investment = inputs['initial_investment']\n    bond_yield = inputs['bond_yield']\n    call_options_gain = inputs['call_options_gain']\n    participation_rate = inputs['participation_rate']\n    principal_protection = initial_investment * (1 + bond_yield)\n    equity_gain = call_options_gain * participation_rate\n    eln_payout = principal_protection + equity_gain\n    return round(eln_payout)"}, "article_title": "Equity-Linked Note (ELN)", "article_doc_id": 5594, "article_content_excerpt": "# Equity-Linked Note (ELN) Definition and Features\n\n## What Is an Equity-Linked Note (ELN)? \n\nAn equity-linked note (ELN) is an investment product that combines a fixed-income investment with additional potential returns that are tied to the performance of equities. Equity-linked notes are usually structured to return the initial investment with a variable interest portion that depends on the performance of the linked equity. ELNs can be structured in many different ways, but the vanilla version works like a combined with a on a specific security, a basket of securities or an index like the S&P 500 or . In the case of a note linked to an equity index, the security would typically be called an equity index-linked note. \n\n## Understanding Equity-Linked Notes \n\nEquity-linked notes provide a way for investors to protect their capital while also getting the potential for an above-average return compared to regular bonds. In theory, the upside potential for returns in an equity-linked note is unlimited, whereas the downside risk is capped. Even in the worst-case scenario, most equity-linked notes offer full principal protection. That is what makes this type of a structured product appealing to investors who nevertheless have a bullish outlook on the market. That said, equity-linked notes only pay on maturity, so there is an for locking in that money if only the principal is returned in the end. \n\n## How ELN Work \n\nIn the simplest form, a $1,000 5-year equity-linked note could be structured to use $800 of the fund to buy a 5-year strip bond with a 4.5% yield-to-maturity and then invest and reinvest the other $200 in call options for the S&P 500 over the 5-year life of the note. There is a chance that the options will expire worthless, in which case the investor gets back the $1,000 initially put in. If, however, the options appreciate in value with the S&P 500, those returns are added to the $1,000 that will eventually be returned to the investor. \n\n## Equity Linked Note Caps, Participation Rates, and Leverage \n\nIn practice, an equity-linked note will have a , which is the percentage amount that the investor in the note participates in the appreciation of the underlying equity. If the participation rate is 100%, then a 5% increase in the underlying is a 5% increase for the eventual payout on the note. However, the cost of structuring the ELN and managing it can lower the participation rate. In the case of a 75% participation rate, for example, a 5% appreciation in the underlying is only worth 3.75% to the investor. \n\nEquity-linked notes can also use different structures and features. Some will use an averaging formula to smooth out returns on the equity-linked portion or a periodic cap that limits the ELN’s upside by realizing returns at a particular level on a regular basis. There are also types of equity-linked notes that use dynamic hedging instead of options, deploying leverage to increase returns from the underlying equity. Overall, equity-linked notes can be a powerful tool for investors who want to protect their principle while still having the potential upside of an equity investment."}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_1375", "name": "Profitability Ratios", "short_description": "Calculates the gross margin as a percentage of revenue, reflecting the relationship between revenue and the cost of goods sold (COGS).", "domain": "financial_ratios", "topic": "profitratio", "topic_extension": false, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-1375", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-1233", "question_id": "test-1132", "difficulty": 2.4849066497880004, "level": "medium", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "7f4d7316fbde50505dbc0b542ba869247ebc116293f33f90921e4cf2e5a1341b", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["gross margin", "profitability", "revenue", "cost of goods sold", "COGS", "profitability ratio", "margin ratio"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "output_scale", "ambiguity_type": "unit_scale", "trigger_signal": "output value is a ratio or rate, often presented as percentage or decimal", "clarification_question": "Should the answer be expressed as a decimal (0.25) or percent (25.0)?", "options": [{"label": "Percentage — DEFAULT", "value": "percentage", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Decimal", "value": "decimal", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "result / 100.0", "max_expr_nodes": 6, "invariant": "result_new == result_old / 100.0", "affected_inputs": []}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Percentage", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "revenue", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The total sales revenue.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "cogs", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The cost of goods sold.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "gross_margin_percentage", "type": "number", "unit": "%", "description": "The gross margin percentage."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    revenue = inputs['revenue']\n    cogs = inputs['cogs']\n    gross_profit = revenue - cogs\n    gross_margin = gross_profit / revenue * 100\n    return gross_margin", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "revenue_positive", "name": "Revenue must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['revenue'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["revenue"], "description": "Revenue, representing total sales, must be a positive value to calculate a meaningful gross margin."}, {"rule_id": "cogs_non_negative", "name": "Cost of Goods Sold (COGS) must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['cogs'] < 0", "applies_to": ["cogs"], "description": "The Cost of Goods Sold (COGS) cannot be negative, as it represents expenses directly tied to production."}, {"rule_id": "revenue_greater_than_cogs", "name": "Revenue should ideally be greater than COGS for positive gross profit", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['revenue'] < inputs['cogs']", "applies_to": ["revenue", "cogs"], "description": "For a positive gross profit and margin, revenue should exceed the cost of goods sold. If COGS is greater than revenue, it implies a gross loss."}, {"rule_id": "gross_margin_percentage_range", "name": "Gross Margin Percentage should be within a plausible range", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "compute(inputs) > 100 or compute(inputs) < -100", "applies_to": ["revenue", "cogs"], "description": "Gross Margin Percentage is typically between -100% and 100%. Values outside this range may indicate unusual financial data or potential data entry errors."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    revenue = inputs['revenue']\n    cogs = inputs['cogs']\n    gross_profit = revenue - cogs\n    gross_margin = gross_profit / revenue * 100\n    return gross_margin"}, "article_title": "Profitability Ratios", "article_doc_id": 2719, "article_content_excerpt": "# Profitability Ratios: What They Are, Common Types, and How Businesses Use Them\n\n## What Are Profitability Ratios? \n\nProfitability ratios are a class of financial metrics that are used to assess a business's ability to generate earnings relative to its revenue, , balance sheet assets, or over time, using data from a specific point in time. They are among the most popular metrics used in . \n\nProfitability ratios can be a window into the of a business. Ratios are best used as comparison tools rather than as metrics in isolation. \n\nProfitability ratios can be used along with , which consider how well a company uses its assets internally to generate income (as opposed to after-cost profits). \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Profitability ratios assess a company's ability to earn profits from its sales or operations, balance sheet assets, or shareholders' equity.\n * They indicate how efficiently a company generates profit and value for shareholders.\n * Profitability ratios include margin ratios and return ratios.\n * Higher ratios are often more favorable than lower ratios, indicating success at converting revenue to profit.\n * These ratios are used to assess a company's current performance compared to its past performance, the performance of other companies in its industry, or the industry average.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/profitability-ratios-508804002f2c42448463becc3b37e79b.jpg)\n\nInvestopedia / Julie Bang\n\n## What Can Profitability Ratios Tell You? \n\nProfitability ratios can shed light on how well a company's management is operating a business. Investors can use them, along with other research, to determine whether or not a company might be a good investment. \n\nBroadly speaking, higher profitability ratios can point to strengths and advantages that a company has, such as the ability to charge more (or less) for products and to maintain lower costs. \n\nA company's profitability ratios are most useful when compared to those of similar companies, the company's own performance history, or average ratios for the company's industry. Normally, a higher value relative to previous value indicates that the company is doing well. \n\n### Fast Fact: \n\nReturn ratios are metrics that compare returns received to investments made by bondholders and shareholders. They reflect how well a business manages the investments to produce value for investors.\n\n## Types of Profitability Ratios \n\nProfitability ratios generally fall into two categories—margin ratios and return ratios. \n\nMargin ratios give insight, from several different angles, into a company's ability to turn sales into profit. Return ratios offer several different ways to examine how well a company generates a for its shareholders using the money they've invested. \n\nSome common examples of the two types of profitability ratios are: \n\n * Gross margin\n * Operating margin\n * Pretax margin\n * Net profit margin\n * Cash flow margin\n * Return on assets (ROA)\n * Return on equity (ROE)\n * \n\n## Margin Ratios \n\nDifferent are used to measure a company's profitability at various cost levels of inquiry. These include gross margin, operating margin, pretax margin, and net profit margin. The margins between profit and costs expand when costs are low and shrink as layers of additional costs (e.g., , operating expenses, and taxes) are taken into consideration. \n\n### Gross Margin \n\nGross profit margin, also known as gross margin, is one of the most widely used profitability ratios. Gross profit is the difference between sales revenue and the costs related to the products sold, the aforementioned COGS. compares gross profit to revenue. \n\nA company with a high gross margin compared to its peers likely has the ability to charge a premium for its products. It may indicate the company has . On the other hand, a pattern of declining gross margins may point to increased competition. \n\nSome industries experience in their operations. For example, retailers typically experience significantly higher revenues and during\n...[truncated]"}
