 return []\n        ema = [values[0]]\n        multiplier = 2 / (period + 1)\n        for price in values[1:]:\n            ema.append((price - ema[-1]) * multiplier + ema[-1])\n        return ema\n    if not current_prices or not prior_prices:\n        return 0.0\n    price_changes = [ccp - pcp for ccp, pcp in zip(current_prices, prior_prices)]\n    absolute_price_changes = [abs(pc) for pc in price_changes]\n    if not price_changes or not absolute_price_changes:\n        return 0.0\n    pcs_ema = calculate_ema(price_changes, period1)\n    apc_ema = calculate_ema(absolute_price_changes, period1)\n    if not pcs_ema or not apc_ema:\n        return 0.0\n    pcds_ema = calculate_ema(pcs_ema, period2)\n    apcds_ema = calculate_ema(apc_ema, period2)\n    if not pcds_ema or not apcds_ema:\n        return 0.0\n    if apcds_ema[-1] == 0:\n        return 0.0\n    tsi = pcds_ema[-1] / apcds_ema[-1] * 100\n    return tsi"}, "article_title": "True Strength Index (TSI)", "article_doc_id": 3714, "article_content_excerpt": "# True Strength Index (TSI): Formula, Calculations, and Interpretation\n\n## What Is the True Strength Index (TSI)? \n\nThe true strength index (TSI) is a technical momentum used by technical analysts. The true strength index is used to identify trends and reversals in the market. The indicator may determine conditions, indicate potential trend direction changes via centerline or signal line crossovers, and warn traders of trend weakness that may occur through . \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * The true strength index is a technical momentum oscillator used by technical analysts to identify market trends and reversals.\n * The TSI fluctuates between positive (bullish) and negative (bearish) territory. \n * When the indicator divergences with price, the TSI may be signaling the price trend is weakening and may reverse.\n * When the TSI crosses above the signal line, it can be used as a buy signal, and when it crosses below, a sell signal. \n * Overbought and oversold levels will vary by the asset being traded.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/dotdash_INV-final-True-Strength-Index-TSI-June-2021-01-f2735372b905432da6169761a2194753.jpg)\n\nImage by Sabrina Jiang © Investopedia 2021\n\n## Formula and How to Calculate the True Strength Index (TSI) \n\nThe formula for calculating the TSI involves the following steps.\n\n\\begin{aligned} &\\text{TSI = (PCDS/APCDS) x 100}\\\\\\ &\\text{PC = CCP }-\\text{ PCP}\\\\\\ &\\text{PCS = 25-period EMA of PC}\\\\\\ &\\text{PCDS = 13-period EMA of PCS}\\\\\\ &\\text{APC = AVCCP }-\\text{ PCP}\\\\\\ &\\text{APCS = 25-period EMA of APC}\\\\\\ &\\text{APCDS = 13-period EMA of APCS}\\\\\\ &\\textbf{where:}\\\\\\ &\\text{PCDS = PC double smoothed}\\\\\\ &\\text{APCDS = Absolute PC double smoothed}\\\\\\ &\\text{PC = Price change}\\\\\\ &\\text{CCP = Current close price}\\\\\\ &\\text{PCP = Prior close price}\\\\\\ &\\text{PCS = PC smoothed}\\\\\\ &\\text{EMA = Exponential moving average}\\\\\\ &\\text{APC = Absolute PC}\\\\\\ &\\text{APCS = Absolute PC smoothed}\\\\\\ \\end{aligned}\n\nThe main skill required in computing the TSI is the ability to .\n\n 1. Record price changes and absolute price changes to calculate an EMA for both these values.\n 2. Calculate the price change 25-period EMA and the absolute price change 25-period EMA.\n 3. Smooth both of these EMAs by applying a 13-period EMA to each of them.\n 4. Compute the TSI value by plugging the now double-smoothed price change and double-smoothed absolute price change into the TSI formula.\n\n## How the TSI Works \n\n is a trading strategy that is used by certain traders to identify entry and exit opportunities. This is done by researching and evaluating the past performance of an , security, or market and making predictions about its direction. Traders use different tools and techniques to pinpoint opportunities. This includes the true strength index, which was created by author and trader William Blau in 1991.\n\nThe TSI is an oscillator that measures the strength of an asset or market's price movement over time as well as any directions in that price. The index is primarily used to identify overbought and oversold conditions in an asset's price. It also helps traders spot divergence, identify direction and changes via the centerline, and highlight short-term price momentum with crossovers. \n\nSince the TSI is based on price movements, oversold and overbought levels tend to vary according to the asset being traded. Some stocks may reach +30 and -30 before tending to see , while other stocks may reverse near +20 and -20. \n\nOn the asset being traded, trades can mark extreme TSI levels to see the points that represent where assets are overbought and oversold. Traders typically watch for other signals to trigger a trade decision. For example, they may wait for the price or TSI to start dropping before selling in overbought territory. Alternatively, they may wait for a signal line . \n\n### Important: \n\nBeing oversold doesn't necessarily mean it is time to buy, and when an asset is overbought it doesn't necessarily mean it is time to sell.\n\n## How to Inte\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_1738", "name": "Discounts For Lack Of Marketability (DLOM): Role in Valuation", "short_description": "Calculates the Discount for Lack of Marketability (DLOM) using the restricted stock method, based on the price difference between common stock and restricted stock.", "domain": "mergers_and_acquisitions", "topic": "valuation_methods", "topic_extension": false, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-1738", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-1057", "question_id": "test-1088", "difficulty": 2.4849066497880004, "level": "medium", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "22286c2fd5c100535d204026cb11f34fb4e617f252109d67fcae48d5aa0da18a", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["Discount for Lack of Marketability", "DLOM", "restricted stock valuation", "marketability discount", "stock price difference"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "output_scale", "ambiguity_type": "unit_scale", "trigger_signal": "output may be expected in decimal format instead of percentage", "clarification_question": "Should the answer be expressed as a decimal (e.g., 0.25) or as a percentage (e.g., 25.0%)?", "options": [{"label": "Percentage (e.g., 25.0%) - DEFAULT", "value": "percent", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Decimal (e.g., 0.25)", "value": "decimal", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "result / 100.0", "max_expr_nodes": 6, "invariant": "result_new == result_old / 100.0", "affected_inputs": []}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Percentage", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "common_stock_price", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The price of the company's common stock.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "restricted_stock_price", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The price of the restricted stock.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "dlom", "type": "number", "unit": "%", "description": "The Discount for Lack of Marketability as a percentage."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    common_stock_price = inputs['common_stock_price']\n    restricted_stock_price = inputs['restricted_stock_price']\n    dlom = (common_stock_price - restricted_stock_price) / common_stock_price * 100\n    return round(dlom, 2)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "dlom_d1", "name": "Common Stock Price Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['common_stock_price'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The price of the common stock must be a positive value."}, {"rule_id": "dlom_d2", "name": "Restricted Stock Price Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['restricted_stock_price'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The price of the restricted stock must be a positive value."}, {"rule_id": "dlom_d3", "name": "Common Stock Price Greater Than Restricted Stock Price for a Discount", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['common_stock_price'] <= inputs['restricted_stock_price']", "applies_to": [], "description": "For a valid Discount for Lack of Marketability, the common stock price is typically expected to be greater than the restricted stock price. If not, it implies a premium, not a discount."}, {"rule_id": "dlom_d4", "name": "DLOM Plausibility Range (30-50%)", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (30 <= compute(inputs) <= 50)", "applies_to": ["dlom"], "description": "Based on studies, the Discount for Lack of Marketability (DLOM) typically ranges between 30% and 50%. This check alerts if the calculated DLOM falls outside this common range."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    common_stock_price = inputs['common_stock_price']\n    restricted_stock_price = inputs['restricted_stock_price']\n    dlom = (common_stock_price - restricted_stock_price) / common_stock_price * 100\n    return round(dlom, 2)"}, "article_title": "Discounts For Lack Of Marketability (DLOM): Role in Valuation", "article_doc_id": 3339, "article_content_excerpt": "# Discounts For Lack Of Marketability (DLOM): Role in Valuation\n\n## What Does Discounts For Lack Of Marketability Mean? \n\nDiscounts for lack of marketability (DLOM) refer to the method used to help calculate the value of closely held and restricted shares. The theory behind DLOM is that a discount exists between a stock that is publicly traded and thus has a market, and the market for privately held stock, which often has little if any marketplace. \n\nVarious methods have been used to quantify the discount that can be applied including the method, method, and the option pricing method. \n\n## Understanding Discounts For Lack Of Marketability (DLOM) \n\nThe restricted stock method purports that the only difference between a company's and its restricted stock is the lack of marketability of the restricted stock. \n\nSubsequently, the price difference between both units should arise due to this lack of marketability. The IPO method relates to the price difference between shares that are sold pre-IPO and post-IPO. The percent difference between the two prices is considered the DLOM using this method. The option pricing method uses the option's price and the strike price of the option as the determinants of the DLOM. The option price as a percentage of the strike price is considered the DLOM under this method. \n\nThe consensus of many studies suggests that the DLOM ranges between 30% to 50%. \n\n## Discounts For Lack Of Marketability Challenges \n\nNoncontrolling, nonmarketable ownership interests in closely held companies pose some unique challenges for valuation analysts. These issues often arise during , estate tax, , income tax, property tax and other taxation disputes. To assist valuators in the field, the offers some guidance, particularly around two related issues that further cloud analysis: Discount for Lack of Liquidity (DLOL) and Discount for Lack of Control (DLOC). \n\nWithout question, selling an interest in a privately held company is a more costly, uncertain and time-consuming process than liquidating a position in a publicly traded entity. An investment in which the owner can achieve liquidity in a timely fashion is worth more than an investment in which the owner cannot sell the investment quickly. As such, privately held companies should sell at a discount to actual intrinsic value because of additional costs, increased uncertainty and longer time horizons tied to selling unconventional securities."}
