abel": "Value is gross (before fees/interest) - DEFAULT", "value": "gross_value", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Value is net (after fees/interest) - implies no further deduction needed", "value": "net_value", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Gross value (fees/interest not deducted)", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}], "inputs": [{"name": "initial_investment", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The initial amount of cash invested by the trader.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "final_value", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The final value of the investment upon selling.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "margin_debt", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The amount of margin debt that needs to be repaid.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "roi", "type": "number", "unit": "percent", "description": "The return on investment expressed as a percentage."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    initial_investment = inputs['initial_investment']\n    final_value = inputs['final_value']\n    margin_debt = inputs['margin_debt']\n    net_profit = final_value - margin_debt - initial_investment\n    roi = net_profit / initial_investment * 100\n    return roi", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "initial_investment_positive", "name": "Initial Investment Positive Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['initial_investment'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Initial investment must be a positive value to calculate ROI."}, {"rule_id": "final_value_non_negative", "name": "Final Value Non-Negative Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['final_value'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Final value of the investment cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "margin_debt_non_negative", "name": "Margin Debt Non-Negative Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['margin_debt'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Margin debt cannot be a negative value."}, {"rule_id": "final_value_covers_margin_debt", "name": "Final Value Covers Margin Debt Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['final_value'] < inputs['margin_debt']", "applies_to": [], "description": "The final value of the investment must be greater than or equal to the margin debt to avoid a deficit before considering initial investment."}, {"rule_id": "regulation_t_initial_margin", "name": "Regulation T Initial Margin Compliance", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['margin_debt'] > inputs['initial_investment']", "applies_to": [], "description": "According to Regulation T, initial margin requires that margin debt generally should not exceed the investor's initial cash investment."}, {"rule_id": "roi_plausibility_check", "name": "ROI Plausibility Range Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "abs(compute(inputs)) > 1000 or compute(inputs) < -90", "applies_to": [], "description": "The calculated ROI is extremely high or low, which may indicate an input error or an unusually volatile investment."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    initial_investment = inputs['initial_investment']\n    final_value = inputs['final_value']\n    margin_debt = inputs['margin_debt']\n    net_profit = final_value - margin_debt - initial_investment\n    roi = net_profit / initial_investment * 100\n    return roi"}, "article_title": "Margin Debt", "article_doc_id": 1557, "article_content_excerpt": "# Margin Debt: Definition, How It Works, and the Pros and Cons of Using It\n\n## What Is Margin Debt? \n\nMargin debt is the a brokerage customer takes on by . \n\nWhen purchasing securities through a , investors have the option of using a cash account and covering the entire cost of the investment themselves, or using a —meaning they borrow part of the initial capital from their broker. The portion that investors borrow is known as margin debt, while the portion they fund themselves is the , or equity. \n\nUsing margin debt has both risks and potential benefits. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Margin debt is the amount of money that an investor borrows from their broker via a margin account.\n * Margin debt can be used to buy securities.\n * Regulation T sets the initial margin at a minimum of 50%, which means an investor can only take on margin debt of 50% of the account balance.\n * Meanwhile, the typical margin requirement at brokerages is 25%, meaning that customers’ equity must stay above that ratio to prevent a margin call.\n * Using margin debt as a form of leverage can magnify gains but also exacerbate losses.\n\n## How Margin Debt Works \n\nAs an example of using margin debt to buy securities, suppose an who we’ll call Sheila wants to buy 1,000 shares of Johnson & Johnson () for $100 per share. She doesn’t want to put down the entire $100,000 at this time, but the Federal Reserve Board’s limits her broker to lending her 50% of the initial investment—also called the initial margin.\n\nShe deposits $50,000 in , while taking on $50,000 in margin debt. The 1,000 shares of Johnson & Johnson that she then purchases act as for this loan. \n\n(Not all brokers would allow Sheila to borrow that much. Brokerages often have their own rules for buying on margin, which can be stricter than those imposed by regulators.) \n\n### Note\n\nExcessive buying on margin is considered one of the causes of the famous . At that time, margin rules were much looser, often allowing investors to borrow 90% of the money to buy stocks and putting down only 10% in cash. We know today how that turned out.\n\n## Advantages and Disadvantages of Margin Debt \n\nBuying on margin has both risks and potential benefits for investors. Generally speaking, it isn’t for beginners or for those who can’t afford to lose money. \n\n### Disadvantages \n\nTwo scenarios illustrate the potential risks and rewards of taking on margin debt. \n\nIn the first, Johnson & Johnson’s price drops to $60. Sheila’s margin debt remains at $50,000, but her equity has fallen to $10,000, which is the value of the stock (1,000 × $60 = $60,000) minus her margin debt of $50,000. The and the exchanges have a requirement of 25%, meaning that customers’ equity must remain above that ratio in margin accounts.\n\nFalling below the maintenance margin requirement triggers a . Unless Sheila deposits another $5,000 in cash to bring her margin up to 25% of the securities’ $60,000 value, or $15,000, the broker is entitled to sell her stock (without notifying her) until her account complies with the rules. This is known as a margin call. \n\nHere again, brokerages may have stricter rules than the law requires, such as setting their maintenance margin requirement at 30% or 40%, for example.\n\nPros\n\n * Allows investor to buy stock with borrowed money\n\n * Investing on margin can magnify any gains because of leverage, resulting in greater profit\n\nCons\n\n * Buying on margin means taking on debt that must be repaid \n\n * If stock loses value, investor may face a margin call and have to come up with cash quickly\n\n### Advantages \n\nA second scenario demonstrates the potential rewards of trading on margin. Say that in the example above, Johnson & Johnson’s share price rises to $150. Sheila’s 1,000 shares are now worth $150,000, with $50,000 of that being margin debt and $100,000 equity. If Sheila sells commission- and fee-free, she receives $100,000 after repaying her broker. Her is equal to 100%—a $50,000 return on her $50,000 cash investment. \n\nNow let’s\n...[truncated]"}
