 for JIBAR) — DEFAULT", "value": "3_month", "is_default": true}, {"label": "1-month term", "value": "1_month", "is_default": false}, {"label": "6-month term", "value": "6_month", "is_default": false}, {"label": "12-month term", "value": "12_month", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "3-month term", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}, {"id": "rate_representation_basis", "ambiguity_type": "rate_representation", "trigger_signal": "Article states JIBAR is calculated as a yield and then converted into a discount. It's unclear which representation the inputs and expected output refer to.", "clarification_question": "Do the input bid/offer rates and the expected JIBAR output represent a yield rate or a discount rate?", "options": [{"label": "Discount rate (JIBAR is typically quoted as a discount rate) — DEFAULT", "value": "discount", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Yield rate", "value": "yield", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Discount rate", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "bid_rates", "type": "array[number]", "required": true, "description": "A list of bid rates (as decimals) from participating banks.", "unit": null, "aliases": ["bids", "bank_bid_rates"]}, {"name": "offer_rates", "type": "array[number]", "required": true, "description": "A list of offer rates (as decimals) from participating banks.", "unit": null, "aliases": ["offers", "bank_offer_rates"]}], "output": {"name": "jibar_rate", "type": "number", "unit": "percent", "description": "The calculated Johannesburg Interbank Average Rate (JIBAR)."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    bid_rates = inputs['bid_rates']\n    offer_rates = inputs['offer_rates']\n    mid_rates = [(bid + offer) / 2 for bid, offer in zip(bid_rates, offer_rates)]\n    mid_rates.sort()\n    trimmed_mid_rates = mid_rates[2:-2]\n    jibar_rate = sum(trimmed_mid_rates) / len(trimmed_mid_rates)\n    return jibar_rate", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "bid_offer_list_length_match", "name": "Bid and Offer Rates List Length Mismatch", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "len(inputs['bid_rates']) != len(inputs['offer_rates'])", "applies_to": ["bid_rates", "offer_rates"], "description": "Ensures that the number of bid rates provided is equal to the number of offer rates to allow for paired calculation."}, {"rule_id": "minimum_rates_count", "name": "Insufficient Number of Rates", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "len(inputs['bid_rates']) < 8", "applies_to": ["bid_rates", "offer_rates"], "description": "Requires at least 8 bid and offer rates from participating banks to align with JIBAR calculation methodology that trims 4 rates."}, {"rule_id": "positive_bid_rates", "name": "Non-positive Bid Rates Detected", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "any(rate <= 0 for rate in inputs['bid_rates'])", "applies_to": ["bid_rates"], "description": "Flags any bid rate that is not positive, as interbank rates are typically positive."}, {"rule_id": "positive_offer_rates", "name": "Non-positive Offer Rates Detected", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "any(rate <= 0 for rate in inputs['offer_rates'])", "applies_to": ["offer_rates"], "description": "Flags any offer rate that is not positive, as interbank rates are typically positive."}, {"rule_id": "bid_rate_less_than_offer_rate", "name": "Bid Rate Exceeds Offer Rate", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "any(bid > offer for bid, offer in zip(inputs['bid_rates'], inputs['offer_rates']))", "applies_to": ["bid_rates", "offer_rates"], "description": "Verifies that each bank's bid rate does not exceed its offer rate, which is standard market practice."}, {"rule_id": "jibar_result_positive", "name": "Calculated JIBAR Rate is Not Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "compute(inputs) <= 0", "applies_to": ["jibar_rate"], "description": "Ensures the final calculated JIBAR rate is positive, reflecting a valid benchmark interest rate."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": false, "error": "division by zero", "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    bid_rates = inputs['bid_rates']\n    offer_rates = inputs['offer_rates']\n    mid_rates = [(bid + offer) / 2 for bid, offer in zip(bid_rates, offer_rates)]\n    mid_rates.sort()\n    trimmed_mid_rates = mid_rates[2:-2]\n    jibar_rate = sum(trimmed_mid_rates) / len(trimmed_mid_rates)\n    return jibar_rate"}, "article_title": "Johannesburg Interbank Average Rate (JIBAR)", "article_doc_id": 4673, "article_content_excerpt": "# Johannesburg Interbank Average Rate (JIBAR) in South Africa\n\n## What Is the Johannesburg Interbank Average Rate (JIBAR)? \n\nThe Johannesburg Interbank Average Rate (JIBAR) is the money market rate that is used in South Africa. The benchmark for short-term loans and instruments, the rate comes in one-month, three-month, six-month, and 12-month discount terms. The 3-month JIBAR rate is the most widely used and accepted. \n\nAn individual or business that seeks to borrow money from a South African bank will typically be quoted a rate tied to the three-month JIBAR, the most commonly used. For example, the rate quoted to a borrower looking to get a mortgage may be ‘JIBAR + 7%.’ As rates in the increase, the also increases, and vice versa. \n\n### key takeaways\n\n * The Johannesburg Interbank Average Rate (JIBAR) is the benchmark for short-term interest rates in South Africa.\n * Derived from the bid and offer rates from eight major banks, JIBAR comes in terms ranging from one to 12 months, with the three-month rate the most commonly used reference.\n * JIBAR rates are used in setting bank certificate of deposit rates, loan rates, and futures contract rates.\n\n## Understanding the Johannesburg Interbank Average Rate (JIBAR) \n\nToday, the Johannesburg Interbank Average Rate (JIBAR) is used as the benchmark for short-term interest rates in the South African markets. It is determined as an average of the borrowing and lending rates indicated by a number of local and international banks. JIBAR is calculated as a yield and then converted into a discount. \n\nThe rate is calculated daily by the Johannesburg Stock Exchange for one-month, three-month, six-month, and 12-month discount terms after all bid and offer rates are received by participating banks. The derived rate is then used by banks to buy and sell their own (NCDs). \n\nThe bid and offer rates used to calculate JIBAR are submitted by eight banks that transact with NCDs of at least 100 million (the South African currency). A mid-rate is calculated as a halfway point between the bid and offer rates provided by contributors. The two highest and two lowest mid-rates are discarded, and the remaining four mid rates are averaged to arrive at JIBAR. \n\nWhile JIBAR represents NCD rates, it also represents, to a lesser extent, the cost of funding in the and the domestic market for fixed bank deposits. \n\n### 6.8%\n\nThe three-month JIBOR as of Jan. 2, 2020\n\n## Johannesburg Interbank Average Rate (JIBAR) and Derivatives \n\nJIBAR is also an important tool in the market. JIBAR Futures (STIR) are short-term interest rate futures contracts which have the three-month Johannesburg Interbank Average Rate as the underlying instrument. This has a value at its expiration of 100 minus the three-month JIBAR rate at the expiry date. The contract is an efficient way to gain exposure to the South African interest rate market and can be utilized by hedgers seeking protection against adverse interest rate movements and speculators hoping to take advantage of short-term movements in interest rates. \n\nThe value of the STIR contract decreases as the expected three-month JIBAR rate at futures expiry increases. When interest rates are expected to go up, an investor or trader will the contract. Investors go the contract when they believe interest rates will decrease at some point in the future. \n\n## Example of the Johannesburg Interbank Average Rate (JIBAR) \n\nThe calculation of a South African reference rate started in the 1990s with the South African Futures Exchange (Safex) Bank Bill rate. The current reference rate system was established in 1999. Prior to November 2012, the acronym stood for the Johannesburg Interbank Agreed Rate. \n\nAccording to the South African Reserve Bank, the three-month JIBOR averaged 8.19% from 1999 until 2020, reaching an all-time high of 16.96% in February 1999 and a record low of 5.06% in September 2012. \n\n### Important: \n\nThe current JIBAR rate is available daily from Thomson Reuters and Bloomberg.\n...[truncated]"}
