fication_question": "Is the 'basis_points' input value a whole number (e.g., 35 for 0.35%) or an already converted decimal (e.g., 0.0035)?", "options": [{"label": "Decimal (e.g., 0.0035) - DEFAULT", "value": "decimal_format", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Whole number (e.g., 35, requiring division by 10000)", "value": "whole_number_format", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "The 'basis_points' input is provided as a decimal (e.g., 0.0035).", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}], "inputs": [{"name": "sofr_changes", "type": "array[number]", "required": true, "description": "A list of annual changes in the SOFR, each entry representing the SOFR's change for one year. Expressed as decimals (e.g., 0.014 for 1.4%).", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "notional_principal", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The notional principal amount over which the swap is executed.", "unit": "USD", "aliases": []}, {"name": "fixed_rate", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The fixed annual interest rate paid by one party. Expressed as a decimal (e.g., 0.025 for 2.5%).", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "basis_points", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The spread in basis points added to the SOFR to calculate the variable rate. Expressed as a decimal (e.g., 0.0035 for 35 basis points).", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "years", "type": "integer", "required": true, "description": "The number of years the swap agreement lasts.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "gains_losses", "type": "number", "unit": "USD", "description": "The total gain or loss for the corporate client (party A) over the swap duration."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    sofr_changes = inputs['sofr_changes']\n    notional_principal = inputs['notional_principal']\n    fixed_rate = inputs['fixed_rate']\n    basis_points = inputs['basis_points']\n    years = inputs['years']\n    if len(sofr_changes) != years:\n        raise ValueError('The length of sofr_changes must match the number of years.')\n    party_A_gains_losses = []\n    for year in range(years):\n        variable_rate = sofr_changes[year] + basis_points\n        variable_payment = notional_principal * variable_rate\n        fixed_payment = notional_principal * fixed_rate\n        party_A_gains_losses.append(variable_payment - fixed_payment)\n    return sum(party_A_gains_losses)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "dc001", "name": "Notional Principal Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['notional_principal'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["notional_principal"], "description": "The notional principal amount must be a positive value."}, {"rule_id": "dc002", "name": "Fixed Rate Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['fixed_rate'] < 0", "applies_to": ["fixed_rate"], "description": "The fixed interest rate cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "dc003", "name": "Basis Points Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['basis_points'] < 0", "applies_to": ["basis_points"], "description": "The basis points spread cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "dc004", "name": "Years Positive Integer", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (isinstance(inputs['years'], int) and inputs['years'] > 0)", "applies_to": ["years"], "description": "The number of years must be a positive integer."}, {"rule_id": "dc005", "name": "SOFR Changes Length Matches Years", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "len(inputs['sofr_changes']) != inputs['years']", "applies_to": ["sofr_changes", "years"], "description": "The number of annual SOFR changes provided must exactly match the total number of years for the swap."}, {"rule_id": "dc006", "name": "SOFR Changes Elements Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "any(s < 0 for s in inputs['sofr_changes'])", "applies_to": ["sofr_changes"], "description": "Individual SOFR change values should typically be non-negative. Negative values may indicate unusual market conditions or input errors."}, {"rule_id": "dc007", "name": "Rates Plausibility (Decimal Format)", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (0 <= inputs['fixed_rate'] <= 1) or not (0 <= inputs['basis_points'] <= 0.01) or any(not (0 <= s <= 1) for s in inputs['sofr_changes'])", "applies_to": ["fixed_rate", "basis_points", "sofr_changes"], "description": "Interest rates (fixed rate, basis points, SOFR changes) are expected to be provided in decimal format (e.g., 0.05 for 5%). Values outside the [0, 1] range (or [0, 0.01] for basis points) might indicate incorrect scaling (e.g., entered as percentage)."}, {"rule_id": "dc008", "name": "SOFR Changes List Structure", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['sofr_changes'], list) and all(isinstance(x, (int, float)) for x in inputs['sofr_changes'])", "applies_to": ["sofr_changes"], "description": "The 'sofr_changes' input must be a list where each element is a number (integer or float)."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    sofr_changes = inputs['sofr_changes']\n    notional_principal = inputs['notional_principal']\n    fixed_rate = inputs['fixed_rate']\n    basis_points = inputs['basis_points']\n    years = inputs['years']\n    if len(sofr_changes) != years:\n        raise ValueError('The length of sofr_changes must match the number of years.')\n    party_A_gains_losses = []\n    for year in range(years):\n        variable_rate = sofr_changes[year] + basis_points\n        variable_payment = notional_principal * variable_rate\n        fixed_payment = notional_principal * fixed_rate\n        party_A_gains_losses.append(variable_payment - fixed_payment)\n    return sum(party_A_gains_losses)"}, "article_title": "Swap", "article_doc_id": 5406, "article_content_excerpt": "# Swap Definition and How to Calculate Gains\n\n## What Is a Swap? \n\nA swap is a derivative contract through which two parties exchange the cash flows or liabilities from two different financial instruments. Most swaps involve cash flows based on a notional principal amount related to a loan or bond, although the security can be almost anything. Usually, the principal does not change hands. \n\nEach cash flow comprises one leg of the swap. One cash flow is generally fixed, while the other is variable and based on a benchmark interest rate, floating currency exchange rate, or index price. \n\nThe most common kind of swap is an interest rate swap. Swaps do not trade on typical exchanges, and generally, retail investors do not engage in them. Rather, swaps are transacted over the counter (OTC) or on security-based Swap Execution Facilities (SEFs). They occur primarily between businesses or financial institutions.\n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * A swap is a contract that involves the exchange of related to a financial security.\n * are the most commonly used swaps and usually involve a fixed interest rate and a variable interest rate.\n * Credit default swaps contributed to the causes of the 2008 financial crisis.\n * Institutions evaluate their outlooks for, e.g., interest rate movements, when they consider entering into an interest rate swap.\n * SOFR has replaced LIBOR as the benchmark short-term rate index used in some swaps. \n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/Term-Definitions_swap-27b93a31e83c423a854db04030a67673.jpg)\n\nJessica Olah / Investopedia\n\n## Understanding Swaps \n\nIn an interest rate swap, the parties to the contract exchange cash flows based on a of an underlying security. The amount of the principal is not actually exchanged. But the cash flows related to the interest rates are. Also, the swap can be an , where the underlying principal of a loan will decrease over time.\n\nParties undertake swaps in order to (protect against) or to . For example, imagine that ABC Co. has just issued $1 million in five-year bonds with a variable annual interest rate defined as the plus 1.3% (or 130 basis points). Also, assume that the SOFR is at 2.5% and ABC’s management is anxious about an interest rate rise. \n\nThe management team finds another company, XYZ Inc., that is willing to pay ABC an annual rate of the SOFR​ plus 1.3% on a notional principal amount of $1 million for five years. In other words, XYZ will fund ABC’s interest payments on its latest bond issue. \n\nIn exchange, ABC agrees to pay XYZ a fixed annual rate of 5% on a notional value of $1 million for five years. ABC will benefit from the swap if rates rise significantly over the next five years. XYZ will benefit if rates fall, stay flat, or rise only gradually. \n\n### Important: \n\nLIBOR is no longer used as a benchmark index rate for short-term loans between financial institutions. It will cease publication of rates on Sept. 30, 2024. The benchmark index now used is the Secured Overnight Financing Rate (SOFR) and its one-month, six-month, and nine-month extensions.\n\n## Calculations of Gains or Losses \n\nBelow are two scenarios for the interest rate swap described above. In the first scenario, the SOFR rises 0.75% per year. In the second scenario, the SOFR rises 0.25% per year. Remember, XYZ Inc. has agreed to make an annual payment to the ABC company in the amount of the SOFR plus 1.3% on a principal amount of $1 million for five years. ABC has agreed to pay XYZ an annual amount equal to 5% of $1 million for that time period. \n\n### Scenario 1 \n\nAs the SOFR rises by 0.75% per year, ABC’s total interest payments to its bondholders over the five-year period (and paid by XYZ) amount to $265,000. But thanks to the swap, that figure is offset by a $15,000 gain. Let’s break down the calculation: \n \n<table> \n<tr> \n<td>\n\n</td> \n<td>\n\n**LIBOR + 1.30%**\n</td> \n<td>\n\n**Variable Interest Paid by XYZ to ABC**\n</td> \n<td>\n\n**5% Interest Paid by ABC to XYZ**\n</td> \n<td>\n\n**ABC’s Gain/Loss**\n</td> \n<td>\n\n*\n...[truncated]"}
