 "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "tax_rate", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "Corporate tax rate (Tc) represented as a decimal (e.g., 0.30 for 30%).", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "wacc", "type": "number", "unit": "decimal", "description": "The Weighted Average Cost of Capital."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    market_value_equity = inputs['market_value_equity']\n    market_value_debt = inputs['market_value_debt']\n    cost_of_equity = inputs['cost_of_equity']\n    cost_of_debt = inputs['cost_of_debt']\n    tax_rate = inputs['tax_rate']\n    total_value = market_value_equity + market_value_debt\n    equity_weight = market_value_equity / total_value\n    debt_weight = market_value_debt / total_value\n    wacc = equity_weight * cost_of_equity + debt_weight * cost_of_debt * (1 - tax_rate)\n    return wacc", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "wacc_mve_001", "name": "Market Value of Equity must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['market_value_equity'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The market value of equity cannot be negative as it represents an ownership stake."}, {"rule_id": "wacc_mvd_001", "name": "Market Value of Debt must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['market_value_debt'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The market value of debt cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "wacc_coe_001", "name": "Cost of Equity must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['cost_of_equity'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The cost of equity cannot be negative; it represents the return required by equity investors."}, {"rule_id": "wacc_cod_001", "name": "Cost of Debt must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['cost_of_debt'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The cost of debt cannot be negative; it represents the return required by debt holders."}, {"rule_id": "wacc_tr_001", "name": "Tax Rate must be between 0 and 1 (inclusive)", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (0 <= inputs['tax_rate'] <= 1)", "applies_to": [], "description": "The tax rate must be a value between 0 (0%) and 1 (100%) when expressed as a decimal."}, {"rule_id": "wacc_tcv_001", "name": "Total market value of capital must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['market_value_equity'] + inputs['market_value_debt'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The sum of market value of equity and debt must be positive to calculate WACC, preventing division by zero."}, {"rule_id": "wacc_coe_002", "name": "Cost of Equity plausibility check (decimal)", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['cost_of_equity'] > 1", "applies_to": [], "description": "Cost of equity is typically expressed as a decimal (e.g., 0.09 for 9%). A value greater than 1 might indicate it was entered as a percentage without conversion."}, {"rule_id": "wacc_cod_002", "name": "Cost of Debt plausibility check (decimal)", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['cost_of_debt'] > 1", "applies_to": [], "description": "Cost of debt is typically expressed as a decimal (e.g., 0.05 for 5%). A value greater than 1 might indicate it was entered as a percentage without conversion."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    market_value_equity = inputs['market_value_equity']\n    market_value_debt = inputs['market_value_debt']\n    cost_of_equity = inputs['cost_of_equity']\n    cost_of_debt = inputs['cost_of_debt']\n    tax_rate = inputs['tax_rate']\n    total_value = market_value_equity + market_value_debt\n    equity_weight = market_value_equity / total_value\n    debt_weight = market_value_debt / total_value\n    wacc = equity_weight * cost_of_equity + debt_weight * cost_of_debt * (1 - tax_rate)\n    return wacc"}, "article_title": "Financing", "article_doc_id": 1024, "article_content_excerpt": "# Financing: What It Means and Why It Matters\n\n## What Is Financing? \n\nFinancing is the process of providing funds for , making purchases, or investing. , such as banks, are in the business of providing capital to businesses, consumers, and investors to help them achieve their goals. The use of financing is vital in any economic system, as it allows companies to purchase products out of their immediate reach. \n\nPut differently, financing is a way to leverage the to put future expected money flows to use for projects started today. Financing also takes advantage of the fact that some individuals in an economy will have a surplus of money that they wish to put to work to generate returns, while others demand money to undertake investment (also with the hope of generating returns), creating a market for money. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Financing is the process of funding business activities, making purchases, or investments.\n * There are two types of financing: equity financing and debt financing.\n * The main advantage of equity financing is that there is no obligation to repay the money acquired through it. Equity financing places no additional financial burden on the company, though the downside is quite large.\n * Debt financing tends to be cheaper and comes with tax breaks. However, large debt burdens can lead to default and credit risk.\n * The weighted average cost of capital (WACC) gives a clear picture of a firm's total cost of financing.\n\n## Understanding Financing \n\nThere are two main types of financing available for companies: and . Debt is a loan that must be paid back often with interest, but it is typically cheaper than raising capital because of tax deduction considerations. Equity does not need to be paid back, but it relinquishes ownership stakes to the shareholder. Both debt and equity have their . \n\n### Important: \n\nMost companies use a combination of both debt and equity to finance operations.\n\n## Types of Financing \n\n### Equity Financing \n\n\"\" is another word for ownership in a company. For example, the owner of a grocery store chain needs to grow operations. Instead of debt, the owner would like to sell a 10% stake in the company for $100,000, valuing the firm at $1 million. Companies like to sell equity because the investor bears all the risk; if the business fails, the investor gets nothing.\n\nAt the same time, giving up equity is giving up some control. Equity investors want to have a say in how the company is operated, especially in difficult times, and are often entitled to votes based on the number of shares held. So, in exchange for ownership, an investor gives their money to a company and receives some claim on future earnings. \n\nSome investors are happy with growth in the form of share price ; they want the share price to go up. Other investors are looking for principal protection and income in the form of regular . \n\n### Advantages of Equity Financing \n\nFunding your business through investors has several advantages, including the following: \n\n * The biggest advantage is that you do not have to pay back the money. If your business enters , your investor or investors are not . They are part-owners in your company, and because of that, their money is lost along with your company.\n * You do not have to make monthly payments, so there is often more cash on hand for operating expenses.\n * Investors understand that it takes time to build a business. You will get the money you need without the pressure of having to see your product or business thriving within a short amount of time.\n\n### Disadvantages of Equity Financing \n\nSimilarly, there are a number of disadvantages that come with equity financing, including the following: \n\n * How do you feel about having a new partner? When you raise equity financing, it involves giving up ownership of a portion of your company. The riskier the investment, the more of a stake the investor will want. You might have to give up 50% or more of your company, and unless you later\n...[truncated]"}
