as a general decrease, or specifically as a 'dilutive' deal?", "options": [{"label": "General decrease in EPS (negative percentage) - DEFAULT", "value": "general_decrease", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Signifies a dilutive deal", "value": "dilutive_deal", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "A negative result signifies a general decrease in EPS.", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "eps_before", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The earnings per share (EPS) before the deal.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "eps_after", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The earnings per share (EPS) after the deal.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "increase_percentage", "type": "number", "unit": "percent", "description": "The percentage increase in EPS due to the deal."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    eps_before = inputs['eps_before']\n    eps_after = inputs['eps_after']\n    if eps_before <= 0 or eps_after <= 0:\n        pass\n    increase_percentage = (eps_after - eps_before) / eps_before * 100\n    return increase_percentage", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "eps_before_positive", "name": "EPS Before Deal Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['eps_before'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["eps_before"], "description": "The earnings per share before the deal (eps_before) must be a positive number to perform a meaningful percentage increase calculation and avoid division by zero."}, {"rule_id": "eps_after_positive", "name": "EPS After Deal Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['eps_after'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["eps_after"], "description": "The earnings per share after the deal (eps_after) must be a positive number for a meaningful calculation."}, {"rule_id": "accretive_deal_expected", "name": "Accretive Deal Expected", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "compute(inputs) < 0", "applies_to": ["eps_before", "eps_after"], "description": "The calculated result is a negative percentage, indicating a decrease in EPS. While mathematically correct, for an 'accretive deal increase' function, this suggests the deal might be dilutive, which might not be the user's intent or expectation."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    eps_before = inputs['eps_before']\n    eps_after = inputs['eps_after']\n    if eps_before <= 0 or eps_after <= 0:\n        pass\n    increase_percentage = (eps_after - eps_before) / eps_before * 100\n    return increase_percentage"}, "article_title": "Accretive", "article_doc_id": 4375, "article_content_excerpt": "# Accretive: Definition and Examples in Business and Finance\n\n## What is Accretive? \n\nIn both finance and in general lexicon, the term \"accretive\" is the adjective form of the word \"\", which refers to gradual or incremental growth. For example, an acquisition deal may be deemed accretive for the absorbing company, if that deal contributes to an increase in . \n\nBy definition, in corporate finance, of assets or businesses must ultimately add more value to a company, than the expenditures associated with the acquisition. This can be due to the fact that the newly-acquired assets in question are purchased at a discount to their perceived , or if the assets are expected to grow, as a direct result of the transaction. \n\nKey Takeaways \n\\--The term \"accretive\" is an adjective that refers to business deals that result in gradual or incremental growth in value for a company. \n\\--In corporate finance, accretive acquisitions of assets must add more value to a company, than the costs of acquiring the target entity, \n\\--Accretive deals can occur if acquired assets are purchased at a discount to their perceived current market value. \n\\--In general finance, accretive investments refer to any security that is purchased at a discount. \n\n## Breaking Down Accretive \n\nIn general finance, accretion refers to the change in the price of a bond or security. In fixed-income investments, the word accretive may be used to describe the increase in value attributable to interest accrued but not paid. For example, discounted bonds earn interest through accretion, until they reach maturity. In such cases, acquired bonds are acquired when compared to the value of the bond, also known as the par. As the bond matures, the value increases, based on the that was in effect at the time of issuance. \n\n## Determining the Rate of Accretion \n\nThe rate of accretion is determined by dividing the discount by the number of years in the term. In the case of zero bonds, the interest acquired is not . While the value of the bond increases based on the agreed-upon interest rate, it must be held for the agreed-upon term, before it can be cashed out. \n\n## Examples of Accretion \n\nIf a person purchases a bond with a value of $1,000, for the discounted price of $750, with the understanding that it will be held for 10 years, the deal is considered accretive, because the bond pays out the initial investment, plus interest. Depending on the type of bond purchased, interest may be paid out at regular intervals (annually, semi-annually, etc.), or it may be paid in lump sum, upon maturity. \n\nWith zero coupon bonds, there is no interest accrual. Instead, it is purchased at a discount, such as the initial $750 investment for a bond with a face value of $1,000. The bond pays the value, also known as the , of $1,000, in a lump sum upon maturity. \n\nIn corporate finance acquisition deals are often accretive. First, let's assume that the earnings per share of Corporation X is listed as $100, and earnings per share of Corporation Y is listed as $50. When Corporation X acquires Corporation Y, Corporations X’s earnings per share increase to $150--rendering this a 50% accretive deal. \n\n**[Important: The antonym to \"accretive\" is \"dilutive\", which describes any deal which causes a corporation's earnings per share value to drop.]**"}
