he tax rate and fees/expenses rate provided as decimals (e.g., 0.02) or percentages (e.g., 2%)?", "options": [{"label": "Decimal (e.g., 0.02) - DEFAULT", "value": "decimal", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Percentage (e.g., 2%)", "value": "percentage", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Rates are provided as decimals.", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}], "inputs": [{"name": "gross_dividend", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The total gross dividend amount received before deductions.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "tax_rate", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The tax rate applied to the dividend (as a decimal, e.g., 0.35 for 35%). Should be the effective tax rate considering ordinary or qualified status.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "fees_and_expenses_rate", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The total rate of fees and expenses applied to the dividend (as a decimal, e.g., 0.02 for 2%).", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "net_dividend", "type": "number", "unit": null, "description": "The net amount of the dividend after taxes and fees are deducted."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    gross_dividend = inputs['gross_dividend']\n    tax_rate = inputs['tax_rate']\n    fees_and_expenses_rate = inputs['fees_and_expenses_rate']\n    tax_deduction = gross_dividend * tax_rate\n    fee_deduction = gross_dividend * fees_and_expenses_rate\n    net_dividend = gross_dividend - tax_deduction - fee_deduction\n    return round(net_dividend)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "gd1", "name": "Gross Dividend must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "inputs['gross_dividend'] >= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The gross dividend amount cannot be negative. Please provide a non-negative value for gross_dividend."}, {"rule_id": "tr1", "name": "Tax Rate must be between 0 and 1 (inclusive)", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "0 <= inputs['tax_rate'] <= 1", "applies_to": [], "description": "The tax rate must be expressed as a decimal between 0 and 1. If it is a percentage, convert it to decimal (e.g., 28% -> 0.28)."}, {"rule_id": "fe1", "name": "Fees and Expenses Rate must be between 0 and 1 (inclusive)", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "0 <= inputs['fees_and_expenses_rate'] <= 1", "applies_to": [], "description": "The fees and expenses rate must be expressed as a decimal between 0 and 1. If it is a percentage, convert it to decimal (e.g., 1.5% -> 0.015)."}, {"rule_id": "trfe1", "name": "Combined Deduction Rates should not exceed 100%", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "(inputs['tax_rate'] + inputs['fees_and_expenses_rate']) > 1", "applies_to": [], "description": "The sum of the tax rate and fees/expenses rate should not exceed 1 (or 100%). If it does, the net dividend would be negative, indicating an input error."}, {"rule_id": "tr2", "name": "Tax Rate might be a percentage (e.g., 28 instead of 0.28)", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['tax_rate'] > 1 and inputs['tax_rate'] <= 100", "applies_to": [], "description": "The tax rate provided is greater than 1 but less than or equal to 100. This often indicates it was entered as a percentage (e.g., 28 for 28%) instead of a decimal (0.28). Consider dividing by 100 if it's a percentage."}, {"rule_id": "fe2", "name": "Fees and Expenses Rate might be a percentage (e.g., 1.5 instead of 0.015)", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['fees_and_expenses_rate'] > 1 and inputs['fees_and_expenses_rate'] <= 100", "applies_to": [], "description": "The fees and expenses rate provided is greater than 1 but less than or equal to 100. This often indicates it was entered as a percentage (e.g., 1.5 for 1.5%) instead of a decimal (0.015). Consider dividing by 100 if it's a percentage."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    gross_dividend = inputs['gross_dividend']\n    tax_rate = inputs['tax_rate']\n    fees_and_expenses_rate = inputs['fees_and_expenses_rate']\n    tax_deduction = gross_dividend * tax_rate\n    fee_deduction = gross_dividend * fees_and_expenses_rate\n    net_dividend = gross_dividend - tax_deduction - fee_deduction\n    return round(net_dividend)"}, "article_title": "Gross Dividends", "article_doc_id": 2389, "article_content_excerpt": "# Gross Dividends: Meaning, How They Work, Example\n\n## What Are Gross Dividends? \n\nSimilar in concept to gross income, gross dividends are the sum total of all dividends received by an investor for tax purposes. Gross dividends include all that are paid, plus capital-gains distributions and received by the taxpayer during the year before taxes, fees, and expenses are deducted. \n\nGross dividends can be contrasted with net dividends. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Gross dividends, for tax purposes, include all ordinary dividends plus capital gains distributions and non-taxable distributions.\n * Gross dividends will be adjusted for the presence of qualified dividends as well as any associated fees and expenses of receiving dividends.\n * Taxpayers use IRS form 1099-DIV to calculate their taxable exposure to dividend and related investment income.\n\n## Understanding Gross Dividends \n\nMost of the time, gross dividends paid to American investors are reported on IRS . Ordinary dividends are reported in Box 1a, while the other types of dividend income are listed elsewhere. All dividends are considered ordinary unless they are specifically classified as . Box 1b is designated for reporting qualified dividends, which shows the portion of the amount in Box 1a that may be eligible for reduced capital gains rates. Box 3 shows non-dividend distributions.\n\nA 1099-DIV is required to be sent to anyone who has received dividends (including capital gain dividends and exempt-interest dividends) and other distributions on stock of ten dollars or more, or if funds were withheld to pay foreign tax on dividends and other distributions on stock over a given year. Not all dividend income reported on the 1099-DIV is reported on Schedule B.\n\nIn many countries, income from dividends is treated at a more favorable tax rate than ordinary income. Investors may look to dividend-paying stocks in order to take advantage of potentially more favorable tax conditions. The amount of tax owed on dividends depends on overall income and whether the dividends are qualified or nonqualified. \n\n## Example of a Gross Dividend Versus a Net Dividend \n\nAs an example, let's say that company ABCXYZ decides to issue a dividend of $1.20 to its shareholders. This means for each share owned, the company pays $1.20 in dividends. If a shareholder-owned 1,000 shares, they would receive an annual payout of $1,200 in gross dividends. Companies in the U.S. typically pay quarterly dividends, while non-U.S. companies generally pay annual or semi-annual dividends. \n\nIf the dividend was considered an ordinary one and taxed at a rate of 35%, with another 2% going toward fees and expenses, the net dividend would actually be $756. If the dividend was a qualified one instead, with a reduced tax rate of 15%, the net dividend would actually be $996."}
