rue, "description": "The initial principal amount of the mortgage.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "annual_interest_rate", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The annual interest rate as a decimal (e.g., 0.05 for 5%).", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "period", "type": "integer", "required": true, "description": "The total number of periods (months) over which payments are made.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "monthly_payout", "type": "number", "unit": "dollar", "description": "The monthly payout amount for the MBS investors, consisting of principal and interest."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    principal = inputs['principal']\n    annual_interest_rate = inputs['annual_interest_rate']\n    period = inputs['period']\n    monthly_interest_rate = annual_interest_rate / 12\n    if monthly_interest_rate <= 0:\n        raise ValueError('Annual interest rate must be positive.')\n    monthly_payout = principal * monthly_interest_rate / (1 - (1 + monthly_interest_rate) ** (-period))\n    return round(monthly_payout, 2)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "principal_positive", "name": "Principal amount must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['principal'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The principal amount of the mortgage must be a positive value."}, {"rule_id": "annual_interest_rate_positive", "name": "Annual interest rate must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['annual_interest_rate'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The annual interest rate must be a positive value to calculate a meaningful payout."}, {"rule_id": "period_positive_integer", "name": "Period must be a positive integer", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not isinstance(inputs['period'], int) or inputs['period'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The total number of periods (months) must be a positive integer."}, {"rule_id": "annual_interest_rate_plausibility", "name": "Annual interest rate plausibility check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['annual_interest_rate'] > 1.0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The annual interest rate appears unusually high (above 100%). Please confirm if it is expressed as a decimal or percentage."}, {"rule_id": "period_plausibility", "name": "Period plausibility check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['period'] > 600", "applies_to": [], "description": "The total number of periods (months) seems unusually long (over 50 years). Please confirm the unit or value."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    principal = inputs['principal']\n    annual_interest_rate = inputs['annual_interest_rate']\n    period = inputs['period']\n    monthly_interest_rate = annual_interest_rate / 12\n    if monthly_interest_rate <= 0:\n        raise ValueError('Annual interest rate must be positive.')\n    monthly_payout = principal * monthly_interest_rate / (1 - (1 + monthly_interest_rate) ** (-period))\n    return round(monthly_payout, 2)"}, "article_title": "Vintage", "article_doc_id": 468, "article_content_excerpt": "# Vintage: What it is, How it Works, Special Considerations\n\n## What Is Vintage? \n\nVintage is a slang term used by (MBS) traders and investors to refer to an MBS that is seasoned over some time period. An MBS typically has a of around 30 years, and a particular issue's \"vintage\" exposes the holder to less prepayment and default risk, although this decreased risk also limits price appreciation. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Vintage is a colloquial term used to describe mortgage-backed securities (MBS) that have been \"seasoned.\" \n * That is, they've been issued long enough, and enough on-time payments have been made, that the risk of default is lower.\n * Vintage is the age of an item as it relates to the year it was created. It's a way to assess the inherent risk of an MBS. \n * Two MBS with the same vintage may have different levels of assumed risk, however, and as a result, different perceived values. \n\n## How Vintage Works \n\nThe underlying loans of certain vintage MBS have unique characteristics, such as , that make the vintage trade at a premium price. These unique characteristics are a result of how underlying assets in MBS are pooled. MBS' underlying assets are generally grouped across certain geographical regions with similar terms to and interest rates. This makes forecasting payment plans more predictable. \n\nMBS are predominantly issued by a U.S. (GSE). The investments are comprised of the debt obligations associated with groups of mortgage loans, predominantly residential property loans. The security, representing a particular claim against the principal and interest payments owed by borrowers, is then issued by the creating entity. MBS are traded on the secondary market.\n\n## Vintage as Applied to MBS \n\nThe term vintage relates to the age of an item as it relates to the year it was created. If an item was created in 2012, then the is 2012, and its age can be determined by subtracting the vintage year from the current year. \n\nThe variation in the vintages of particular MBS may represent different levels of risk to investors. With the U.S. subprime mortgage crisis that began in 2007, for example, lenders had started originating large numbers of high-risk mortgages from around 2004 to 2007. Loans from those vintage years displayed higher , and were, therefore, riskier, than loans made before and after. \n\n## Special Considerations \n\nWhile the vintage may be one factor used to determine the of a certain MBS, other factors are also considered. In this case, two MBS with the same vintage may have different levels of assumed risk and, therefore, may have different . Some additional factors include the remaining value of the mortgage pool, the current market value of the properties backing the mortgages and the accrued interest. \n\nAn MBS schedule varies from many other investment vehicles. While bonds may pay semiannually, annually or at the previously agreed-upon , an MBS pays out to investors on a monthly basis. While a bond payment may only include the earned interest until the maturity date, where a lump sum of the original principal is returned, MBS provide monthly payments of both interest and a portion of the principal. The monthly payment required correlates to the traditional payment schedule of mortgage debtors."}
