r", "required": true, "description": "The selling price per unit.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "variable_cost_per_unit", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The variable cost per unit.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "fixed_operating_costs", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "Total fixed operating costs.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "degree_of_operating_leverage", "type": "number", "unit": null, "description": "The degree of operating leverage (DOL), indicating sensitivity of operating income to sales changes."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    unit_quantity = inputs['unit_quantity']\n    unit_price = inputs['unit_price']\n    variable_cost_per_unit = inputs['variable_cost_per_unit']\n    fixed_operating_costs = inputs['fixed_operating_costs']\n    contribution_margin = unit_price - variable_cost_per_unit\n    total_contribution = unit_quantity * contribution_margin\n    operating_income = total_contribution - fixed_operating_costs\n    if operating_income == 0:\n        raise ValueError('Operating income (total contribution minus fixed costs) must not be zero.')\n    dol = total_contribution / operating_income\n    return dol", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "unit_quantity_required", "name": "Unit Quantity Missing", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs.get('unit_quantity') is None", "applies_to": ["unit_quantity"], "description": "The 'unit_quantity' input is required but was not provided."}, {"rule_id": "unit_price_required", "name": "Unit Price Missing", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs.get('unit_price') is None", "applies_to": ["unit_price"], "description": "The 'unit_price' input is required but was not provided."}, {"rule_id": "variable_cost_per_unit_required", "name": "Variable Cost Per Unit Missing", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs.get('variable_cost_per_unit') is None", "applies_to": ["variable_cost_per_unit"], "description": "The 'variable_cost_per_unit' input is required but was not provided."}, {"rule_id": "fixed_operating_costs_required", "name": "Fixed Operating Costs Missing", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs.get('fixed_operating_costs') is None", "applies_to": ["fixed_operating_costs"], "description": "The 'fixed_operating_costs' input is required but was not provided."}, {"rule_id": "unit_quantity_positive", "name": "Unit Quantity Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['unit_quantity'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["unit_quantity"], "description": "The number of units sold ('unit_quantity') must be a positive value."}, {"rule_id": "unit_price_positive", "name": "Unit Price Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['unit_price'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["unit_price"], "description": "The selling price per unit ('unit_price') must be a positive value."}, {"rule_id": "variable_cost_per_unit_less_than_unit_price", "name": "Variable Cost Must Be Less Than Unit Price", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['variable_cost_per_unit'] >= inputs['unit_price']", "applies_to": ["variable_cost_per_unit", "unit_price"], "description": "The variable cost per unit must be less than the unit price to ensure a positive contribution margin."}, {"rule_id": "operating_income_not_zero", "name": "Operating Income Must Not Be Zero", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "(inputs['unit_quantity'] * (inputs['unit_price'] - inputs['variable_cost_per_unit'])) - inputs['fixed_operating_costs'] == 0", "applies_to": ["unit_quantity", "unit_price", "variable_cost_per_unit", "fixed_operating_costs"], "description": "Operating income (total contribution margin minus fixed operating costs) cannot be zero, as it would lead to an undefined degree of operating leverage."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    unit_quantity = inputs['unit_quantity']\n    unit_price = inputs['unit_price']\n    variable_cost_per_unit = inputs['variable_cost_per_unit']\n    fixed_operating_costs = inputs['fixed_operating_costs']\n    contribution_margin = unit_price - variable_cost_per_unit\n    total_contribution = unit_quantity * contribution_margin\n    operating_income = total_contribution - fixed_operating_costs\n    if operating_income == 0:\n        raise ValueError('Operating income (total contribution minus fixed costs) must not be zero.')\n    dol = total_contribution / operating_income\n    return dol"}, "article_title": "Operating Leverage", "article_doc_id": 6155, "article_content_excerpt": "# Operating Leverage: What It Is, How It Works, How to Calculate\n\n## What Is Operating Leverage? \n\nOperating leverage is a cost-accounting formula (a financial ratio) that measures the degree to which a firm or project can increase operating income by increasing revenue. A business that generates sales with a high and low variable costs has high operating leverage. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * The operating leverage ratio is used to calculate a company’s break-even point and help set appropriate selling prices to cover all costs and generate a profit.\n * Companies with high operating leverage must cover a larger amount of fixed costs each month regardless of whether they sell any units of product.\n * Low-operating-leverage companies may have high costs that vary directly with their sales but have lower fixed costs to cover each month.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/operatingleverage_sourcefile-edit-0b331034cca9406dafbc155d26458594.jpg)\n\nInvestopedia / NoNo Flores\n\n## Understanding Operating Leverage \n\nThe higher the , the greater the potential danger from forecasting risk, in which a relatively small error in forecasting sales can be magnified into large errors in . \n\n### The Operating Leverage Formula Is: \n\n\\text{Degree of operating leverage} = \\frac{\\text{Contribution margin}}{\\text{Profit}}\n\nThis can be restated as: \n\n\\begin{aligned} &\\text{Degree of operating leverage} = \\frac{Q*CM}{Q*CM - \\text{Fixed operating costs}}\\\\\\ &\\textbf{where:}\\\\\\ &Q = \\text{unit quantity}\\\\\\ &CM = \\text{contribution margin (price - variable cost per unit)}\\\\\\ \\end{aligned}\n\nThe operating leverage formula is used to calculate a company’s break-even point and help set appropriate selling prices to cover all costs and generate a profit. The formula can reveal how well a , such as its warehouse, machinery, and equipment, to generate profits. The more profit a company can squeeze out of the same amount of fixed assets, the higher its operating leverage.\n\nOne conclusion companies can learn from examining operating leverage is that firms that minimize fixed costs can increase their profits without making any changes to the selling price, contribution margin, or the number of units they sell. \n\n## Example Of Operating Leverage \n\nFor example, Company A sells 500,000 products for a unit price of $6 each. The company’s fixed costs are $800,000. It costs $0.05 in per unit to make each product.\n\nCalculate company A’s degree of operating leverage as follows:\n\n\\begin{aligned} &\\frac{500,000*\\left(\\$6.00 - \\$0.05 \\right )}{500,000*\\left(\\$6.00 - \\$0.05 \\right )-\\$800,000}\\\\\\ &=\\frac{\\$2,975,000}{\\$2,175,000}\\\\\\ &=1.37 \\text{ or } 137\\%. \\end{aligned}\n\nA 10% revenue increase should result in a 13.7% increase in operating income (10% x 1.37 = 13.7%). \n\n## High and Low Operating Leverage \n\nIt is important to compare operating leverage between companies in the same industry, as some industries have higher fixed costs than others. The concept of a high or low ratio is then more clearly defined. \n\nMost of a company’s costs are that recur each month, such as rent, regardless of sales volume. As long as a business earns a substantial profit on each sale and sustains adequate sales volume, fixed costs are covered, and profits are earned. \n\nOther company costs are variable costs that are only incurred when sales occur. This includes labor to assemble products and the cost of raw materials used to make products. Some companies earn less profit on each sale but can have a lower sales volume and still generate enough to cover fixed costs. \n\n### Important: \n\nOne concept positively linked to operating leverage is capacity utilization, which is how much the company uses its resources to generate revenues. Increasing utilization infers increased production and sales; thus, variable costs should rise. If fixed costs remain the same, a firm will have high operating leverage while operating at a higher capacity.\n\nFor example, a software business has greater fixed costs in develop\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_1633", "name": "Death Taxes", "short_description": "Calculates the estate tax liability for an estate based on its total value, an exclusion amount, a base tax rate applied to the taxable portion, and an additional base tax.", "domain": "personal_finance", "topic": "taxcalc", "topic_extension": false, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-1633", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-529", "question_id": "test-1561", "difficulty": 2.995732273553991, "level": "medium", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "1d9dffbe16477c93926ed89fdf4d05f64b88fdc34094c1fb30be18e7abdba8ff", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["estate tax", "inheritance tax", "death tax", "tax liability", "estate valuation", "exclusion amount", "tax rate", "base tax", "death duties", "federal estate tax"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "base_tax_rate_scale", "ambiguity_type": "unit_scale", "trigger_signal": "base_tax_rate value appears to be a decimal (e.g., 0.X) when a percentage (e.g., X) is expected, or vice versa.", "clarification_question": "Is the base_tax_rate provided as a percentage (e.g., 40 for 40%) or as a decimal (e.g., 0.40 for 40%)?", "options": [{"label": "Percentage (e.g., 40 for 40%) — DEFAULT", "value": "percentage_input", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Decimal (e.g., 0.40 for 40%)", "value": "decimal_input", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "(result - base_tax) * 100 + base_tax", "max_expr_nodes": 14, "invariant": "result_new - base_tax == (result_old - base_tax) * 100", "affected_inputs": ["base_tax"]}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Percentage (e.g., 40 for 40%)", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}, {"id": "exclusion_amount_year", "ambiguity_type": "time_basis", "trigger_signal": "the article mentions different exclusion amounts for different years (e.g., 2023 vs 2024).", "clarification_question": "Which year's exclusion amount should be applied for the estate value?", "options": [{"label": "Use the provided exclusion_amount as-is — DEFAULT", "value": "as_provided", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Consider exclusion amount for 2023 ($12.92 million)", "value": "exclusion_2023", "is_default": false}, {"label": "Consider exclusion amount for 2024 ($13.61 million)", "value": "exclusion_2024", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "The provided exclusion_amount input is correct for the relevant year.", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}, {"id": "tax_type", "ambiguity_type": "semantic_categorization", "trigger_signal": "the term 'death tax' can refer to both estate tax and inheritance tax.", "clarification_question": "Are we calculating 'estate tax' (tax on the estate) or 'inheritance tax' (tax on the beneficiary)?", "options": [{"label": "Estate Tax (tax on the estate) — DEFAULT", "value": "estate_tax", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Inheritance Tax (tax on the beneficiary)", "value": "inheritance_tax", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "This calculation is for Estate Tax.", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "estate_value", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The total value of the estate.", "unit": "dollars", "aliases": []}, {"name": "exclusion_amount", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The exclusion threshold for the estate value, above which taxes are applicable.", "unit": "dollars", "aliases": []}, {"name": "base_tax_rate", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The tax rate applied to the taxable amount, expressed as a percentage (e.g., 40 for 40%).", "unit": "percent", "aliases": []}, {"name": "base_tax", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The fixed base tax amount added to the taxed portion of the exceeding estate value.", "unit": "dollars", "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "estate_tax_liability", "type": "number", "unit": "dollars", "description": "The calculated estate tax liability for the given estate, rounded to the nearest integer."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    estate_value = inputs['estate_value']\n    exclusion_amount = inputs['exclusion_amount']\n    base_tax_rate = inputs['base_tax_rate']\n    base_tax = inputs['base_tax']\n    taxable_amount = max(estate_value - exclusion_amount, 0)\n    estate_tax_liability = base_tax_rate / 100 * taxable_amount + base_tax\n    return round(estate_tax_liability)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "estate_value_non_negative", "name": "Estate value must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "inputs['estate_value'] >= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The total value of the estate must be zero or positive."}, {"rule_id": "exclusion_amount_non_negative", "name": "Exclusion amount must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "inputs['exclusion_amount'] >= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The exclusion threshold for the estate value must be zero or positive."}, {"rule_id": "base_tax_rate_positive", "name": "Base tax rate must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "inputs['base_tax_rate'] > 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The base tax rate applied to the taxable amount must be greater than zero."}, {"rule_id": "base_tax_rate_plausible_range", "name": "Base tax rate must be a plausible percentage", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "0 <= inputs['base_tax_rate'] <= 100", "applies_to": [], "description": "The base tax rate, when expressed as a percentage (e.g., 40 for 40%), should typically be between 0 and 100."}, {"rule_id": "base_tax_non_negative", "name": "Base tax must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "inputs['base_tax'] >= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The fixed base tax amount must be zero or positive."}, {"rule_id": "taxable_portion_calc_consistency", "name": "Taxable portion calculation consistency", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['estate_value'] > inputs['exclusion_amount'] and compute(inputs) == inputs['base_tax']", "applies_to": [], "description": "Alert if the estate value exceeds the exclusion amount but the computed tax liability equals only the base tax, suggesting the taxable portion was not correctly applied or was zero due to other factors."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    estate_value = inputs['estate_value']\n    exclusion_amount = inputs['exclusion_amount']\n    base_tax_rate = inputs['base_tax_rate']\n    base_tax = inputs['base_tax']\n    taxable_amount = max(estate_value - exclusion_amount, 0)\n    estate_tax_liability = base_tax_rate / 100 * taxable_amount + base_tax\n    return round(estate_tax_liability)"}, "article_title": "Death Taxes", "article_doc_id": 3171, "article_content_excerpt": "# What Are Death Taxes? How to Reduce or Avoid Them\n\n## What Are Death Taxes? \n\nDeath taxes are taxes imposed by the federal and some state governments on someone's upon their death. These taxes are levied on the beneficiary who receives the property in the deceased's will or the estate that pays the tax before transferring the inherited property. Death taxes apply to estates valued over $12.92 million in 2023 and 13.61 million in 2024.\n\nDeath taxes are also called death duties, estate taxes, or inheritance taxes. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Death taxes are taxes on a deceased's estate imposed by a government.\n * \"Death tax\" is another term for estate and inheritance taxes.\n * Death taxes generally only apply to estates and inheritances over a specific value. In 2023, an estate must have assets of over $12.92 million to be subject to federal taxes. In 2024, the number is $13.61 million. \n\n## Understanding Death Taxes \n\nA death tax can be any tax imposed on property transfer after someone's death. The term “death tax” gained popularity in the 1990s and was used to describe estate and by those who wanted the taxes repealed. In , the deceased’s estate pays the tax before the assets are transferred to a beneficiary. With the inheritance tax, the person who inherits the assets pays. \n\nThe estate tax, charged by the federal government and some state governments, is based on the value of property and assets at the time of the owner's death. The federal estate tax ranges from 18% to 40% of the inheritance amount.\n\nTwelve states impose a state estate tax separate from the federal government. These states are Connecticut, Hawaii, Illinois, Maine, Maryland, Massachusetts, Minnesota, New York, Oregon, Rhode Island, Vermont, Washington, and the District of Columbia.\n\nThe federal government does not impose an inheritance tax, but several states do—Iowa, Kentucky, Maryland, Nebraska, New Jersey, and Pennsylvania; however, in all of these states, property passing to a is exempt from inheritance taxes. Nebraska and Pennsylvania impose taxes on property passing to a child or grandchild in some instances.\n\n## Death Tax Thresholds \n\nMost people end up not paying the death tax because it applies to only a few people. This is because the 2017 Tax Cuts and Jobs Act applied the estate tax to the basic exclusion amount, which in 2023 is $12.92 million and in 2024 is $13.61 million.\n\n### Important: \n\nThe Tax Cuts and Jobs Act expires after 2025. The basic exclusion amount is set to drop back down to pre-TCJA levels if Congress doesn't renew the act.\n\nFor example, assume an individual leaves an estate valued at $13 million (accounted for inflation) in non-exempt assets to the children and has never left any gifts that exceeded the exclusion amount. The amount above the federal level in 2023 ($13 million – $12.92 million), $80,000, will be subject to estate tax. According to the Unified Rate Schedule, the taxable amount is subject to a 28% tax plus a base tax of $18,200. Therefore, the estate will have a death tax liability of (28% x $80,000) + $18,200 = $40,600.\n\nSo, if a decedent's estate is valued at less than the applicable exemption amount for the year of death, the estate won't owe any federal estate taxes. \n\n### Unified Tax Credit \n\nThe has a set amount that an individual can during their lifetime before any death taxes or gift taxes apply. The tax credit unifies both the gift and estate taxes into one tax system, decreasing the tax bill of the individual or estate, dollar to dollar.\n\nSince some people prefer to use the unified tax credits to save on estate taxes after their deaths, the unified tax credit may not be used for reducing gift taxes while still alive. It may instead be used on the inheritance amount bequeathed to beneficiaries after death. \n\n### Unlimited Marital Deduction \n\nAnother provision available to reduce death tax is the , which allows an individual to transfer an unrestricted amount of assets to their spouse at any time, including\n...[truncated]"}
