": "Percentage (e.g., 5.0%) - DEFAULT", "value": "percentage", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Decimal (e.g., 0.05)", "value": "decimal", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "result / 100.0", "max_expr_nodes": 6, "invariant": "result_new == result_old / 100.0", "affected_inputs": []}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Expressed as a percentage", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "face_value", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The face value (redemption value) of the commercial paper.", "unit": "currency", "aliases": []}, {"name": "purchase_price", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The price at which the commercial paper was purchased.", "unit": "currency", "aliases": []}, {"name": "days_to_maturity", "type": "integer", "required": true, "description": "The number of days until the commercial paper matures.", "unit": "days", "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "discount_rate", "type": "number", "unit": "percent", "description": "The annualized discount rate expressed as a percentage."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    face_value = inputs['face_value']\n    purchase_price = inputs['purchase_price']\n    days_to_maturity = inputs['days_to_maturity']\n    discount_rate = (face_value - purchase_price) / purchase_price * (360 / days_to_maturity) * 100\n    return discount_rate", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "dr001", "name": "Positive Face Value", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['face_value'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["face_value"], "description": "Face value must be a positive number."}, {"rule_id": "dr002", "name": "Positive Purchase Price", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['purchase_price'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["purchase_price"], "description": "Purchase price must be a positive number."}, {"rule_id": "dr003", "name": "Purchase Price Less Than Face Value", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['purchase_price'] >= inputs['face_value']", "applies_to": ["purchase_price", "face_value"], "description": "The purchase price must be strictly less than the face value for a valid discount."}, {"rule_id": "dr004", "name": "Days to Maturity Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['days_to_maturity'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["days_to_maturity"], "description": "Days to maturity must be a positive integer."}, {"rule_id": "dr005", "name": "Days to Maturity Within Standard Range", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['days_to_maturity'] > 270", "applies_to": ["days_to_maturity"], "description": "Commercial paper typically has a maturity period between 1 and 270 days. Values outside this range may indicate a different instrument or an error."}, {"rule_id": "dr006", "name": "Minimum Denomination for Commercial Paper", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['face_value'] < 100000", "applies_to": ["face_value"], "description": "Commercial paper typically has a minimum denomination of $100,000. Values below this may not represent standard commercial paper."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    face_value = inputs['face_value']\n    purchase_price = inputs['purchase_price']\n    days_to_maturity = inputs['days_to_maturity']\n    discount_rate = (face_value - purchase_price) / purchase_price * (360 / days_to_maturity) * 100\n    return discount_rate"}, "article_title": "Commercial Paper", "article_doc_id": 180, "article_content_excerpt": "# Commercial Paper: Definition, Advantages, and Example\n\nDefinition\n\nCommercial paper is an unsecured, short-term debt instrument issued by corporations.\n\n## What Is Commercial Paper? \n\nCommercial paper is an unsecured, short-term debt instrument issued by corporations. It's typically used to finance short-term liabilities such as payroll, , and inventories. Commercial paper involves a specific amount of money that is to be repaid by a specific date. Minimum denominations are $100,000. Terms to maturity extend from one to 270 days. They average 30 days. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Commercial paper is a form of unsecured, short-term debt.\n * It's commonly issued by companies to finance their payrolls, payables, inventories, and other short-term liabilities.\n * Maturities on commercial paper range from one to 270 days, with an average of around 30 days.\n * Commercial paper is issued at a discount and matures at its face value.\n * The minimum denomination of commercial paper is $100,000 and it pays a fixed rate of interest that fluctuates with the market. \n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/Commercial-paper-4199154-edit-ec6447e8a3a841a6bceb57e6b00f5c5f.jpg)\n\nInvestopedia / Madelyn Goodnight\n\n## Understanding Commercial Paper \n\nCommercial paper was first introduced during colonial times and was referred to as a bill of exchange. They became more modern during the 1920s when New York merchants began to sell their short-term obligations to dealers to access capital needed to cover near-term obligations. These dealers, or , purchased the paper (also known as promissory notes) at a discount from their par value. They then sold the paper to banks and other investors. The merchants would repay the investors an amount equal to the par value of the note.\n\nCommercial paper is not backed by any form of collateral, making it an unsecured debt and will . It differs from asset-backed commercial paper (ABCP), a class of debt instrument backed by assets selected by the issuer. In either case, commercial paper is only issued by firms with high ratings from credit rating agencies. These firms can easily find buyers without having to offer a substantial discount (at a higher cost to themselves) for the . \n\nCommercial paper is issued by large institutions in denominations of $100,000 or more. Other corporations, financial institutions, and wealthy individuals are usually buyers of commercial paper. \n\n### Fast Fact: \n\nMarcus Goldman, the founder of investment bank , was the first dealer in the money market to purchase commercial paper. His company became one of the biggest commercial paper dealers in America following the Civil War.\n\n## Types of Commercial Paper \n\nThere are a bunch of different types of commercial paper, as companies can issue different forms of items depending on the criteria they’re willing to commit to. Here are the main types of commercial paper: \n\n### Promissory Notes \n\nPromissory notes are written promises to pay a specific amount of money on a certain date. They are used by companies to borrow funds without having to use any collateral, and promissory notes can range from just a few days to up to a year. Promissory notes are sold at a from their face value and redeemed at face value upon maturity, meaning the difference between those two amounts is technically the interest earned. \n\n### Drafts \n\nDrafts are orders written by one party (the drawer) directing another party (the drawee) to pay a specified sum to a third party (the payee). The drawee is usually a bank. As commercial paper, drafts can be used in trade financing to facilitate the purchase of goods and services. Drafts can be either sight drafts which are payable on demand or time drafts which can be payable at a specific future date. \n\n### Bankers' Acceptances \n\nBankers' acceptances are time drafts that have been accepted and guaranteed by a bank. They are commonly used in to ensure payment to exporters. The bank's acceptance of the draft means that the bank promises to\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_1959", "name": "Trend Analysis", "short_description": "Calculates the slope of a linear regression line to model the relationship between two variables, typically used for trend analysis.", "domain": "financial_markets", "topic": "trend_analysis", "topic_extension": true, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-1959", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-95", "question_id": "test-2189", "difficulty": 5.375278407684165, "level": "hard", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "52efae1b650ddd0bf4f370c12930b92ed7e7c930889c9a0d3f09810da1073ad2", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["linear regression", "slope calculation", "trend analysis", "market index impact", "NAV change", "relationship modeling"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "trend_time_horizon", "ambiguity_type": "time_basis", "trigger_signal": "The time horizon for the trend analysis (short, intermediate, long-term) is not explicitly defined.", "clarification_question": "What time horizon does this trend analysis represent?", "options": [{"label": "Short-term trend (e.g., daily/weekly data) - DEFAULT", "value": "short_term", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Intermediate-term trend (e.g., monthly/quarterly data)", "value": "intermediate_term", "is_default": false}, {"label": "Long-term trend (e.g., annual data)", "value": "long_term", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "The slope represents a short-term trend based on the given daily data.", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}, {"id": "output_scale_slope", "ambiguity_type": "unit_scale", "trigger_signal": "Slope can be interpreted as a decimal (e.g., 0.05) or a percentage (e.g., 5%).", "clarification_question": "Should the slope be expressed as a decimal or a percentage?", "options": [{"label": "Decimal - DEFAULT", "value": "decimal", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Percentage", "value": "percent", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "result * 100.0", "max_expr_nodes": 6, "invariant": "result_new == result_old * 100.0", "affected_inputs": []}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "The slope is expressed as a decimal.", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "x_values", "type": "array[number]", "required": true, "description": "A list of independent variable data points (e.g., market index values).", "unit": null, "aliases": ["independent_variables", "market_data"]}, {"name": "y_values", "type": "array[number]", "required": true, "description": "A list of dependent variable data points (e.g., NAV changes). Must have the same length as x_values.", "unit": null, "aliases": ["dependent_variables", "fund_performance"]}], "output": {"name": "slope", "type": "number", "unit": null, "description": "The slope of the linear regression line, representing the rate of change of y_values with respect to x_values, rounded to two decimal places."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    x_values = inputs['x_values']\n    y_values = inputs['y_values']\n    if len(x_values) != len(y_values):\n        raise ValueError('Input lists must be of the same length.')\n    if len(x_values) < 2:\n        raise ValueError('At least two data points are required for linear regression.')\n    n = len(x_values)\n    sum_x = sum(x_values)\n    sum_y = sum(y_values)\n    sum_x_squared = sum((x ** 2 for x in x_values))\n    sum_xy = sum((x * y for x, y in zip(x_values, y_values)))\n    denominator = n * sum_x_squared - sum_x ** 2\n    if denominator == 0:\n        raise ValueError('Cannot calculate slope: all x_values are identical.')\n    slope = (n * sum_xy - sum_x * sum_y) / denominator\n    return round(slope, 2)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "lr_001", "name": "Input Type Check (x_values)", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['x_values'], list)", "applies_to": ["x_values"], "description": "The independent variable 'x_values' must be provided as a list."}, {"rule_id": "lr_002", "name": "Input Type Check (y_values)", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['y_values'], list)", "applies_to": ["y_values"], "description": "The dependent variable 'y_values' must be provided as a list."}, {"rule_id": "lr_003", "name": "Equal Length of Input Lists", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "len(inputs['x_values']) != len(inputs['y_values'])", "applies_to": ["x_values", "y_values"], "description": "The lists of independent ('x_values') and dependent ('y_values') variables must have the same number of data points."}, {"rule_id": "lr_004", "name": "Minimum Data Points Required", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "len(inputs['x_values']) < 2", "applies_to": ["x_values"], "description": "At least two data points are required to perform linear regression."}, {"rule_id": "lr_005", "name": "Numeric Elements in x_values", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "all(isinstance(val, (int, float)) for val in inputs['x_values'])", "applies_to": ["x_values"], "description": "All elements in 'x_values' must be numeric (integers or floats)."}, {"rule_id": "lr_006", "name": "Numeric Elements in y_values", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "all(isinstance(val, (int, float)) for val in inputs['y_values'])", "applies_to": ["y_values"], "description": "All elements in 'y_values' must be numeric (integers or floats)."}, {"rule_id": "lr_007", "name": "Non-Identical X-Values for Slope Calculation", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "len(inputs['x_values']) > 0 and len(set(inputs['x_values'])) == 1", "applies_to": ["x_values"], "description": "All x_values cannot be identical, as this results in an undefined slope due to division by zero."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    x_values = inputs['x_values']\n    y_values = inputs['y_values']\n    if len(x_values) != len(y_values):\n        raise ValueError('Input lists must be of the same length.')\n    if len(x_values) < 2:\n        raise ValueError('At least two data points are required for linear regression.')\n    n = len(x_values)\n    sum_x = sum(x_values)\n    sum_y = sum(y_values)\n    sum_x_squared = sum((x ** 2 for x in x_values))\n    sum_xy = sum((x * y for x, y in zip(x_values, y_values)))\n    denominator = n * sum_x_squared - sum_x ** 2\n    if denominator == 0:\n        raise ValueError('Cannot calculate slope: all x_values are identical.')\n    slope = (n * sum_xy - sum_x * sum_y) / denominator\n    return round(slope, 2)"}, "article_title": "Trend Analysis", "article_doc_id": 3693, "article_content_excerpt": "# Understanding Trend Analysis and Trend Trading Strategies\n\n## What Is Trend Analysis? \n\nTrend analysis is a technique used in that attempts to predict future stock price movements based on recently observed trend data. Trend analysis uses historical data, such as price movements and trade volume, to forecast the long-term direction of market sentiment. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Trend analysis tries to predict a trend, such as a bull market run, and then ride that trend until data suggests a trend reversal, such as a bull-to-bear market.\n * Trend analysis is based on the idea that what has happened in the past gives traders an idea of what will happen in the future.\n * Trend analysis focuses on three typical time horizons: short-; intermediate-; and long-term.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/Trendanalysis-587b2a1157474b069868ba7bd5306ac9.jpg)\n\nInvestopedia / Michela Buttignol\n\n## Understanding Trend Analysis \n\nTrend analysis tries to predict a trend, such as a run, and ride that trend until data suggests a trend , such as a bull-to-bear market. Trend analysis is helpful because moving with trends, and not against them, will lead to profit for an investor. It is based on the idea that what has happened in the past gives traders an idea of what will happen in the future. There are three main types of trends: short-, intermediate- and long-term. \n\nA is a general direction the market is taking during a specified period of time. Trends can be both upward and downward, relating to bullish and , respectively. While there is no specified minimum amount of time required for a direction to be considered a trend, the longer the direction is maintained, the more notable the trend. \n\nTrend analysis is the process of looking at current trends in order to predict future ones and is considered a . This can include attempting to determine whether a current market trend, such as gains in a particular market sector, is likely to continue, as well as whether a trend in one market area could result in a trend in another. Though a trend analysis may involve a large amount of data, there is no guarantee that the results will be correct. \n\n### Types of Trends to Analyze\n\nThere are three main types of market trend for analysts to consider:\n\n 1. **Upward trend:** An upward trend, also known as a , is a sustained period of rising prices in a particular security or market. Upward trends are generally seen as a sign of economic strength and can be driven by factors such as strong demand, rising profits, and favorable economic conditions.\n 2. **Downward trend:** A downward trend, also known as a , is a sustained period of falling prices in a particular security or market. Downward trends are generally seen as a sign of economic weakness and can be driven by factors such as weak demand, declining profits, and unfavorable economic conditions.\n 3. **Sideways trend:** A , also known as a market, is a period of relatively stable prices in a particular security or market. Sideways trends can be characterized by a lack of clear direction, with prices fluctuating within a relatively narrow range.\n\n \n\n## How to Perform a Trend Analysis \n\nIn order to begin analyzing applicable data, it is necessary to first determine which market segment will be analyzed. For instance, you could focus on a particular industry, such as the automotive or pharmaceuticals sector, as well as a particular type of investment, such as the . \n\nOnce the sector has been selected, it is possible to examine its general performance. This can include how the sector was affected by internal and external forces. For example, changes in a similar industry or the creation of a new governmental regulation would qualify as forces impacting the market. Analysts then take this data and attempt to predict the direction the market will take moving forward. \n\n## Trend Trading Strategies \n\n attempt to isolate and extract profit from trends. There are many different trend trading strategies using a variety\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_2749", "name": "Elastic", "short_description": "Calculates the price elasticity of demand, measuring how the quantity demanded of a product changes in response to changes in its price.", "domain": "financial_markets", "topic": "market_elasticity", "topic_extension": true, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-2749", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-337", "question_id": "test-1865", "difficulty": 3.688879454113936, "level": "medium", "execution_smoke_ok": false, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "execution_smoke_error": "float division by zero", "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "787a0d8cb95c58dd05d678da27ac0f3b414312cb748973d6015cde970b664548", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["price elasticity of demand", "demand responsiveness to price", "elastic goods", "inelastic goods", "market analysis", "economic measure", "consumer behavior", "price sensitivity"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "elasticity_type", "ambiguity_type": "definition_scope", "trigger_signal": "elasticity mentioned without specifying type (price, income, cross-price)", "clarification_question": "Which type of elasticity are you interested in?", "options": [{"label": "Price Elasticity of Demand (DEFAULT)", "value": "price_elasticity", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Income Elasticity of Demand", "value": "income_elasticity", "is_default": false}, {"label": "Cross-Price Elasticity of Demand", "value": "cross_price_elasticity", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Price Elasticity of Demand", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}, {"id": "elasticity_calculation_method", "ambiguity_type": "formula_basis", "trigger_signal": "elasticity mentioned, but calculation method (point vs. arc) not specified", "clarification_question": "Should elasticity be calculated using the initial values (point elasticity) or midpoints (arc elasticity