n round(total_cost, 2)"}, "article_title": "Last In, First Out (LIFO)", "article_doc_id": 4054, "article_content_excerpt": "# Last In, First Out (LIFO): The Inventory Cost Method Explained\n\n## What Is Last In, First Out (LIFO)? \n\nLast in, first out (LIFO) is a method used to account for business inventory that records the most recently produced items in a series as the ones that are sold first. That is, the cost of the most recent products purchased or produced is the first to be expensed as , while the cost of older products, which is often lower, will be reported as inventory. \n\nTwo alternative methods of inventory costing include , in which the oldest inventory items are recorded as sold first, and the , which takes the weighted average of all units available for sale during the accounting period and uses that average cost to determine COGS and ending inventory. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Last in, first out (LIFO) is a method used to account for inventory.\n * Under LIFO, the costs of the most recent products purchased (or produced) are the first to be expensed.\n * LIFO is used only in the United States and is permitted under generally accepted accounting principles (GAAP).\n * LIFO accounting can minimize taxable income during years in which inflation is driving up the costs of doing business. \n\n## Understanding Last In, First Out (LIFO) \n\nLast in, first out (LIFO) is only used in the United States where any of the three inventory-costing methods can be used under . The , which is used in most countries, forbids the use of the LIFO method. \n\nMost companies that use LIFO inventory valuations need to maintain large inventories, such as retailers and auto dealerships. The method allows them to take advantage of lower taxable income and higher cash flow when their expenses are rising. \n\nMost U.S. . If a company uses a LIFO valuation when it files taxes, it must also use LIFO when it reports financial results to its , which lowers its .\n\n## LIFO, Inflation, and Net Income \n\nWhen there is zero , all three inventory-costing methods produce the same result. But if inflation is high, the choice of accounting method can dramatically affect valuation ratios. FIFO, LIFO, and average cost have different impacts: \n\n * FIFO provides a better indication of the value of on the balance sheet, but it also increases net income because inventory that might be several years old is used to value COGS. Increasing net income sounds good, but it can increase the taxes that a company must pay.\n * LIFO is not a good indicator of ending inventory value because it may understate the value of inventory. LIFO results in lower net income (and taxes) because COGS is higher. However, there are fewer inventory under LIFO during inflation.\n * Average cost produces results that fall somewhere between FIFO and LIFO.\n\nIn times of deflation, the complete opposite of the above is true. \n\n## Example of LIFO \n\nAssume company A has 10 widgets. The first five widgets cost $100 each and arrived two days ago. The last five widgets cost $200 each and arrived one day ago. Based on the LIFO method of inventory management, the last widgets in are the first ones to be sold. Seven widgets are sold, but how much can the accountant record as a cost? \n\nEach widget has the same sales price, so is the same. But the cost of the widgets is based on the inventory method selected. \n\nBased on the LIFO method, the last inventory in is the sold. This means the widgets that cost $200 sold first. The company then sold two more of the $100 widgets. In total, the cost of the widgets under the LIFO method is $1,200, or five at $200 and two at $100. \n\nIn contrast, using the FIFO method, the $100 widgets are sold first, followed by the $200 widgets. So, the cost of the widgets sold will be recorded as $900, or five at $100 and two at $200. \n\nThis is why LIFO creates higher costs and lowers net income in times of inflation. It also reduces .\n\nIn periods of deflation, LIFO creates lower costs and increases net income, which also increases taxable income. \n\n## Which Is Better, LIFO or FIFO?\n\nThat depends on the business you\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_1885", "name": "Throughput", "short_description": "Calculates the total time required for a production process by summing processing, inspection, move, and queue times.", "domain": "corporate_finance", "topic": "operational_efficiency", "topic_extension": true, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-1885", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-884", "question_id": "test-1006", "difficulty": 2.4849066497880004, "level": "medium", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "fc9fdb44d20d467fbb4bfa9c1d00944ef7cc0b6e2ae406f50c68bf0f7d50261d", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["throughput time", "production process duration", "manufacturing cycle time", "operational efficiency", "process timing"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "input_time_basis", "ambiguity_type": "data_source_interpretation", "trigger_signal": "time components not explicitly defined as average or target values", "clarification_question": "Are the input time components (processing, inspection, move, queue) based on average observed times or target/standard times?", "options": [{"label": "Average observed times (DEFAULT)", "value": "average_observed", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Target/Standard times", "value": "target_standard", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Average observed times", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "processing_time", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The time spent on processing steps in production.", "unit": "hours", "aliases": []}, {"name": "inspection_time", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The time spent on quality control and inspection.", "unit": "hours", "aliases": []}, {"name": "move_time", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The time spent on transporting, shipping, and delivery.", "unit": "hours", "aliases": []}, {"name": "queue_time", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The idle time or wait time between processes.", "unit": "hours", "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "total_throughput_time", "type": "number", "unit": "hours", "description": "The total throughput time for the entire production process."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    processing_time = inputs['processing_time']\n    inspection_time = inputs['inspection_time']\n    move_time = inputs['move_time']\n    queue_time = inputs['queue_time']\n    total_throughput_time = processing_time + inspection_time + move_time + queue_time\n    return total_throughput_time", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "input_non_negative", "name": "Non-negative time components", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['processing_time'] < 0 or inputs['inspection_time'] < 0 or inputs['move_time'] < 0 or inputs['queue_time'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "All time components (processing, inspection, move, queue) must be non-negative."}, {"rule_id": "plausible_total_time", "name": "Positive total throughput time for positive inputs", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "compute(inputs) <= 0 and (inputs['processing_time'] > 0 or inputs['inspection_time'] > 0 or inputs['move_time'] > 0 or inputs['queue_time'] > 0)", "applies_to": [], "description": "If any individual time component is positive, the total throughput time must be greater than zero."}, {"rule_id": "excessive_single_component_time", "name": "Excessively high single time component", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['processing_time'] > 1000 or inputs['inspection_time'] > 1000 or inputs['move_time'] > 1000 or inputs['queue_time'] > 1000", "applies_to": [], "description": "One or more time components are unusually high, which could indicate a data entry error or incorrect units (e.g., minutes instead of hours)."}, {"rule_id": "extreme_total_throughput_time", "name": "Extreme total throughput time", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "compute(inputs) > 5000", "applies_to": [], "description": "The calculated total throughput time is extremely high, suggesting a potential input error or an exceptionally long production process."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    processing_time = inputs['processing_time']\n    inspection_time = inputs['inspection_time']\n    move_time = inputs['move_time']\n    queue_time = inputs['queue_time']\n    total_throughput_time = processing_time + inspection_time + move_time + queue_time\n    return total_throughput_time"}, "article_title": "Throughput", "article_doc_id": 3580, "article_content_excerpt": "# What Is Throughput? Definition, Formula, Benefits, and Calculation\n\nDefinition\n\nThroughput is the quantity of a service or product a company is able to produce over a certain period.\n\nThroughput, in business, is the amount of a product or service that a company can produce and deliver to a client within a specified period of time. The term is often used in the context of a company's or the speed at which something is processed. \n\nBusinesses with high throughput levels can take away from their lower throughput peers because high throughput generally indicates that a company can produce a product or service more efficiently than its competitors. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Throughput is a term used to describe the rate at which a company produces or processes its products or services.\n * The goal behind measuring the throughput concept is often to identify and minimize the weakest links in the production process.\n * Assumptions about capacity and the company's supply chain can affect throughput.\n * Maintaining high throughput becomes a challenge when different products are being produced using a combination of joint and separate processes.\n * When a company can maximize its throughput, it can also maximize its revenues.\n\n## Understanding Throughput \n\nThe idea of throughput, also known as the flow rate, is part of the theory of constraints in business management. The guiding ideology of this theory is that a chain is only as strong as its weakest link. The goal for business managers is to find ways to minimize how the weakest links affect a company's performance and to maximize throughput for the product's end users. Once throughput is maximized by removing inefficiencies, allowing to flow in the most ideal manner, a company can reach maximization. \n\nA company's level of is closely related to throughput, and management can make several types of assumptions about capacity. If the company assumes that production will operate continually without any interruptions, management is using theoretical , but this level of capacity is not reachable. No production process can produce the maximum output forever because machines need to be repaired and maintained, and employees take vacation days. It's more realistic for businesses to use practical capacity, which accounts for machine repairs, wait times, and holidays. \n\n### Important: \n\nOnly products that are actually sold count toward throughput.\n\n## Factors Affecting Throughput \n\nA company’s throughput also depends on how well the company manages its , which is the interaction between the company and its suppliers. If, for whatever reason, supplies are not available as an input to production, the disruption has a negative impact on throughput. \n\nIn many cases, two products may start in production using the same process, which means that the joint costs are allocated between each product. When production reaches the split-off point, however, the products are produced using separate processes. This situation makes it more difficult to maintain a high level of throughput. \n\n## Formula and Calculation of Throughput \n\nThroughput can be calculated using the following formula: \n\n> T = I/F \n\nwhere: \n\n * T = Throughput\n * I = (the number of units in the production process)\n * F = The time the inventory units spend in production from start to finish\n\n## Benefits of Knowing Throughput Time \n\nThroughput time refers to the total amount of time that it takes to run a particular process in its entirety from start to finish. For example, a manufacturer can measure how long it takes to produce a product, from initial customer order to sourcing raw materials to manufacturing to sale. \n\nThroughput time can be further broken down into components: \n\n * _Processing time_ is how long all of the steps of producing a good or service take\n * _Inspection time_ involves running quality control and monitoring finished goods\n * _Move time_ includes how long it takes to transport, ship, and deliver items across the logisti\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_2456", "name": "Weighted Average Life (WAL)", "short_description": "Calculates the Weighted Average Life (WAL) of an amortizing bond, loan, or mortgage, representing the average time until principal repayment is received, weighted by each payment's contribution to the total principal.", "domain": "financial_markets", "topic": "weighted_average_life", "topic_extension": true, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-2456", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-777", "question_id": "test-1253", "difficulty": 2.6390573296152584, "level": "medium", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "292be0b5f3a42ee6c94273e30a28f8f7d978c7f88020f750b9509fb010ab5d84", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["Weighted Average Life", "WAL", "amortizing bond", "loan", "mortgage", "principal repayment timing", "credit risk fixed-income"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "output_precision", "ambiguity_type": "output_formatting", "trigger_signal": "user asks for specific decimal places or general rounding", "clarification_question": "How many decimal places should the Weighted Average Life be rounded to?", "options": [{"label": "Default (as calculated, not rounded)", "value": "default_unrounded", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Round to 2 decimal places", "value": "round_2_decimals", "is_default": false}, {"label": "Round to nearest integer", "value": "round_nearest_integer", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Result is provided with full precision (not explicitly rounded).", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}, {"id": "wal_scope", "ambiguity_type": "interpretation_scope", "trigger_signal": "user query implies 'duration' or interest rate sensitivity", "clarification_question": "Are you interested in a measure based solely on principal repayment (Weighted Average Life) or one that considers interest payments and present value (like Duration)?", "options": [{"label": "Principal repayment only (WAL) — DEFAULT", "value": "principal_only", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Considering interest payments and present value (Duration concept)", "value": "duration_concept", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "hard", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "The calculation is for Weighted Average Life (WAL), which considers only principal payments as per the definition.", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "payments", "type": "array[number]", "required": true, "description": "A list of principal payments for each period.", "unit": "currency", "aliases": []}, {"name": "periods", "type": "array[number]", "required": true, "description": "A list of time periods (e.g., years) corresponding to each payment.", "unit": "years", "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "weighted_average_life", "type": "number", "unit": "years", "description": "The weighted average life of the bond or loan in years."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    payments = inputs['payments']\n    periods = inputs['periods']\n    if len(payments) != len(periods):\n        raise ValueError('Payments and periods lists must be of the same length.')\n    total_weighted_payments = sum((payment * period for payment, period in zip(payments, periods)))\n    total_unweighted_payments = sum(payments)\n    if total_unweighted_payments == 0:\n        raise ValueError('Total unweighted payments must be greater than zero.')\n    weighted_average_life = total_weighted_payments / total_unweighted_payments\n    return weighted_average_life", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "payments_is_list", "name": "Payments input type check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['payments'], list)", "applies_to": ["payments"], "description": "The 'payments' input must be a list."}, {"rule_id": "periods_is_list", "name": "Periods input type check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['periods'], list)", "applies_to": ["periods"], "description": "The 'periods' input must be a list."}, {"rule_id": "payments_elements_numeric", "name": "Payments list elements must be numeric", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "all(isinstance(item, (int, float)) for item in inputs['payments'])", "applies_to": ["payments"], "description": "All elements in the 'payments' list must be numeric (integers or floats)."}, {"rule_id": "periods_elements_numeric", "name": "Periods list elements must be numeric", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "all(isinstance(item, (int, float)) for item in inputs['periods'])", "applies_to": ["periods"], "description": "All elements in the 'periods' list must be numeric (integers or floats)."}, {"rule_id": "lists_same_length", "name": "Payments and Periods length check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "len(inputs['payments']) != len(inputs['periods'])", "applies_to": ["payments", "periods"], "description": "The 'payments' and 'periods' lists must have the same number of elements."}, {"rule_id": "payments_non_negative", "name": "Payments non-negative check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "any(p < 0 for p in inputs['payments'])", "applies_to": ["payments"], "description": "All principal payments in the 'payments' list must be non-negative."}, {"rule_id": "periods_positive", "name": "Periods positive check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "any(p <= 0 for p in inputs['periods'])", "applies_to": ["periods"], "description": "All periods in the 'periods' list must be positive (e.g., > 0)."}, {"rule_id": "total_payments_greater_than_zero", "name": "Total unweighted payments check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "sum(inputs['payments']) == 0", "applies_to": ["payments"], "description": "The sum of all principal payments must be greater than zero to calculate WAL."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    payments = inputs['payments']\n    periods = inputs['periods']\n    if len(payments) != len(periods):\n        raise ValueError('Payments and periods lists must be of the same length.')\n    total_weighted_payments = sum((payment * period for payment, period in zip(payments, periods)))\n    total_unweighted_payments = sum(payments)\n    if total_unweighted_payments == 0:\n        raise ValueError('Total unweighted payments must be greater than zero.')\n    weighted_average_life = total_weighted_payments / total_unweighted_payments\n    return weighted_average_life"}, "article_title": "Weighted Average Life (WAL)", "article_doc_id": 4847, "article_content_excerpt": "# Understanding Weighted Average Life (WAL), How It Works, Example\n\n## What Is Weighted Average Life (WAL)? \n\nThe weighted average life (WAL) is the average length of time that each dollar of unpaid principal on a loan, a , or an remains outstanding. Calculating WAL shows an investor, an analyst, or a portfolio manager how many years it will take to receive roughly half of the amount of the outstanding principal. The formula is useful in measuring the credit risk associated with fixed-income securities. \n\n## Understanding Weighted Average Life (WAL) \n\nThe time weightings used in weighted average life calculations are based on payments to the . In many loans, such as mortgages, each payment consists of payments to principal and payments to . In WAL, only the principal payments are considered and these payments tend to get larger over time, with early payments of a mortgage going mostly to interest, while payments made towards the end of the loan are applied mostly to the principal balance of the loan. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Weighted average life is used to determine the dollar amount that remains outstanding on a mortgage or loan balance.\n * The calculation is \"weighted\" because it considers when the payments to the principal are made—if, for example, nearly all of the principal payments are made in five years, WAL will be close to five years.\n * Weighted average life does not consider payments to interest on the loan.\n * Most investors will select the bond with the smaller WAL, as the lower number suggests that the bond carries less credit risk.\n\nTime periods with higher dollar amounts have more weight in WAL. For example, if the majority of the to principal is in 10 years, the weighted will be closer to 10 years. \n\n## Weighted Average Life Example \n\nThere are four steps involved in calculating an amortizing bond's WAL. Assume a bond makes one payment per year. Over the next five years, the bond's payments are $1,000, $2,000, $4,000, $6,000 and $10,000. Therefore, the total value of the (unweighted) payments before the WAL computation is $23,000. \n\nThe first step of the calculation is to take each of these payments and multiply them by the number of years until the payment occurs. In this example, these values would be: \n\n * Year 1 = 1 x $1,000 = $1,000\n * Year 2 = 2 x $2,000 = $4,000\n * Year 3 = 3 x $4,000 = $12,000\n * Year 4 = 4 x $6,000 = $24,000\n * Year 5 = 5 x $10,000 = $50,000\n\nThe second step in the calculation is to add these weighted amounts together. In this example, the total weighted payments equal $91,000. Step three is to add up the bond's total unweighted payments. In this example, the total is $23,000. The final step is to take the total weighted payments and divide this value by the total unweighted payments to get the WAL: \n\nWeighted average life = $91,000 / $23,000 = 3.96 years \n\nIn this example, WAL is roughly equal to 4.00 and, at the end of four years, $13,000 of the $23,000 of principal is paid (slightly more than half). The largest payment is the final payment, so the WAL is closer to the total five-year term of the bond. On the other hand, if year two and year five payments were switched, the weighted average life would be much lower: \n\n * Year 1 = 1 x $1,000 = $1,000\n * Year 2 = 2 x $10,000 = $20,000\n * Year 3 = 3 x $4,000 = $12,000\n * Year 4 = 4 x $6,000 = $24,000\n * Year 5 = 5 x $2,000 = $10,000\n\nWeighted average life = $67,000 / $23,000 = 2.91 years \n\nWAL gives investors or analysts a rough idea of how quickly the bond in question pays out returns. Since rational investors want to receive returns earlier, if two bonds were compared, the investor would select the one with the shorter WAL. Stated differently, the most significant of a loan is the risk of loss of principal and a smaller WAL indicates a higher likelihood that the principal will be repaid in full."}
