res", "total_shares"]}, {"name": "shares_reduced", "type": "integer", "required": true, "description": "The number of shares repurchased by the company.", "unit": null, "aliases": ["shares_bought_back", "shares_repurchased"]}], "output": {"name": "post_buyback_eps", "type": "number", "unit": null, "description": "The new EPS after the buyback."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    initial_eps = inputs['initial_eps']\n    shares_outstanding = inputs['shares_outstanding']\n    shares_reduced = inputs['shares_reduced']\n    new_shares_outstanding = shares_outstanding - shares_reduced\n    if new_shares_outstanding <= 0:\n        raise ValueError('Shares outstanding cannot be zero or negative after buyback.')\n    net_income = initial_eps * shares_outstanding\n    post_buyback_eps = net_income / new_shares_outstanding\n    return {'post_buyback_eps': post_buyback_eps}", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "initial_eps_type_check", "name": "Initial EPS Type Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not isinstance(inputs['initial_eps'], (int, float))", "applies_to": ["initial_eps"], "description": "Initial EPS must be a numeric value (integer or float)."}, {"rule_id": "shares_outstanding_type_check", "name": "Shares Outstanding Type Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not isinstance(inputs['shares_outstanding'], int)", "applies_to": ["shares_outstanding"], "description": "Shares outstanding must be an integer."}, {"rule_id": "shares_reduced_type_check", "name": "Shares Reduced Type Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not isinstance(inputs['shares_reduced'], int)", "applies_to": ["shares_reduced"], "description": "Shares reduced must be an integer."}, {"rule_id": "shares_outstanding_positive", "name": "Shares Outstanding Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['shares_outstanding'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["shares_outstanding"], "description": "The number of shares outstanding must be greater than zero."}, {"rule_id": "shares_reduced_non_negative", "name": "Shares Reduced Must Be Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['shares_reduced'] < 0", "applies_to": ["shares_reduced"], "description": "The number of shares reduced by buyback cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "shares_reduced_less_than_outstanding", "name": "Shares Reduced Cannot Exceed Shares Outstanding", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['shares_reduced'] >= inputs['shares_outstanding']", "applies_to": ["shares_reduced", "shares_outstanding"], "description": "The number of shares reduced must be strictly less than the initial shares outstanding, otherwise new shares would be zero or negative."}, {"rule_id": "initial_eps_negative", "name": "Initial EPS is Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['initial_eps'] < 0", "applies_to": ["initial_eps"], "description": "A negative initial EPS indicates the company is unprofitable. While possible, a buyback to 'boost value' might be unusual in this scenario."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": false, "error": "Shares outstanding cannot be zero or negative after buyback.", "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    initial_eps = inputs['initial_eps']\n    shares_outstanding = inputs['shares_outstanding']\n    shares_reduced = inputs['shares_reduced']\n    new_shares_outstanding = shares_outstanding - shares_reduced\n    if new_shares_outstanding <= 0:\n        raise ValueError('Shares outstanding cannot be zero or negative after buyback.')\n    net_income = initial_eps * shares_outstanding\n    post_buyback_eps = net_income / new_shares_outstanding\n    return {'post_buyback_eps': post_buyback_eps}"}, "article_title": "Share Repurchase", "article_doc_id": 5209, "article_content_excerpt": "# Share Repurchase: Why Do Companies Do Share Buybacks?\n\n## What Is a Share Repurchase? \n\nA share repurchase is a whereby a company buys back its own shares from the marketplace. A company might buy back its shares because management considers them . The company buys shares directly from the market or offers its shareholders the option of tendering their shares directly to the company at a fixed price. \n\nRepurchases reduce the number of outstanding shares, which is something that investors often feel will drive up share prices. This assumes demand for the shares will not be diminished by the action. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * A share repurchase or buyback is a decision by a company to buy back its own shares from the marketplace.\n * A company might buy back its shares to boost the value of the stock and to improve the financial statements.\n * Companies tend to repurchase shares when they have cash on hand and the stock market is on an upswing.\n * There is a risk that the stock price could fall after a share repurchase.\n * Apple is one of the biggest repurchasers of its stock.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/sharerepurchase.asp-final-9d76deba49914257b120ef96a646e3e1.png)\n\nInvestopedia / Julie Bang\n\n## How Share Repurchases Work \n\nShare repurchases take place when companies decide to buy back their stock. Companies that repurchase their stock from the open market or directly from investors. Also known as a , it is commonly done to achieve:\n\n * An increase in \n * A boost in the company's financial position\n * \n\nBecause a share repurchase reduces the number of shares outstanding, it increases . A higher EPS elevates the market value of the remaining shares. After repurchase, the shares are canceled or held as , so they are no longer held publicly and are not outstanding. \n\nA share repurchase in various ways. A share repurchase reduces a company's available cash, which is then reflected on the balance sheet as a reduction by the amount the company spent on the buyback. \n\nAt the same time, the share repurchase reduces by the same amount on the liabilities side of the balance sheet. Investors interested in finding out how much a company has spent on share repurchases can find the information in their quarterly earnings reports. \n\n## Reasons for Share Repurchases \n\nA reduces the total assets of the business so that its return on assets, return on equity, and other metrics improve when compared to not repurchasing shares. means earnings per share (EPS) can grow more quickly as revenue and cash flow increase. \n\nIf the business pays out the same amount of total money to shareholders annually in and the total number of shares decreases, each receives a larger annual dividend. If the corporation grows its earnings and its total dividend payout, decreasing the total number of shares further increases the dividend growth. Shareholders expect a corporation paying regular dividends to continue doing so. \n\nIn some cases, a buyback can hide a slightly declining . If the share repurchase to a greater extent than the fall in net income, the EPS will rise irrespective of the financial state of the business. \n\nShare repurchases fill the gap between excess capital and dividends so that the business returns more to shareholders without locking into a pattern. For example, assume the corporation wants to return 75% of its earnings to shareholders and keep its at 50%. The company returns the other 25% in the form of share repurchases to complement the dividend. \n\n### Important: \n\nNew provisions were put into place to prevent companies from trying to boost their stock price to benefit corporate executives. The , which was signed by President Joe Biden on Aug. 16, 2022, includes an excise tax of 1% on share buybacks of $1 million or more made after Dec. 31, 2022. Any new public or employee stock issues will not count.\n\n## Advantages and Disadvantages of Share Repurchases \n\n### Advantages \n\nA share repurchase shows the corporation believes its shares are\n...[truncated]"}
