a tuple.", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}, {"id": "model_assumption", "ambiguity_type": "model_selection", "trigger_signal": "least squares method mentioned without explicit linear model assumption", "clarification_question": "Is a linear relationship assumed between the independent and dependent variables, or should a non-linear model be considered?", "options": [{"label": "Assume a linear relationship (Ordinary Least Squares) - DEFAULT", "value": "linear", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Consider a non-linear relationship (e.g., logarithmic, exponential)", "value": "non_linear", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "A linear relationship is assumed, and Ordinary Least Squares is applied.", "impact_scope": "directionality"}], "inputs": [{"name": "x_values", "type": "array[number]", "required": true, "description": "A list of independent variable data points.", "unit": null, "aliases": ["independent_variables", "x_data"]}, {"name": "y_values", "type": "array[number]", "required": true, "description": "A list of dependent variable data points.", "unit": null, "aliases": ["dependent_variables", "y_data"]}], "output": {"name": "coefficients", "type": "array[number]", "unit": null, "description": "A tuple containing the slope and intercept of the regression line."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    x_values = inputs['x_values']\n    y_values = inputs['y_values']\n    n = len(x_values)\n    sum_x = sum(x_values)\n    sum_y = sum(y_values)\n    sum_x_squared = sum((x ** 2 for x in x_values))\n    sum_xy = sum((x * y for x, y in zip(x_values, y_values)))\n    denominator = n * sum_x_squared - sum_x ** 2\n    slope = (n * sum_xy - sum_x * sum_y) / denominator\n    intercept = (sum_y - slope * sum_x) / n\n    return (slope, intercept)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "x_values_structure", "name": "X Values Type Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['x_values'], list)", "applies_to": ["x_values"], "description": "x_values must be a list."}, {"rule_id": "y_values_structure", "name": "Y Values Type Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['y_values'], list)", "applies_to": ["y_values"], "description": "y_values must be a list."}, {"rule_id": "x_values_elements_numeric", "name": "X Values Elements Numeric Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "all(isinstance(item, (int, float)) for item in inputs['x_values'])", "applies_to": ["x_values"], "description": "All elements in x_values must be numeric (integers or floats)."}, {"rule_id": "y_values_elements_numeric", "name": "Y Values Elements Numeric Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "all(isinstance(item, (int, float)) for item in inputs['y_values'])", "applies_to": ["y_values"], "description": "All elements in y_values must be numeric (integers or floats)."}, {"rule_id": "length_match", "name": "Input List Length Match", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "len(inputs['x_values']) == len(inputs['y_values'])", "applies_to": ["x_values", "y_values"], "description": "x_values and y_values must be of the same length."}, {"rule_id": "min_data_points", "name": "Minimum Data Points Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "len(inputs['x_values']) >= 2", "applies_to": ["x_values", "y_values"], "description": "At least two data points are required to calculate a regression line."}, {"rule_id": "x_values_variance", "name": "X Values Variance Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "(len(inputs['x_values']) * sum(x**2 for x in inputs['x_values']) - sum(inputs['x_values'])**2) != 0", "applies_to": ["x_values"], "description": "The independent variable (x_values) must have variance (cannot all be the same) to calculate a unique regression line."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    x_values = inputs['x_values']\n    y_values = inputs['y_values']\n    n = len(x_values)\n    sum_x = sum(x_values)\n    sum_y = sum(y_values)\n    sum_x_squared = sum((x ** 2 for x in x_values))\n    sum_xy = sum((x * y for x, y in zip(x_values, y_values)))\n    denominator = n * sum_x_squared - sum_x ** 2\n    slope = (n * sum_xy - sum_x * sum_y) / denominator\n    intercept = (sum_y - slope * sum_x) / n\n    return (slope, intercept)"}, "article_title": "Least Squares Criterion", "article_doc_id": 4089, "article_content_excerpt": "# Least Squares Criterion: What it is, How it Works\n\n## What Is the Least Squares Criterion? \n\nThe least squares criterion is a formula used to measure the accuracy of a straight line in depicting the data that was used to generate it. That is, the formula determines the line of best fit. \n\nThis mathematical formula is used to predict the behavior of the dependent variables. The approach is also called the least squares regression line. \n\n## Understanding the Least Squares Criterion \n\nThe least squares criterion is determined by minimizing the created by a mathematical function. A square is determined by squaring the distance between a data point and the regression line or mean value of the data set. \n\nA least squares analysis begins with a set of data points plotted on a graph. Independent variables are plotted on the horizontal x-axis while dependent variables are plotted on the vertical y-axis. The analyst uses the least squares formula to determine the most accurate straight line that will explain the relationship between an independent variable and a dependent variable. \n\n### Common Uses of Least Squares \n\nAdvances in computing power in addition to new financial engineering techniques have increased the use of least square methods and extended its basic principles. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * The least squares criterion method is used throughout finance, economics, and investing.\n * It is used to estimate the accuracy of a line in depicting the data that was used to create it.\n * Least squares results can be used to summarize data and make predictions about related but unobserved values from the same group or system.\n\nLeast squares and related statistical methods have become commonplace throughout , economics, and investing, even if its beneficiaries aren't always aware of their use. \n\nFor example, the robo-advisors now used by many investing platforms employ Monte Carlo simulation techniques to manage portfolios, though this is accomplished behind the scenes and out of the sight of the account holders who use them. \n\nOther applications include time-series analysis of return distributions, economic forecasting and policy strategy, and advanced option modeling. \n\n### What Does Least Squares Tell You? \n\nInstead of trying to solve an equation exactly, mathematicians use the to arrive at a close approximation. This is referred to as a maximum-likelihood estimate. \n\nThe least squares approach limits the distance between a function and the data points that the function explains. It is used in regression analysis, often in modeling in which a curve is fit into a set of data. \n\n### Important: \n\nMathematicians use the least squares method to arrive at a maximum-likelihood estimate.\n\nThe least squares approach is a popular method for determining regression equations, and it tells you about the relationship between response variables and predictor variables. \n\nModeling methods that are often used when fitting a function to a curve include the straight-line method, the , the logarithmic method, and the Gaussian method. \n\nLinear or ordinary least squares is the simplest and most commonly used linear regression estimator for analyzing observational and experimental data. It finds a straight line of best fit through a set of given data points."}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_1740", "name": "Discrete Distribution", "short_description": "Calculate the probability of a given number of successes in a binomial distribution. This function computes the probability of achieving a specific number of successes in a fixed number of independent Bernoulli trials.", "domain": "financial_markets", "topic": "probability_distributions", "topic_extension": true, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-1740", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-307", "question_id": "test-1926", "difficulty": 3.8712010109078907, "level": "medium", "execution_smoke_ok": false, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "execution_smoke_error": "__import__ not found", "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "c7da06606f3bc76876eaa403a6e88c43ebb4f9311009ab1bb95d8a7b63f05e6e", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["binomial distribution probability", "probability of successes", "independent Bernoulli trials", "trading strategy prediction accuracy", "coin flipping probability", "options pricing probability"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "output_scale", "ambiguity_type": "unit_scale", "trigger_signal": "question asks for decimal, FIC outputs percentage (or vice versa)", "clarification_question": "Should the answer be expressed as a percentage (e.g., 8.0%) or as a decimal (e.g., 0.08)?", "options": [{"label": "Percentage (e.g., 8.0%) \n— DEFAULT", "value": "percent", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Decimal (e.g., 0.08)", "value": "decimal", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "result / 100.0", "max_expr_nodes": 6, "invariant": "result_new == result_old / 100.0", "affected_inputs": []}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Percentage", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "trials", "type": "integer", "required": true, "description": "The number of independent trials.", "u