has a large magnitude, which might indicate an unusual market shock or potential input error. Confirm the value."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": true, "lint_fixes": ["inputs['dW_t'] -> inputs['dw_t']"], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    a = inputs['a']\n    b = inputs['b']\n    r_t = inputs['r_t']\n    sigma = inputs['sigma']\n    dW_t = inputs['dw_t']\n    dt = inputs['dt']\n    dr_t = a * (b - r_t) * dt + sigma * dW_t\n    return dr_t"}, "article_title": "Vasicek Interest Rate Model", "article_doc_id": 423, "article_content_excerpt": "# Vasicek Interest Rate Model Definition, Formula, and Other Models\n\n## What Is the Vasicek Interest Rate Model? \n\nThe term Vasicek Interest Rate Model refers to a mathematical method of modeling the movement and evolution of . It is a single-factor short-rate model that is based on market risk. The Vasicek interest model is commonly used in economics to determine where interest rates will move in the future. Put simply, it estimates where interest rates will move in a given period of time and can be used to help analysts and investors figure out how the economy and investments will fare in the future. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * The Vasicek Interest Rate Model is a single-factor short-rate model that predicts where interest rates will end up at the end of a given period of time.\n * It outlines an interest rate's evolution as a factor composed of market risk, time, and equilibrium value. \n * The model is often used in the valuation of interest rate futures and in solving for the price of various hard-to-value bonds.\n * The Vasicek Model values the instantaneous interest rate using a specific formula.\n * This model also accounts for negative interest rates.\n\n## How the Vasicek Interest Rate Model Works \n\nPredicting how interest rates evolve can be difficult. Investors and analysts have many tools available to help them figure out how they'll change over time in order to make well-informed decisions about how their investments and the . The Vasicek Interest Rate Model is among the models that can be used to help estimate where interest rates will go.\n\nAs noted above, the Vasicek Interest Rate model, which is commonly referred to as the Vasicek model, is a mathematical model used in financial economics to estimate potential pathways for future interest rate changes. As such, it's considered a , which is a form of modeling that helps make investment decisions.\n\nIt outlines the movement of an interest rate as a factor composed of , time, and equilibrium value. The rate tends to revert toward the of these factors over time. The model shows where interest rates will end up at the end of a given period of time by considering current market , the long-run mean interest rate value, and a given market risk factor.\n\nThe Vasicek interest rate model values the instantaneous interest rate using the following equation:\n\n\\begin{aligned} &dr_t = a ( b - r^t ) dt + \\sigma dW_t \\\\\\ &\\textbf{where:} \\\\\\ &W = \\text{Random market risk (represented by}\\\\\\ &\\text{a Wiener process)} \\\\\\ &t = \\text{Time period} \\\\\\ &a(b-r^t) = \\text{Expected change in the interest rate} \\\\\\ &\\text{at time } t \\text{ (the drift factor)} \\\\\\ &a = \\text{Speed of the reversion to the mean} \\\\\\ &b = \\text{Long-term level of the mean} \\\\\\ &\\sigma = \\text{Volatility at time } t \\\\\\ \\end{aligned}\n\nThe model specifies that the instantaneous interest rate follows the stochastic differential equation, where _d_ refers to the derivative of the variable following it. In the absence of market shocks (i.e., when _d_ Wt = 0) the interest rate remains constant (rt = b). When rt < b, the drift factor becomes positive, which indicates that the interest rate will increase toward . \n \n\n### Important: \n\nThe Vasicek model is often used in the valuation of interest rate and may also be used in solving for the price of various hard-to-value .\n\n## Special Considerations \n\nAs mentioned earlier, the Vasicek model is a one- or single-factor short rate model. A single-factor model is one that only recognizes one factor that affects market returns by accounting for interest rates. In this case, is what affects interest rate changes. \n\nThis model also accounts for . Rates that dip below zero can help central bank authorities during times of economic uncertainty. Although negative rates aren't commonplace, they have been proven to help central banks manage their economies. For instance, Denmark's central banks lowered interest rates below zero in 2012. European banks followed two years later followed by th\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_330", "name": "Volume Analysis", "short_description": "Calculate the Positive Volume Index (PVI) based on trading volumes and closing prices. This index helps analyze the influence of high trading volumes on stock prices.", "domain": "financial_markets", "topic": "stock_market_analysis", "topic_extension": false, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-330", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-323", "question_id": "test-1805", "difficulty": 3.465735902799726, "level": "medium", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "fd4c87631d89e0947f992e2fbd241e6034b777da28498d2429c0ce89f75f735d", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["Positive Volume Index", "PVI", "volume analysis", "technical analysis", "stock volume", "price movement", "market strength", "trading decisions"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "volume_units", "ambiguity_type": "input_binding", "trigger_signal": "volume value provided without explicit units (shares, contracts)", "clarification_question": "Are the provided trading volumes specified in number of shares or number of contracts?", "options": [{"label": "Shares (DEFAULT)", "value": "shares", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Contracts", "value": "contracts", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Volumes are expressed in number of shares.", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}, {"id": "price_definition", "ambiguity_type": "input_binding", "trigger_signal": "price inputs may have different interpretations (adjusted vs unadjusted)", "clarification_question": "Are 'closing_price_today' and 'closing_price_yesterday' strictly end-of-day closing prices, or could they represent adjusted closing prices (e.g., for dividends/splits)?", "options": [{"label": "Unadjusted closing prices (DEFAULT)", "value": "unadjusted_closing", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Adjusted closing prices", "value": "adjusted_closing", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Unadjusted closing prices are used.", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}, {"id": "data_frequency", "ambiguity_type": "input_binding", "trigger_signal": "data frequency not explicitly stated for prices and volumes", "clarification_question": "Are the provided prices and volumes based on daily data, or could they represent a different frequency (e.g., weekly, monthly)?", "options": [{"label": "Daily data (DEFAULT)", "value": "daily", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Weekly data", "value": "weekly", "is_default": false}, {"label": "Monthly data", "value": "monthly", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Daily data is assumed for prices and volumes.", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}], "inputs": [{"name": "pvi_previous", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The previous day's Positive Volume Index (PVI) value.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "closing_price_today", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "Today's closing price of the security.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "closing_price_yesterday", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The previous day's closing price of the security.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "current_volume", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "Today's trading volume of the security.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "previous_volume", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The previous day's trading volume of the security.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "pvi", "type": "number", "unit": null, "description": "The updated Positive Volume Index (PVI), rounded to the nearest integer."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    pvi_previous = inputs['pvi_previous']\n    closing_price_today = inputs['closing_price_today']\n    closing_price_yesterday = inputs['closing_price_yesterday']\n    current_volume = inputs['current_volume']\n    previous_volume = inputs['previous_volume']\n    if current_volume > previous_volume:\n        price_change_ratio = (closing_price_today - closing_price_yesterday) / closing_price_yesterday\n        pvi = pvi_previous + price_change_ratio * pvi_previous\n    else:\n        pvi = pvi_previous\n    return round(pvi)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "pvi_previous_missing", "name": "Previous PVI is Missing", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "'pvi_previous' not in inputs", "applies_to": ["pvi_previous"], "description": "The previous PVI value is a required input for calculating the updated Positive Volume Index."}, {"rule_id": "pvi_previous_value_non_negative", "name": "Previous PVI must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs.get('pvi_previous', 0) < 0", "applies_to": ["pvi_previous"], "description": "The previous PVI value should not be negative as it represents an index level."}, {"rule_id": "closing_price_yesterday_positive", "name": "Yesterday's Closing Price Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs.get('closing_price_yesterday', 0) <= 0", "applies_to": ["closing_price_yesterday"], "description": "Yesterday's closing price must be greater than zero to correctly calculate the percentage price change ratio and avoid division by zero."}, {"rule_id": "closing_prices_non_negative", "name": "Closing Prices Must Be Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs.get('closing_price_today', 0) < 0 or inputs.get('closing_price_yesterday', 0) < 0", "applies_to": ["closing_price_today", "closing_price_yesterday"], "description": "Closing prices cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "volumes_non_negative", "name": "Trading Volumes Must Be Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs.get('current_volume', 0) < 0 or inputs.get('previous_volume', 0) < 0", "applies_to": ["current_volume", "previous_volume"], "description": "Trading volumes cannot be negative."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    pvi_previous = inputs['pvi_previous']\n    closing_price_today = inputs['closing_price_today']\n    closing_price_yesterday = inputs['closing_price_yesterday']\n    current_volume = inputs['current_volume']\n    previous_volume = inputs['previous_volume']\n    if current_volume > previous_volume:\n        price_change_ratio = (closing_price_today - closing_price_yesterday) / closing_price_yesterday\n        pvi = pvi_previous + price_change_ratio * pvi_previous\n    else:\n        pvi = pvi_previous\n    return round(pvi)"}, "article_title": "Volume Analysis", "article_doc_id": 503, "article_content_excerpt": "# Volume Analysis: How to Calculate its Meaning\n\n## What Is Volume Analysis? \n\nVolume analysis is the examination of the number of shares or contracts of a that have been traded in a given period. Volume analysis is used by technical analysts as one of many factors that inform their trading decisions. By analyzing trends in volume in conjunction with price movements, investors can determine the significance of changes in a security's price. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Volume analysis involves examining relative or absolute changes in an asset's trading volume to make inferences about future price movements.\n * Volume can be an indicator of market strength, as rising markets on increasing volume are typically viewed as strong and healthy. When prices fall on increasing volume, the trend is gathering strength to the downside.\n * Various tools, such as the positive volume index (PVI) employ volume in technical analysis.\n\n## Understanding Volume Analysis \n\nVolume analysis is done by all types of analysts following specific securities in the financial markets. Generally, refers to the number of shares transacted per day. Having an understanding of the entire market’s trading volume versus the volume of a single holding can be one important comparison that helps analysts to . \n\nOftentimes, high volumes of trading can infer a lot about investors’ outlook on a market or security. A significant price increase along with a significant volume increase, for example, could be a credible sign of a continued bullish trend or a bullish reversal. Adversely, a significant price decrease with a significant volume increase can point to a continued bearish trend or a bearish trend reversal. \n\nIn general, it can be important for technical analysts to include volume charts in daily charting diagrams. Volume charts are usually available below a standard graph. These charts will also usually display moving average trendlines. \n\n can help an investor to have a more balanced view of all the broad market factors that could be influencing a security’s price which helps an investor to make a more informed decision. \n\n## Volume Indicators \n\nIn technical analysis, there are two popular indicators designed specifically to support investors that incorporate volume into their trading decisions. The and Negative Volume Index (NVI) were developed by Paul Dysart in the 1930s. These indexes increased in popularity in 1975 when they were discussed in a 1976 book titled \"Stock Market Logic\" by Norman Fosback. \n\nThe PVI and NVI are both based on the previous day’s trading volume and a security’s market price. When trading volume increases from the previous day the PVI is adjusted. When trading volume decreases from the previous day the NVI is adjusted. These basic index calculations show how volume is affecting price. \n\nWhen PVI increases or decreases, it means that price changes are being driven by high volumes. Conversely, when NVI increases or decreases it means that prices are fluctuating with little effect from volume. \n\n## Calculating the Positive Volume Index \n\nIf current volume is greater than the previous day's volume: \n\n> \\begin{aligned} &\\text{PVI} = \\text{PVI}_{previous} + \\left(\\frac{\\text{CP}_{today}-\\text{CP}_{yesterday}}{\\text{CP}_{yesterday}}\\right) * \\text{PVI}_{previous} \\\\\\ &\\textbf{where:}\\\\\\ &\\text{PVI}_{previous} = \\text{The previous PVI}\\\\\\ &\\text{CP}_{today} = \\text{Today's closing price}\\\\\\ &\\text{CP}_{previous} = \\text{The previous closing price}\\\\\\ \\end{aligned}\n\nIf current volume is lower than the previous day's volume, PVI is unchanged. \n\n### Negative Volume Index \n\nIf the current volume is less than the previous day’s volume: \n\n> \\begin{aligned} &\\text{NVI} = \\text{NVI}_{previous} + \\left(\\frac{\\text{CP}_{today}-\\text{CP}_{yesterday}}{\\text{CP}_{yesterday}}\\right) * \\text{NVI}_{previous} \\\\\\ &\\textbf{where:}\\\\\\ &\\text{NVI}_{previous} = \\text{The previous NVI}\\\\\\ &\\text{CP}_{today} = \\text{Today's closing price}\\\\\\ &\\text{CP}_{previous} = \\te\n...[truncated]"}
