onthly fees. It's usually easier and cheaper to consolidate debt on your own with a personal loan from a bank or a low-interest credit card.\n\n## Types of Debt Consolidation Loans \n\nYou can consolidate debt by using different types of loans or credit cards. Which will be best for you will dep\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_1558", "name": "Revenue Generating Unit (RGU)", "short_description": "Calculate the average revenue per unit (ARPU) for a given period. This function computes the ARPU by dividing the total revenue by the average number of units (or users) during the specified period. ARPU is a common metric used by telecom, media, and internet services companies to assess revenue generation per user or unit.", "domain": "financial_ratios", "topic": "average_revenue_per_unit", "topic_extension": true, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-1558", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-966", "question_id": "test-1035", "difficulty": 2.4849066497880004, "level": "medium", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "179fa1cb952bc058ea468281c3efe92c2353a7398f029a614471857bbe5f4ab4", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["Average Revenue Per Unit", "ARPU", "Revenue Generating Unit", "RGU", "subscriber revenue", "telecom metric", "media services revenue"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "output_currency_scale", "ambiguity_type": "unit_scale", "trigger_signal": "currency unit for ARPU not explicitly specified or implied", "clarification_question": "Should the Average Revenue Per Unit (ARPU) be expressed in dollars per unit or cents per unit?", "options": [{"label": "Dollars per unit (e.g., 80.00) - DEFAULT", "value": "dollars_per_unit", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Cents per unit (e.g., 8000 cents)", "value": "cents_per_unit", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "result * 100.0", "max_expr_nodes": 6, "invariant": "result_new == result_old * 100.0", "affected_inputs": []}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Dollars per unit", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "total_revenue", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The total revenue generated during the period.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "start_units", "type": "integer", "required": true, "description": "The number of units/users at the beginning of the period.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "end_units", "type": "integer", "required": true, "description": "The number of units/users at the end of the period.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "arpu", "type": "number", "unit": "currency_per_unit", "description": "The average revenue per unit for the period."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    total_revenue = inputs['total_revenue']\n    start_units = inputs['start_units']\n    end_units = inputs['end_units']\n    average_units = (start_units + end_units) / 2\n    arpu = total_revenue / average_units\n    return arpu", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "r001", "name": "Total Revenue is Required", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "total_revenue is None", "applies_to": ["total_revenue"], "description": "The total revenue input is missing. It is required to calculate ARPU."}, {"rule_id": "r002", "name": "Start Units are Required", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "start_units is None", "applies_to": ["start_units"], "description": "The start units input is missing. It is required to calculate ARPU."}, {"rule_id": "r003", "name": "End Units are Required", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "end_units is None", "applies_to": ["end_units"], "description": "The end units input is missing. It is required to calculate ARPU."}, {"rule_id": "r004", "name": "Total Revenue Must Be Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "total_revenue < 0", "applies_to": ["total_revenue"], "description": "Total revenue cannot be negative, as this would imply revenue loss rather than generation for ARPU calculation."}, {"rule_id": "r005", "name": "Start Units Must Be Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "start_units < 0", "applies_to": ["start_units"], "description": "The number of units at the beginning of the period cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "r006", "name": "End Units Must Be Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "end_units < 0", "applies_to": ["end_units"], "description": "The number of units at the end of the period cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "r007", "name": "Average Units Cannot Be Zero", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "(start_units + end_units) == 0", "applies_to": ["start_units", "end_units"], "description": "The average number of units cannot be zero, as this would lead to division by zero in the ARPU calculation."}, {"rule_id": "r008", "name": "ARPU Must Be Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "compute(inputs) < 0", "applies_to": ["total_revenue", "start_units", "end_units"], "description": "A negative Average Revenue Per Unit (ARPU) indicates an unusual scenario, typically revenue loss without offsetting units. Review inputs."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    total_revenue = inputs['total_revenue']\n    start_units = inputs['start_units']\n    end_units = inputs['end_units']\n    average_units = (start_units + end_units) / 2\n    arpu = total_revenue / average_units\n    return arpu"}, "article_title": "Revenue Generating Unit (RGU)", "article_doc_id": 3049, "article_content_excerpt": "# Revenue Generating Unit (RGU): What it is, How it Works\n\n## What Is a Revenue Generating Unit (RGU)? \n\nA revenue generating unit (RGU) is an individual service subscriber who generates for a company. This is used as a performance measure for management, analysts, and investors. \n\nRGUs are tracked by telecom companies, cable companies, and other businesses that have a base of subscribers for a service. RGU growth can occur or through acquisitions. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * A revenue generating unit (RGU) refers to a service subscriber or user that creates ongoing sources of income for a firm.\n * Telecom, media, and internet services companies are most likely to keep track of RGU data and to try to increase RGU flows.\n * The average revenue per unit measures the mean revenue generated per RGU.\n\n## Understanding Revenue Generating Units (RGUs) \n\nRevenue generating units (RGUs) are subscribers—either individuals or businesses, but most commonly applied to individuals—who pay for monthly services such as mobile phones, internet, streaming services, or cable TV. \n\nRGUs as a term has become interchangeable with \"customer relationships,\" \"customers\" or simply \"subscribers,\" where users are the \"units\" in question. Whatever a company decides to name them, it compiles this data, segments, and analyzes. RGU figures are often used to calculate (ARPU), another key metric for the telecom and cable industries. \n\nA company is interested in net additions to RGUs. It will analyze where RGUs were added geographically and in which product lines. The company will attempt to attribute these gains in subscribers to a particular marketing campaign or change in the competitive landscape. Similarly, if there were RGU losses, it would try to determine the reasons and take steps to address the attrition. \n\n## Finding RGU Data \n\n is a good example of a company that breaks down its RGU data. \n\nIts quarterly and annual filings contain RGU tables that segment cable service type (voice, video, data), mobile service type (prepaid, postpaid), and by countries where the company operates. Net additions or losses of RGUs are then discussed in the company's , or management discussion and analysis.\n\n## Average Revenue Per Unit (ARPU) \n\nThe average revenue per unit is equivalent to total revenue divided by average units (or users) during a period. The period-end date is not the measure date for the denominator because the number of units can fluctuate intra-period. Instead, the beginning of the period and the end of the period numbers are typically averaged. \n\nHowever, the number of units or users may not remain constant throughout the standard time period. It can vary somewhat from day to day, as new users appear or old users cease to take advantage of a service. Therefore, the number of units for a given period must be estimated in order to give the most accurate ARPU figure possible for that period. \n\nIn order to accurately calculate ARPU, one must first define a standard time period. Most telephone and communications carriers, for example, calculate ARPU on a month-to-month basis. The total revenue generated during the standard time period should then be divided by the number of units or users."}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_1213", "name": "Growth Industry", "short_description": "Calculates the Compound Annual Growth Rate (CAGR) of an investment over a specified period, assuming steady growth. Frequently used to evaluate the growth potential of investments.", "domain": "investment_analysis", "topic": "compound_annual_growth_rate", "topic_extension": true, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-1213", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-709", "question_id": "test-1442", "difficulty": 2.772588722239781, "level": "medium", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "bb6f14f14293c1c107a3d7d8f75cf0cba0117b9fca35b8a253eb004e0c613335", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["compound annual growth rate", "CAGR", "investment growth", "average growth rate", "tech startup valuation", "growth industry"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "output_scale", "ambiguity_type": "unit_scale", "trigger_signal": "Output is a rate/percentage, user might expect a different scale (decimal vs. percentage). The question explicitly asked for percentage.", "clarification_question": "Should the compound annual growth rate be expressed as a decimal (e.g., 0.08) or a percentage (e.g., 8.0%)?", "options": [{"label": "Decimal — DEFAULT", "value": "decimal", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Percentage", "value": "percent", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "result * 100.0", "max_expr_nodes": 6, "invariant": "result_new == result_old * 100.0", "affected_inputs": []}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Decimal (as per function's natural output)", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "beginning_value", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The initial value of the investment.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "ending_value", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The value of the investment at the end of the period.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "num_years", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The total number of years over which the growth is measured.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "cagr", "type": "number", "unit": "decimal", "description": "The compound annual growth rate, expressed as a decimal."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    beginning_value = inputs['beginning_value']\n    ending_value = inputs['ending_value']\n    num_years = inputs['num_years']\n    if beginning_value <= 0 or ending_value <= 0 or num_years <= 0:\n        raise ValueError('All input values must be greater than zero.')\n    cagr = (ending_value / beginning_value) ** (1 / num_years) - 1\n    return cagr", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "cagr_bv_type", "name": "Beginning Value Type Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['beginning_value'], (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "Beginning value must be a number."}, {"rule_id": "cagr_ev_type", "name": "Ending Value Type Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['ending_value'], (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "Ending value must be a number."}, {"rule_id": "cagr_ny_type", "name": "Number of Years Type Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['num_years'], (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "Number of years must be a number."}, {"rule_id": "cagr_bv_positive", "name": "Beginning Value Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity"