n", "expression": "'purchase_price' not in inputs", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'purchase_price' input is required for calculation."}, {"rule_id": "bey_input_days_to_maturity_f3", "name": "Days to Maturity Missing", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "'days_to_maturity' not in inputs", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'days_to_maturity' input is required for calculation."}, {"rule_id": "bey_face_value_e1", "name": "Face Value Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['face_value'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The bond's face value must be a positive number."}, {"rule_id": "bey_purchase_price_e2", "name": "Purchase Price Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['purchase_price'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The bond's purchase price must be a positive number."}, {"rule_id": "bey_days_to_maturity_e3", "name": "Days to Maturity Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['days_to_maturity'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The number of days to maturity must be a positive integer."}, {"rule_id": "bey_discounted_bond_e4", "name": "Bond Not Discounted or Zero Return", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['face_value'] <= inputs['purchase_price']", "applies_to": [], "description": "For a 'discounted bond', the face value is typically greater than the purchase price. A non-positive return will be calculated otherwise."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    face_value = inputs['face_value']\n    purchase_price = inputs['purchase_price']\n    days_to_maturity = inputs['days_to_maturity']\n    return_on_investment = (face_value - purchase_price) / purchase_price\n    bey = return_on_investment * (365 / days_to_maturity) * 100\n    return bey"}, "article_title": "Bond Equivalent Yield (BEY)", "article_doc_id": 1394, "article_content_excerpt": "# Bond Equivalent Yield (BEY): Definition, Formula, and Example\n\n## What Is the Bond Equivalent Yield? \n\nIn financial terms, the bond equivalent yield (BEY) is a metric that lets investors calculate the annual percentage yield for , even if they are discounted short-term plays that only pay out on a monthly, quarterly, or semi-annual basis. \n\nHowever, by having BEY figures at their fingertips, investors can compare the performance of these investments with those of traditional fixed income securities that last a year or more and produce annual yields. This empowers investors to make more informed choices when constructing their overall fixed-income portfolios. \n\n## Understanding Bond Equivalent Yield \n\nTo truly understand how the bond equivalent yield formula works, it's important to know the basics of bonds in general and to grasp how bonds differ from stocks. \n\nCompanies looking to raise capital may either issue stocks (equities) or bonds (fixed income). , which are distributed to investors in the form of common shares, have the potential to earn higher returns than bonds, but they also carry greater risk. Specifically, if a company files for bankruptcy and subsequently liquidates its assets, its bondholders are first in line to collect any cash. Only if there are assets left over do shareholders see any money. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Fixed income securities come in different forms.\n * Discounted (zero-coupon) bonds have shorter durations than traditional fixed income securities, which makes it impossible to calculate their annual yields.\n * The bond equivalent yield (BEY) formula can help approximate what a discounted bond would pay annually, letting investors compare their returns with those of traditional bonds.\n\nBut even if a company remains solvent, its earnings may nonetheless fall short of expectations. This could depress share prices and cause losses to stockholders. But that same company is legally obligated to pay back its debt to bondholders, regardless of how profitable it may or may not be. \n\nNot all bonds are the same. Most bonds pay investors annual or semi-annual interest payments. But some bonds, referred to as zero-coupon bonds, do not pay interest at all. Instead, they are issued at a deep discount to par, and investors collect returns when the bond matures. To compare the return on discounted fixed income securities with the returns on traditional bonds, analysts rely on the bond equivalent yield formula. \n\n## A Closer Look at the Bond Equivalent Yield Formula \n\nThe bond equivalent yield formula is calculated by dividing the difference between the face value of the bond and the purchase price of the bond, by the price of the bond. That answer is then multiplied by 365 divided by \"d,\" which represents the number of days left until the bond's maturity. In other words, the first part of the equation is the standard return formula used to calculate traditional bond yields, while the second part of the formula annualizes the first part, to determine the equivalent figure for discounted bonds. \n\n### Important: \n\nAlthough calculating the bond equivalent yield can be complicated, most modern spreadsheets contain built-in BEY calculators that can simplify the process.\n\nStill confused? Consider the following example. \n\nAssume an investor buys a $1,000 zero-coupon bond for $900 and expects to be paid par value in six months. In this case, the investor would pocket $100. To determine BEY, we take the bond's face value (par) and subtract the actual price paid for the bond: \n\n * $1,000 - $900 = $100\n\nWe then divide $100 by $900 to obtain the return on investment, which is 11%. The second portion of the formula annualizes 11% by multiplying it by 365 divided by the number of days until the bond matures, which is half of 365. The bond equivalent yield is thus 11% multiplied by two, which comes out to 22%."}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_440", "name": "Interest Rate", "short_description": "Calculates the compound interest earned on an investment or loan given principal, interest rate, and number of compounding periods.", "domain": "investment_analysis", "topic": "ci", "topic_extension": false, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-440", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-699", "question_id": "test-1437", "difficulty": 2.772588722239781, "level": "medium", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "8c40d28788fb079000ae3edb211b812edcc0e46886d777cbb4206b91ff4c885d", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["compound interest calculation", "investment growth", "loan interest earned", "future value of investment", "interest on savings"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "interest_rate_format", "ambiguity_type": "unit_scale", "trigger_signal": "interest rate value might be provided as a percentage or decimal", "clarification_question": "Is the provided interest rate (e.g., 4 for 4%, or 0.04 for 4%) a percentage or a decimal?", "options": [{"label": "Decimal (e.g., 0.04 for 4%) - DEFAULT", "value": "decimal", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Percentage (e.g., 4 for 4%) - divide by 100", "value": "percentage_to_decimal", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Decimal (e.g., 0.04 for 4%)", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}], "inputs": [{"name": "principal", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The initial amount of money loaned or invested.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "interest_rate", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The interest rate per compounding period (as a decimal).", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "n", "type": "integer", "required": true, "description": "The number of compounding periods.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "interest", "type": "number", "unit": "currency", "description": "The calculated compound interest over the specified number of periods."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    principal = inputs['principal']\n    interest_rate = inputs['interest_rate']\n    n = inputs['n']\n    compound_interest = principal * ((1 + interest_rate) ** n - 1)\n    return round(compound_interest)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "ci_001", "name": "Positive Principal", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "principal > 0", "applies_to": ["principal"], "description": "The principal amount must be a positive value."}, {"rule_id": "ci_002", "name": "Non-negative Interest Rate", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "interest_rate >= 0", "applies_to": ["interest_rate"], "description": "The interest rate cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "ci_003", "name": "Positive Compounding Periods", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "n > 0", "applies_to": ["n"], "description": "The number of compounding periods must be a positive integer."}, {"rule_id": "ci_004", "name": "Integer Compounding Periods Type", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(n, int)", "applies_to": ["n"], "description": "The number of compounding periods 'n' must be an integer."}, {"rule_id": "ci_005", "name": "Interest Rate Format Alert", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "interest_rate >= 1.0", "applies_to": ["interest_rate"], "description": "The interest rate appears to be entered as a percentage (e.g., 4 for 4%) rather than a decimal (e.g., 0.04). Confirm the correct format."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    principal = inputs['principal']\n    interest_rate = inputs['interest_rate']\n    n = inputs['n']\n    compound_interest = principal * ((1 + interest_rate) ** n - 1)\n    return round(compound_interest)"}, "article_title": "Interest Rate", "article_doc_id": 704, "article_content_excerpt": "# Interest Rates: Different Types and What They Mean to Borrowers\n\n## What Is an Interest Rate? \n\nThe interest rate is the amount a lender charges a borrower and is a percentage of the principal—the amount loaned. The interest rate on a loan is typically noted on an annual basis and expressed as an (APR).\n\nAn interest rate can also apply to a savings account or (CD). In this case, a bank or credit union pays a percentage of the funds deposited to the account holder. (APY) refers to the interest earned on these deposit accounts.\n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * The interest rate is the amount charged on top of the principal by a lender to a borrower for the use of assets.\n * An interest rate also applies to the amount earned at a bank or credit union from a deposit account.\n * Most mortgages use simple interest. However, some loans use compound interest, which is applied to the principal but also to the accumulated interest of previous periods.\n * A borrower that is considered low-risk by the lender will have a lower interest rate. A loan that is considered high-risk will have a higher interest rate.\n * The APY is the interest rate that is earned at a bank or credit union from a savings account or CD. Savings accounts and CDs use compounded interest.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/interest-rates-1d0e17952d9949b1bab273e830855f90.png)\n\nInvestopedia / Julie Bang\n\n## Understanding Interest Rates \n\nInterest is essentially a charge to the borrower for the use of an asset. Assets borrowed can include cash, consumer goods, vehicles, and property. Because of this, an interest rate can be thought of as the \"cost of money\"—higher interest rates make borrowing the same amount of money more expensive. \n\nInterest rates transactions. Individuals borrow money to purchase homes, fund projects, launch or fund businesses, or pay for college tuition. Businesses take out loans to fund capital projects and expand their operations by purchasing fixed and long-term assets such as land, buildings, and machinery. Borrowed money is repaid either in a lump sum by a pre-determined date or in periodic installments. \n\nFor loans, the interest rate is applied to the principal, which is the amount of the loan. The interest rate is the for the borrower and the rate of return for the lender. The money to be repaid is usually more than the borrowed amount since lenders require compensation for the loss of use of the money during the loan period. The lender could have invested the funds during that period instead of providing a loan, which would have generated income from the asset. The difference between the total repayment sum and the original loan is the interest charged. \n\nWhen the borrower is considered to be low risk by the lender, the borrower will usually be charged a lower interest rate. If the borrower is considered high risk, the interest rate that they are charged will be higher, which results in a higher cost loan. \n\n### Important: \n\nRisk is typically assessed when a lender looks at a potential borrower's credit score, which is why it's important to have an excellent one if you want to qualify for the best loans.\n\n## Simple Interest Rate \n\nIf you take out a $300,000 loan from the bank and the loan agreement stipulates that the interest rate on the loan is 4% simple interest, this means that you will have to pay the bank the original loan amount of $300,000 + (4% x $300,000) = $300,000 + $12,000 = $312,000. \n\nThe example above was calculated based on the annual formula, which is: \n\n> **Simple interest** = principal x interest rate x time \n\nThe individual who took out the loan will have to pay $12,000 in interest at the end of the year, assuming it was only a one-year lending agreement. If the loan was a 30-year mortgage, the interest payment will be: \n\n**Simple interest** = $300,000 x 4% x 30 = $360,000 \n\nA simple interest rate of 4% annually translates into an annual interest payment of $12,000. After 30 years, the borrower would have made $12,000 x 30 year\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_477", "name": "Investing", "short_description": "Calculate the total return on an investment over a specified period. This function computes the total return as a percentage, which includes any capital gains and dividends received during the holding period.", "domain": "investment_analysis", "topic": "roi", "topic_extension": false, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-477", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-601", "question_id": "test-1578", "difficulty": 2.995732273553991, "level": "medium", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "13c42393916d11fc45d932e42ef9c837eed115b0fc22f8384694881115d478f1", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["investment return", "total return calculation", "capital gains", "dividends", "investment performance", "return on investment"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "output_scale", "ambiguity_type": "unit_scale", "trigger_signal": "Output is a percentage, but user might expect a decimal value.", "clarification_question": "Should the total return be expressed as a decimal (e.g., 0.08 for 8%) or a percentage (e.g., 8.0)?", "options": [{"label": "Percentage (e.g., 8.0) — DEFAULT", "value": "percentage", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Decimal (e.g., 0.08)", "value": "decimal", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "result / 100.0", "max_expr_nodes": 6, "invariant": "result_new == result_old / 100.0", "affected_inputs": []}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "The output is a percentage (e.g., 8.0 for 8%).", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "initial_investment", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The initial amount invested.", "unit": null, "aliases": ["initial_capital", "principal_invested"]}, {"name": "final_value", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The final value of the investment at the end of the period.", "unit": null, "aliases": ["ending_value", "market_value", "investment_value_end"]}, {"name": "dividends", "type": "number", "required": false, "description": "Any dividends received during the holding period. Defaults to 0.0.", "unit": null, "aliases": ["cash_dividends", "income_received", "yield_income"]}], "output": {"name": "total_return", "type": "number", "unit": "%", "description": "The total return on the investment as a percentage."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    initial_investment = inputs['initial_investment']\n    final_value = inputs['final_value']\n    dividends = inputs.get('dividends', 0.0)\n    if initial_investment <= 0:\n        raise ValueError('Initial investment must be greater than 0.')\n    total_value = final_value + dividends\n    total_return = (total_value - initial_investment) / initial_investment * 100\n    return total_return", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "initial_investment_missing", "name": "Required input 'initial_investment' is missing", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "'initial_investment' not in inputs", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'initial_investment' is a required input for calculating total return."}, {"rule_id": "final_value_missing", "name": "Required input 'final_value' is missing", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "'final_value' not in inputs", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'final_value' of the investment is a required input."}, {"rule_id": "initial_investment_type_check", "name": "Initial investment must be a number", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not isinstance(inputs.get('initial_investment'), (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'initial_investment' must be a numeric value."}, {"rule_id": "final_value_type_check", "name": "Final value must be a number", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not isinstance(inputs.get('final_value'), (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'final_value' must be a numeric value."}, {"rule_id": "dividends_type_check", "name": "Dividends must be a number", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs.get('dividends') is not None and not isinstance(inputs.get('dividends'), (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "If provided, 'dividends' must be a numeric value."}, {"rule_id": "initial_investment_positive", "name": "Initial Investment must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['initial_investment'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The initial investment amount must be greater than zero."}, {"rule_id": "final_value_non_negative", "name": "Final Value should be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['final_value'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The final value of an investment is typically expected to be non-negative. A negative value may indicate a substantial loss or an input error."}, {"rule_id": "dividends_non_negative", "name": "Dividends should be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs.get('dividends', 0.0) < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Dividends received are typically non-negative. A negative value might indicate an error."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    initial_investment = inputs['initial_investment']\n    final_value = inputs['final_value']\n    dividends = inputs.get('dividends', 0.0)\n    if initial_investment <= 0:\n        raise ValueError('Initial investment must be greater than 0.')\n    total_value = final_value + dividends\n    total_return = (total_value - initial_investment) / initial_investment * 100\n    return total_return"}, "article_title": "Investing", "article_doc_id": 772, "article_content_excerpt": "# Investing Explained: Types of Investments and How to Get Started\n\n## What Is Investing? \n\nInvesting, broadly, is putting money to work for a period of time in a project or undertaking to generate positive returns (profits that exceed the amount of the initial investment). It's the act of allocating resources, usually capital (i.e., money), with the expectation of generating an income, profit, or gains. \n\nYou can invest in many types of endeavors, either directly or indirectly. You might use money to start a business or buy assets such as real estate in hopes of generating rental income or reselling it later at a higher price. \n\nInvesting also differs from speculation, as evidenced by the investor's timeframe. Speculators are typically looking to gain from short-term price fluctuations that occur in weeks, days, or even minutes. Investors usually consider that a greater period of time, like months or years, is needed to generate acceptable returns.\n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Investing involves deploying capital (money) toward projects or activities expected to generate a positive return over time.\n * The type of returns generated depends on the type of project or asset; real estate can produce both rents and capital gains; many stocks pay quarterly dividends; bonds tend to pay regular interest.\n * In investing, risk and return are two sides of the same coin; low risk generally means low expected returns, while higher returns are usually accompanied by higher risk.\n * Investors can take the do-it-yourself approach or employ the services of a professional money manager.\n * Whether buying a security qualifies as investing or speculation depends on four factors: the amount of risk taken, the holding period, the frequency of the investment activity, and the source of returns.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/investing.asp-final-9cbfccbd50344a828ddf1882a2fdc07c.png)\n\nInvestopedia / Sydney Saporito\n\n## Understanding Investing \n\nInvesting is to grow one's money over time. The core premise of investing is the expectation of a positive return in the form of income or price appreciation with . The spectrum of assets in which one can invest and earn a return is vast. \n\n go hand-in-hand in investing; low risk generally means low expected returns, while higher returns are usually accompanied by higher risk. At the low-risk end of the spectrum are basic investments such as certificates of deposit (CDs). Bonds or fixed-income instruments are higher up on the risk scale, while stocks or equities are regarded as riskier. \n\nCommodities and derivatives are generally considered to be among the riskiest investments. One can also invest in something practical, such as land, real estate, or items such as fine art and antiques. \n\nRisk and return expectations can vary widely within the same asset class. For example, a that trades on the New York Stock Exchange will have a very different risk-return profile from a that trades on a small exchange. \n\nThe returns generated by an asset depend on its type. For instance, many stocks pay quarterly dividends, whereas bonds generally pay interest every quarter. In many jurisdictions, . \n\nIn addition to regular income, such as a dividend or interest, price appreciation is an important component of return. Total return from an investment can thus be regarded as the sum of income and capital appreciation. \n\nStandard & Poor's estimates that from 1926 to 2023, dividends have contributed approximately 32% of total return for the S&P 500 while capital gains have contributed 68%. are, therefore, an important piece of investing.\n\n### Note\n\nEconomists view investing and saving to be two sides of the same coin. This is because when you save money by depositing in a bank, the bank then lends that money to individuals or companies that want to borrow that money to put it to good use. Therefore, your savings are often someone else's investment.\n\n## Types of Investments \n\nToday, investment is mostly associated with financial i\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_2870", "name": "Negative Convexity", "short_description": "Calculates the convexity approximation of a bond using a simplified formula. Convexity is a measure of a bond's price sensitivity to interest rate changes, beyond what duration alone provides, and is important for risk management and enhancing price-movement predictions.", "domain": "risk_management", "topic": "risk_metrics", "topic_extension": false, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-2870", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-495", "question_id": "test-1750", "difficulty": 3.332204510175204, "level": "medium", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "46a8786892b2fe046fa5a6756e9ac62de7a40dc66219674da303a30e830fb51b", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["bond convexity", "convexity approximation", "interest rate risk", "bond price sensitivity", "callable bonds", "mortgage bonds", "market risk exposure"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "dy_scale_basis", "ambiguity_type": "unit_scale", "trigger_signal": "The 'change in interest rate' (dy) is provided without explicit unit or scale confirmation (decimal vs. percentage).", "clarification_question": "Is the 'change in interest rate' (dy) input provided as a decimal (e.g., 0.01 for 1%) or as a percentage (e.g., 1 for 1%)?", "options": [{"label": "Decimal form (e.g., 0.01 for 1%) - DEFAULT", "value": "decimal", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Percentage form (e.g., 1 for 1%)", "value": "percent", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "hard", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "The change in interest rate (dy) is provided in decimal form (e.g., 0.01 for 1%).", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}], "inputs": [{"name": "p_plus", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "Bond price when interest rate is decreased.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "p_minus", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "Bond price when interest rate is increased.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "p_zero", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "Current bond price.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "dy", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "Change in interest rate in decimal form. Represents the magnitude of the rate change.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "convexity_approximation", "type": "number", "unit": null, "description": "The approximate convexity of the bond."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    p_plus = inputs['p_plus']\n    p_minus = inputs['p_minus']\n    p_zero = inputs['p_zero']\n    dy = inputs['dy']\n    convexity_approximation = (p_plus + p_minus - 2 * p_zero) / (2 * p_zero * dy ** 2)\n    return convexity_approximation", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "input_p_plus_invalid_type", "name": "Check for valid p_plus input type", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not isinstance(inputs.get('p_plus'), (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "The input 'p_plus' (bond price when interest rate is decreased) must be a numeric value."}, {"rule_id": "input_p_minus_invalid_type", "name": "Check for valid p_minus input type", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not isinstance(inputs.get('p_minus'), (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "The input 'p_minus' (bond price when interest rate is increased) must be a numeric value."}, {"rule_id": "input_p_zero_invalid_type", "name": "Check for valid p_zero input type", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not isinstance(inputs.get('p_zero'), (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "The input 'p_zero' (current bond price) must be a numeric value."}, {"rule_id": "input_dy_invalid_type", "name": "Check for valid dy input type", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not isinstance(inputs.get('dy'), (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "The input 'dy' (change in interest rate) must be a numeric value."}, {"rule_id": "p_zero_positive", "name": "Current bond price must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['p_zero'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The current bond price (p_zero) must be a positive value to represent a valid bond price."}, {"rule_id": "dy_non_zero", "name": "Change in interest rate (dy) cannot be zero", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['dy'] == 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The change in interest rate (dy) cannot be zero, as it is used in the denominator of the convexity formula, which would lead to a division by zero error."}, {"rule_id": "dy_magnitude_positive", "name": "Change in interest rate (dy) should be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['dy'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "While mathematically valid for the formula due to squaring, 'dy' as a 'change in interest rate' conventionally represents a positive magnitude. A negative value might indicate an unconventional interpretation or a misunderstanding of the input's expected sign."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    p_plus = inputs['p_plus']\n    p_minus = inputs['p_minus']\n    p_zero = inputs['p_zero']\n    dy = inputs['dy']\n    convexity_approximation = (p_plus + p_minus - 2 * p_zero) / (2 * p_zero * dy ** 2)\n    return convexity_approximation"}, "article_title": "Negative Convexity", "article_doc_id": 5784, "article_content_excerpt": "# Negative Convexity: Definition, Example, Simplified Formula\n\n## What Is Negative Convexity? \n\nNegative convexity exists when the shape of a bond's is concave. A bond's convexity is the of its duration, and it is measured as the second of the bond's price with respect to its yield. Most mortgage bonds are negatively convex, and callable bonds usually exhibit negative convexity at lower yields. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Negative convexity exists when the price of a bond falls as well as interest rates, resulting in a concave yield curve. \n * Assessing a bond's convexity is a great way to measure and manage a portfolio's exposure to market risk.\n\n## Understanding Negative Convexity \n\nA bond's refers to the degree to which a bond's price is impacted by the rise and fall of interest rates. Convexity demonstrates how the duration of a bond changes as the interest rate changes. Typically, when interest rates decrease, a bond's price increases. However, for bonds that have negative convexity, prices decrease as interest rates fall. \n\nFor example, with a callable bond, as interest rates fall, the incentive for the issuer to call the bond increases; therefore, its price will not rise as quickly as the price of a non-callable bond. The price of a might actually drop as the likelihood that the bond will be called increases. This is why the shape of a callable bond's curve of price with respect to yield is concave or negatively convex. \n\n## Convexity Calculation Example \n\nSince duration is an imperfect price change estimator, investors, analysts, and traders . Convexity is a useful risk-management tool and is used to measure and manage a portfolio's exposure to market risk. This helps to increase the accuracy of price-movement predictions. \n\nWhile the exact formula for convexity is rather complicated, an approximation for convexity can be found using the following simplified formula: \n\nConvexity approximation = (P(+) + P(-) - 2 x P(0)) / (2 x P(0) x dy ^2) \n\nWhere: \n\nP(+) = bond price when interest rate is decreased \n\nP(-) = bond price when interest rate is increased \n\nP(0) = bond price \n\ndy = change in interest rate in decimal form \n\nFor example, assume a bond is currently priced at $1,000. If interest rates are decreased by 1%, the bond's new price is $1,035. If interest rates are increased by 1%, the bond's new price is $970. The approximate convexity would be: \n\nConvexity approximation = ($1,035 + $970 - 2 x $1,000) / (2 x $1,000 x 0.01^2) = $5 / $0.2 = 25 \n\nWhen applying this to estimate a bond's price using duration a must be used. The formula for the convexity adjustment is: \n\nConvexity adjustment = convexity x 100 x (dy)^2 \n\nIn this example, the convexity adjustment would be: \n\nConvexity adjustment = 25 x 100 x (0.01)^2 = 0.25 \n\nFinally, using duration and convexity to obtain an estimate of a bond's price for a given change in interest rates, an investor can use the following formula: \n\nBond price change = duration x yield change + convexity adjustment"}
