e.g., 2 for 2%)?", "options": [{"label": "Decimal (e.g., 0.02 for 2%) \n— DEFAULT", "value": "decimal_input", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Integer percentage (e.g., 2 for 2%)", "value": "percent_input", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "hard", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Tax rates in 'tax_brackets' are provided in decimal form.", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}, {"id": "residency_factor_scope", "ambiguity_type": "calculation_timing", "trigger_signal": "residency factor is applied, but it's not explicitly stated if it adjusts the net worth before calculation or the final tax liability", "clarification_question": "Does the 'residency_factor' adjust the taxpayer's net worth before tax calculation, or the final calculated tax liability?", "options": [{"label": "Adjusts final tax liability (as a multiplier on total tax) \n— DEFAULT", "value": "adjusts_final_tax", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Adjusts net worth (as a multiplier on net_worth)", "value": "adjusts_net_worth", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "The residency factor is applied as a multiplier to the final calculated tax liability.", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "net_worth", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The net worth of the taxpayer, representing the total value of all assets minus liabilities.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "tax_brackets", "type": "array[number]", "required": true, "description": "A list of tuples, where each tuple contains a threshold value and the tax rate for the segment above the previous threshold. Example format: [(threshold1, rate1), (threshold2, rate2), ...]", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "residency_factor", "type": "number", "required": false, "description": "A factor to account for residency status, typically 1.0 for residents and less for non-residents.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "total_tax_liability", "type": "number", "unit": "currency", "description": "The calculated wealth tax liability based on progressive rates, adjusted for residency."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    net_worth = inputs['net_worth']\n    tax_brackets = inputs['tax_brackets']\n    residency_factor = inputs.get('residency_factor', 1.0)\n    total_tax_liability = 0\n    previous_threshold = 0\n    for threshold, rate in tax_brackets:\n        if net_worth > threshold:\n            tax_for_bracket = (threshold - previous_threshold) * rate\n            total_tax_liability += tax_for_bracket\n            previous_threshold = threshold\n        else:\n            tax_for_bracket = (net_worth - previous_threshold) * rate\n            total_tax_liability += tax_for_bracket\n            break\n    total_tax_liability *= residency_factor\n    return round(total_tax_liability)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "net_worth_positive", "name": "Net worth must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['net_worth'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The taxpayer's net worth cannot be a negative value."}, {"rule_id": "tax_brackets_structure", "name": "Tax brackets must be a list of 2-element tuples/lists", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (isinstance(inputs['tax_brackets'], list) and all(isinstance(item, (list, tuple)) and len(item) == 2 for item in inputs['tax_brackets']))", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'tax_brackets' input must be a list where each element is a tuple or list containing exactly two elements: a threshold and a rate."}, {"rule_id": "tax_brackets_values_non_negative", "name": "Tax bracket thresholds and rates must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not all(threshold >= 0 and rate >= 0 for threshold, rate in inputs['tax_brackets'])", "applies_to": [], "description": "All threshold values and tax rates within 'tax_brackets' must be non-negative."}, {"rule_id": "tax_brackets_sorted", "name": "Tax brackets must be sorted by threshold", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "any(inputs['tax_brackets'][i][0] > inputs['tax_brackets'][i+1][0] for i in range(len(inputs['tax_brackets']) - 1))", "applies_to": [], "description": "The tax brackets must be sorted in ascending order by their threshold values."}, {"rule_id": "residency_factor_range", "name": "Residency factor must be between 0 and 1", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs.get('residency_factor', 1.0) < 0 or inputs.get('residency_factor', 1.0) > 1", "applies_to": [], "description": "The residency factor must be a value between 0.0 and 1.0, inclusive."}, {"rule_id": "tax_brackets_coverage", "name": "Tax brackets must cover the entire net worth", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (len(inputs['tax_brackets']) > 0 and (inputs['tax_brackets'][-1][0] == float('inf') or inputs['tax_brackets'][-1][0] >= inputs['net_worth']))", "applies_to": [], "description": "The provided tax brackets should sufficiently cover the entire 'net_worth' value, typically by having the last bracket's threshold set to infinity or a value greater than or equal to the net worth."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    net_worth = inputs['net_worth']\n    tax_brackets = inputs['tax_brackets']\n    residency_factor = inputs.get('residency_factor', 1.0)\n    total_tax_liability = 0\n    previous_threshold = 0\n    for threshold, rate in tax_brackets:\n        if net_worth > threshold:\n            tax_for_bracket = (threshold - previous_threshold) * rate\n            total_tax_liability += tax_for_bracket\n            previous_threshold = threshold\n        else:\n            tax_for_bracket = (net_worth - previous_threshold) * rate\n            total_tax_liability += tax_for_bracket\n            break\n    total_tax_liability *= residency_factor\n    return round(total_tax_liability)"}, "article_title": "Wealth Tax", "article_doc_id": 4825, "article_content_excerpt": "# Wealth Tax: Definition, Examples, Pros & Cons\n\nDefinition\n\nA wealth tax applies to the net fair market value of all or some of a taxpayer's various asset types, including cash, bank deposits, shares, fixed assets, personal cars, real property, pension plans, money funds, owner-occupied housing, and trusts.\n\n## What Is a Wealth Tax? \n\nA wealth tax is a tax based on the of assets currently owned by a taxpayer, as opposed to taxes on asset sales, income, or real estate. Some developed countries choose to tax wealth, although the United States has historically relied on taxing annual to raise revenue. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * A wealth tax is a tax levied on the net fair market value of a taxpayer’s assets.\n * France, Norway, Spain, and Switzerland all have wealth taxes.\n * U.S. politicians have proposed adding a wealth tax to distribute the tax burden more fairly in a society with immense economic disparity.\n\n## Understanding Wealth Taxes \n\nA wealth tax, also called capital tax or equity tax, is imposed on the wealth possessed by individuals. The tax usually applies to a person’s net worth, which is assets minus liabilities. These assets include (but are not limited to) cash, bank deposits, shares, , personal cars, real property, pension plans, money funds, owner-occupied housing, and . \n\nAn on real estate and an intangible tax on financial assets are both examples of a wealth tax. Generally, countries that impose wealth taxes also impose income and other taxes. \n\nOnly four countries currently levy a net wealth tax: France, Norway, Spain, and Switzerland. In the early 1990s, 12 countries reportedly imposed a wealth tax, indicating that the popularity of this form of taxation is diminishing.\n\nIn 2024, the Brazilian government proposed a new 2% global wealth tax that would impact 3,000 of the wealthiest people in the world. However, the tax proposal's future remains a question of feasibility since major countries such as the United States have not signed on.\n\nIn the United States, federal and state governments do not impose wealth taxes. Instead, the U.S. imposes annual and . However, some consider property tax a form of wealth tax, as the government taxes the same asset year after year. The U.S. also imposes an on the death of individuals owning high-value estates.\n\nHowever, that levy represents a relatively insignificant contribution to U.S. tax receipts. For example, in 2024 the total collections from gift and estate taxes were equivalent to only 0.64% of U.S. GDP.\n\nDuring the 2020 election, the immense and increasing disparity in wealth in the United States prompted and , in addition to the income tax. In March 2021, Warren introduced S.510, a revised version of her earlier proposal, to impose a tax on the of very wealthy individuals. Although the first version failed, a new version of her proposal was introduced in 2024, and taxes have been a key part of the presidential candidate's platforms. \n\n## Examples of a Wealth Tax \n\nIn effect, a wealth tax impacts the net value of the assets accumulated over time and owned by a taxpayer as of the end of each . An income tax impacts the flow of the additions in value that a taxpayer realizes, whether as earnings, investment returns such as interest, , or rents, and/or profits on disposition of assets during the year. \n\nLet’s look at an example of how the wealth tax differs from income tax. Assume a single taxpayer earns $120,000 annually and falls in the 24% . That individual’s liability for the year will be 24% × $120,000 = $28,800. What is the tax liability if the government taxes wealth instead of income? If the taxpayer’s assessed net worth is $450,000 and the wealth tax is 24%, then the tax debt for the year will be 24% × $450,000 = $108,000. \n\nIn reality, annual wealth tax rates are significantly lower than annual income tax rates. In France, for example, the wealth tax used to apply to total worldwide assets. As of 2023, however, it only applied to real estate assets worth more\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_2551", "name": "Salvage Value", "short_description": "Calculate yearly depreciation expenses using the sum-of-years digits method, allocating a larger deduction in initial years.", "domain": "accounting_and_financial_reporting", "topic": "depreciation_and_amortization", "topic_extension": false, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-2551", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-192", "question_id": "test-2057", "difficulty": 4.430816798843313, "level": "hard", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "f06d203d63c8ecddd48944cacb6670eabb439208af1df3f86e8cd490a248163c", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["depreciation", "sum of years digits", "accelerated depreciation", "asset", "useful life", "salvage value", "cost", "expense"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "salvage_value_basis", "ambiguity_type": "value_interpretation", "trigger_signal": "salvage value can be minimal or zero in depreciation calculations as per accounting standards", "clarification_question": "Should the provided salvage value be strictly used as an absolute amount, or is there an intent to treat it as minimal/zero?", "options": [{"label": "Use provided salvage value as-is (absolute amount) - DEFAULT", "value": "as_is", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Treat salvage value as zero due to minimality (recompute with salvage_value = 0)", "value": "treat_as_zero", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Use the provided salvage value as an absolute amount.", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "cost", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The original cost of the asset.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "salvage_value", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The estimated salvage value of the asset at the end of its useful life.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "useful_life", "type": "integer", "required": true, "description": "The useful life of the asset in years.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "depreciation_expenses", "type": "array[number]", "unit": null, "description": "A list of depreciation expenses for each year of the asset's useful life."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    cost = inputs['cost']\n    salvage_value = inputs['salvage_value']\n    useful_life = inputs['useful_life']\n    if useful_life <= 0:\n        raise ValueError('Useful life must be a positive integer.')\n    if cost <= salvage_value:\n        raise ValueError('Cost must be greater than salvage value.')\n    depreciable_amount = cost - salvage_value\n    sum_of_years = useful_life * (useful_life + 1) / 2\n    depreciation_expenses = []\n    for year in range(useful_life):\n        fraction = (useful_life - year) / sum_of_years\n        depreciation_expense = depreciable_amount * fraction\n        depreciation_expenses.append(depreciation_expense)\n    return depreciation_expenses", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "ul001", "name": "Useful life must be a positive integer", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not isinstance(inputs['useful_life'], int) or inputs['useful_life'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["useful_life"], "description": "The useful life of the asset must be a positive integer."}, {"rule_id": "c001", "name": "Cost must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['cost'] < 0", "applies_to": ["cost"], "description": "The original cost of the asset cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "sv001", "name": "Salvage value must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['salvage_value'] < 0", "applies_to": ["salvage_value"], "description": "The estimated salvage value cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "cs001", "name": "Cost must be greater than salvage value", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['cost'] <= inputs['salvage_value']", "applies_to": ["cost", "salvage_value"], "description": "The original cost of the asset must be strictly greater than its estimated salvage value to allow for depreciation."}, {"rule_id": "deplen001", "name": "Number of depreciation expenses matches useful life", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "len(compute(inputs)) == inputs['useful_life']", "applies_to": ["useful_life"], "description": "The length of the calculated depreciation expenses list should match the asset's useful life."}, {"rule_id": "depsum001", "name": "Sum of depreciation equals depreciable amount", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "abs(sum(compute(inputs)) - (inputs['cost'] - inputs['salvage_value'])) < 1e-6", "applies_to": ["cost", "salvage_value"], "description": "The sum of all yearly depreciation expenses should approximately equal the total depreciable amount (cost - salvage value)."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    cost = inputs['cost']\n    salvage_value = inputs['salvage_value']\n    useful_life = inputs['useful_life']\n    if useful_life <= 0:\n        raise ValueError('Useful life must be a positive integer.')\n    if cost <= salvage_value:\n        raise ValueError('Cost must be greater than salvage value.')\n    depreciable_amount = cost - salvage_value\n    sum_of_years = useful_life * (useful_life + 1) / 2\n    depreciation_expenses = []\n    for year in range(useful_life):\n        fraction = (useful_life - year) / sum_of_years\n        depreciation_expense = depreciable_amount * fraction\n        depreciation_expenses.append(depreciation_expense)\n    return depreciation_expenses"}, "article_title": "Salvage Value", "article_doc_id": 5135, "article_content_excerpt": "# Salvage Value Meaning and Example\n\n## What Is Salvage Value? \n\nSalvage value is the estimated book value of an after is complete, based on what a company expects to receive in exchange for the asset at the end of its . As such, an asset’s estimated salvage value is an important component in the calculation of a depreciation schedule. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Salvage value is the book value of an asset after all depreciation has been fully expensed.\n * The salvage value of an asset is based on what a company expects to receive in exchange for selling or parting out the asset at the end of its useful life.\n * Companies may depreciate their assets fully to $0 because the salvage value is so minimal.\n * Salvage value will influence the total depreciable amount a company uses in its depreciation schedule.\n * A company may calculate salvage value by taking a percentage of the cost, working with an appraiser, or relying on historical data.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/salvagevalue.asp-final-292f031e45fc401696a539e78dda392d.png)\n\nNoNo Flores / Investopedia\n\n## Understanding Salvage Value \n\nAn estimated salvage value can be determined for any asset that a company will be depreciating on its books over time. Every company will have its own standards for estimating salvage value. Some companies may choose to always depreciate an asset to $0 because its salvage value is so minimal. \n\nIn general, the salvage value is important because it will be the carrying value of the asset on a company’s books . It is based on the value a company expects to receive from the sale of the asset at the end of its useful life. In some cases, salvage value may just be a value the company believes it can obtain by selling a depreciated, inoperable asset for parts. \n\n### Depreciation and Salvage Value Assumptions \n\nCompanies take into consideration the matching principle when making assumptions for asset depreciation and salvage value. The matching principle is an concept that requires a company to recognize expense in the same period as the related revenues are earned. If a company expects that an asset will contribute to revenue for a long period of time, it will have a long, useful life. \n\nIf a company is not sure of an asset’s useful life, it may estimate a lower number of years and a higher salvage value to carry the asset on its books after full depreciation or sell the asset at its salvage value. If a company wants to front-load depreciation expenses, it can use an method that deducts more depreciation expenses upfront. Many companies use a salvage value of $0 because they believe that an asset’s utilization has fully matched its expense recognition with revenues over its useful life. \n\n### Important: \n\nA company can change its expected salvage value at any time. It just needs to prospectively change the estimated amount to book to depreciate each month.\n\n## Depreciation Methods \n\nThere are several assumptions required for developing depreciation schedules. There are five primary methods of depreciation that financial accountants can choose from: , , , , and . The declining balance, double-declining balance, and sum of years digits methods are accelerated depreciation methods with higher depreciation expense upfront in earlier years. \n\nEach of these methods requires consideration for salvage value. An asset’s depreciable amount is its total after all depreciation expense has been recorded, which is also the result of minus salvage value. The carrying value of an asset as it is being depreciated is its historical cost minus accumulated depreciation to date. \n\n### Straight-Line Depreciation \n\nStraight-line depreciation is generally the most basic depreciation method. It includes equal depreciation expenses each year throughout the entire useful life until the entire asset is depreciated to its salvage value. \n\nAssume, for example, that a company buys a machine at a cost of $5,000. The company decides on a salvage value of $1,000 and a useful life\n...[truncated]"}
