= ending_balance - amount_owed_converted\n    return profit", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "positive_amounts", "name": "Positive Borrowed and Invested Amounts", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['borrowed_amount'] <= 0 or inputs['invested_amount'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["borrowed_amount", "invested_amount"], "description": "Borrowed and invested amounts must be positive."}, {"rule_id": "non_negative_rates", "name": "Non-negative Interest Rates", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['borrowing_rate'] < 0 or inputs['investment_rate'] < 0", "applies_to": ["borrowing_rate", "investment_rate"], "description": "Interest rates (borrowing and investment) must be non-negative."}, {"rule_id": "positive_exchange_rate", "name": "Positive Exchange Rate", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['exchange_rate'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["exchange_rate"], "description": "The exchange rate must be a positive value."}, {"rule_id": "carry_trade_precondition", "name": "Investment Rate Higher than Borrowing Rate", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['investment_rate'] <= inputs['borrowing_rate']", "applies_to": ["investment_rate", "borrowing_rate"], "description": "For a profitable carry trade strategy, the investment rate is typically higher than the borrowing rate."}, {"rule_id": "plausible_exchange_rate", "name": "Plausible Exchange Rate Value", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (0.00001 <= inputs['exchange_rate'] <= 1000)", "applies_to": ["exchange_rate"], "description": "The exchange rate should be within a plausible range (e.g., between 0.00001 and 1000) for common currency pairs."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    invested_amount = inputs['invested_amount']\n    investment_rate = inputs['investment_rate']\n    borrowed_amount = inputs['borrowed_amount']\n    borrowing_rate = inputs['borrowing_rate']\n    exchange_rate = inputs['exchange_rate']\n    ending_balance = invested_amount * (1 + investment_rate)\n    amount_owed = borrowed_amount * (1 + borrowing_rate)\n    amount_owed_converted = amount_owed / exchange_rate\n    profit = ending_balance - amount_owed_converted\n    return profit"}, "article_title": "Currency Carry Trade", "article_doc_id": 326, "article_content_excerpt": "# Currency Carry Trade: Definition As Trading Strategy and Example\n\n## What Is a Currency Carry Trade? \n\nA currency carry trade is a strategy in which traders borrow in a low-interest-rate currency and invest the proceeds in a high-interest-rate currency, aiming to profit from the interest rate differential. The strategy generally involves using to magnify any potential returns. \n\nThe carry trade is one of the most popular strategies, as it can be entered by simply finding and selling a low-yielding currency and buying a high-yielding one. Until recently, one of the most popular carry trades involved trading the low-yielding or even Japanese yen against currencies like the Australian dollar or the New Zealand dollar. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * A currency carry trade is a strategy that involves borrowing in a low-yielding currency, investing in a high-yielding currency, and collecting the interest rate differential.\n * Traders using this strategy often rely on leverage to magnify potential gains.\n * The carry trade is one of the most popular trading strategies in the forex market.\n\n## Understanding a Currency Carry Trade \n\nThe currency carry trade is one of the most popular in the forex market. In a way, it is similar to the “buy low, sell high” motto. The first and main step in entering a carry trade is to determine which currency offers a high yield and which offers a lower one. \n\nFor example, from the late 2000s to up until mid-2024, the Japanese yen was known for offering wide spreads against many global currencies, such as the and the . \n\n### Mechanics of the Carry Trade \n\nIn a carry trade, a trader from the difference in the interest rates of the two countries, as long as the between the currencies does not change significantly. Many professional traders use this trade because leverage allows them to magnify the potential gains. \n\nIf the trader in our example uses a common leverage factor of 10:1, the trader can potentially earn 10 times the interest rate difference. Considering that some offer leverage as high as 300:1, it’s not hard to see the appeal of carry trading. It’s equally easy to see how disastrous the outcome can be, if the trade goes against the trader. \n\nThe is the currency exchanged in a carry trade transaction, typically characterized by a low interest rate. Investors borrow the funding currency and go short, while taking long positions in the asset currency, which has a higher interest rate. The central banks of funding currency countries such as the and the U.S. often engage in to prop up economic growth, resulting in low interest rates. As the rates drop, speculators borrow the money and hope to unwind their short positions before the rates increase. \n\n### When to Get in a Carry Trade, When to Get Out \n\nThe best time to get into a carry trade is when are raising, or thinking about raising, . People entering the carry trade will further help push up the value of the currency pair. Similarly, these trades work well during times of low since traders are willing to take on more risk. As long as the currency’s value doesn’t fall—even if it doesn’t move much, or at all—traders will still be able to get paid by collecting the interest rate differential. \n\nConversely, a period of interest rate reduction won’t offer big rewards in carry trades. That shift in also means a shift in currency values. When rates are dropping, demand for the currency also tends to dwindle, and selling off the currency becomes difficult. For the currency trade to be profitable, there needs to be no movement or some degree of . \n\n## Currency Carry Trade Example \n\nAs an example of a currency carry trade, assume that rates in Japan are 0.5 percent, and rates in the United States are 4%. If a trader borrows in the Japanese yen, and invests in the U.S. dollar, he can expect to collect the 3.5% spread. \n\nThe first step is to borrow yen and convert them into dollars. The second step is to invest those dollars into a security paying the U.S. rate\n...[truncated]"}
