ulated_depreciation\n        book_value -= current_period_depreciation\n        if current_period == year:\n            depreciation_expense_for_target_year = current_period_depreciation\n            break\n    return max(0.0, depreciation_expense_for_target_year)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "ddb_f_001", "name": "Integer Type Adherence for Years", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not isinstance(inputs['useful_life_years'], int) or not isinstance(inputs['year'], int)", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'useful_life_years' and 'year' inputs must be integers."}, {"rule_id": "ddb_e_001", "name": "Initial Book Value Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['initial_book_value'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["initial_book_value"], "description": "The initial book value of the asset must be a positive number."}, {"rule_id": "ddb_e_002", "name": "Salvage Value Must Be Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['salvage_value'] < 0", "applies_to": ["salvage_value"], "description": "The salvage value cannot be a negative number."}, {"rule_id": "ddb_e_003", "name": "Salvage Value Less Than Initial Book Value", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['salvage_value'] >= inputs['initial_book_value']", "applies_to": ["initial_book_value", "salvage_value"], "description": "Salvage value is typically expected to be less than the initial book value. If equal or greater, no depreciation can occur, which might not be the intended use of DDB."}, {"rule_id": "ddb_e_004", "name": "Useful Life Years Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['useful_life_years'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["useful_life_years"], "description": "The useful life of the asset must be a positive integer."}, {"rule_id": "ddb_e_005", "name": "Target Year Must Be Within Useful Life", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['year'] < 1 or inputs['year'] > inputs['useful_life_years']", "applies_to": ["year", "useful_life_years"], "description": "The target year for depreciation must be a positive integer and cannot exceed the asset's useful life."}, {"rule_id": "ddb_e_006", "name": "Calculated Depreciation Expense Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "compute(inputs) < 0", "applies_to": ["initial_book_value", "salvage_value", "useful_life_years", "year"], "description": "The calculated depreciation expense should not be negative. This indicates a potential logical error or unexpected input combination."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    initial_book_value = inputs['initial_book_value']\n    salvage_value = inputs['salvage_value']\n    useful_life_years = inputs['useful_life_years']\n    year = inputs['year']\n    book_value = initial_book_value\n    straight_line_rate = 1.0 / useful_life_years\n    double_declining_rate = 2.0 * straight_line_rate\n    depreciation_expense_for_target_year = 0.0\n    for current_period in range(1, year + 1):\n        if book_value <= salvage_value:\n            current_period_depreciation = 0.0\n        else:\n            calculated_depreciation = book_value * double_declining_rate\n            if book_value - calculated_depreciation < salvage_value:\n                current_period_depreciation = book_value - salvage_value\n            else:\n                current_period_depreciation = calculated_depreciation\n        book_value -= current_period_depreciation\n        if current_period == year:\n            depreciation_expense_for_target_year = current_period_depreciation\n            break\n    return max(0.0, depreciation_expense_for_target_year)"}, "article_title": "Double Declining Balance Depreciation Method (DDB)", "article_doc_id": 3403, "article_content_excerpt": "# Double-Declining Balance (DDB) Depreciation Method Definition With Formula\n\n## What Is the Double-Declining Balance (DDB) Depreciation Method? \n\nThe double-declining balance (DDB) method, also known as the reducing balance method, is one of two common methods a business uses to account for the expense of a long-lived asset. The double-declining balance depreciation method is an method that counts as an expense more rapidly (when compared to that uses the same amount of depreciation each year over an asset's useful life). Similarly, compared to the standard , the double-declining method depreciates assets twice as quickly. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * The double-declining balance (DDB) method is an accelerated depreciation calculation used in business accounting.\n * Specifically, the DDB method depreciates assets twice as fast as the traditional declining balance method.\n * The DDB method records larger depreciation expenses during the earlier years of an asset’s useful life, and smaller ones in later years.\n * As a result, companies opt for the DDB method for assets that are likely to lose most of their value early on, or which will become obsolete more quickly.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/double-declining-balance-depreciation-method-4197537-57ec7242afce4164a7e78fbea8a1d828.jpg)\n\nInvestopedia / Madelyn Goodnight\n\n## Double-Declining Balance (DDB) Depreciation Formula \n\n> \\begin{aligned} &\\text{Depreciation}=2\\times \\text{SLDP}\\times\\text{BV}\\\\\\ &\\textbf{where:}\\\\\\ &\\text{SLDP = Straight-line depreciation percent}\\\\\\ &\\text{BV = Book value at the beginning of the period}\\\\\\ \\end{aligned}\n\n## Understanding DDB Depreciation \n\nThe is one of the two accelerated depreciation methods and it uses a depreciation rate that is some multiple of the straight-line method rate. The double-declining balance (DDB) method is a type of declining balance method that instead uses double the normal depreciation rate. \n\nDepreciation rates used in the declining balance method could be 150%, 200% (double), or 250% of the straight-line rate. When the depreciation rate for the declining balance method is set as a multiple, doubling the straight-line rate, the declining balance method is effectively the double-declining balance method. Over the depreciation process, the double depreciation rate remains constant and is applied to the reducing each depreciation period. The book value, or depreciation base, of an asset, declines over time. \n\nWith the constant double depreciation rate and a successively lower depreciation base, charges calculated with this method continually drop. The balance of the book value is eventually reduced to the asset's salvage value after the last depreciation period. However, the final depreciation charge may have to be limited to a lesser amount to keep the salvage value as estimated. \n\nUnder the for public companies, expenses are recorded in the same period as the revenue that is earned as a result of those expenses. Thus, when a company purchases an expensive asset that will be used for many years, it does not deduct the entire purchase price as a business expense in the year of purchase but instead deducts the price over several years.\n\nBecause the double- results in larger depreciation expenses near the beginning of an asset’s life—and smaller depreciation expenses later on—it makes sense to use this method with assets that lose value quickly. \n\n### Accelerated Depreciation\n\nDouble declining balance depreciation allows for higher depreciation expenses in early years and lower expenses as an asset nears the end of its life. This is considered an accelerated depreciation method.\n\n## Example of DDB Depreciation \n\nAs a hypothetical example, suppose a business purchased a $30,000 delivery truck, which was expected to last for 10 years. After 10 years, it would be worth $3,000, its salvage value. Under the straight-line depreciation method, the company would deduct $2,700 per year for 10 years–that is, $30,000 minus $3,000, d\n...[truncated]"}
