curs if all market returns are identical, which would make beta undefined."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    asset_returns = inputs['asset_returns']\n    market_returns = inputs['market_returns']\n    if len(asset_returns) != len(market_returns):\n        raise ValueError('Asset and market return lists must have the same length.')\n    if len(asset_returns) < 2:\n        raise ValueError('Requires at least two data points in asset_returns and market_returns.')\n    mean_asset = sum(asset_returns) / len(asset_returns)\n    mean_market = sum(market_returns) / len(market_returns)\n    covariance = sum(((a - mean_asset) * (m - mean_market) for a, m in zip(asset_returns, market_returns))) / (len(asset_returns) - 1)\n    market_variance = sum(((m - mean_market) ** 2 for m in market_returns)) / (len(market_returns) - 1)\n    if market_variance == 0:\n        raise ValueError('Market variance cannot be zero, as all market returns are identical.')\n    beta = covariance / market_variance\n    return beta"}, "article_title": "Market Risk", "article_doc_id": 1606, "article_content_excerpt": "# Market Risk Definition: How to Deal with Systematic Risk\n\n## What Is Market Risk? \n\nMarket risk is the possibility that an individual or other entity will experience losses due to factors that affect the overall performance of investments in the . That is to say, it is risk of market price and interest rate movements. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Market risk, or systematic risk, affects the performance of the entire market simultaneously.\n * Market risk cannot be eliminated through diversification.\n * Specific risk, or unsystematic risk, involves the performance of a particular security and can be mitigated through diversification. \n * Market risk may arise due to changes to interest rates, exchange rates, geopolitical events, or recessions.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/market-risk.asp-Final-267d57db9f87429cb80051c8a5132847.jpg)\n\nInvestopedia / Yurle Villegas\n\n## Understanding Market Risk \n\nMarket risk and (unsystematic) make up the two major categories of investment risk. Market risk, also called , _cannot_ be eliminated through diversification, though it can be hedged in other ways. Sources of market risk include , political turmoil, changes in , natural disasters, and terrorist attacks. Systematic risk, or market risk, tends to influence the entire market at the same time. \n\nThis can be contrasted with , which is unique to a specific company or industry. Also known as nonsystematic risk, specific risk, diversifiable risk, or residual risk, in the context of an investment , unsystematic risk can be reduced through . \n\nMarket risk exists because of price changes. The standard deviation of changes in the prices of stocks, currencies, or commodities is referred to as price volatility. is often presented in annualized terms and may be expressed as an absolute number, such as $10, or a percentage of the initial value, such as 10%. \n\n### Important: \n\nPublicly traded companies in the United States are required by the to disclose how their productivity and results may be linked to the performance of the financial markets. This requirement is meant to detail a company’s exposure to . For example, a company providing derivative investments or foreign exchange futures may be more exposed to financial risk than companies that do not provide these types of investments. This information helps investors and traders make decisions based on their own risk management rules.\n\n## Other Types of Risk \n\nIn contrast to the market’s overall risk, specific risk or unsystematic risk is and can be protected against through investment diversification. One example of unsystematic risk is a company declaring bankruptcy, thereby making its stock worthless to investors. \n\nThe most common types of market risks include interest rate risk, equity risk, currency risk, and commodity risk. \n\n * covers the volatility that may accompany interest rate fluctuations due to fundamental factors, such as announcements related to changes in . This risk is most relevant to investments in fixed-income securities, such as bonds. \n * Equity risk is the risk involved in the changing prices of stock investments.\n * covers the changing prices of commodities such as crude oil and corn.\n * , or exchange-rate risk, arises from the change in the price of one currency in relation to another. Investors or firms holding assets in another country are subject to currency risk.\n\n## Managing Market Risk \n\nIf you are , there is no single way to completely avoid market risk. But you can use to protect against volatility and minimize the impact that market risk will have on your investments and overall financial health. For example, you can buy to protect against a downside move when targeting specific securities. Or, if you want to a large portfolio of stocks, you can utilize . \n\nUse a variety of these strategies to manage market risk and protect your portfolio. \n\n### Tip: \n\nDollar-cost averaging won’t protect you against market risk. But investing the same amount of money on a regular\n...[truncated]"}
