l currency.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "non_monetary_assets", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The value of non-monetary assets in the subsidiary's local currency.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "monetary_exchange_rate", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The exchange rate for monetary assets (e.g., LC/USD) on the balance sheet date.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "non_monetary_exchange_rate", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The exchange rate for non-monetary assets (e.g., LC/USD) on the transaction date.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "converted_total_assets", "type": "number", "unit": null, "description": "The total value of the subsidiary's assets after conversion into the parent company's currency (USD)."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    monetary_assets = inputs['monetary_assets']\n    non_monetary_assets = inputs['non_monetary_assets']\n    monetary_exchange_rate = inputs['monetary_exchange_rate']\n    non_monetary_exchange_rate = inputs['non_monetary_exchange_rate']\n    converted_monetary_assets = monetary_assets / monetary_exchange_rate\n    converted_non_monetary_assets = non_monetary_assets / non_monetary_exchange_rate\n    converted_total_assets = converted_monetary_assets + converted_non_monetary_assets\n    return converted_total_assets", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "assets_non_negative", "name": "Monetary Assets Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['monetary_assets'] < 0", "applies_to": ["monetary_assets"], "description": "Monetary assets must be a non-negative value."}, {"rule_id": "non_monetary_assets_non_negative", "name": "Non-Monetary Assets Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['non_monetary_assets'] < 0", "applies_to": ["non_monetary_assets"], "description": "Non-monetary assets must be a non-negative value."}, {"rule_id": "monetary_exchange_rate_positive", "name": "Monetary Exchange Rate Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['monetary_exchange_rate'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["monetary_exchange_rate"], "description": "The monetary exchange rate must be a positive value to ensure valid conversion and avoid division by zero."}, {"rule_id": "non_monetary_exchange_rate_positive", "name": "Non-Monetary Exchange Rate Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['non_monetary_exchange_rate'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["non_monetary_exchange_rate"], "description": "The non-monetary exchange rate must be a positive value to ensure valid conversion and avoid division by zero."}, {"rule_id": "converted_total_assets_positive", "name": "Converted Total Assets Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "compute(inputs) <= 0 and (inputs['monetary_assets'] > 0 or inputs['non_monetary_assets'] > 0)", "applies_to": [], "description": "If there are positive assets, the converted total assets should also be positive."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    monetary_assets = inputs['monetary_assets']\n    non_monetary_assets = inputs['non_monetary_assets']\n    monetary_exchange_rate = inputs['monetary_exchange_rate']\n    non_monetary_exchange_rate = inputs['non_monetary_exchange_rate']\n    converted_monetary_assets = monetary_assets / monetary_exchange_rate\n    converted_non_monetary_assets = non_monetary_assets / non_monetary_exchange_rate\n    converted_total_assets = converted_monetary_assets + converted_non_monetary_assets\n    return converted_total_assets"}, "article_title": "Temporal Method", "article_doc_id": 3536, "article_content_excerpt": "# Temporal Method: What it Means, Examples\n\n## What Is the Temporal Method? \n\nThe temporal method (also known as the historical method) converts the currency of a foreign subsidiary into the currency of the parent company. This technique of foreign is used when the local currency of the subsidiary is not the same as the currency of the parent company. Differing are used depending on the financial statement item being translated. \n\n## Understanding the Temporal Method \n\nWhen a company has operations or subsidiaries in a country other than where the parent company is domiciled, the parent company must on the foreign entity's financial statements back into the parent company's currency in order to calculate its profits and losses and generate the . The currency used by the parent company is sometimes referred to as the subsidiary’s \"\" or \"reporting currency.\" \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * The temporal method is used to convert the currency of a foreign subsidiary into the same currency as the parent company.\n * The parent company's currency is called the functional currency.\n * The currency translation technique allows the parent company to report profits or losses and file financial statements when it has subsidiaries outside of the country where it is domiciled.\n * Gains or losses due to exchange rate conversions are reported in the parent company's net earnings.\n\nIf the subsidiary's functional currency differs from its local currency, the temporal method is used to perform currency translations. Exchange rate values are based on the time and are acquired or incurred, which makes it possible to convert the numbers on the books of an integrated foreign entity into the parent company's currency. \n\nMonetary assets and liabilities are converted using the exchange rate in effect as of the balance sheet date. and liabilities are converted using the exchange rate in effect on the date of the transaction. Gains and losses due to foreign exchange are reported in net earnings. \n\n## Example of the Temporal Method \n\nAn example of the temporal method would be XYZ being domiciled in Great Britain. The local currency of XYZ is the British pound. However, if the majority of XYZ's clients reside in continental Europe, then it may conduct its business in euros. The euro would be the functional currency. In this instance, the parent company of XYZ would use the temporal method to translate XYZ's financial statements back into the currency used by the parent company. \n\nMonetary assets such as , investments, and cash are converted to the parent's currency at the exchange rate in effect on the balance sheet date. Non-monetary assets are longer-term assets—such as property, plant, and equipment—are converted using the exchange rate in effect on the date the asset was obtained. Since all foreign exchange gains and losses are reported in net earnings of the parent company, the result can be an increase in the volatility of the parent company's earnings if it has substantial income coming from subsidiaries in different countries."}
