uding mortgage, HELOCs, and home equity loans.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "equity_percentage", "type": "number", "unit": "percent", "description": "The percentage of equity held in the home."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    home_value = inputs['home_value']\n    total_loans_balance = inputs['total_loans_balance']\n    equity_amount = home_value - total_loans_balance\n    equity_percentage = equity_amount / home_value * 100\n    return round(equity_percentage, 2)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "home_value_positive", "name": "Home Value Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['home_value'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The home value must be a positive number to calculate equity percentage meaningfully."}, {"rule_id": "total_loans_balance_non_negative", "name": "Total Loan Balance Must Be Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['total_loans_balance'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The total loan balance against the home cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "negative_equity_alert", "name": "Negative Equity Detected", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "compute(inputs) < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The calculated equity percentage is negative, indicating that the total loan balance exceeds the home's value (negative equity). This is a plausible but significant financial condition."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    home_value = inputs['home_value']\n    total_loans_balance = inputs['total_loans_balance']\n    equity_amount = home_value - total_loans_balance\n    equity_percentage = equity_amount / home_value * 100\n    return round(equity_percentage, 2)"}, "article_title": "Home-Equity Loan", "article_doc_id": 2069, "article_content_excerpt": "# How a Home Equity Loan Works, Rates, Requirements & Calculator\n\n## What Is a Home Equity Loan? \n\nA home equity loan—also known as an equity loan, home equity installment loan, or —is a type of consumer debt. Home equity loans allow homeowners to borrow against the equity in their homes. The loan amount is based on the difference between the home’s current market value and the . Home equity loans tend to be fixed-rate, while the typical alternative, , generally have variable rates. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * A home equity loan, also known as a home equity installment loan or a second mortgage, is a type of consumer debt.\n * Home equity loans allow homeowners to borrow against the equity in their residence. \n * Home equity loan amounts are based on the difference between a home’s current market value and the homeowner’s mortgage balance due.\n * Home equity loans come in two varieties: fixed-rate loans and home equity lines of credit (HELOCs). \n * Fixed-rate home equity loans provide one lump sum, whereas HELOCs offer borrowers revolving lines of credit.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/homeequityloan-e11896bf4ac1475a9806a55f92e0c312.jpg)\n\nInvestopedia / Zoe Hansen\n\n## How a Home Equity Loan Works \n\nEssentially, a home equity loan is akin to a mortgage, hence the name second mortgage. The serves as for the . The amount that a homeowner is allowed to borrow will be based partially on a of 80% to 90% of the home’s value. Of course, the amount of the loan and the rate of interest charged also depend on the borrower’s and payment history. \n\n### Warning: \n\nMortgage lending discrimination is illegal. based on race, religion, sex, marital status, use of public assistance, national origin, disability, or age, there are steps that you can take. One such step is to file a report with the or the U.S. .\n\nTraditional home equity loans have a set term, just . The borrower makes regular, fixed payments covering both and . As with any mortgage, if the loan is not paid off, the home could be sold to satisfy . \n\nA home equity loan can be a good way to in your home into cash, especially if you invest that cash in home renovations that increase the value of your home. However, always remember that you’re putting your home on the line—if real estate values decrease, you could end up owing more than your home is worth. \n\nShould you want to relocate, you might end up losing money on the sale of the home or be unable to move. And if you’re getting the loan , resist the temptation to run up those credit card bills again. Before doing something that puts your house in jeopardy, weigh all of your options. \n\n> “If considering a home equity loan for a large amount, be sure to on multiple loan types. A may be a better option than a home equity loan, depending on how much you need.” \n\n— Certified Financial Planner, Blue Ocean Global Wealth \n\n## Special Considerations \n\nHome equity loans exploded in popularity after the because they provided a way for consumers to get around one of its main provisions: the elimination of deductions for the interest on most consumer purchases. The act left in place one big exception: interest in the service of residence-based debt.\n\nHowever, the suspended the deduction for interest paid on home equity loans and HELOCs until 2026—unless, according to the , “they are used to buy, build or substantially improve the taxpayer’s home that secures the loan.” For example, the interest on a home equity loan or pay for a child’s college expenses is not tax deductible.\n\nAs with a mortgage, you can ask for a , but before you do, make your own honest estimate of your finances. “You should have a good sense of where your credit and home value are , in order to save money,” says , branch manager at Fairway Independent Mortgage Corp. and author of _The Loan Guide: How to Get the Best Possible Mortgage_. “Especially on the appraisal [of your home], which is a major expense. If your appraisal comes in too low to support the loan, the money is a\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_116", "name": "Collar", "short_description": "Calculates the breakeven point for a collar options strategy, considering the stock purchase price, put option cost, and call option premium.", "domain": "financial_markets", "topic": "option_pricing", "topic_extension": false, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-116", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-399", "question_id": "test-1739", "difficulty": 3.332204510175204, "level": "medium", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "d292bcdfccf6567a960e24c2b117a155f5545fb5473a6fbcba851af0dc3012ec", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["collar option strategy", "breakeven point", "hedge wrapper", "risk reversal", "protective put", "covered call", "option strategy"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "collar_type_net_credit_debit", "ambiguity_type": "input_interpretation", "trigger_signal": "collar type not explicitly stated as net credit or net debit, or inconsistent with premium/cost", "clarification_question": "Does the collar strategy result in a net credit (premium received from call exceeds cost of put) or a net debit (cost of put exceeds premium received from call)?", "options": [{"label": "Net Credit (premium received > cost paid) - DEFAULT", "value": "net_credit", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Net Debit (cost paid > premium received)", "value": "net_debit", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Net credit (premium received exceeds cost paid)", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}], "inputs": [{"name": "stock_purchase_price", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The price at which the underlying stock was originally purchased.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "put_cost", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The cost of purchasing the put option to protect against downside.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "call_premium", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The premium received from selling the call option, which limits upside but generates income.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "net_credit", "type": "boolean", "required": false, "description": "Indicates if the collar strategy results in a net credit (True) or a net debit (False). Defaults to True.", "unit": null, "aliases": ["is_credit_collar"]}], "output": {"name": "breakeven_price", "type": "number", "unit": null, "description": "The breakeven stock price for the collar strategy, at which no profit or loss is incurred."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    stock_purchase_price = inputs['stock_purchase_price']\n    put_cost = inputs['put_cost']\n    call_premium = inputs['call_premium']\n    net_credit = inputs.get('net_credit', True)\n    if net_credit:\n        breakeven = stock_purchase_price - (call_premium - put_cost)\n    else:\n        breakeven = stock_purchase_price + (put_cost - call_premium)\n    return breakeven", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "e_positive_stock_price", "name": "Stock Purchase Price Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['stock_purchase_price'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The stock purchase price must be a positive value, reflecting a real asset acquisition."}, {"rule_id": "e_non_negative_put_cost", "name": "Put Option Cost Cannot Be Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['put_cost'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The cost of purchasing the put option cannot be negative; it represents an expense."}, {"rule_id": "e_non_negative_call_premium", "name": "Call Option Premium Cannot Be Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['call_premium'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The premium received from selling the call option cannot be negative; it represents income."}, {"rule_id": "e_net_credit_consistency", "name": "Net Credit/Debit Flag Consistency", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "(inputs['net_credit'] and inputs['call_premium'] < inputs['put_cost']) or (not inputs['net_credit'] and inputs['put_cost'] < inputs['call_premium'])", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'net_credit' flag should align with the relative values of the call premium and put cost. If 'net_credit' is true, the call premium should be greater than the put cost. If 'net_credit' is false, the put cost should be greater than the call premium. This is an alert, as the calculation proceeds with the explicit flag."}, {"rule_id": "e_positive_breakeven_price", "name": "Breakeven Price Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "compute(inputs) <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The calculated breakeven stock price must be a positive value, as stock prices are inherently positive."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    stock_purchase_price = inputs['stock_purchase_price']\n    put_cost = inputs['put_cost']\n    call_premium = inputs['call_premium']\n    net_credit = inputs.get('net_credit', True)\n    if net_credit:\n        breakeven = stock_purchase_price - (call_premium - put_cost)\n    else:\n        breakeven = stock_purchase_price + (put_cost - call_premium)\n    return breakeven"}, "article_title": "Collar", "article_doc_id": 165, "article_content_excerpt": "# The Collar Options Strategy Explained in Simple Terms\n\nDefinition\n\nA collar (or hedge wrapper or risk-reversal) is an options strategy for guarding against significant losses. However, it puts a limit on large gains.\n\n## What Is a Collar? \n\nA collar, also known as a hedge wrapper or risk-reversal, is an options strategy used to protect against significant losses but also limits your potential profits. It's used when you're optimistic about a stock you own long-term but worry about short-term volatility in the market. \n\nAn investor who already owns an underlying a stock (or other asset) creates a collar by buying an out-of-the-money put option, which protects against the stock price going down. At the same time, the investor writes an out-of-the-money call option, where the current price is lower than the option's strike price. This produces income from selling the call option, which hopefully at least covers the cost of buying the put option. It also allows the trader to profit on the asset up to the call's strike price, but not higher. Thus, the strategy caps the potential profit at the call option's strike price. As such, while the collar options strategy can protect against significant losses, it limits potential gains. We explain in this more and clearer detail below. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * A collar is an options strategy that involves buying a downside put and selling an upside call to protect against large losses, but that also limits large upside gains.\n * The protective collar strategy involves two strategies known as a protective put and covered call.\n * An investor's best-case scenario is when the underlying stock price is equal to the strike price of the written call option at expiry.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/collar-final-8cf92d5817a44e9296b3ce605384a25b.jpg)\n\nInvestopedia / Sydney Burns\n\n## Understanding a Collar \n\nInvestors typically use collars if they own a stock whose value is higher than when they bought it, and they are optimistic about the stock going up but unsure of its shorter-term prospects. To protect their gains against a downside move in the stock, they can carry out the collar option strategy. The best outcome for an investor is when the stock's price matches the set price of the call option they've sold right when the option is about to expire.\n\nThe collar strategy combines two methods: buying a put to protect against price drops and selling a call to earn some money upfront. Let's break this down: \n\n * Buying a put (also called a or married put): This is like having insurance on your stock. If the stock's price falls, you can sell it at a preset price, protecting you from significant losses.\n * Selling a call (also known as a covered call): This is where you agree to sell your stock at a specific price in the future. In return, you get paid now. This payment can help cover the cost of the put option you bought.\n\nHere's your checklist for carrying this out: \n\n * Both the put and the call options should end in the same month, and you should have the same number for each.\n * The price you can sell your stock with the put should be lower than its current price.\n * The price at which you agree to sell your stock with the call should be higher than its current price.\n * The money you make from selling the call should cover the cost of buying the put, so you don't have to spend extra money.\n\nThis setup is ideal if you don't want to spend extra money and are fine with not getting the profits should the stock go up higher than you thought. Thus, this is not the best choice if you're very bullish on a stock. \n\nA is a similar that uses three option actions. \n\n## Collar Break-Even Point and Profit or Loss \n\nFor investors using a collar strategy, their break-even point is calculated by looking at the difference between what they spent and what they earned from the . When they end up with more money from the options than they paid, a net credit, they add this extra to the stock's purchase price. If\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_2198", "name": "Lorenz Curve", "short_description": "Calculate the Gini coefficient from the Lorenz curve, a measure of statistical dispersion intended to represent the income or wealth inequality within a nation or social group. It is based on the area under the Lorenz curve.", "domain": "others", "topic": "economic_inequality", "topic_extension": true, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-2198", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-917", "question_id": "test-1014", "difficulty": 2.4849066497880004, "level": "medium", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "6d410fd13c18c781a96ebeaeae88ca0afbe35416e0aca737fda8947a6ec7623e", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null, "echeck_lint": {"fixed_count": 1, "unresolved_count": 0, "fixed_rule_ids": ["gini_range"], "unresolved_rule_ids": []}}, "selection_hints": ["Gini coefficient", "Lorenz curve", "income inequality", "wealth distribution", "economic disparity", "inequality measure"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "output_scale", "ambiguity_type": "unit_scale", "trigger_signal": "question asks for percentage, FIC outputs decimal (or vice versa)", "clarification_question": "Should the Gini coefficient be expressed as a decimal (e.g., 0.35) or a percentage (e.g., 35%)?", "options": [{"label": "Decimal (0.0 to 1.0) — DEFAULT", "value": "decimal", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Percentage (0% to 100%)", "value": "percent", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Decimal (0.0 to 1.0)", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "x_values", "type": "array[number]", "required": true, "description": "A list of percentiles of the population (0 to 1), representing the cumulative share of people.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "y_values", "type": "array[number]", "required": true, "description": "A list of cumulative income or wealth values (0 to 1) for the corresponding percentiles in x_values.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "gini_coefficient", "type": "number", "unit": null, "description": "The Gini coefficient, ranging from 0 (perfect equality) to 1 (maximal inequality), rounded to two decimal places."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    x_values = inputs['x_values']\n    y_values = inputs['y_values']\n\n    def lorenz_curve_area(x_values, y_values):\n        area = 0\n        for i in range(1, len(x_values)):\n            width = x_values[i] - x_values[i - 1]\n            height_avg = (y_values[i] + y_values[i - 1]) / 2\n            area += width * height_avg\n        return area\n    area_under_line_of_equality = 0.5\n    area_under_lorenz_curve = lorenz_curve_area(x_values, y_values)\n    gini_coefficient = (area_under_line_of_equality - area_under_lorenz_curve) / area_under_line_of_equality\n    return round(gini_coefficient, 2)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "lorenz_x_type", "name": "x_values must be a list", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('x_values'), list)", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'x_values' input representing population percentiles must be provided as a list."}, {"rule_id": "lorenz_y_type", "name": "y_values must be a list", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('y_values'), list)", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'y_values' input representing cumulative income/wealth must be provided as a list."}, {"rule_id": "lorenz_length_match", "name": "x_values and y_values must have same length", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "len(inputs['x_values']) != len(inputs['y_values'])", "applies_to": ["x_values", "y_values"], "description": "The lists for 'x_values' and 'y_values' must have an equal number of elements, representing corresponding data points."}, {"rule_id": "lorenz_x_validity", "name": "x_values must be valid percentiles", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (all(isinstance(x, (float, int)) and 0 <= x <= 1 for x in inputs['x_values']) and len(inputs['x_values']) >= 2 and inputs['x_values'][0] == 0 and inputs['x_values'][-1] == 1 and all(inputs['x_values'][i] <= inputs['x_values'][i+1] for i in range(len(inputs['x_values']) - 1)))", "applies_to": ["x_values"], "description": "All 'x_values' (population percentiles) must be numbers between 0 and 1, sorted in ascending order, starting with 0 and ending with 1, and contain at least two points."}, {"rule_id": "lorenz_y_validity", "name": "y_values must be valid cumulative shares", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (all(isinstance(y, (float, int)) and 0 <= y <= 1 for y in inputs['y_values']) and len(inputs['y_values']) >= 2 and inputs['y_values'][0] == 0 and inputs['y_values'][-1] == 1 and all(inputs['y_values'][i] <= inputs['y_values'][i+1] for i in range(len(inputs['y_values']) - 1)))", "applies_to": ["y_values"], "description": "All 'y_values' (cumulative income/wealth shares) must be numbers between 0 and 1, sorted in ascending order, starting with 0 and ending with 1, and contain at least two points."}, {"rule_id": "lorenz_curve_position", "name": "Lorenz curve cannot be above line of equality", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "any(inputs['y_values'][i] > inputs['x_values'][i] for i in range(len(inputs['x_values'])))", "applies_to": ["x_values", "y_values"], "description": "For a valid Lorenz curve, each cumulative income/wealth share (y_values) must not exceed its corresponding cumulative population percentile (x_values)."}, {"rule_id": "gini_range", "name": "Gini coefficient must be between 0 and 1", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "compute(inputs) < 0 or compute(inputs) > 1", "applies_to": [], "description": "The calculated Gini coefficient must fall within the theoretical range of 0 (perfect equality) and 1 (maximal inequality)."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    x_values = inputs['x_values']\n    y_values = inputs['y_values']\n\n    def lorenz_curve_area(x_values, y_values):\n        area = 0\n        for i in range(1, len(x_values)):\n            width = x_values[i] - x_values[i - 1]\n            height_avg = (y_values[i] + y_values[i - 1]) / 2\n            area += width * height_avg\n        return area\n    area_under_line_of_equality = 0.5\n    area_under_lorenz_curve = lorenz_curve_area(x_values, y_values)\n    gini_coefficient = (area_under_line_of_equality - area_under_lorenz_curve) / area_under_line_of_equality\n    return round(gini_coefficient, 2)"}, "article_title": "Lorenz Curve", "article_doc_id": 4300, "article_content_excerpt": "# Lorenz Curve: Definition and Uses\n\n## What Is a Lorenz Curve? \n\nA Lorenz curve, developed by American economist Max Lorenz in 1905, is a graphical representation of or wealth inequality. The graph plots percentiles of the population on the horizontal axis according to income or and plots cumulative income or wealth on the vertical axis. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * A Lorenz curve is a graphical representation of the distribution of income or wealth within a population.\n * Lorenz curves graph percentiles of the population against cumulative income or wealth of people at or below that percentile. \n * Lorenz curves, along with their derivative statistics, are widely used to measure inequality across a population. \n * The Lorenz curve is a central piece in calculating the Gini coefficient, a mathematical representation of inequality levels.\n * Because Lorenz curves are mathematical estimates based on fitting a continuous curve to incomplete and discontinuous data, they may be imperfect measures of true inequality.\n\n## Understanding the Lorenz Curve \n\nIn practice, a Lorenz curve is usually a mathematical function estimated from an incomplete set of observations of income or wealth. The Lorenz curve is often accompanied by a straight diagonal line with a slope of 1, which represents perfect equality in or wealth distribution; the Lorenz curve lies beneath it, showing the observed or estimated distribution. \n\nWhile the Lorenz curve is most often used to represent , it can also demonstrate unequal distribution in any system. The farther the curve is from the baseline, represented by the straight diagonal line, the higher the level of inequality. In economics, the Lorenz curve denotes inequality in the distribution of either wealth or income. These are not synonymous since it is possible to have either high earnings but zero or negative , or low earnings but a large net worth. \n\nA Lorenz curve usually starts with an empirical measurement of wealth or income distribution across a population based on data such as , which report income for a large portion of the population. A graph of the data may be used directly as a Lorenz curve, or and statisticians may fit a curve that represents a continuous function to fill in any gaps in the observed data. \n\n### Important: \n\nThe closer the Lorenz curve is to the line of equality, the less inequality exists. The further the Lorenz curve is to the line of equality, the more inequality exists. \n\n## Components of the Lorenz Curve \n\nThe Bank of St. Louis collects net worth statistics from U.S. households. As of the second quarter of 2024, the underlying data demonstrates that the bottom 50% of households hold just 2.5% of overall household wealth, while the top 10% holds 67% of total household wealth.\n\nThere are several important components to understand when analyzing a Lorenz curve: \n\n * The _x-axis_ is often denoted as the percentile. In the graph above, the x-axis is the percentile of net worth ranking compared to other U.S. households.\n * The _y-axis_ is often denoted as the cumulative percentage of occurrences. In the graph above, the percentages represent the cumulative amount of net worth of households.\n * The _line of equality_ is demonstrated by a 45-degree, upward-sloping line. In the graph above, it is denoted as the dashed line.\n * The _Lorenz curve_ is demonstrated often by an upward-sloping but often exponentially rising curve. In the graph above, it is denoted as a solid line.\n * The Gini coefficient (discussed below) is the gap between the line of equality and the Lorenz curve. \n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/LorenzCurve-29714394134e45eb8e83b7c57783ec2a.JPG)\n\nLorenz Curve, U.S. Household Net Worth (2019).\n\n## The Lorenz Curve and the Gini Coefficient \n\nThe is used to express the extent of inequality in a single figure. It most often ranges from 0 (or 0%) to 1 (or 100%). Complete equality, in which every individual has the exact same income or wealth, corresponds to a coefficient of 0\n...[truncated]"}
