n"}, {"id": "valuation_basis", "ambiguity_type": "valuation_method", "trigger_signal": "request for 'value' without specifying 'carrying value' or 'fair market value'", "clarification_question": "Are you looking for the carrying value as per the equity method, or the current fair market value of the investment?", "options": [{"label": "Carrying value (equity method) - DEFAULT", "value": "carrying_value_equity_method", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Fair market value (not calculated by this FIC)", "value": "fair_market_value_not_calculated", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "The calculated carrying value using the equity method.", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}, {"id": "ownership_percentage_scale", "ambiguity_type": "unit_scale", "trigger_signal": "ownership percentage provided as integer (e.g., 25) instead of decimal (0.25)", "clarification_question": "Is the ownership percentage provided as a decimal (e.g., 0.25 for 25%) or as a whole number percentage (e.g., 25 for 25%)?", "options": [{"label": "Decimal (e.g., 0.25) - DEFAULT", "value": "decimal", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Whole number percentage (e.g., 25)", "value": "percentage_whole_number", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "hard", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Assumed to be a decimal (e.g., 0.25 for 25%).", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}], "inputs": [{"name": "initial_investment", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The initial value of the investment recorded at historical cost.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "ownership_percentage", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The percentage of ownership in the investee company (e.g., 0.25 for 25%).", "unit": "decimal", "aliases": []}, {"name": "net_income", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The net income reported by the investee company.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "dividends", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The total dividends paid by the investee company.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "adjusted_investment_value", "type": "number", "unit": null, "description": "The adjusted carrying value of the investment."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    initial_investment = inputs['initial_investment']\n    ownership_percentage = inputs['ownership_percentage']\n    net_income = inputs['net_income']\n    dividends = inputs['dividends']\n    income_from_investment = ownership_percentage * net_income\n    dividends_share = ownership_percentage * dividends\n    adjusted_investment_value = initial_investment + income_from_investment - dividends_share\n    return round(adjusted_investment_value)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "initial_investment_non_negative", "name": "Initial investment must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['initial_investment'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The initial investment value must be a non-negative number."}, {"rule_id": "ownership_percentage_range", "name": "Ownership percentage must be between 0 and 1", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (0 <= inputs['ownership_percentage'] <= 1)", "applies_to": [], "description": "Ownership percentage must be expressed as a decimal between 0 and 1 (inclusive)."}, {"rule_id": "net_income_non_negative", "name": "Net income must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['net_income'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "As per the function's constraints, net income should be a non-negative value for this calculation."}, {"rule_id": "dividends_non_negative", "name": "Dividends must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['dividends'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Dividends paid cannot be a negative value."}, {"rule_id": "ownership_percentage_for_equity_method", "name": "Review ownership for equity method applicability", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['ownership_percentage'] < 0.20", "applies_to": [], "description": "Ownership percentage is less than 20%, which typically suggests a lack of significant influence. The equity method of accounting is generally used when significant influence is present. Review if this method is appropriate."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    initial_investment = inputs['initial_investment']\n    ownership_percentage = inputs['ownership_percentage']\n    net_income = inputs['net_income']\n    dividends = inputs['dividends']\n    income_from_investment = ownership_percentage * net_income\n    dividends_share = ownership_percentage * dividends\n    adjusted_investment_value = initial_investment + income_from_investment - dividends_share\n    return round(adjusted_investment_value)"}, "article_title": "Equity Method", "article_doc_id": 5597, "article_content_excerpt": "# Equity Method of Accounting: Definition and Example\n\n## What Is the Equity Method of Accounting? \n\nThe equity method is an technique used to record the profits earned by a company through its investment in another . \n\nUnder the equity method of accounting, the investor company reports the earned by the other company on its . This amount is proportional to the percentage of its equity investment in the other company. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * The equity method of accounting is a technique used to record the profits earned by a company through its investment in another company.\n * The equity method is generally used when a company holds significant influence over the company it is investing in.\n * The investment is initially recorded at historical cost, and adjustments are made to the value based on the ’s percentage ownership in net income, loss, and dividend payouts.\n * Net income of the investee company increases the investor’s asset value on their balance sheet, while the investee’s loss or dividend payout decreases it.\n * The investor also records the percentage of the investee’s net income or loss on their income statement.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/EquityMethod_Final_4196997-4a403840ea2d4bf4aee5ff825b931e67.jpg)\n\nPaige McLaughlin / Investopedia\n\n## Understanding the Equity Method \n\nThe equity method is the standard technique used when one company, the investor, has a significant influence over another company, the investee. When a company holds approximately 20% or more of a company’s stock, it is considered to have significant influence.\n\nSignificant influence means that the investor company can impact the value of the investee company, which in turn benefits the investor. As a result, the change in value of that investment must be reported on the investor’s . \n\nCompanies with less than 20% interest in another company may also hold significant influence, in which case they also need to use the equity method. Significant influence is defined as an ability to exert power over another company. This power includes representation on the , involvement in policy development, and the interchanging of managerial personnel. \n\n### Important\n\nOwning 20% or more of the shares in a company doesn’t automatically mean that the investor exerts significant influence. Operating agreements, ongoing litigation, or the presence of other majority stockholders may indicate that the investor doesn’t exert significant influence and that the equity method of accounting is inappropriate.\n\n## Recording Revenue and Asset Changes Under the Equity Method \n\nThe equity method acknowledges the substantive economic relationship between two entities. The investor records their share of the investee’s as revenue from investment on the income statement. For example, if a firm owns 25% of a company with a $1 million net income, the firm reports earnings from its investment of $250,000 under the equity method. \n\nWhen the investor has a significant influence over the operating and financial results of the investee, this can directly affect the value of the investor’s investment. The investor records their initial investment in the second company’s stock as an at historical cost. Under the equity method, the investment’s value is periodically adjusted to reflect the changes in value due to the investor’s share in the company’s income or losses. Adjustments are also made when dividends are paid out to shareholders. \n\nUsing the equity method, a company reports the carrying value of its investment independent of any fair value change in the market. With a significant influence over another company’s operating and financial policies, the investor is basing their investment value on changes in the value of that company’s net assets from operating and financial activities and the resulting performances, including earnings and losses. \n\nFor example, when the investee company reports a net loss, the investor company records its share of the loss as “loss on inv\n...[truncated]"}
