ue": "decimal", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Percentage (e.g., 3.75) (will be converted to decimal)", "value": "percentage", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Annual interest rate is assumed to be a decimal.", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}], "inputs": [{"name": "principal", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The initial principal or face value of the bond/loan.", "unit": null, "aliases": ["loan_amount", "face_value", "mortgage_amount"]}, {"name": "annual_interest_rate", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The annual interest rate expressed as a decimal.", "unit": null, "aliases": ["rate", "interest_rate"]}, {"name": "years", "type": "integer", "required": true, "description": "The total number of years to amortize the loan/bond.", "unit": null, "aliases": ["loan_term", "term_in_years"]}], "output": {"name": "first_month_interest_paid", "type": "number", "unit": "dollars", "description": "The amount of interest paid during the first month of the mortgage, rounded to two decimal places."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    principal = inputs['principal']\n    annual_interest_rate = inputs['annual_interest_rate']\n    years = inputs['years']\n    monthly_interest_rate = annual_interest_rate / 12\n    first_month_interest_paid = principal * monthly_interest_rate\n    return round(first_month_interest_paid, 2)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "e_val_001", "name": "Positive Principal Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['principal'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The principal amount must be a positive value."}, {"rule_id": "e_val_002", "name": "Positive Interest Rate Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['annual_interest_rate'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The annual interest rate must be a positive value."}, {"rule_id": "e_val_003", "name": "Positive Years Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['years'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The number of years must be a positive integer."}, {"rule_id": "e_plaus_004", "name": "Interest Rate Plausibility Check (Decimal vs Percentage)", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['annual_interest_rate'] >= 1.0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The annual interest rate (expected as a decimal, e.g., 0.05 for 5%) appears to be entered as a percentage (e.g., 5 for 5%). This may lead to incorrect calculations."}, {"rule_id": "e_plaus_005", "name": "Loan Term Upper Bound Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['years'] > 100", "applies_to": [], "description": "A loan term exceeding 100 years is highly unusual and may indicate an incorrect input."}, {"rule_id": "e_plaus_006", "name": "Loan Term Lower Bound Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['years'] < 1", "applies_to": [], "description": "A loan term less than 1 year is uncommon for mortgages and might be an incorrect input."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    principal = inputs['principal']\n    annual_interest_rate = inputs['annual_interest_rate']\n    years = inputs['years']\n    monthly_interest_rate = annual_interest_rate / 12\n    first_month_interest_paid = principal * monthly_interest_rate\n    return round(first_month_interest_paid, 2)"}, "article_title": "What Is an Amortized Bond? How They Work, and Example", "article_doc_id": 4484, "article_content_excerpt": "# What Is an Amortized Bond? How They Work, and Example\n\n## What Is an Amortized Bond? \n\nAn amortized bond is one in which the principal (face value) on the debt is paid down regularly, along with its interest expense over the life of the bond. A fixed-rate residential is one common example because the monthly payment remains constant over its life of, say, 30 years. However, each payment represents a slightly different percentage mix of interest versus principal. An amortized bond is different from a or loan, where there is a large portion of the principal that must be repaid only at its maturity. \n\n## Understanding Amortized Bonds \n\nThe principal paid off over the life of an amortized loan or bond is divvied up according to an , typically through calculating equal payments all along the way. This means that in the early years of a loan, the interest portion of the debt service will be larger than the principal portion. As the loan matures, however, the portion of each payment that goes towards interest will become lesser and the payment to principal will be larger. The calculations for an amortizing loan are similar to that of an using the , and can be carried out quickly using an . \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * An amortized bond is a type where each payment goes towards both interest and principal.\n * In the early stages of the loan, much of each payment will go towards interest, and in late stages, a greater percentage goes towards principal.\n * A fixed-rate 30-year mortgage is an example of an amortized loan.\n * An amortization schedule is used to compute the percentage that is interest and the percentage that is principal within each bond payment.\n * Two accounting methods are used for amortizing bond premiums and discounts: straight-line and effective-interest.\n\nAmortization of debt affects two fundamental risks of bond investing. First, it greatly reduces the of the loan or bond because the principal of the loan is repaid over time, rather than all at once upon maturity, when the risk of default is the greatest. Second, amortization reduces the duration of the bond, lowering the debt's sensitivity to , as compared with other non-amortized debt with the same maturity and coupon rate. This is because as time passes, there are smaller interest payments, so the (WAM) of the cash flows associated with the bond is lower. \n\n## Example of Amortizing a Bond \n\n30-year fixed-rate mortgages are amortized so that each monthly payment goes towards interest and principal. Say you purchase a home with a $400,000 30-year fixed-rate mortgage with a 5% interest rate. The monthly payment is $2,147.29, or $25,767.48 per year. \n\nAt the end of year one, you have made 12 payments, most of the payments have been towards interest, and only $3,406 of the principal is paid off, leaving a loan balance of $396,593. The next year, the monthly payment amount remains the same, but the principal paid grows to $6,075. Now fast forward to year 29 when $24,566 (almost all of the $25,767.48 annual payments) will go towards principal. Free or amortization calculators are easily found online to help with these calculations quickly. \n\n## Straight-Line vs. Effective-Interest Method of Amortization \n\nTreating a bond as an amortized asset is an accounting method used by companies that issue bonds. It allows issuers to treat the as an asset over the life of the bond until its maturity date. A bond is sold at a discount when a company sells it for less than its and sold at a premium when the price received is greater than face value. \n\nIf a bond is issued —that is, offered for sale below its par or face value—the discount must be treated either as an expense or it can be amortized as an asset. In this way, an amortized bond is used specifically for tax purposes because the amortized bond discount is treated as part of a company's interest expense on its income statement. The interest expense, a non-operating cost, reduces a company's (EBT) and, therefore, the amount of\n...[truncated]"}
