me": "call", "type": "boolean", "required": true, "description": "True for a call option, False for a put option.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "current_price", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The current price of the underlying asset.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "strike_price", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The pre-determined price at which the underlying asset can be bought or sold.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "premium_per_share", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The premium paid per share for the option contract.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "contracts", "type": "integer", "required": true, "description": "The number of option contracts, typically representing 100 shares each.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "expiration_price", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The price of the underlying asset at expiration.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "profit_or_loss", "type": "number", "unit": "USD", "description": "The net profit or loss from the options trade at expiration."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    call = inputs['call']\n    strike_price = inputs['strike_price']\n    premium_per_share = inputs['premium_per_share']\n    contracts = inputs['contracts']\n    expiration_price = inputs['expiration_price']\n    shares_per_contract = 100\n    total_shares = shares_per_contract * contracts\n    total_premium = premium_per_share * total_shares\n    if call:\n        intrinsic_value = max(0, expiration_price - strike_price)\n    else:\n        intrinsic_value = max(0, strike_price - expiration_price)\n    total_intrinsic_value = intrinsic_value * total_shares\n    profit_or_loss = total_intrinsic_value - total_premium\n    return profit_or_loss", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "price_non_negative", "name": "Input prices must be non-negative and premium must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['current_price'] < 0 or inputs['strike_price'] < 0 or inputs['expiration_price'] < 0 or inputs['premium_per_share'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["current_price", "strike_price", "expiration_price", "premium_per_share"], "description": "All price inputs must be non-negative, and premium per share must be strictly positive."}, {"rule_id": "contracts_positive", "name": "Number of contracts must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['contracts'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["contracts"], "description": "The number of option contracts must be a positive integer."}, {"rule_id": "premium_plausibility_high", "name": "Premium per share seems unusually high", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['premium_per_share'] >= inputs['strike_price']", "applies_to": ["premium_per_share", "strike_price"], "description": "The premium per share is unusually high, equal to or exceeding the strike price. This could indicate an input error or highly unusual market conditions."}, {"rule_id": "call_deep_out_of_money", "name": "Call option deeply out of the money at expiration", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['call'] and inputs['expiration_price'] < inputs['strike_price'] * 0.5", "applies_to": ["call", "expiration_price", "strike_price"], "description": "For a call option, the expiration price is significantly below the strike price, indicating it expired deeply out of the money, likely resulting in maximum loss."}, {"rule_id": "put_deep_out_of_money", "name": "Put option deeply out of the money at expiration", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "(not inputs['call']) and inputs['expiration_price'] > inputs['strike_price'] * 1.5", "applies_to": ["call", "expiration_price", "strike_price"], "description": "For a put option, the expiration price is significantly above the strike price, indicating it expired deeply out of the money, likely resulting in maximum loss."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    call = inputs['call']\n    strike_price = inputs['strike_price']\n    premium_per_share = inputs['premium_per_share']\n    contracts = inputs['contracts']\n    expiration_price = inputs['expiration_price']\n    shares_per_contract = 100\n    total_shares = shares_per_contract * contracts\n    total_premium = premium_per_share * total_shares\n    if call:\n        intrinsic_value = max(0, expiration_price - strike_price)\n    else:\n        intrinsic_value = max(0, strike_price - expiration_price)\n    total_intrinsic_value = intrinsic_value * total_shares\n    profit_or_loss = total_intrinsic_value - total_premium\n    return profit_or_loss"}, "article_title": "Options Contract", "article_doc_id": 6189, "article_content_excerpt": "# Options Contract: What It Is, How It Works, Types of Contracts\n\nDefinition\n\nAn options contract is an agreement between two parties for a potential transaction on an underlying security at a preset price, called the strike price, before or on the expiration date.\n\n## What Is an Options Contract? \n\nAn options contract is a financial agreement that grants the buyer the right, but not the obligation, to buy or sell a particular asset (like a stock) at a preset price within a given period. As financial markets have grown increasingly complex and, at times, more volatile, options have emerged as a potent way to guard against uncertainty and capitalize on price changes. In just a couple of decades, options, with their ability to leverage gains, manage risk, and strategic flexibility, have moved from an esoteric tool for professionals into a mainstream vehicle. \n\nFrom individual investors to large institutional players, many market participants use options for speculation, hedging, and generating income. The numbers tell the story: trading volume in options has increased by about 150% in the past decade and about 15-fold since 2000. The vast increase in options trading has been helped by a massive spike in retail investor interest, which peaked at almost 50% of all trading volume during the pandemic and has remained in the low 40s by percentage for most months since.\n\nBelow, we take you through what you need to know about these contracts, how they work, who trades them and why, and the advantages and pitfalls to avoid should you add them to your trading strategy. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Options are financial derivatives that give buyers the right, but not the obligation, to buy or sell an underlying asset at a preset price on or before a specific date.\n * There are two main types of options: call options, which give the holder (buyer) the right to buy the underlying asset, and put options, which give the holder (buyer) the right to sell the underlying asset.\n * Depending on your goals and risk tolerance, options contracts can be used for hedging, speculation, and generating income.\n * The price of an option, known as the premium, is affected by the underlying asset's price, the strike price, time until expiration, and market volatility.\n * Options trading carries inherent risks, such as the potential for significant losses if the market moves against your position, and requires a thorough understanding of the mechanics and strategies involved.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/optionscontract.asp-FINAL-369818cf68054f9eb1b4139dd3a413e7.png)\n\nInvestopedia / Jiaqi Zhou\n\n## Understanding Options Contracts \n\nOptions contracts are valued based on the . These contracts allow the buyer to buy or sell—depending on the type of contract they hold—the underlying asset at a price set out in the agreement, either within a specific time frame or at the expiration date. The underlying assets include currencies, stocks, indexes, interest rates, exchange-traded funds, and more.\n\nThe terms of option contracts specify the underlying security, the price at which that security can be bought or sold (the strike price), and the expiration date of the contract. For stocks, a standard contract covers 100 shares, but this number can be adjusted for stock splits, special dividends, or mergers. \n\nOptions are generally used for hedging purposes but can also be employed to speculate on price moves. The contracts generally cost a fraction of what the underlying shares would. Options can provide leverage, meaning that the premium allows you to be exposed to a larger position of shares for a fraction of the cost of buying the underlying security. In exchange for this right, the buyer of the option pays a to the party selling the option. \n\nOptions strategies are adaptable to various market conditions. Traders buy or sell options contracts based on whether they are bullish or bearish on the underlying asset, and they often use strategies that combine several option\n...[truncated]"}
