unit": null, "aliases": ["tax_percentage"]}, {"name": "inflation_rate", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The inflation rate during the period as a decimal (e.g., 0.025 for 2.5%).", "unit": null, "aliases": ["inflation", "annual_inflation"]}], "output": {"name": "after_tax_real_rate_of_return", "type": "number", "unit": null, "description": "The after-tax real rate of return, as a decimal, after accounting for taxes and inflation."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    nominal_return = inputs['nominal_return']\n    tax_rate = inputs['tax_rate']\n    inflation_rate = inputs['inflation_rate']\n    after_tax_return = nominal_return * (1 - tax_rate)\n    after_tax_real_rate_of_return = (1 + after_tax_return) / (1 + inflation_rate) - 1\n    return after_tax_real_rate_of_return", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "nr001", "name": "Nominal Return Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['nominal_return'] < 0", "applies_to": ["nominal_return"], "description": "The nominal rate of return is typically expected to be non-negative for growth calculations. A negative value may indicate a loss, which is valid, but the user should be aware."}, {"rule_id": "tr001", "name": "Tax Rate Out of Bounds", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (0 <= inputs['tax_rate'] <= 1)", "applies_to": ["tax_rate"], "description": "The tax rate must be between 0 (0%) and 1 (100%) inclusive."}, {"rule_id": "ir001", "name": "Inflation Rate Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['inflation_rate'] < 0", "applies_to": ["inflation_rate"], "description": "A negative inflation rate (deflation) is possible but uncommon. Ensure this is the intended input for calculating real returns."}, {"rule_id": "ir002", "name": "Inflation Rate Too Low", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "(1 + inputs['inflation_rate']) <= 0", "applies_to": ["inflation_rate"], "description": "The value (1 + inflation_rate) must be strictly positive to ensure a valid calculation and avoid division by zero or negative base. Inflation rate must be greater than -1."}, {"rule_id": "atr001", "name": "After-Tax Return Invalid Base", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "(1 + (inputs['nominal_return'] * (1 - inputs['tax_rate']))) <= 0", "applies_to": ["nominal_return", "tax_rate"], "description": "The intermediate value (1 + after-tax return) must be strictly positive for a valid real rate calculation. This implies the after-tax return cannot be -1 or less."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    nominal_return = inputs['nominal_return']\n    tax_rate = inputs['tax_rate']\n    inflation_rate = inputs['inflation_rate']\n    after_tax_return = nominal_return * (1 - tax_rate)\n    after_tax_real_rate_of_return = (1 + after_tax_return) / (1 + inflation_rate) - 1\n    return after_tax_real_rate_of_return"}, "article_title": "After-Tax Real Rate of Return", "article_doc_id": 4433, "article_content_excerpt": "# After-Tax Real Rate of Return: Definition and How to Calculate It\n\n## What Is the After-Tax Real Rate of Return? \n\nThe after-tax real rate of return is the actual financial benefit of an investment after accounting for the effects of and . \n\nIt is a more accurate measure of an investor’s net earnings after income taxes have been paid and the rate of inflation has been adjusted. Both of these factors must be accounted for because they impact the gains that an investor receives. This can be contrasted with the and the of an investment. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * The after-tax real rate of return takes into consideration inflation and taxes to determine the true profit or loss of an investment.\n * The opposite of the after-tax real rate of return is the nominal rate of return, which only looks at gross returns.\n * Tax-advantaged investments, such as Roth individual retirement accounts (Roth IRAs) and municipal bonds, will see less of a discrepancy between nominal rates of return and after-tax rates of return.\n\n## Understanding the After-Tax Real Rate of Return \n\nOver the course of a year, an investor might earn a nominal of 12% on his stock investment, but the real rate of return—the money he gets to put in his pocket at the end of the day—will be less than 12%. Inflation might have been 3% for the year, knocking his real rate of return down to 9%. And since he sold his stock at a profit, he will have to pay taxes on those profits, taking more off his return, say 2%, for an after-tax real rate of return of 7%. \n\nThe he paid to buy and sell the stock also diminishes his return. Thus, to truly grow their nest eggs over time, must focus on the after-tax real rate of return, not the nominal rate of return. \n\nThe after-tax real rate of return is a more accurate measure of investment earnings and usually differs significantly from an investment’s nominal (gross) rate of return, or its return before fees, inflation, and taxes. However, investments in securities, such as municipal bonds and inflation-protected securities, such as , as well as investments held in tax-advantaged accounts, such as , will show less discrepancy between nominal rates of return and after-tax real rates of return. \n\n### Tip\n\nThe difference between the nominal rate of return and the after-tax real rate of return isn’t likely to be as great on tax-advantaged accounts like Roth IRAs as it is on other investments.\n\n## Example of the After-Tax Real Rate of Return \n\nLet’s be more specific about how the after-tax real rate of return is determined. First, the return is calculated by determining the after-tax return before inflation, which is calculated as nominal return × (1 - tax rate). For example, consider an investor whose nominal return on his equity investment is 17% and his applicable tax rate is 15%. Therefore, his after-tax return is: 0.17 \\times (1 - 0.15) = 0.1445 = 14.45\\%\n\nLet’s assume that the inflation rate during this period is 2.5%. To calculate the real rate of return after tax, divide 1 plus the after-tax return by 1 plus the inflation rate, then subtract 1. Dividing by inflation reflects the fact that a dollar in hand today is worth more than a dollar in hand tomorrow. In other words, future dollars have less purchasing power than today’s dollars.\n\nFollowing our example, the after-tax real rate of return is:\n\n\\frac{(1 + 0.1445)}{(1 + 0.025)} - 1 = 1.1166 - 1 = 0.1166 = 11.66\\%\n\nThat figure is quite a bit lower than the 17% gross return received on the investment. As long as the real rate of return after taxes is positive, however, an investor will be ahead of inflation. If it’s negative, the return will not be sufficient to sustain an investor’s in the future. \n\n## What Is the Difference Between the After-Tax Real Rate of Return and the Nominal Rate of Return?\n\nThe after-tax real rate of return is figured after accounting for fees, inflation, and tax rates. The nominal rate of return is simply the gross rate of return before considering any outside fa\n...[truncated]"}
