n": "The life expectancy at birth in years.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "mean_years_school", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The mean number of years of schooling a country's residents have undergone.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "expected_years_school", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The expected number of years of schooling that a child will receive.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "gni_per_capita", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The gross national income per capita adjusted for purchasing power parity (PPP).", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "hdi", "type": "number", "unit": "dimensionless", "description": "The Human Development Index, a value between 0 and 1."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "import math\n\ndef compute(inputs):\n    life_expectancy = inputs['life_expectancy']\n    mean_years_school = inputs['mean_years_school']\n    expected_years_school = inputs['expected_years_school']\n    gni_per_capita = inputs['gni_per_capita']\n    life_expectancy_index = (life_expectancy - 20) / (85 - 20) if 20 <= life_expectancy <= 85 else 0\n    education_index = (mean_years_school / 15 + expected_years_school / 18) / 2\n    gni_index = (gni_per_capita - 100) / (75000 - 100) if 100 <= gni_per_capita <= 75000 else 0\n    hdi = (life_expectancy_index * education_index * gni_index) ** (1 / 3)\n    return hdi", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "hdi_life_expectancy_range", "name": "Life Expectancy Range Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (20 <= inputs['life_expectancy'] <= 85)", "applies_to": ["life_expectancy"], "description": "Life expectancy at birth must be between 20 and 85 years for accurate HDI calculation. Values outside this range will result in a life expectancy index of 0."}, {"rule_id": "hdi_mean_school_min", "name": "Mean Years of Schooling Minimum Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['mean_years_school'] < 0", "applies_to": ["mean_years_school"], "description": "Mean years of schooling cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "hdi_mean_school_max", "name": "Mean Years of Schooling Maximum Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['mean_years_school'] > 15", "applies_to": ["mean_years_school"], "description": "Mean years of schooling exceeding 15 years may lead to an education index component greater than 1, indicating unusual input, though the calculation will proceed."}, {"rule_id": "hdi_expected_school_min", "name": "Expected Years of Schooling Minimum Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['expected_years_school'] < 0", "applies_to": ["expected_years_school"], "description": "Expected years of schooling cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "hdi_expected_school_max", "name": "Expected Years of Schooling Maximum Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['expected_years_school'] > 18", "applies_to": ["expected_years_school"], "description": "Expected years of schooling exceeding 18 years may lead to an education index component greater than 1, indicating unusual input, though the calculation will proceed."}, {"rule_id": "hdi_gni_per_capita_range", "name": "GNI per Capita Range Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (100 <= inputs['gni_per_capita'] <= 75000)", "applies_to": ["gni_per_capita"], "description": "GNI per capita must be between $100 and $75,000 for accurate HDI calculation. Values outside this range will result in a GNI index of 0."}, {"rule_id": "hdi_output_range", "name": "HDI Output Range Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not 0 <= compute(inputs) <= 1.000000001", "applies_to": [], "description": "The Human Development Index (HDI) must be a value between 0 and 1. An out-of-range result indicates an issue with input values or calculation."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": false, "error": "__import__ not found", "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "import math\n\ndef compute(inputs):\n    life_expectancy = inputs['life_expectancy']\n    mean_years_school = inputs['mean_years_school']\n    expected_years_school = inputs['expected_years_school']\n    gni_per_capita = inputs['gni_per_capita']\n    life_expectancy_index = (life_expectancy - 20) / (85 - 20) if 20 <= life_expectancy <= 85 else 0\n    education_index = (mean_years_school / 15 + expected_years_school / 18) / 2\n    gni_index = (gni_per_capita - 100) / (75000 - 100) if 100 <= gni_per_capita <= 75000 else 0\n    hdi = (life_expectancy_index * education_index * gni_index) ** (1 / 3)\n    return hdi"}, "article_title": "Human Development Index (HDI)", "article_doc_id": 2149, "article_content_excerpt": "# What Is the Human Development Index (HDI)?\n\n## What Is the Human Development Index (HDI)? \n\nThe Human Development Index (HDI) is a statistic developed and compiled by the United Nations since 1990 to measure various countries’ levels of social and economic development. It is composed of four principal areas of interest: mean years of schooling, expected years of schooling, at birth, and (GNI) per capita. \n\nThis index is a tool used to follow changes in development levels over time and compare the development levels of different countries. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * The Human Development Index (HDI) is a measurement system used by the United Nations to evaluate the level of individual human development in each country.\n * It was introduced by the U.N. in 1990.\n * The HDI was created to emphasize that people and their capabilities should be the ultimate criteria for assessing the development of a country, not economic growth alone.\n * The HDI uses components such as average annual income and educational expectations to rank and compare countries.\n * Social advocates have criticized the HDI for not representing a broad enough measure of the quality of life and economists for providing little additional useful information beyond simpler measures of the economic standard of living.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/human-development-index-hdi.asp-final-57aa610efde34482bf9a48594216674a.jpg)\n\nInvestopedia / Jake Shi\n\n## Understanding the Human Development Index (HDI) \n\nThe HDI was established to place emphasis on individuals—or,**** more precisely, on their opportunities to realize satisfying work and lives. Evaluating a country’s potential for individual human development provides a supplementary metric for evaluating a country’s level of development besides considering standard economic growth statistics, such as (GDP). \n\nThis index can also be used to examine the various policy choices of nations; if, for example, two countries have approximately the same GNI per capita, then the HDI can help to evaluate why they produce widely disparate human development outcomes. Proponents of the HDI hope it can be used to stimulate such productive public policy debate.\n\n## How Is the HDI Measured? \n\nThe HDI is a summary measurement of basic achievement levels in human development. The computed HDI of a country is an average of indexes of each of the life aspects that are examined: knowledge and understanding, a long and healthy life, and an acceptable . Each of the components is normalized to a scale between zero and one, and then the of the three components is calculated.\n\n * The **health** aspect of the HDI is measured by the life expectancy, as calculated at the time of birth, in each country, and normalized so that this component is equal to zero when life expectancy is 20 and equal to one when life expectancy is 85.\n * **Education** is measured on two levels: the mean years of schooling for residents of a country, and the expected years of schooling that a child has at the average age for starting school. These are each separately normalized so that both 15 mean years of schooling and 18 years of expected schooling equal one, and a simple mean of the two is calculated.\n * The **economic metric** chosen to represent the standard of living is GNI per capita based on , a common metric used to reflect average income. The standard of living is normalized so that it is equal to one when the GNI per capita is $75,000 and equal to zero when the GNI per capita is $100.\n\nThe final HDI score for each country is calculated as a geometric mean of the three components by taking the cube root of the product of the normalized component scores.\n\n### Fast Fact: \n\nSwitzerland scores the highest among 193 countries in the 2023/2024 HDI rankings from the U.N.\n\n## HDI Rankings \n\nTop HDI scores go heavily to Northern European countries, while the lowest-scoring nations are largely found on the African continent. \n\nThe top 25 countries in the 2023/2024 HDI rank\n...[truncated]"}
