l_start = inputs['target_interval_start']\n    target_interval_end = inputs['target_interval_end']\n    if not data:\n        return 0\n    if interval_width <= 0:\n        raise ValueError('Interval width must be a positive number.')\n    min_value, max_value = (min(data), max(data))\n    intervals = []\n    current_start = min_value\n    while current_start <= max_value:\n        current_end = current_start + interval_width\n        intervals.append((current_start, current_end))\n        current_start = current_end\n    if not intervals and data:\n        intervals.append((min_value, min_value + interval_width))\n    frequency_distribution = {interval: 0 for interval in intervals}\n    for value in data:\n        for start, end in intervals:\n            if start <= value < end:\n                frequency_distribution[start, end] += 1\n                break\n    target_frequency = 0\n    target_key = (target_interval_start, target_interval_end)\n    if target_key in frequency_distribution:\n        target_frequency = frequency_distribution[target_key]\n    return target_frequency", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "data_not_empty", "name": "Data set must not be empty", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "len(inputs['data']) == 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The input 'data' list cannot be empty as frequency distribution requires data points."}, {"rule_id": "interval_width_positive", "name": "Interval width must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['interval_width'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'interval_width' must be a positive number to form meaningful intervals."}, {"rule_id": "target_interval_order", "name": "Target interval start must be less than end", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['target_interval_start'] >= inputs['target_interval_end']", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'target_interval_start' must be strictly less than 'target_interval_end' to define a valid range."}, {"rule_id": "data_elements_numerical", "name": "All data elements must be numerical", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "all(isinstance(x, (int, float)) for x in inputs['data'])", "applies_to": ["data"], "description": "All elements within the 'data' list must be either integers or floating-point numbers."}, {"rule_id": "target_interval_plausibility", "name": "Target interval plausibly contains data", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "len(inputs['data']) > 0 and (inputs['target_interval_end'] <= min(inputs['data']) or inputs['target_interval_start'] >= max(inputs['data']))", "applies_to": ["target_interval_start", "target_interval_end", "data"], "description": "The target interval appears to be entirely outside the observed data range. This might lead to a zero frequency, but could be intentional."}, {"rule_id": "interval_width_not_too_small", "name": "Interval width should not be excessively small", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "len(inputs['data']) > 1 and (max(inputs['data']) - min(inputs['data'])) > 0 and inputs['interval_width'] < 1e-6 * (max(inputs['data']) - min(inputs['data']))", "applies_to": ["interval_width", "data"], "description": "An excessively small interval width relative to the data range might lead to too many bins or float precision issues."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": false, "error": "__import__ not found", "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "import math\n\ndef compute(inputs):\n    data = inputs['data']\n    interval_width = inputs['interval_width']\n    target_interval_start = inputs['target_interval_start']\n    target_interval_end = inputs['target_interval_end']\n    if not data:\n        return 0\n    if interval_width <= 0:\n        raise ValueError('Interval width must be a positive number.')\n    min_value, max_value = (min(data), max(data))\n    intervals = []\n    current_start = min_value\n    while current_start <= max_value:\n        current_end = current_start + interval_width\n        intervals.append((current_start, current_end))\n        current_start = current_end\n    if not intervals and data:\n        intervals.append((min_value, min_value + interval_width))\n    frequency_distribution = {interval: 0 for interval in intervals}\n    for value in data:\n        for start, end in intervals:\n            if start <= value < end:\n                frequency_distribution[start, end] += 1\n                break\n    target_frequency = 0\n    target_key = (target_interval_start, target_interval_end)\n    if target_key in frequency_distribution:\n        target_frequency = frequency_distribution[target_key]\n    return target_frequency"}, "article_title": "Frequency Distribution", "article_doc_id": 1186, "article_content_excerpt": "# Frequency Distribution: Definition\n\n## What Is a Frequency Distribution? \n\nA frequency distribution is a representation, either in a graphical or tabular format, that displays the number of observations within a given interval. The frequency is how often a value occurs in an interval, while the is the pattern of frequency of the variable. \n\nThe interval size depends on the data being analyzed and the goals of the analyst. The intervals must be mutually exclusive and exhaustive. Frequency distributions are typically used within a statistical context when dealing with quantitative data, such as demographical or population data collected by a census, or financial figures in the context of stock trading. Generally, frequency distributions can be associated with the charting of a . \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * In statistics, a frequency distribution is a representation that displays the number of observations within a given interval.\n * The representation of a frequency distribution can be graphical or tabular.\n * Frequency distributions are particularly useful for normal distributions, which show the observations of probabilities divided among standard deviations.\n * In finance, traders use frequency distributions to take note of price action and identify trends.\n\n## Understanding a Frequency Distribution \n\nAs a tool, a frequency distribution provides a visual representation of the distribution of observations within a particular test. Analysts often use a frequency distribution to visualize or illustrate the data collected in a sample. For example, the height of children can be split into several different categories or ranges. \n\nIn measuring the height of 50 children, some are tall and some are short, but there is a high probability of a higher frequency or concentration in the middle range. The most important factors for gathering data are that the intervals used must not overlap and must contain all of the possible observations. \n\n### Frequency Distribution Calculation\n\nTo calculate frequency distribution: \n\n 1. Calculate the range of the data set.\n 2. Divide the range by the number of the group that you want your data in, then round up.\n 3. Use class width to create groups.\n 4. Find the frequency for each group.\n\n## Visual Representation of a Frequency Distribution \n\nBoth histograms and bar charts provide a visual display using columns, with the y axis representing the frequency count and the x axis representing the variable to be measured. In the height of children, for example, the y axis is the number of children and the x axis is the height. The columns represent the number of children observed, with heights measured in each interval. \n\nIn general, a chart will typically show a normal distribution, which means that the majority of occurrences will fall in the middle columns. Frequency distributions can be a key aspect of charting normal distributions that show observation probabilities divided among . \n\nFrequency distributions can be presented as a frequency table, a histogram, or a bar chart. Below is an example of a frequency distribution as a table. \n \n<table> \n<tr> \n<th>\n\nHeight of Children in a School\n</th> </tr> \n<tr> \n<td>\n\n**Interval (Height)**\n</td> \n<td>\n\n4’\n</td> \n<td>\n\n4’5”\n</td> \n<td>\n\n5’\n</td> \n<td>\n\n5’2”\n</td> </tr> \n<tr> \n<td>\n\n**Frequency**\n</td> \n<td>\n\n2\n</td> \n<td>\n\n5\n</td> \n<td>\n\n6\n</td> \n<td>\n\n3\n</td> </tr> </table>\n\n## Frequency Distribution in Trading \n\nFrequency distributions are not commonly used in the world of ; however, who follow , a pioneering early 20th century trader, use an approach to trading that involves frequency distribution. \n\nInvestment houses still use the approach, which requires considerable practice, to teach traders. The frequency chart is referred to as a point-and-figure chart and was created out of a need for to take note of price action and to identify trends.\n\nThe y axis is the variable measured, and the x axis is the frequency count. Each change in price action is denoted in\n...[truncated]"}
