FAULT", "value": "annual", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Monthly (The provided 'annual_rate' is a nominal annual rate, and 'periods' are in years. The function will need to adjust them to monthly rates/periods for calculation.)", "value": "monthly", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Annual compounding, where 'annual_rate' is the effective annual rate and 'periods' are in years.", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}], "inputs": [{"name": "principal", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The initial principal amount (investment or loan).", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "annual_rate", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The annual interest rate as a decimal (e.g., 0.05 for 5%). This is interpreted as the effective rate per compounding period based on the 'periods' unit.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "periods", "type": "integer", "required": true, "description": "The number of compounding periods (e.g., years, months). This is the total number of periods over which compounding occurs, consistent with the 'annual_rate' interpretation.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "compound_interest", "type": "number", "unit": null, "description": "The total compound interest earned or owed, rounded to two decimal places."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    principal = inputs['principal']\n    annual_rate = inputs['annual_rate']\n    periods = inputs['periods']\n    compound_interest = principal * ((1 + annual_rate) ** periods - 1)\n    return round(compound_interest, 2)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "ci_001", "name": "Principal Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['principal'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["principal"], "description": "The initial principal amount must be a positive value to calculate interest."}, {"rule_id": "ci_002", "name": "Annual Rate Must Be Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['annual_rate'] < 0", "applies_to": ["annual_rate"], "description": "The annual interest rate cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "ci_003", "name": "Annual Rate Plausibility (Percentage vs. Decimal)", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['annual_rate'] > 1.0", "applies_to": ["annual_rate"], "description": "The annual interest rate is typically expressed as a decimal (e.g., 0.04 for 4%). A value greater than 1.0 might indicate it was entered as a percentage (e.g., 4 instead of 0.04)."}, {"rule_id": "ci_004", "name": "Periods Must Be Positive Integer", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (isinstance(inputs['periods'], int) and inputs['periods'] > 0)", "applies_to": ["periods"], "description": "The number of compounding periods must be a positive integer."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    principal = inputs['principal']\n    annual_rate = inputs['annual_rate']\n    periods = inputs['periods']\n    compound_interest = principal * ((1 + annual_rate) ** periods - 1)\n    return round(compound_interest, 2)"}, "article_title": "Compound Interest", "article_doc_id": 204, "article_content_excerpt": "# The Power of Compound Interest: Calculations and Examples\n\n## What Is Compound Interest? \n\nCompound interest is interest that applies not only to the initial principal of an investment or a loan, but also to the accumulated interest from previous periods. In other words, compound interest involves earning, or owing, interest on your interest. \n\nThe power of compounding helps a sum of money grow faster than if just were calculated on the principal alone. And the greater the number of compounding periods, the greater the compound interest growth will be. For savings and investments, compound interest is your friend, as it multiplies your money at an accelerated rate. But if you have debt, compounding of the can make it increasingly difficult to pay off. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Compounding multiplies savings or debt at an accelerated rate.\n * Compound interest is interest calculated on both the initial principal and all of the previously accumulated interest.\n * Generating \"interest on interest\" is known as the power of compound interest.\n * Interest can be compounded on a variety of frequencies, such as daily, monthly, quarterly, or annually.\n * The higher the number of compounding periods, the larger the effect of compounding.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/compoundinterest_final-5c67da5662ba458f8d9d229ab4ca4292.png)\n\nInvestopedia / Julie Bang\n\n## How Compound Interest Works \n\nCompound interest is calculated by multiplying the initial principal amount by one plus the annual interest rate raised to the number of compound periods minus one. The total initial principal or is then subtracted from the resulting value. \n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/COMPOUNDINTERESTFINALJPEGcopy-f248781269194135aa6044e088de7af9.jpg)\n\nKatie Kerpel {Copyright} Investopedia, 2019.\n\nThe formula for calculating is: \n\n * **Compound interest** = total amount of principal and interest in future (or future value) minus principal amount at present (or present value)\n\n> **= [P (1 + i) n] – P**\n\n> **= P [(1 + i) n – 1]**\n\nWhere: \n\n> P = principal \n\n> i = annual interest rate \n\n> n = number of compounding periods \n\nAs an example, take a 3-year loan of $10,000 at an interest rate of 5%, compounding annually. What would be the amount of interest? In this case, it would be: \n\n> $10,000 [(1 + 0.05)3 – 1] = $10,000 [1.157625 – 1] = $1,576.25 \n\n### Tip: \n\nThe Rule of 72 is another way to estimate compound interest. If you divide 72 by your rate of return, you find out how long it will take your money will double in value. For example, if you have $100 that was earning a 4% return, it would grow to $200 in 18 years (72 / 4 = 18).\n\n## The Power of Compound Interest \n\nBecause compound interest includes interest accumulated in previous periods, it grows at an ever-accelerating rate. In the example above, though the total interest payable over the loan's three years is $1,576.25, the interest amount is not the same . The interest payable at the end of each year is shown in the table below. \n\nCompound interest can significantly boost investment returns over the long term. Over 10 years, a $100,000 deposit receiving 5% simple annual interest would earn $50,000 in total interest. But if the same deposit had a monthly compound interest rate of 5%, interest would add up to about $64,700. While compound interest is interest-on-interest, is the addition of all interest payments. \n\n### Tip\n\nOrder your copy of Investopedia's for more wealth-building advice.\n\n### Compounding Interest Periods \n\nCompounding periods are the time intervals between when interest is added to the account. Interest can be compounded annually, semi-annually, quarterly, monthly, daily, continuously, or on any other basis.\n\nInterest on an account but only credited monthly. Only when the interest is credited, or added to the existing balance, does the interest begin to earn additional interest. Standard compounding frequency schedules are usually applied to financial instruments: \n\n * **Savings acco\n...[truncated]"}
