unded rate", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}, {"id": "output_volatility_scale", "ambiguity_type": "unit_scale", "trigger_signal": "implied volatility output format (decimal vs. percentage) not specified", "clarification_question": "Should the implied volatility be expressed as a decimal (e.g., 0.25) or as a percentage (e.g., 25.0%)?", "options": [{"label": "Percentage (e.g., 25.0%) - DEFAULT", "value": "percent", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Decimal (e.g., 0.25)", "value": "decimal", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "result / 100.0", "max_expr_nodes": 6, "invariant": "result_new == result_old / 100.0", "affected_inputs": []}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Percentage (e.g., 25.0%)", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "option_market_price", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The market price of the option.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "stock_price", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The current price of the underlying stock.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "strike_price", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The strike price of the option.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "time_to_expiration", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "Time to expiration in years.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "risk_free_rate", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The risk-free interest rate as a decimal (continuously compounded).", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "option_type", "type": "string", "required": false, "description": "The type of option to solve ('call' or 'put'). Default is 'call'.", "unit": null, "aliases": ["type_of_option"]}], "output": {"name": "implied_volatility", "type": "number", "unit": "percent", "description": "The estimated implied volatility of the option."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "import math\nfrom scipy.stats import norm\nfrom scipy.optimize import brentq\n\ndef compute(inputs):\n    option_market_price = inputs['option_market_price']\n    stock_price = inputs['stock_price']\n    strike_price = inputs['strike_price']\n    time_to_expiration = inputs['time_to_expiration']\n    risk_free_rate = inputs['risk_free_rate']\n    option_type = inputs.get('option_type', 'call')\n\n    def black_scholes_option_price(S, K, T, r, sigma, option_type_local):\n        d1 = (math.log(S / K) + (r + 0.5 * sigma ** 2) * T) / (sigma * math.sqrt(T))\n        d2 = d1 - sigma * math.sqrt(T)\n        if option_type_local == 'call':\n            price = S * norm.cdf(d1) - K * math.exp(-r * T) * norm.cdf(d2)\n        elif option_type_local == 'put':\n            price = K * math.exp(-r * T) * norm.cdf(-d2) - S * norm.cdf(-d1)\n        else:\n            raise ValueError(\"Invalid option_type. Must be 'call' or 'put'.\")\n        return price\n\n    def objective_function(vol):\n        return black_scholes_option_price(stock_price, strike_price, time_to_expiration, risk_free_rate, vol, option_type) - option_market_price\n    implied_volatility = brentq(objective_function, 1e-10, 5.0)\n    return implied_volatility * 100", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "positive_option_market_price", "name": "Option Market Price must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['option_market_price'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["option_market_price"], "description": "The option's market price must be a positive value."}, {"rule_id": "positive_stock_price", "name": "Stock Price must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['stock_price'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["stock_price"], "description": "The underlying stock price must be a positive value."}, {"rule_id": "positive_strike_price", "name": "Strike Price must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['strike_price'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["strike_price"], "description": "The option's strike price must be a positive value."}, {"rule_id": "positive_time_to_expiration", "name": "Time to Expiration must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['time_to_expiration'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["time_to_expiration"], "description": "Time to expiration must be a positive value, representing years remaining until expiry."}, {"rule_id": "valid_risk_free_rate_range", "name": "Risk-Free Rate must be plausible", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['risk_free_rate'] < -0.1 or inputs['risk_free_rate'] > 1.0", "applies_to": ["risk_free_rate"], "description": "The risk-free rate should typically be between -10% and 100% as a decimal for plausibility."}, {"rule_id": "valid_option_type", "name": "Option Type must be 'call' or 'put'", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs.get('option_type', 'call') not in ['call', 'put']", "applies_to": ["option_type"], "description": "The option type must be either 'call' or 'put'."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": false, "error": "__import__ not found", "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "import math\nfrom scipy.stats import norm\nfrom scipy.optimize import brentq\n\ndef compute(inputs):\n    option_market_price = inputs['option_market_price']\n    stock_price = inputs['stock_price']\n    strike_price = inputs['strike_price']\n    time_to_expiration = inputs['time_to_expiration']\n    risk_free_rate = inputs['risk_free_rate']\n    option_type = inputs.get('option_type', 'call')\n\n    def black_scholes_option_price(S, K, T, r, sigma, option_type_local):\n        d1 = (math.log(S / K) + (r + 0.5 * sigma ** 2) * T) / (sigma * math.sqrt(T))\n        d2 = d1 - sigma * math.sqrt(T)\n        if option_type_local == 'call':\n            price = S * norm.cdf(d1) - K * math.exp(-r * T) * norm.cdf(d2)\n        elif option_type_local == 'put':\n            price = K * math.exp(-r * T) * norm.cdf(-d2) - S * norm.cdf(-d1)\n        else:\n            raise ValueError(\"Invalid option_type. Must be 'call' or 'put'.\")\n        return price\n\n    def objective_function(vol):\n        return black_scholes_option_price(stock_price, strike_price, time_to_expiration, risk_free_rate, vol, option_type) - option_market_price\n    implied_volatility = brentq(objective_function, 1e-10, 5.0)\n    return implied_volatility * 100"}, "article_title": "Option Pricing Theory", "article_doc_id": 6183, "article_content_excerpt": "# Option Pricing Theory: Definition, History, Models, and Goals\n\n## What Is Option Pricing Theory? \n\nOption pricing theory derives an estimated value of an using the calculated probability that the contract will finish (ITM) at expiration. Market makers use theoretical models to generate a starting value that they subsequently adjust using proprietary factors to arrive at their offered price, also known as the option premium. Essentially, option pricing theory provides an evaluation of an option's fair value, which traders incorporate into their strategies. \n\nModels used to price options account for variables such as current market price, , volatility, interest rate, and time to expiration to theoretically value an option. Some commonly used models to value options are , binomial option pricing, and Monte-Carlo simulation. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Option pricing theory is a probabilistic approach to assigning a value to an options contract.\n * The primary goal of option pricing theory is to calculate the probability that an option will be exercised, or be in-the-money (ITM), at expiration.\n * Increasing an option's maturity or implied volatility will increase the price of the option, holding all else constant.\n * Some commonly used models to price options include the Black-Scholes model, binomial tree, and Monte-Carlo simulation method.\n\n## Understanding Option Pricing Theory \n\nThe primary goal of option pricing theory is to calculate the probability that an option will be , or be ITM, at expiration and assign a dollar value to it. The price (e.g., a stock price), exercise price, volatility, interest rate, and time to expiration, which is the number of days between the calculation date and the option's exercise date, are that are input into mathematical models to derive an option's theoretical fair value. \n\nOptions pricing theory also derives various risk factors or sensitivities based on those inputs, which are known as an option's \"\". Since market conditions are constantly changing, the Greeks provide traders with a means of determining how sensitive a specific trade is to price fluctuations, fluctuations, and the passage of time. \n\n### Important: \n\nThe greater the chances that the option will finish ITM and be profitable, the greater the value of the option, and vice-versa.\n\nThe longer that an investor has to exercise the option, the greater the likelihood that it will be ITM and profitable at . This means, all else equal, longer-dated options are more valuable. Similarly, the more volatile the underlying asset, the greater the odds that it will expire ITM. Higher , too, should translate into higher option prices. \n\n## Special Considerations \n\nMarketable options require different valuation methods than options. Real traded options prices are determined in the and, as with all assets, the value can differ from a theoretical value. However, having the theoretical value allows traders to assess the likelihood of profiting from trading those options. \n\nThe evolution of the modern-day options market is attributed to the 1973 pricing model published by Fischer Black and Myron Scholes. The Black-Scholes formula is used to derive a theoretical price for financial instruments with a known expiration date. However, this is not the only model. The Cox, Ross, and Rubinstein and are also widely used. \n\n## Using the Black-Scholes Option Pricing Theory \n\nThe original Black-Scholes model required five input variables—the strike price of an option, the current price of the stock, time to expiration, the of return, and volatility. Direct observation of future volatility is impossible, so it must be estimated or implied. Thus, is not the same as historical or realized volatility. \n\n### Fast Fact: \n\nFor many options on stocks, are often used as a sixth input.\n\nThe Black-Scholes model, one of the most highly regarded pricing models, assumes stock prices follow a because asset prices cannot be negative. Other assumptions made by the model are tha\n...[truncated]"}
