tion": "The portion (as a decimal) of costs, after the deductible, that the policyholder is responsible for.", "unit": "decimal", "aliases": []}, {"name": "out_of_pocket_max", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The maximum out-of-pocket expense a policyholder will pay in a year.", "unit": "USD", "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "total_out_of_pocket", "type": "number", "unit": "USD", "description": "The total out-of-pocket cost paid by the policyholder for the healthcare service."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    total_billed_amount = inputs['total_billed_amount']\n    deductible = inputs['deductible']\n    coinsurance_rate = inputs['coinsurance_rate']\n    out_of_pocket_max = inputs['out_of_pocket_max']\n    pay_after_deductible = max(total_billed_amount - deductible, 0)\n    current_out_of_pocket = min(deductible, total_billed_amount)\n    coinsurance_cost = pay_after_deductible * coinsurance_rate\n    total_potential_out_of_pocket = current_out_of_pocket + coinsurance_cost\n    total_out_of_pocket = min(total_potential_out_of_pocket, out_of_pocket_max)\n    return total_out_of_pocket", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "coinsurance_rate_bounds", "name": "Coinsurance Rate must be between 0 and 1", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "0 <= inputs['coinsurance_rate'] <= 1", "applies_to": ["coinsurance_rate"], "description": "The coinsurance rate must be a decimal value between 0 and 1 (inclusive) to represent a valid percentage."}, {"rule_id": "total_billed_amount_non_negative", "name": "Total Billed Amount must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "inputs['total_billed_amount'] >= 0", "applies_to": ["total_billed_amount"], "description": "The total billed amount cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "deductible_non_negative", "name": "Deductible must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "inputs['deductible'] >= 0", "applies_to": ["deductible"], "description": "The deductible amount cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "out_of_pocket_max_non_negative", "name": "Out-of-Pocket Maximum must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "inputs['out_of_pocket_max'] >= 0", "applies_to": ["out_of_pocket_max"], "description": "The out-of-pocket maximum cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "deductible_vs_oop_max", "name": "Deductible should not exceed Out-of-Pocket Maximum", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "inputs['deductible'] <= inputs['out_of_pocket_max']", "applies_to": ["deductible", "out_of_pocket_max"], "description": "Typically, the deductible is less than or equal to the out-of-pocket maximum. A higher deductible might indicate an unusual plan structure."}, {"rule_id": "total_billed_amount_positive", "name": "Total Billed Amount should be positive for meaningful calculation", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "inputs['total_billed_amount'] > 0", "applies_to": ["total_billed_amount"], "description": "A zero or negative total billed amount would result in no out-of-pocket cost and might not be a meaningful scenario."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    total_billed_amount = inputs['total_billed_amount']\n    deductible = inputs['deductible']\n    coinsurance_rate = inputs['coinsurance_rate']\n    out_of_pocket_max = inputs['out_of_pocket_max']\n    pay_after_deductible = max(total_billed_amount - deductible, 0)\n    current_out_of_pocket = min(deductible, total_billed_amount)\n    coinsurance_cost = pay_after_deductible * coinsurance_rate\n    total_potential_out_of_pocket = current_out_of_pocket + coinsurance_cost\n    total_out_of_pocket = min(total_potential_out_of_pocket, out_of_pocket_max)\n    return total_out_of_pocket"}, "article_title": "Out-of-Pocket Limit", "article_doc_id": 6248, "article_content_excerpt": "# What Is an Out-of-Pocket Maximum? Definition and How It Works\n\n## What Is an Out-of-Pocket Maximum? \n\nAn out-of-pocket maximum is the most you have to pay per year for covered healthcare services. When you have spent this amount in your plan year on , , and for in-network care and services, your health insurer will pay for 100% of your healthcare services.\n\nAn out-of-pocket maximum helps you to control the because you know the maximum you will ever have to pay in a year. The out-of-pocket maximum for can't be above a set amount each year. For the 2022 plan year, this amount is $8,700 for an individual and $17,400 for a family.\n\nOut-of-pocket maximums help individuals and families avoid major financial problems associated with high healthcare costs in years when they need a lot of treatment. There are some exceptions, though, so make sure you understand what is and isn't covered. Otherwise, you may end up with a nasty surprise. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * An out-of-pocket maximum, also referred to as an out-of-pocket limit, is the most a health insurance policyholder will pay each year for covered healthcare expenses.\n * When this limit is reached, your health plan will cover 100% of your qualified expenses.\n * You can generally choose from a range of plans with different out-of-pocket limits. However, plans with lower out-of-pocket maximums normally have higher premiums, and those with higher out-of-pocket maximums have lower premiums.\n * Some individuals (or families) may qualify for lower out-of-pocket maximums if they earn under certain income thresholds or meet other requirements.\n\n## Understanding Out-of-Pocket Maximums \n\nIn general, an out-of-pocket maximum is the most you have to pay per year for covered healthcare services. When you have spent up to this amount on your healthcare in a year, your healthcare insurer will pay for 100% of your healthcare costs. Deductibles, copayments, and coinsurance all count toward your out-of-pocket maximum under the . \n\nIn practice, however, it's a little more complicated than that. \n\nFor example, there are some costs that aren't included in your out-of-pocket maximum. These include: \n\n * Your \n * Anything you spend for services your plan doesn't cover\n * Out-of-network care and services\n * Costs above the allowed amount for a service that a provider may charge\n\nThese exceptions mean that even when you reach your out-of-pocket maximum for the year, you will still have to pay your premiums to stay covered. You should also be careful to use in-network healthcare providers if you want to control the costs of your healthcare, because out-of-network costs don't count toward your out-of-pocket maximum. \n\nAlso, costs that aren't considered covered expenses don't count toward the out-of-pocket maximum. For example, if the insured pays $2,000 for an elective surgery that isn't covered, that amount will not count toward the maximum. This means that you could end up paying more than the out-of-pocket limit in a given year. \n\n### Out-of-pocket maximum limits \n\nThe highest out-of-pocket maximum you will have to pay is controlled by federal law. The government has set limits that control how much healthcare insurers can charge for covered services per year. These are: \n\n * For the 2022 plan year: The out-of-pocket limit for a Marketplace plan can’t be more than $8,700 for an individual and $17,400 for a family.\n * For the 2021 plan year: The out-of-pocket limit for a Marketplace plan can’t be more than $8,550 for an individual and $17,100 for a family.\n\n### Choosing an out-of-pocket maximum \n\nDifferent healthcare plans have different out-of-pocket maximum limits, so you may have a choice when it comes to your out-of-pocket maximum. \n\nIn general, you should choose the plan with the lowest out-of-pocket maximum. This will keep the maximum amount you spend per year as low as possible. However, insurance companies balance the out-of-pocket maximums they offer against the premiums they charge. \n\nThis mean\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_2851", "name": "Nanny Tax", "short_description": "Calculates the total federal nanny tax liability, encompassing both employer and employee shares of Social Security and Medicare taxes, plus federal unemployment tax (FUTA), based on annual wages paid to a household employee.", "domain": "personal_finance", "topic": "taxcalc", "topic_extension": false, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-2851", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-269", "question_id": "test-2079", "difficulty": 4.499809670330265, "level": "hard", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "b815a59f5a5d15c2dd93fcbac39b936b3119784d5307042fdb51e67b8f6df556", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["nanny tax", "household employee tax", "social security tax", "medicare tax", "federal unemployment tax", "FUTA", "employment tax", "IRS Publication 926"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "tax_scope_federal_state", "ambiguity_type": "scope", "trigger_signal": "The term 'nanny tax' can implicitly refer to federal, or federal plus state taxes; explicit mention of state taxes in article but not computed by FIC.", "clarification_question": "Does 'nanny tax' refer only to federal taxes, or should state-level taxes also be considered in the calculation?", "options": [{"label": "Federal taxes only (as computed by this function) - DEFAULT", "value": "federal_only", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Federal and state taxes (requires additional state-specific inputs and logic)", "value": "federal_and_state", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Only federal taxes are included, as explicitly defined by the function's scope.", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "wages", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The total cash wages paid to a household employee in a year.", "unit": "currency", "aliases": []}, {"name": "social_security_rate", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The decimal rate for Social Security tax (e.g., 0.062 for 6.2%).", "unit": "decimal_percent", "aliases": []}, {"name": "medicare_rate", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The decimal rate for Medicare tax (e.g., 0.0145 for 1.45%).", "unit": "decimal_percent", "aliases": []}, {"name": "unemployment_wage_base", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The maximum amount of wages subject to federal unemployment tax (FUTA) in a year.", "unit": "currency", "aliases": []}, {"name": "futa_rate", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The decimal rate for federal unemployment tax (FUTA) (e.g., 0.06 for 6%).", "unit": "decimal_percent", "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "total_tax", "type": "number", "unit": null, "description": "The total nanny tax amount, including both the employer and employee shares of Social Security and Medicare taxes and the federal unemployment tax. Typically rounded to the nearest dollar for reporting."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    wages = inputs['wages']\n    social_security_rate = inputs['social_security_rate']\n    medicare_rate = inputs['medicare_rate']\n    unemployment_wage_base = inputs['unemployment_wage_base']\n    futa_rate = inputs['futa_rate']\n    ss_medicare_tax_rate = social_security_rate + medicare_rate\n    ss_medicare_tax = wages * ss_medicare_tax_rate * 2\n    futa_tax = min(wages, unemployment_wage_base) * futa_rate\n    total_tax = ss_medicare_tax + futa_tax\n    return total_tax", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "input_wages_type", "name": "Wages must be a number", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['wages'], (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'wages' input must be a numerical value representing the total cash wages paid."}, {"rule_id": "input_wages_non_negative", "name": "Wages must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['wages'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Total wages paid cannot be a negative value."}, {"rule_id": "input_rates_range", "name": "Tax rates must be between 0 and 1 (inclusive)", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (0 <= inputs['social_security_rate'] <= 1 and 0 <= inputs['medicare_rate'] <= 1 and 0 <= inputs['futa_rate'] <= 1)", "applies_to": [], "description": "Tax rates (Social Security, Medicare, FUTA) must be expressed as decimals between 0 and 1 (inclusive)."}, {"rule_id": "input_unemployment_wage_base_positive", "name": "Unemployment wage base must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['unemployment_wage_base'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The federal unemployment wage base must be a positive value."}, {"rule_id": "wages_below_ss_medicare_threshold", "name": "Wages below federal SS/Medicare threshold", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['wages'] < 2300", "applies_to": [], "description": "For cash wages below $2,300 (2021 federal threshold mentioned in article), Social Security and Medicare taxes may not apply. This calculation assumes applicability regardless of this threshold for simplicity, but flags for awareness."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    wages = inputs['wages']\n    social_security_rate = inputs['social_security_rate']\n    medicare_rate = inputs['medicare_rate']\n    unemployment_wage_base = inputs['unemployment_wage_base']\n    futa_rate = inputs['futa_rate']\n    ss_medicare_tax_rate = social_security_rate + medicare_rate\n    ss_medicare_tax = wages * ss_medicare_tax_rate * 2\n    futa_tax = min(wages, unemployment_wage_base) * futa_rate\n    total_tax = ss_medicare_tax + futa_tax\n    return total_tax"}, "article_title": "Nanny Tax", "article_doc_id": 5727, "article_content_excerpt": "# Tax Nanny: Meaning, Overview, Requirements\n\n## What Is a Nanny Tax? \n\nA nanny tax is a federal tax paid by people who employ household employees and pay wages over a certain amount. In 2021, for cash wages of $2,300 or more per employee, social security and Medicare taxes must be withheld at a rate of 15.3%, with the employer and employee each paying half (7.65%). If paying cash wages of $1,000 or more per quarter per employee, the employer pays a 6% unemployment tax on annual cash wages up to $7,000.\n\n## Understanding the Nanny Tax \n\nHousehold employees are hired persons whose work is controlled by the employer; such employees include babysitters, nannies, butlers, and cooks.﻿﻿ The nanny tax exists because the IRS considers an ongoing household helper as the taxpayer's , rather than an independent contractor. As such, the taxpayer becomes an employer and must pay Social Security, Medicare, and federal and state unemployment taxes on the wages paid to that employee. There may be state-level nanny taxes, as well. The federal and state nanny tax requirements are detailed in IRS Publication 926.﻿﻿ \n\nFor example, if a taxpayer pays an adult babysitter $50 every weekend, they must pay nanny taxes (52 weekends/year x $50 = $2600). The nanny tax does not apply if the babysitter is the taxpayer's parent or spouse or if the babysitter is under the age of 18 and is not primarily engaged in the household employment profession. Nanny taxes also aren’t applicable if a taxpayer hires household help through an employment agency, in which case the agency is the employer and is responsible for paying the associated tax.﻿﻿﻿﻿﻿ \n\nThe nanny tax enables a household employee to receive covered employment benefits and protections, such as Social Security, Medicare, and unemployment benefits.﻿﻿ It also provides a household employee with a verifiable income and a legal employment history, which can be important when applying for a credit card, loan, or mortgage. The nanny tax also allows an employer to take advantage of significant tax savings from a and the .﻿﻿﻿﻿﻿ \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * A nanny tax is a federally required tax paid by people who employ household employees and pay wages over a certain threshold.\n * The IRS deems an ongoing household helper as a household employee, rather than an independent contractor.\n * The nanny tax qualifies household employees to receive certain benefits and protections, such as Social Security, Medicare, and unemployment benefits.\n * Employers and employees pay an equal share of social security and Medicare taxes (7.65% total) on cash wages.\n\n## Nanny Tax Requirements \n\nTaxpayers with household employees must file to become an employer and receive an employer identification number for dealing with the IRS and other agencies. Failure to pay employment taxes can result in penalties, and families who misclassify a household employee as an independent contractor can be charged with tax evasion.\n\nIn 2021, the withholding amount for Social Security taxes was set at 6.2%, and the rate for Medicare taxes is 1.45%, which amounts to a total of 7.65% withheld from all cash wages. The employee and employer are responsible for paying 7.65% each, but some employers choose to pay the total 15.3% tax.\n\nThose looking for help around the house may be disappointed to discover the complexities of maintaining tax compliance. Fortunately, there are plenty of that can help automate some or all of the payroll process."}
