unit": "percent", "description": "The calculated earnings growth rate as a percentage."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    current_eps = inputs['current_eps']\n    previous_eps = inputs['previous_eps']\n    growth_rate = (current_eps / previous_eps - 1) * 100\n    return round(growth_rate, 2)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "current_eps_type_check", "name": "Current EPS Type Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['current_eps'], (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "The current_eps input must be a numeric value (integer or float)."}, {"rule_id": "previous_eps_type_check", "name": "Previous EPS Type Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['previous_eps'], (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "The previous_eps input must be a numeric value (integer or float)."}, {"rule_id": "current_eps_positive", "name": "Current EPS must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "inputs['current_eps'] > 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Current earnings per share (current_eps) must be a positive value."}, {"rule_id": "previous_eps_positive", "name": "Previous EPS must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "inputs['previous_eps'] > 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Previous earnings per share (previous_eps) must be a positive value."}, {"rule_id": "previous_eps_not_zero", "name": "Previous EPS cannot be zero", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "inputs['previous_eps'] != 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Previous earnings per share (previous_eps) cannot be zero, as it leads to division by zero."}, {"rule_id": "extreme_growth_rate", "name": "Plausibility Check: Extreme Growth Rate", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "abs(compute(inputs)) > 500.0 or compute(inputs) < -99.99", "applies_to": [], "description": "The calculated growth rate is exceptionally high (over 500%) or indicates a near-total loss (>99.99% decline), which might indicate unusual financial events or data errors."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    current_eps = inputs['current_eps']\n    previous_eps = inputs['previous_eps']\n    growth_rate = (current_eps / previous_eps - 1) * 100\n    return round(growth_rate, 2)"}, "article_title": "Price/Earnings-to-Growth (PEG) Ratio", "article_doc_id": 2650, "article_content_excerpt": "# Price/Earnings-to-Growth (PEG) Ratio: What It Is and the Formula\n\n## What Is the Price/Earnings-to-Growth (PEG) Ratio? \n\nThe price/earnings to growth ratio (PEG ratio) is a stock's (P/E) ratio divided by the growth rate of its earnings for a specified time period. \n\nThe PEG ratio is used to determine a stock's value while also factoring in the company's expected earnings growth, and it is thought to provide a more complete picture than the more standard P/E ratio. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * The PEG ratio enhances the P/E ratio by adding expected earnings growth into the calculation.\n * The PEG ratio is considered to be an indicator of a stock's true value, and similar to the P/E ratio, a lower PEG may indicate that a stock is undervalued.\n * The PEG for a given company may differ significantly from one reported source to another.\n * Differences will depend on which growth estimate is used in the calculation, such as one-year or three-year projected growth.\n * A PEG lower than 1.0 is best, suggesting that a company is relatively undervalued.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/PEG-Ratio_Final_4191448-6df4ad0f7a2842bb86915ba99293a23e.jpg)\n\nInvestopedia / Paige McLaughlin\n\n## How to Calculate the PEG Ratio \n\n\\begin{aligned} &\\text{PEG Ratio}=\\frac{\\text{Price/EPS}}{\\text{EPS Growth}}\\\\\\ &\\textbf{where:}\\\\\\ &\\text{EPS = The earnings per share}\\\\\\ \\end{aligned}\n\nTo calculate the PEG ratio, an investor or analyst needs to either look up or calculate the P/E ratio of the company in question. The P/E ratio is calculated as the price per share of the company divided by the earnings per share (EPS), or price per share / EPS. \n\nOnce the P/E is calculated, find the expected growth rate for the stock in question, using analyst estimates available on financial websites that follow the stock. Plug the figures into the equation, and solve for the PEG ratio number. \n\n### Accuracy \n\nAs with any ratio, the accuracy of the PEG ratio depends on the inputs used. When considering a company's PEG ratio from a published source, it's important to find out which growth rate was used in the calculation. In an article from Morgan Stanley Wealth Management, for example, the PEG ratio is calculated using a P/E ratio based on current-year data and a five-year expected growth rate.\n\nUsing historical growth rates, for example, may provide an inaccurate PEG ratio if future growth rates are expected to deviate from a company's historical growth. The ratio can be calculated using one-year, three-year, or five-year expected growth rates, for example. \n\n### Fast Fact: \n\nTo distinguish between calculation methods using future growth and historical growth, the terms \"forward PEG\" and \"trailing PEG\" are sometimes used.\n\n## What Does the PEG Ratio Tell You? \n\nWhile a low , factoring in the company's growth rate to may tell a different story. The lower the PEG ratio, the more the stock may be undervalued given its future earnings expectations. Adding a company's expected growth into the ratio helps to adjust the result for companies that may have a high growth rate and a high P/E ratio. \n\nThe degree to which a PEG ratio result indicates an over or underpriced stock varies by industry and by company type. As a broad rule of thumb, some investors feel that a PEG ratio below one is desirable. \n\nAccording to well-known investor Peter Lynch, a company's P/E and expected growth should be equal, which denotes a fairly valued company and supports a PEG ratio of 1.0. When a company's PEG exceeds 1.0, it's considered overvalued while a stock with a PEG of less than 1.0 is considered undervalued.\n\n## Example of How to Use the PEG Ratio \n\nThe PEG ratio provides useful information to compare companies and see which stock might be the better choice for an investor's needs, as follows. \n\nAssume the following data for two hypothetical companies, Company A and Company B: \n\n### Company A: \n\n * Price per share = $46\n * EPS this year = $2.09\n * EPS last year = $1.74\n\n### Company B \n\n * Pric\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_369", "name": "Income Annuity", "short_description": "Calculates the fixed monthly payment amount for an immediate annuity given a lump sum premium, annual interest rate, and payout duration in years.", "domain": "personal_finance", "topic": "saveretire", "topic_extension": false, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-369", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-215", "question_id": "test-2077", "difficulty": 4.499809670330265, "level": "hard", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "db5046ac0a9d181b8572f97014dd7af7d6c34e1fee8dd284a348493706b48735", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["annuity", "immediate annuity", "monthly payment", "retirement income", "lump sum", "payout", "guaranteed income", "fixed income"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "annuity_payment_timing", "ambiguity_type": "time_basis", "trigger_signal": "annuity payment timing (beginning vs. end of period) not specified", "clarification_question": "Are the annuity payments made at the end or beginning of each period?", "options": [{"label": "End of period (Ordinary Annuity) - DEFAULT", "value": "end_of_period", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Beginning of period (Annuity Due)", "value": "beginning_of_period", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "result * (1 + annual_interest_rate / 12)", "max_expr_nodes": 13, "invariant": "result_new == result_old * (1 + annual_interest_rate / 12)", "affected_inputs": ["annual_interest_rate"]}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Payments are made at the end of each period (ordinary annuity).", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "premium", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The initial lump sum payment for the annuity.", "unit": "dollar", "aliases": []}, {"name": "annual_interest_rate", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The annual interest rate in decimal form (e.g., 0.05 for 5%).", "unit": "decimal", "aliases": []}, {"name": "years", "type": "integer", "required": true, "description": "The number of years the annuity is expected to pay out.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "monthly_payment", "type": "number", "unit": "dollar", "description": "The calculated monthly payment from the annuity."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    premium = inputs['premium']\n    annual_interest_rate = inputs['annual_interest_rate']\n    years = inputs['years']\n    monthly_interest_rate = annual_interest_rate / 12\n    total_periods = years * 12\n    if monthly_interest_rate == 0:\n        monthly_payment = premium / total_periods\n    else:\n        monthly_payment = premium * monthly_interest_rate / (1 - (1 + monthly_interest_rate) ** (-total_periods))\n    return monthly_payment", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "premium_positive", "name": "Premium must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['premium'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["premium"], "description": "The initial lump sum payment (premium) for the annuity must be a positive value."}, {"rule_id": "annual_interest_rate_non_negative", "name": "Annual interest rate must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['annual_interest_rate'] < 0", "applies_to": ["annual_interest_rate"], "description": "The annual interest rate cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "years_positive", "name": "Number of years must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['years'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["years"], "description": "The number of years for annuity payments must be a positive integer."}, {"rule_id": "annual_interest_rate_plausible_decimal", "name": "Annual interest rate should be a plausible decimal", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['annual_interest_rate'] >= 1.0", "applies_to": ["annual_interest_rate"], "description": "The annual interest rate is typically expressed as a decimal (e.g., 0.04 for 4%). A value of 1.0 or greater suggests it might have been entered as a percentage (e.g., '4' instead of '0.04')."}, {"rule_id": "monthly_payment_positive", "name": "Calculated monthly payment must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "compute(inputs) <= 0", "applies_to": ["monthly_payment"], "description": "The calculated monthly payment from the annuity must be a positive value."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    premium = inputs['premium']\n    annual_interest_rate = inputs['annual_interest_rate']\n    years = inputs['years']\n    monthly_interest_rate = annual_interest_rate / 12\n    total_periods = years * 12\n    if monthly_interest_rate == 0:\n        monthly_payment = premium / total_periods\n    else:\n        monthly_payment = premium * monthly_interest_rate / (1 - (1 + monthly_interest_rate) ** (-total_periods))\n    return monthly_payment"}, "article_title": "Income Annuity", "article_doc_id": 587, "article_content_excerpt": "# Income Annuity: What it is, How it Works\n\n## What Is an Income Annuity? \n\nAn income annuity is an contract that is designed to start paying income as soon as the policy is initiated. Once funded, an income annuity is annuitized immediately, although the underlying income units may be in either fixed or variable investments. As such, income payments may fluctuate over time. \n\nAn income annuity, also known as an immediate annuity, a single-premium immediate annuity (SPIA), or an , is typically purchased with a lump sum payment (premium), often by individuals who are retired or are close to retirement. These annuities may be contrasted with deferred annuities that begin paying out years later. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * An income annuity is a financial product designed to swap a lump sum amount for guaranteed periodic cash flow (e.g., monthly or annual payments).\n * An income, or immediate annuity, generally starts payment one month after the premium is paid and may continue for as long as the buyer is alive.\n * Such annuities are especially suitable for retirees who are concerned about outliving their retirement savings.\n\n## Understanding Income Annuities \n\nInvestors seeking income annuities should have a clear picture of how much income will be received and for how long. Most annuities pay out until the death of the , and some pay out until the death of a spouse. \n\nAlthough the insurance product may be annuitized immediately, variable investments can allow for some principal protection by participating in equity markets. Even if all income units are in fixed investments, there may be a provision allowing for a higher return if a specific index performs exceptionally well. \n\nThe return an annuity buyer gets from their income annuity is based on how long they live—greater longevity equals more payments and a better return. Payments may begin as soon as a month after a contract is signed and a premium payment is made. Income annuity payments may be monthly, quarterly, semi-annually, or annually. Many income annuities offer a death benefit.\n\nIf a option is chosen, the designated beneficiary of an annuitant who dies before receiving enough payments to equal their initial premium will receive the balance. As such, an annuitant's age, life expectancy, and health are relevant to deciding whether such an annuity is suitable. \n\nIncome annuities may be purchased for a little as a few thousand dollars. More significant income annuities may require special vetting, however. Some income annuities may be to build income for use later in life. \n\n## Who Benefits Most From Income Annuities \n\nThe strategy behind an income annuity is to create a steady stream of income for a retiree that cannot be outlived. In effect, an immediate annuity may act as longevity insurance. A good rule of thumb is that payments backed by an income annuity should replace a retiree's wage payments until they pass away. \n\nAnother strategy utilizing an income annuity is using them to provide income to pay a retiree's expenses—such as rent or mortgage, food, and energy—assisted living facility fees, and insurance premiums, or provide the cash for any other recurring payment needs. \n\nOne disadvantage of income annuities is that once they are initiated, they cannot be rolled back or stopped. Also, payments for such annuity may be fixed and not indexed to inflation, and will thus stay the same. As such, the purchasing power of each payment will decrease over time as inflation takes its toll."}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_711", "name": "Bell Curve", "short_description": "Calculates the percentage of data points falling within one standard deviation of the mean in a normally distributed dataset, using the empirical (68-95-99.7) rule.", "domain": "risk_management", "topic": "statistical_distribution_analysis", "topic_extension": true, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-711", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-79", "question_id": "test-2198", "difficulty": 5.480638923341991, "level": "hard", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "e8cda331b181c13dd207a8a053162e62717f7a1d876c3bad250fc8d207a6b002", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["bell curve", "normal distribution", "empirical rule", "68-95-99.7 rule", "standard deviation", "data distribution", "risk analysis", "hedge fund returns"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "input_percentage_scale", "ambiguity_type": "unit_scale", "trigger_signal": "input financial values (mean, std_dev, data_points) not explicitly specified as decimal or percentage", "clarification_question": "Are the input values for 'mean', 'std_dev', and 'data_points' provided as raw percentages (e.g., 5 for 5%) or as decimals (e.g., 0.05 for 5%)?", "options": [{"label": "Raw percentages (e.g., 5 for 5%) - DEFAULT", "value": "raw_percentage", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Decimal values (e.g., 0.05 for 5%)", "value": "decimal_value", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Input values (mean, std_dev, data_points) are assumed to be raw percentages (e.g., 5 for 5%).", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}], "inputs": [{"name": "mean", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The mean (average) of the data distribution.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "std_dev", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The standard deviation of the data distribution.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "data_points", "type": "array[number]", "required": true, "description": "A list of numeric data points.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "percentage_within_1_std_dev", "type": "number", "unit": "%", "description": "The percentage of data points within one standard deviation of the mean, rounded to two decimal places."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    mean = inputs['mean']\n    std_dev = inputs['std_dev']\n    data_points = inputs['data_points']\n    lower_bound = mean - std_dev\n    upper_bound = mean + std_dev\n    count_within_1_std_dev = sum((lower_bound <= x <= upper_bound for x in data_points))\n    percentage_within_1_std_dev = count_within_1_std_dev / len(data_points) * 100\n    return round(percentage_within_1_std_dev, 2)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "input_mean_type", "name": "Mean must be numeric", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['mean'], (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'mean' input must be a numeric value (integer or float)."}, {"rule_id": "input_std_dev_type", "name": "Standard deviation must be numeric", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['std_dev'], (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'std_dev' input must be a numeric value (integer or float)."}, {"rule_id": "input_data_points_type", "name": "Data points must be a list", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['data_points'], list)", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'data_points' input must be a list."}, {"rule_id": "input_data_points_empty", "name": "Data points list cannot be empty", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "len(inputs['data_points']) == 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'data_points' list cannot be empty as it's required for calculation."}, {"rule_id": "input_data_points_elements_type", "name": "All data points must be numeric", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "all(isinstance(x, (int, float)) for x in inputs['data_points'])", "applies_to": [], "description": "All elements in the 'data_points' list must be numeric values."}, {"rule_id": "std_dev_non_negative", "name": "Standard deviation cannot be negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['std_dev'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Standard deviation must be a non-negative value."}, {"rule_id": "output_percentage_range", "name": "Output percentage must be between 0 and 100", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (0 <= compute(inputs) <= 100)", "applies_to": [], "description": "The calculated percentage of data points within one standard deviation should be between 0 and 100."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    mean = inputs['mean']\n    std_dev = inputs['std_dev']\n    data_points = inputs['data_points']\n    lower_bound = mean - std_dev\n    upper_bound = mean + std_dev\n    count_within_1_std_dev = sum((lower_bound <= x <= upper_bound for x in data_points))\n    percentage_within_1_std_dev = count_within_1_std_dev / len(data_points) * 100\n    return round(percentage_within_1_std_dev, 2)"}, "article_title": "Bell Curve", "article_doc_id": 1317, "article_content_excerpt": "# Bell Curve Definition: Normal Distribution Meaning Example in Finance\n\nDefinition\n\nA bell curve is a normal distribution. It gets its name from its bell shape, with the top of the curve or the highest point being the most probable event in a series of data.\n\n## What Is a Bell Curve? \n\nA bell curve is a common type of distribution for a variable, also known as the normal distribution. The term \"bell curve\" originates from the fact that the graph used to depict a consists of a symmetrical bell-shaped curve. \n\nThe highest point on the curve, or the top of the bell, represents the most probable event in a series of data (its , , and __ in this case), while all other possible occurrences are symmetrically distributed around the mean, creating a downward-sloping curve on each side of the peak. The width of the bell curve is described by its . \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * A bell curve is a graph depicting the normal distribution, which has a shape reminiscent of a bell.\n * The top of the curve shows the mean, mode, and median of the data collected. \n * Its standard deviation depicts the bell curve's relative width around the mean.\n * Bell curves (normal distributions) are used commonly in statistics, including in analyzing economic and financial data.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/bellcurve-2adf98d9dfce459b970031037e39a60f.jpg)\n\nInvestopedia / Nez Riaz\n\n## Understanding a Bell Curve \n\nThe term \"bell curve\" is used to describe a graphical depiction of a whose underlying standard deviations from the mean create the curved bell shape. \n\nA standard deviation is a measurement used to quantify the variability of data dispersion, in a set of given values around the mean. The mean, in turn, refers to the average of all data points in the data set or sequence and will be found at the highest point on the bell curve. \n\nFinancial analysts and investors often use a normal probability distribution when analyzing the returns of a security or of overall market sensitivity. In finance, standard deviations that depict the returns of a security are known as . \n\nFor example, stocks that display a bell curve usually are blue-chip stocks and ones that have lower volatility and more predictable behavioral patterns. Investors use the normal probability distribution of a stock's past returns to make assumptions regarding expected future returns. \n\nIn addition to teachers who use a bell curve when comparing test scores, the bell curve is often also used in the world of statistics where it can be widely applied. Bell curves are also sometimes employed in performance management, placing employees who perform their jobs in an average fashion in the normal distribution of the graph. \n\nThe high performers and the lowest performers are represented on either side with the dropping slope. It can be useful to larger companies when doing performance reviews or when making managerial decisions. \n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/The-Normal-Distribution1-51cb75a3e0a34eb6bbff7e966557757e.jpg)\n\nInvestopedia / Julie Bang\n\n## Example of a Bell Curve \n\nA bell curve's width is defined by its , which is calculated as the level of variation of data in a sample around the mean. Using the empirical rule, for example, if 100 test scores are collected and used in a normal probability distribution, 68% of those test scores should fall within one standard deviation above or below the mean. \n\nMoving two standard deviations away from the mean should include 95% of the 100 test scores collected. Moving three standard deviations away from the mean should represent 99.7% of the scores (see the figure above). \n\nTest scores that are extreme outliers, such as a score of 100 or 0, would be considered long-tail data points that consequently lie squarely outside of the three-standard deviation range. \n\n## Bell Curve vs. Non-Normal Distributions \n\nThe normal probability distribution assumption doesn’t always hold true in the financial world, however. 