ds carry-forward) — DEFAULT", "value": "annual_only", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Annual limit plus carry-forward", "value": "with_carry_forward", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "hard", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Only the annual contribution limit for each year is considered, without accounting for carry-forward of unused room.", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}, {"id": "contribution_type_inclusion", "ambiguity_type": "input_binding", "trigger_signal": "Types of contributions (e.g., qualifying transfers, exempt contributions) are not explicitly defined as included/excluded.", "clarification_question": "Do the provided contributions include qualifying transfers or exempt contributions that might not count towards the limit?", "options": [{"label": "All provided contributions count towards the limit — DEFAULT", "value": "all_inclusive", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Exclude specific non-taxable contributions", "value": "exclude_specific", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "All amounts listed in 'contributions_by_year' are considered taxable contributions counting towards the annual limit.", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}], "inputs": [{"name": "contributions_by_year", "type": "dict[string,number]", "required": true, "description": "A JSON object/dictionary where keys are years and values are total contributions made in that year in CAD.", "unit": "CAD", "aliases": []}, {"name": "annual_limits", "type": "dict[string,number]", "required": true, "description": "A JSON object/dictionary where keys are years and values are TFSA contribution limits for that year in CAD.", "unit": "CAD", "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "total_penalty", "type": "number", "unit": "CAD", "description": "The total penalty in Canadian dollars for the over-contributions, rounded to two decimal places."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    contributions_by_year = inputs['contributions_by_year']\n    annual_limits = inputs['annual_limits']\n    total_penalty = 0.0\n    for year, contribution in contributions_by_year.items():\n        if year in annual_limits:\n            limit = annual_limits[year]\n            if contribution > limit:\n                over_contribution = contribution - limit\n                monthly_penalty_rate = 0.01\n                months_in_year = 12\n                annual_penalty = over_contribution * monthly_penalty_rate * months_in_year\n                total_penalty += annual_penalty\n    return round(total_penalty, 2)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "f001", "name": "ContributionsByYearPresentAndType", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not isinstance(inputs.get('contributions_by_year'), dict)", "applies_to": [], "description": "`contributions_by_year` input must be a dictionary."}, {"rule_id": "f002", "name": "AnnualLimitsPresentAndType", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not isinstance(inputs.get('annual_limits'), dict)", "applies_to": [], "description": "`annual_limits` input must be a dictionary."}, {"rule_id": "e001", "name": "NonNegativeContributions", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "any(val < 0 for val in inputs['contributions_by_year'].values())", "applies_to": ["contributions_by_year"], "description": "All contribution amounts must be non-negative."}, {"rule_id": "e002", "name": "NonNegativeAnnualLimits", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "any(val < 0 for val in inputs['annual_limits'].values())", "applies_to": ["annual_limits"], "description": "All annual contribution limits must be non-negative."}, {"rule_id": "e003", "name": "YearsMatchLimits", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not all(year in inputs['annual_limits'] for year in inputs['contributions_by_year'])", "applies_to": ["contributions_by_year", "annual_limits"], "description": "Every year for which contributions are provided must have a corresponding annual limit."}, {"rule_id": "e004", "name": "NonNegativeTotalPenalty", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "compute(inputs) < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The calculated total penalty should not be negative."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    contributions_by_year = inputs['contributions_by_year']\n    annual_limits = inputs['annual_limits']\n    total_penalty = 0.0\n    for year, contribution in contributions_by_year.items():\n        if year in annual_limits:\n            limit = annual_limits[year]\n            if contribution > limit:\n                over_contribution = contribution - limit\n                monthly_penalty_rate = 0.01\n                months_in_year = 12\n                annual_penalty = over_contribution * monthly_penalty_rate * months_in_year\n                total_penalty += annual_penalty\n    return round(total_penalty, 2)"}, "article_title": "Tax-Free Savings Account (TFSA)", "article_doc_id": 3490, "article_content_excerpt": "# Tax-Free Savings Account (TFSA): Definition and Calculation\n\n## What Is a Tax-Free Savings Account? \n\nA tax-free savings account (TFSA) is a Canadian savings account in which contributions, interest earned, dividends, and capital gains grow tax free. Money withdrawn from it is also tax free. \n\nThe money deposited in TFSAs is an contribution, meaning it's made with money that's already been taxed. Therefore, it doesn't reduce taxable income. \n\nWhile it's called a , a TFSA can hold investments that include mutual funds, securities, and bonds, as well as cash. This account is available to individuals age 18 and older in Canada and can be used for any purpose. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Tax-free savings accounts are a type of tax-advantaged account available to Canadian residents age 18 or older.\n * TFSAs let you save money on taxes because the gains on investments in the account are not taxed and withdrawals are tax free.\n * TFSAs have annual contribution limits called contribution room.\n * Contributions less than the annual limit leave a carryover amount that can be added to the next year's allowed contribution.\n * Carryovers are retroactive back to the year that TFSAs were created, 2009.\n\n## How Tax-Free Savings Accounts Work \n\nTax-free savings accounts were introduced in Canada in 2009. They were intended to help Canadians save and invest their money throughout their lives. \n\nThe TFSA account lets people save money for any reason, not simply for retirement. For example, you can save for a car, for your education, to buy a home, to set aside extra living expenses, and/or for retirement. What's more, you don't need to have earned income to contribute. \n\nWhile there are exceptions, the money earned by investments in a TFSA is generally not taxed. Plus, savers maintain control over their TFSAs. They can make contributions, decide on investments, and withdraw funds whenever they wish without penalty. \n\nWhen first introduced, they offered Canadians age 18 years and older the opportunity to make an after-tax contribution of up to C$5,000 for the year. In 2013, that annual limit was increased to C$5,500 and remained there through 2018, except for 2015, when the limit was increased to C$10,000 temporarily. In 2019, the contribution limit was set at C$6,000 and it remains the same for 2022.\n\n### Contributions \n\nThe maximum amount that you're allowed to deposit to a TFSA is called your \"contribution room.\" Importantly, for every year since 2009 that you were age 18 or older and a resident of Canada, you accumulate contribution room even if you haven't had an account open.\n\nAny unused contribution room can be carried forward. For example, if you contributed the maximum amount each year until 2019, when you contributed only C$3,000 of C$6,000 available contribution room, you could contribute the C$3,000 carryover in 2020. That would have been in addition to the C$6,000 annual contribution limit for 2020 for a total contribution of C$9,000. \n\nLikewise, if you hadn't made any contributions since 2016, your 2020 contribution room for the TFSA account would have been C$23,000: C$5,500 for each of the years 2017 and 2018 (C$11,000) and C$6,000 each for the years 2019 and 2020 (C$12,000).\n\nThe TFSA annual room limit is indexed to inflation and rounded to the nearest $500. Also, according to the Canadian Revenue Agency \"qualifying transfers, exempt contributions and specified distributions are not considered in the calculation of contribution room.\"\n\n### Over-Contributions \n\nAny contribution made to a TFSA beyond the maximum allowable amount is considered an over-contribution. The (CRA) will charge a tax penalty of 1% per month on the excess contribution until it is withdrawn.\n\nAccount holders should be aware that money withdrawn during the year doesn't reduce the amount already contributed. If you contribute additional funds in the mistaken belief that your withdrawal reduced your already-contributed amount, you may over-contribute and, as a resu\n...[truncated]"}
