e - asset_price - net_premium_paid\n    return profit", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "asset_price_type", "name": "Asset Price Type Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['asset_price'], (int, float))", "applies_to": ["asset_price"], "description": "The 'asset_price' input must be a numerical value (integer or float)."}, {"rule_id": "option_strike_price_type", "name": "Option Strike Price Type Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['option_strike_price'], (int, float))", "applies_to": ["option_strike_price"], "description": "The 'option_strike_price' input must be a numerical value (integer or float)."}, {"rule_id": "net_premium_paid_type", "name": "Net Premium Paid Type Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['net_premium_paid'], (int, float))", "applies_to": ["net_premium_paid"], "description": "The 'net_premium_paid' input must be a numerical value (integer or float)."}, {"rule_id": "direction_type", "name": "Direction Type Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['direction'], str)", "applies_to": ["direction"], "description": "The 'direction' input must be a string."}, {"rule_id": "asset_price_positive", "name": "Asset Price Positive Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "inputs['asset_price'] > 0", "applies_to": ["asset_price"], "description": "The 'asset_price' must be a positive value."}, {"rule_id": "option_strike_price_positive", "name": "Option Strike Price Positive Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "inputs['option_strike_price'] > 0", "applies_to": ["option_strike_price"], "description": "The 'option_strike_price' must be a positive value."}, {"rule_id": "net_premium_paid_non_negative", "name": "Net Premium Paid Non-Negative Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "inputs['net_premium_paid'] >= 0", "applies_to": ["net_premium_paid"], "description": "The 'net_premium_paid' must be a non-negative value."}, {"rule_id": "direction_valid_value", "name": "Direction Value Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "inputs['direction'] in ['up', 'down']", "applies_to": ["direction"], "description": "The 'direction' must be either 'up' or 'down'."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    asset_price = inputs['asset_price']\n    option_strike_price = inputs['option_strike_price']\n    net_premium_paid = inputs['net_premium_paid']\n    direction = inputs['direction']\n    if direction == 'up':\n        profit = asset_price - option_strike_price - net_premium_paid\n    else:\n        profit = option_strike_price - asset_price - net_premium_paid\n    return profit"}, "article_title": "Long Straddle", "article_doc_id": 4275, "article_content_excerpt": "# Long Straddle: What It Is and How It's Used\n\n## What Is Long Straddle? \n\nThe long straddle is an options strategy where the trader purchases a on the same underlying asset with the same and . The goal is to profit from a strong move in either direction by the underlying asset following a market event. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * A long straddle is an options strategy where a trader buys a long call and a long put on the same underlying asset with the same expiration date and strike price.\n * The goal of a long straddle is to profit from a strong move in the market, usually triggered by a newsworthy event.\n * The risk of using a long straddle is that the market may fail to react strongly enough to garnish a profit.\n\n## Understanding Long Straddles \n\nThe long straddle strategy bets that the will move significantly in price, either higher or lower. The profit profile is the same no matter which way the asset moves. Typically, the trader thinks the underlying asset will move from a low state to a high volatility state based on the imminent release of new information. \n\nThe strike price is or as close to it as possible. Since calls benefit from an upward move and a put benefits from a downward move in the underlying security, both of these components cancel out small moves in either direction. The goal of a long straddle is to by the underlying asset. \n\nTraders may use a long straddle ahead of a significant event that impacts a company, such as: \n\n * An earnings report\n * action\n * The passage of a law\n * An election\n\nWhen the event occurs, or activity is commonly unleashed. This causes the underlying asset to move quickly. \n\n### Important: \n\nAn options contract can last weeks or years depending on the expiration date.\n\n## Long Straddle Risk \n\nThe risk inherent in the long straddle strategy is that the market may not react strongly enough to the anticipated event. Prices of put and call options also inflate in anticipation of the event. This means the cost of attempting the strategy is much higher than solely betting on one direction. \n\nSellers recognize that there is increased risk built into a scheduled, news-making event and raise prices. If the event does not generate a strong move in either direction for the underlying security, then the purchased likely will expire worthless and create a loss. \n\n## Calculating Profit \n\nAs the price of the underlying asset increases, the potential profit is unlimited. If the price of the underlying asset goes to zero, the profit would be the strike price less the paid for the options. \n\nThe maximum risk is the total cost to enter the position, which is the price of the call option plus the price of the put option. The maximum loss is the total for the paid plus any trade commissions. This loss occurs when the price of the underlying asset equals the strike price of the options at expiration. \n\nThe profit when the price of the underlying asset is increasing is: \n\n> Profit (up) = Underlying asset price- Call option strike price- Net premium paid \n\nThe profit when the price of the underlying asset is decreasing is: \n\n> Profit (down) = Put option strike price - Underlying asset price - Net premium paid \n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/understandingstraddles22-19b55dd41aee458287dda61e4929428a.png)\n\nImage by Julie Bang © Investopedia 2019\n\n## Example of a Long Straddle \n\nA stock is priced at $50 per share. A with a strike price of $50 is at $3, and the cost of a with the same strike is also $3. An investor enters into a straddle by purchasing one of each option. The option sellers assume a 70% probability that the move in the stock will be $6 or less in either direction. \n\nProfit occurs at expiration if the stock is priced above $56 or below $44, regardless of how it was initially priced. The maximum loss of $6 for one call and one put contract occurs only if the stock is priced precisely at $50 on the close of the expiration day. The trader will experience less loss if the price is between $44 an\n...[truncated]"}
