default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "1.0 / result", "max_expr_nodes": 6, "invariant": "result_new * result_old == 1.0", "affected_inputs": []}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Quote/Base (e.g., EUR per USD)", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "spot_rate", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The current spot exchange rate between two currencies (e.g., EUR per USD).", "unit": null, "aliases": ["s", "current_spot_rate"]}, {"name": "domestic_interest_rate", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The annual interest rate in the domestic currency (or the base currency, as a decimal).", "unit": "decimal", "aliases": ["id", "domestic_rate", "base_currency_rate"]}, {"name": "foreign_interest_rate", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The annual interest rate in the foreign currency (or the quoted currency, as a decimal).", "unit": "decimal", "aliases": ["if", "foreign_rate", "quoted_currency_rate"]}], "output": {"name": "forward_rate", "type": "number", "unit": null, "description": "The calculated forward foreign exchange rate (e.g., EUR per USD)."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    spot_rate = inputs['spot_rate']\n    domestic_interest_rate = inputs['domestic_interest_rate']\n    foreign_interest_rate = inputs['foreign_interest_rate']\n    forward_rate = spot_rate * (1 + domestic_interest_rate) / (1 + foreign_interest_rate)\n    return forward_rate", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "spot_rate_positive", "name": "Spot Rate must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['spot_rate'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["spot_rate"], "description": "The spot exchange rate must be a positive value."}, {"rule_id": "domestic_rate_non_negative", "name": "Domestic Interest Rate must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['domestic_interest_rate'] < 0", "applies_to": ["domestic_interest_rate"], "description": "The domestic interest rate cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "foreign_rate_non_negative", "name": "Foreign Interest Rate must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['foreign_interest_rate'] < 0", "applies_to": ["foreign_interest_rate"], "description": "The foreign interest rate cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "domestic_rate_plausibility", "name": "Domestic Interest Rate plausibility check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['domestic_interest_rate'] >= 10.0", "applies_to": ["domestic_interest_rate"], "description": "The domestic interest rate appears unusually high (1000% or more). Confirm if it's correct or if it should be a decimal (e.g., 0.05 instead of 5)."}, {"rule_id": "foreign_rate_plausibility", "name": "Foreign Interest Rate plausibility check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['foreign_interest_rate'] >= 10.0", "applies_to": ["foreign_interest_rate"], "description": "The foreign interest rate appears unusually high (1000% or more). Confirm if it's correct or if it should be a decimal (e.g., 0.05 instead of 5)."}, {"rule_id": "denominator_non_zero", "name": "Denominator (1 + foreign_interest_rate) must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "(1 + inputs['foreign_interest_rate']) <= 0", "applies_to": ["foreign_interest_rate"], "description": "The term (1 + foreign_interest_rate) must be positive to avoid mathematical errors and ensure a meaningful forward rate."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    spot_rate = inputs['spot_rate']\n    domestic_interest_rate = inputs['domestic_interest_rate']\n    foreign_interest_rate = inputs['foreign_interest_rate']\n    forward_rate = spot_rate * (1 + domestic_interest_rate) / (1 + foreign_interest_rate)\n    return forward_rate"}, "article_title": "Covered Interest Rate Parity", "article_doc_id": 294, "article_content_excerpt": "# Covered Interest Rate Parity: Definition, Calculation, and Example\n\nCovered interest rate parity refers to a theoretical condition in which the relationship between interest rates and the and currency values of two countries are in equilibrium. The covered interest rate parity situation means there is no opportunity for arbitrage using forward contracts, which often exists between countries with different interest rates. \n\nCovered interest rate parity (CIP) can be compared with (UIP). \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * The covered interest rate parity condition says that the relationship between interest rates and spot and forward currency values of two countries are in equilibrium.\n * It assumes no opportunity for arbitrage using forward contracts.\n * Covered and uncovered interest rate parity are the same when forward and expected spot rates are the same.\n\n## Formula for Covered Interest Rate Parity \n\nThe formula for CIRP is most commonly expressed as follows to determine the forward foreign exchange rate: \n\n\\begin{aligned}&F=S\\times\\frac{(1+i_d)}{(1+i_f)}\\\\\\&\\textbf{where:}\\\\\\&F=\\text{The forward foreign exchange rate}\\\\\\&S=\\text{The current spot exchange rate}\\\\\\&i_d=\\text{The interest rate in the domestic currency}\\\\\\&\\qquad\\text{ or the base currency}\\\\\\&i_f=\\text{The interest rate in the foreign currency}\\\\\\&\\qquad\\text{ or the quoted currency}\\end{aligned}\n\nUnder normal circumstances, a currency that offers lower interest rates tends to trade at a forward foreign in relation to another currency offering higher interest rates. \n\n### Fast Fact: \n\nThere are several different ways to calculate the forward foreign exchange rate, but the most common method is used here.\n\n## What Does Covered Interest Rate Parity Tell You? \n\nCovered interest rate parity is a no-arbitrage condition that could be used in the foreign exchange markets to determine the forward foreign exchange rate. The condition also states that investors could hedge foreign exchange risk or unforeseen fluctuations in exchange rates (with ). \n\nConsequently, the foreign exchange risk is said to be covered. Interest rate parity may occur for a period, but that does not mean it will remain because interest rates and currency rates change over time. \n\n## Example of How to Use Covered Interest Rate Parity \n\nAs an example, assume Country X's currency is trading with Country Z's currency, but the annual interest rate in Country X is 6% and the interest rate in country Z is 3%. All other things being equal, it would make sense to borrow in the currency of Z, convert it in the spot market to currency X, and invest the proceeds in Country X. \n\nHowever, to repay the loan in currency Z, one must enter into a forward contract to exchange the currency back from X to Z. Covered interest rate parity exists when the forward rate of converting X to Z eradicates all the profit from the transaction. \n\nSince the currencies are trading at par, one unit of Country X's currency is equivalent to one unit of Country Z's currency. Assume that the domestic currency is Country Z's currency. Therefore, the forward price is equivalent to 0.97, or 1 x [ ( 1 + 3% ) / ( 1 + 6% ) ]. \n\nLooking at the currency markets, we can apply the forward foreign exchange rate formula to figure out what the rate might be. Say the spot rate for the pair was trading at 1.35. Also, assume that the interest rate (using the prime lending rate) for the U.S. was 1.1% and 3.25% for the U.K. The domestic currency is the British pound, making the forward rate 1.38, calculated by: 1.35 x [ ( 1 + 0.0325)/( 1 + 0.011 ) ]. \n\n## The Difference Between Covered Interest Rate Parity and Uncovered Interest Rate Parity \n\nCovered interest parity involves using forward contracts to cover the exchange rate. Meanwhile, uncovered interest rate parity involves forecasting rates and not covering exposure to foreign exchange risk _—_ that is, there are no forward rate contracts, and it uses only the expected spot rate. There is no difference betwe\n...[truncated]"}
