ity - tax_credit\n    else:\n        remaining_liability = max(0, tax_liability - tax_credit)\n    return remaining_liability", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "dl001", "name": "Tax Liability Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['tax_liability'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Tax liability cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "dl002", "name": "Tax Credit Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['tax_credit'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Tax credit amount cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "dl003", "name": "Tax Liability Type Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not isinstance(inputs.get('tax_liability'), (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "Tax liability must be a numeric value."}, {"rule_id": "dl004", "name": "Tax Credit Type Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not isinstance(inputs.get('tax_credit'), (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "Tax credit must be a numeric value."}, {"rule_id": "dl005", "name": "Refundable Flag Type Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not isinstance(inputs.get('refundable'), bool)", "applies_to": [], "description": "Refundable flag must be a boolean value (True/False)."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": false, "error": "Refundable flag must be a boolean value.", "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    tax_liability = inputs.get('tax_liability')\n    tax_credit = inputs.get('tax_credit')\n    refundable = inputs.get('refundable', False)\n    if not isinstance(tax_liability, (int, float)) or not isinstance(tax_credit, (int, float)):\n        raise ValueError('Tax liability and tax credit must be numeric values.')\n    if not isinstance(refundable, bool):\n        raise ValueError('Refundable flag must be a boolean value.')\n    if tax_liability < 0 or tax_credit < 0:\n        raise ValueError('Tax liability and tax credit must be non-negative values.')\n    if refundable:\n        remaining_liability = tax_liability - tax_credit\n    else:\n        remaining_liability = max(0, tax_liability - tax_credit)\n    return remaining_liability"}, "article_title": "Tax Benefit", "article_doc_id": 3474, "article_content_excerpt": "# Tax Benefit: Definition, Types, and IRS Rules\n\n## What Is a Tax Benefit? \n\nThe term “tax benefit” refers to any tax law that helps you reduce your . Benefits range from deductions and tax credits to exclusions and exemptions. They cover various areas, including programs for families, education, employees, and natural disasters. \n\nSome tax benefits are related to the ability to pay taxes. For example, the and the recognize the cost of raising a family. Other tax benefits, including mortgage interest and charitable donation deductions, are incentives designed to further social policy goals. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Tax benefits create savings for individual and business taxpayers.\n * Common tax benefits include deductions, credits, exclusions, and shelters.\n * You can take standard or itemized deductions plus any available above-the-line deductions.\n * To qualify for tax benefits, you must meet specific requirements, such as income limits, filing status, and dependent status.\n * Be sure to stay abreast of any tax benefits you may be eligible for so you don’t miss out on tax savings.\n\n## Understanding Tax Benefits \n\nTax benefits help individuals and corporations reduce their overall tax bills. These benefits are a significant part of the tax regulations and legislation set by local, state, and federal governments. \n\nTax benefits such as , credits, exemptions, and exclusions reduce the amount you owe annually to federal and state governments.\n\nOn the other hand, help lower taxes through particular investments. These are legal vehicles that provide favorable tax treatment. Common examples of tax shelters include and employer-sponsored plans.\n\n### Eligibility \n\nYou must be eligible for tax benefits to claim them. For instance, to qualify for status, you must be unmarried, have a qualifying dependent who lives with you, and pay more than half of the household expenses for the year.\n\nTax benefits for can only be claimed by those who spend money on tuition and other related costs during the tax year.\n\nIt makes financial sense to learn about any tax benefits you might be eligible for. Without the proper knowledge, you could end up paying more in taxes than you owe. It can be helpful to consult a tax professional, such as an , to maximize your tax savings. \n\n## Types of Tax Benefits \n\nAs noted above, tax benefits come in all shapes and sizes. We’ve highlighted some of the more common ones below. \n\n### Tax Deductions \n\nA tax deduction reduces your taxable income. When you file your annual income tax return, you have the option to take the standard deduction or to itemize your deductions: \n\n * **Standard Deduction** : The is a fixed dollar amount that reduces taxable income. For 2024, the standard deduction is $14,600 for single filers and married taxpayers filing separately, $21,900 for heads of household, and $29,200 for married couples filing jointly and surviving spouses. For 2025, these figures increase to $15,000, $22,500, and $30,000, respectively.\n * **Itemized Deductions** : are qualified expenses allowed by the to decrease your taxable income by listing them on Schedule A of your tax return. The sum of your itemized deductions reduces your . There is no limit on itemized deductions for tax years 2024 or 2025 due to the .\n\nItemizing your deductions makes sense if the sum of your qualified expenses is greater than your standard deduction. For example, if a single taxpayer’s itemized expenses total $15,000, they would likely itemize rather than take the $13,850 standard deduction. However, if the same filer’s qualified expenses total just $8,000, they would save money by taking the standard deduction. \n\nEven if you don’t itemize, you can take certain along with the standard deduction. These include deductions for student loan interest, traditional contributions, contributions to Health Savings Accounts, and more. All these deductions lower taxes by reducing taxable income and possibly lowering your tax bracket. \n\nSay, for example,\n...[truncated]"}
