ions.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "above_the_line_deductions", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "Adjustments to gross income, such as IRA contributions.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "standard_deduction", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The standard deduction amount, applicable if itemized deductions are not used.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "itemized_deductions", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "Total calculated itemized deductions, applicable if greater than standard deduction.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "taxable_income", "type": "number", "unit": null, "description": "The taxable income after applying deductions."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    gross_income = inputs['gross_income']\n    above_the_line_deductions = inputs['above_the_line_deductions']\n    standard_deduction = inputs['standard_deduction']\n    itemized_deductions = inputs['itemized_deductions']\n    adjusted_gross_income = gross_income - above_the_line_deductions\n    effective_deductions = max(standard_deduction, itemized_deductions)\n    taxable_income = adjusted_gross_income - effective_deductions\n    return round(taxable_income)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "gi_001", "name": "Gross income must be provided", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "'gross_income' not in inputs or inputs['gross_income'] is None", "applies_to": [], "description": "Gross income is a required input for calculating taxable income."}, {"rule_id": "ded_001", "name": "All deduction types must be provided", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "'above_the_line_deductions' not in inputs or inputs['above_the_line_deductions'] is None or 'standard_deduction' not in inputs or inputs['standard_deduction'] is None or 'itemized_deductions' not in inputs or inputs['itemized_deductions'] is None", "applies_to": [], "description": "Above-the-line, standard, and itemized deductions are all required inputs."}, {"rule_id": "gi_002", "name": "Gross income must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['gross_income'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Gross income cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "ded_002", "name": "Deductions must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['above_the_line_deductions'] < 0 or inputs['standard_deduction'] < 0 or inputs['itemized_deductions'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "All deduction amounts (above-the-line, standard, itemized) must be non-negative."}, {"rule_id": "agi_001", "name": "Adjusted Gross Income should not be negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "(inputs['gross_income'] - inputs['above_the_line_deductions']) < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Adjusted Gross Income (AGI) is typically not negative. A negative AGI might indicate unusual input values or very high above-the-line deductions exceeding gross income."}, {"rule_id": "tax_001", "name": "Taxable income significantly negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "compute(inputs) < -1000", "applies_to": [], "description": "The calculated taxable income is significantly negative, which is unusual as taxable income for tax liability purposes is typically floored at zero. This may indicate excessive deductions relative to income."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    gross_income = inputs['gross_income']\n    above_the_line_deductions = inputs['above_the_line_deductions']\n    standard_deduction = inputs['standard_deduction']\n    itemized_deductions = inputs['itemized_deductions']\n    adjusted_gross_income = gross_income - above_the_line_deductions\n    effective_deductions = max(standard_deduction, itemized_deductions)\n    taxable_income = adjusted_gross_income - effective_deductions\n    return round(taxable_income)"}, "article_title": "Taxable Income", "article_doc_id": 3515, "article_content_excerpt": "# Taxable Income: What It Is, What Counts, and How to Calculate\n\n## What Is Taxable Income? \n\nTaxable income is the portion of your gross income used to calculate how much tax you owe in a given tax year. It can be described broadly as minus allowable itemized or standard deductions. Taxable income includes wages, salaries, bonuses, and tips, as well as investment income and various types of unearned income. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Taxable income is the portion of your gross income that the IRS deems subject to taxes.\n * It consists of both earned and unearned income.\n * Taxable income comes from compensation, businesses, partnerships, and royalties, among other sources.\n * Taxable income is generally less than adjusted gross income because of deductions that reduce it.\n * You can begin calculating your taxable income by determining your filing status and gathering the documents related to all your income sources.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/TaxableIncome_Final_4188122-0fb0b743d67242d4a20931ef525b1bb1.jpg)\n\nInvestopedia / Paige McLaughlin\n\n## Understanding Taxable Income \n\n consists of both earned and . Unearned income that is considered taxable includes canceled debts, government benefits (such as unemployment benefits and disability payments), strike benefits, and lottery payments. Taxable income also includes earnings generated from assets that have been sold during the year and from and interest income.\n\nWhen it comes to deductions, the IRS offers individual tax filers the option to claim the or a list of . Itemized deductions include interest paid on mortgages, medical expenses exceeding a specific threshold (7.5% of your AGI), and a range of other expenses.\n\nWhen businesses file their taxes, they do not report their directly as taxable income. Rather, they subtract their from their revenue to calculate their . Then, they subtract deductions to calculate their taxable income.\n\n### Important: \n\n and are based on taxable income, not gross income.\n\n \n\n## Sources of Taxable Income \n\nTaxable income is any income you earn during the tax year. The most common is employee compensation. But there are other sources of income that are taxable. \n\n### Employee Compensation \n\nAs noted above, this is the most common type of taxable income. This comes in the form of salaries and wages, tips, bonuses, and fees that are paid to you by your employer. The income is reported to you on your W-2, which the company sends out to you electronically or by snail mail. This form also includes any applicable deductions to your taxable income, such as income tax, , , and 401(k) contributions, among others.\n\nAccording to the IRS, people who provide childcare either in their own homes or elsewhere must include the amount they receive as taxable income. This rule also applies to any money you receive if you babysit.\n\nIf you receive certain as a director, partner, or through your employer, you must include their value, too. The IRS has a full list of what's taxable and exemptions on its website.\n\n### Income From Business and Investments \n\nYou are responsible for declaring any income you earn from certain types of business and investment activity. This includes any rental income you receive from properties that you own. It doesn't matter if the rental activity you receive is the result of a business, or if you earn it for a profit. Keep in mind that you may be able to declare the expenses related to the rental, which can offset the income you receive.\n\n### Income from Partnerships \n\nThe IRS doesn't tax entities but any income, deductions, and losses that stem from these entities are passed through to individual partners. As such, the partnership doesn't pay taxes. If you're a partner, you must declare any pass-throughs on your annual tax return. This must occur even if the pass-through doesn't apply to you directly.\n\n### Income from S Corporations \n\nJust like a partnership, this type of corporation doesn't pay any income tax on earnings. This is pas\n...[truncated]"}
