, {"name": "strike_price", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The agreed-upon price at which the underlying asset can be sold.", "unit": "currency", "aliases": ["exercise_price"]}, {"name": "premium_paid", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The premium paid per share for purchasing the put option.", "unit": "currency", "aliases": ["option_cost_per_share", "put_premium"]}, {"name": "shares_per_option", "type": "integer", "required": true, "description": "The number of shares covered by each put option contract.", "unit": "shares", "aliases": ["contract_multiplier"]}, {"name": "final_stock_price", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The stock price at the option's expiration or exercise date.", "unit": "currency", "aliases": ["spot_price_at_expiration", "market_price"]}], "output": {"name": "profit_or_loss", "type": "number", "unit": "currency", "description": "The total profit or loss from the long put option position."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    strike_price = inputs['strike_price']\n    premium_paid = inputs['premium_paid']\n    shares_per_option = inputs['shares_per_option']\n    final_stock_price = inputs['final_stock_price']\n    intrinsic_value_per_share = max(strike_price - final_stock_price, 0)\n    total_intrinsic_value = intrinsic_value_per_share * shares_per_option\n    profit_or_loss = total_intrinsic_value - premium_paid * shares_per_option\n    return profit_or_loss", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "f001", "name": "Missing Strike Price", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "'strike_price' not in inputs or inputs['strike_price'] is None", "applies_to": [], "description": "Strike price is a required input for calculating put option profit."}, {"rule_id": "f002", "name": "Missing Premium Paid", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "'premium_paid' not in inputs or inputs['premium_paid'] is None", "applies_to": [], "description": "Premium paid is a required input for calculating put option profit."}, {"rule_id": "f003", "name": "Missing Shares Per Option", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "'shares_per_option' not in inputs or inputs['shares_per_option'] is None", "applies_to": [], "description": "Number of shares per option contract is a required input for calculating total profit."}, {"rule_id": "f004", "name": "Missing Final Stock Price", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "'final_stock_price' not in inputs or inputs['final_stock_price'] is None", "applies_to": [], "description": "Final stock price is a required input for determining intrinsic value."}, {"rule_id": "e001", "name": "Non-Positive Strike Price", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['strike_price'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["strike_price"], "description": "Strike price must be a positive monetary value."}, {"rule_id": "e002", "name": "Non-Positive Premium Paid", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['premium_paid'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["premium_paid"], "description": "Premium paid must be a positive monetary value."}, {"rule_id": "e003", "name": "Non-Positive Shares Per Option", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['shares_per_option'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["shares_per_option"], "description": "Shares per option must be a positive integer."}, {"rule_id": "e004", "name": "Negative Final Stock Price", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['final_stock_price'] < 0", "applies_to": ["final_stock_price"], "description": "Final stock price cannot be negative."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    strike_price = inputs['strike_price']\n    premium_paid = inputs['premium_paid']\n    shares_per_option = inputs['shares_per_option']\n    final_stock_price = inputs['final_stock_price']\n    intrinsic_value_per_share = max(strike_price - final_stock_price, 0)\n    total_intrinsic_value = intrinsic_value_per_share * shares_per_option\n    profit_or_loss = total_intrinsic_value - premium_paid * shares_per_option\n    return profit_or_loss"}, "article_title": "Long Put: Definition, Example, Vs. Shorting Stock", "article_doc_id": 4273, "article_content_excerpt": "# Long Put: Definition, Example, Vs. Shorting Stock\n\n## What Is a Long Put? \n\nA long put refers to buying a , typically in anticipation of a decline in the . The term \"long\" here has nothing to do with the length of time before expiration but rather refers to the trader's action of having _bought_ the option with the hope of selling it at a higher price at a later point in time. \n\nA trader could buy a put for speculative reasons, betting that the underlying asset will fall which increases the value of the long put option. A long put could also be used to a long position in the underlying asset. If the underlying asset falls, the put option increases in value helping to offset the loss in the underlying. \n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/LongPut2-3d94ffb6f6964e578b68c7ec25bd1acd.png)\n\nImage by Julie Bang © Investopedia 2019\n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * A long put is a position when somebody buys a put option. It is in and of itself, however, a bearish position in the market.\n * Investors go long put options if they think a security's price will fall.\n * Investors may go long put options to speculate on price drops or to hedge a portfolio against downside losses.\n * Downside risk is thus limited using a long put options strategy.\n\n## Understanding a Long Put \n\nA long put has a , which is the price at which the put buyer has the right to sell the underlying asset. Assume the underlying asset is a stock and the option’s strike price is $50. That means the put option entitles that trader to sell the stock at $50, even if the stock drops to $20, for example. On the other hand, if the stock rises and remains above $50, the option is worthless because it is not useful to sell at $50 when the stock is trading at $60 and can be sold there (without the use of an option). \n\nIf a trader wishes to utilize their right to sell the underlying at the strike price, they will the option. Exercising is not required. Instead, the trader can simply exit the option at any time prior to by selling it. \n\nA long put option may be exercised before the expiration if it’s an whereas European options can only be exercised at the expiration date. If the option is exercised early or expires , the option holder would be the underlying asset. \n\n## Long Put Strategy vs. Shorting Stock \n\nA long put may be a favorable strategy for investors, rather than shorting shares. A short stock position theoretically has unlimited risk since the stock price has no capped upside. A short stock position also has limited profit potential, since a stock cannot fall below $0 per share. A long put option is similar to a short stock position because the profit potentials are limited. A put option will only increase in value up to the underlying stock reaching zero. The benefit of the put option is that risk is limited to the paid for the option. \n\nThe drawback to the put option is that the price of the underlying must fall before the expiration date of the option, otherwise, the amount paid for the option is lost. \n\nTo profit from a short stock trade a trader sells a stock at a certain price hoping to be able to buy it back at a lower price. Put options are similar in that if the underlying stock falls then the put option will increase in value and can be sold for a profit. If the option is exercised, it will put the trader short in the underlying stock, and the trader will then need to buy the underlying stock to realize the profit from the trade. \n\n## Long Put Options to Hedge \n\nA long put option could also be used to hedge against unfavorable moves in a long stock position. This hedging strategy is known as a protective put or married put. \n\nFor example, assume an investor is long 100 shares of Bank of America Corporation () at $25 per share. The investor is long-term on the stock, but fears that the stock may fall over the next month. Therefore, the investor purchases one put option with a strike price of $20 for $0.10 (multiplied by 100 shares since each put option represents 100\n...[truncated]"}
