 "is_default": true}, {"label": "Includes non-qualified home equity loans", "value": "includes_non_qualified_hel", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Mortgage debt includes only qualified acquisition or improvement debt.", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}], "inputs": [{"name": "interest_paid", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The total interest paid on the mortgage during the tax year.", "unit": "USD", "aliases": []}, {"name": "mortgage_debt", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The total mortgage debt secured by the home(s).", "unit": "USD", "aliases": []}, {"name": "acquisition_date", "type": "string", "required": true, "description": "The date when the home was acquired (in 'YYYY-MM-DD' format).", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "filing_status", "type": "string", "required": true, "description": "The taxpayer's filing status ('single', 'married filing jointly', 'married filing separately').", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "deductible_interest", "type": "number", "unit": "USD", "description": "The deductible amount of mortgage interest, subject to debt limits and proportional reduction if debt exceeds limits."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    interest_paid = inputs['interest_paid']\n    mortgage_debt = inputs['mortgage_debt']\n    acquisition_date = inputs['acquisition_date']\n    filing_status = inputs['filing_status']\n    limit_old = 1000000 if filing_status != 'married filing separately' else 500000\n    limit_new = 750000 if filing_status != 'married filing separately' else 375000\n    cutoff_date = '2017-12-15'\n    if acquisition_date <= cutoff_date:\n        applicable_limit = limit_old\n    else:\n        applicable_limit = limit_new\n    if mortgage_debt <= applicable_limit:\n        deduction = interest_paid\n    else:\n        deduction = interest_paid * (applicable_limit / mortgage_debt)\n    return deduction", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "interest_paid_non_negative", "name": "Interest Paid Must Be Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['interest_paid'] < 0", "applies_to": ["interest_paid"], "description": "The amount of interest paid cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "mortgage_debt_non_negative", "name": "Mortgage Debt Must Be Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['mortgage_debt'] < 0", "applies_to": ["mortgage_debt"], "description": "The total mortgage debt cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "filing_status_enum_check", "name": "Filing Status Must Be Valid", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['filing_status'] not in ['single', 'married filing jointly', 'married filing separately']", "applies_to": ["filing_status"], "description": "The filing status must be one of 'single', 'married filing jointly', or 'married filing separately'."}, {"rule_id": "acquisition_date_format", "name": "Acquisition Date Format Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (isinstance(inputs['acquisition_date'], str) and len(inputs['acquisition_date']) == 10 and inputs['acquisition_date'][4] == '-' and inputs['acquisition_date'][7] == '-' and inputs['acquisition_date'][:4].isdigit() and inputs['acquisition_date'][5:7].isdigit() and inputs['acquisition_date'][8:].isdigit())", "applies_to": ["acquisition_date"], "description": "The acquisition date must be in 'YYYY-MM-DD' string format."}, {"rule_id": "mortgage_debt_zero_division", "name": "Mortgage Debt Cannot Be Zero If Interest Paid", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['mortgage_debt'] == 0 and inputs['interest_paid'] > 0", "applies_to": ["mortgage_debt", "interest_paid"], "description": "If interest was paid, mortgage debt cannot be zero, as this would lead to division by zero in proportional reduction calculation."}, {"rule_id": "deductible_interest_non_negative_result", "name": "Deductible Interest Must Be Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "compute(inputs) < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The calculated deductible interest amount should not be negative."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    interest_paid = inputs['interest_paid']\n    mortgage_debt = inputs['mortgage_debt']\n    acquisition_date = inputs['acquisition_date']\n    filing_status = inputs['filing_status']\n    limit_old = 1000000 if filing_status != 'married filing separately' else 500000\n    limit_new = 750000 if filing_status != 'married filing separately' else 375000\n    cutoff_date = '2017-12-15'\n    if acquisition_date <= cutoff_date:\n        applicable_limit = limit_old\n    else:\n        applicable_limit = limit_new\n    if mortgage_debt <= applicable_limit:\n        deduction = interest_paid\n    else:\n        deduction = interest_paid * (applicable_limit / mortgage_debt)\n    return deduction"}, "article_title": "Tax-Deductible Interest", "article_doc_id": 3478, "article_content_excerpt": "# Tax-Deductible Interest: Definition and Types That Qualify\n\n## What Is Tax-Deductible Interest? \n\nTax-deductible interest is a borrowing expense that a taxpayer can claim on a federal or state tax return to reduce their taxable income. \n\nSeveral types of interest are tax-deductible, including mortgage interest on a primary or second home, student loan interest, and interest on some business loans, including business . \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Interest is the amount of money you pay a lender to borrow money.\n * The allows taxpayers to deduct several interest expenses, including home mortgage interest and student loan interest.\n * You can itemize investment interest and qualified mortgage interest (including points if you’re the buyer) on Schedule A of Form 1040 or 1040-SR.\n * The student loan interest deduction is an adjustment to income on your , so you don’t need to itemize to take it.\n * Some interest is not tax deductible, such as that you pay on personal car loans and credit card balances. \n\n## Understanding Tax-Deductible Interest \n\n is the amount of money you pay a lender for the privilege of borrowing money or delaying the repayment of a debt. \n\nAll loans incur interest, which the lender may roll into your monthly payment. For example, you pay back a portion of the principal (i.e., the amount you borrowed) plus interest every month with most . On the other hand, loans—like credit cards—accrue interest only on unpaid balances. \n\nTo make certain loans more affordable, the IRS allows you to deduct several types of interest expenses, including: \n\n * Investment interest\n * Qualified mortgage interest (including points if you’re the buyer)\n * Student loan interest\n * Nonfarm business interest\n * Farm business interest\n * Interest related to income-producing activities\n\nNot all types of interest are . Specifically, the IRS does not allow you to deduct personal interest such as: \n\n * The interest you pay on a loan to buy a car for personal use\n * Credit card and installment loan interest on personal expenses\n * Mortgage points (for sellers), service charges, credit investigation fees, and interest associated with tax-exempt income\n\n## Student Loan Interest Tax Deduction \n\nWhile you can’t deduct your student loans, you can on the interest you pay by claiming the . \n\nGenerally, you can deduct the smaller of $2,500 or the interest you actually paid during the year. However, the deduction may be gradually reduced (phased out) and eventually eliminated depending on your filing status and : \n \n<table> \n<tr> \n<th>\n\nStudent Loan Interest Deduction Income Limits for 2023\n</th> </tr> \n<tr> \n<th>\n\nFiling Status\n</th> \n<th>\n\nPhaseout Begins\n</th> \n<th>\n\nDeduction Eliminated\n</th> </tr> \n<tr> \n<td>\n\nSingle\n</td> \n<td>\n\n$75,000\n</td> \n<td>\n\n$90,000\n</td> </tr> \n<tr> \n<td>\n\nHead of household\n</td> \n<td>\n\n$75,000\n</td> \n<td>\n\n$90,000\n</td> </tr> \n<tr> \n<td>\n\nQualifying widow(er)\n</td> \n<td>\n\n$75,000\n</td> \n<td>\n\n$90,000\n</td> </tr> \n<tr> \n<td>\n\nMarried filing jointly\n</td> \n<td>\n\n$155,000\n</td> \n<td>\n\n$185,000\n</td> </tr> \n<tr> \n<td>\n\nMarried filing separately\n</td> \n<td>\n\nN/A\n</td> \n<td>\n\nN/A\n</td> </tr> </table> \n \n<table> \n<tr> \n<th>\n\nStudent Loan Interest Deduction Income Limits for 2024\n</th> </tr> \n<tr> \n<th>\n\nFiling Status\n</th> \n<th>\n\nPhaseout Begins\n</th> \n<th>\n\nDeduction Eliminated\n</th> </tr> \n<tr> \n<td>\n\nSingle\n</td> \n<td>\n\n$80,000\n</td> \n<td>\n\n$95,000\n</td> </tr> \n<tr> \n<td>\n\nHead of household\n</td> \n<td>\n\n$80,000\n</td> \n<td>\n\n$95,000\n</td> </tr> \n<tr> \n<td>\n\nQualifying widow(er)\n</td> \n<td>\n\n$80,000\n</td> \n<td>\n\n$95,000\n</td> </tr> \n<tr> \n<td>\n\nMarried filing jointly\n</td> \n<td>\n\n$165,000\n</td> \n<td>\n\n$195,000\n</td> </tr> \n<tr> \n<td>\n\nMarried filing separately\n</td> \n<td>\n\nN/A\n</td> \n<td>\n\nN/A\n</td> </tr> </table>\n\nTo claim the deduction, you must meet all of the following conditions: \n\n * You paid interest on a qualified student loan during the tax year\n * You’re legally obligated to pay interest on a qualified student loan\n *\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_2494", "name": "Working Ratio", "short_description": "Measures a company's ability to recover operating costs from annual revenue by comparing adjusted total annual expenses to annual gross income.", "domain": "financial_ratios", "topic": "effratio", "topic_extension": false, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-2494", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-894", "question_id": "test-1008", "difficulty": 2.4849066497880004, "level": "medium", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "0dbfe3be22f42e7afd1604f28adb9dfa4e59c7d51bde8f4dfc415814fdc667bd", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["working ratio", "operating costs", "annual revenue", "financial sustainability", "expense coverage"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "output_scale", "ambiguity_type": "unit_scale", "trigger_signal": "question asks for percentage, FIC outputs decimal (or vice versa)", "clarification_question": "Should the answer be expressed as a decimal (0.08) or percent (8.0)?", "options": [{"label": "Decimal (e.g., 0.08) - DEFAULT", "value": "decimal", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Percentage (e.g., 8.0%)", "value": "percent", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "result * 100.0", "max_expr_nodes": 6, "invariant": "result_new == result_old * 100.0", "affected_inputs": []}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Decimal", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "total_annual_expenses", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The total annual expenses of the company.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "depreciation", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The annual depreciation expense.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "debt_expenses", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The annual debt-related expenses.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "annual_gross_income", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The annual gross income of the company.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "working_ratio", "type": "number", "unit": null, "description": "The working ratio, where a value below 1 indicates that the company can cover its operating costs from its annual revenue, and a value above 1 indicates it cannot."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    total_annual_expenses = inputs['total_annual_expenses']\n    depreciation = inputs['depreciation']\n    debt_expenses = inputs['debt_expenses']\n    annual_gross_income = inputs['annual_gross_income']\n    if annual_gross_income == 0:\n        raise ValueError('Annual gross income must be greater than zero.')\n    operating_expenses = total_annual_expenses - (depreciation + debt_expenses)\n    working_ratio = operating_expenses / annual_gross_income\n    return working_ratio", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "agi_gt_zero", "name": "Annual Gross Income must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['annual_gross_income'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Annual gross income must be strictly greater than zero to avoid division by zero."}, {"rule_id": "non_negative_inputs", "name": "All financial inputs must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "any(inputs[k] < 0 for k in ['total_annual_expenses', 'depreciation', 'debt_expenses', 'annual_gross_income'])", "applies_to": [], "description": "Financial inputs like total annual expenses, depreciation, debt expenses, and annual gross income should typically not be negative."}, {"rule_id": "operating_expenses_non_negative", "name": "Calculated operating expenses must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "(inputs['total_annual_expenses'] - (inputs['depreciation'] + inputs['debt_expenses'])) < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Operating expenses (total annual expenses minus depreciation and debt expenses) should not be negative."}, {"rule_id": "deductions_lt_total", "name": "Depreciation and Debt Expenses should not exceed Total Annual Expenses", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "(inputs['depreciation'] + inputs['debt_expenses']) > inputs['total_annual_expenses']", "applies_to": [], "description": "The sum of depreciation and debt expenses cannot exceed the total annual expenses from which they are subtracted."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    total_annual_expenses = inputs['total_annual_expenses']\n    depreciation = inputs['depreciation']\n    debt_expenses = inputs['debt_expenses']\n    annual_gross_income = inputs['annual_gross_income']\n    if annual_gross_income == 0:\n        raise ValueError('Annual gross income must be greater than zero.')\n    operating_expenses = total_annual_expenses - (depreciation + debt_expenses)\n    working_ratio = operating_expenses / annual_gross_income\n    return working_ratio"}, "article_title": "Working Ratio", "article_doc_id": 4979, "article_content_excerpt": "# Working Ratio: Meaning, Example, Limitations\n\n## What Is the Working Ratio? \n\nThe working ratio measures a company's ability to recover from annual revenue. It is calculated by taking total annual expenses, excluding and debt-related expenses, and dividing it by the annual gross income. \n\nThis is the formula for calculating working ratio: \n\n﻿\\begin{aligned} &\\text{Working Ratio} = \\frac{ \\text{TAE} - ( \\text{Depreciation} + \\text{Debt Expenses} ) }{ \\text{Annual Gross Income} } \\\\\\ &\\textbf{where:} \\\\\\ &\\text{TAE} = \\text{total annual expenses} \\\\\\ \\end{aligned}﻿ \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * The working ratio measures a company's ability to recover operating costs from annual revenue.\n * It is calculated by taking total annual expenses, excluding depreciation and debt-related expenses, and dividing it by the annual gross income.\n * The lower the ratio, the more profitable a company is.\n * A working ratio below one implies the company is able to recover operating expenses, whereas a ratio above one reflects its inability to do so. \n\n## Understanding the Working Ratio \n\nThe working ratio is tasked with gauging a company's financial sustainability. All businesses will incur costs to operate and generate sales. These costs range from rent, equipment, and charges, to marketing, staff wages, and . Those who are unable to consistently clear these expenses and pay their bills aren’t running a viable business and probably won’t be in business for long. \n\nThe threshold for this ratio is one. Any number below that indicates that the company is able to recover operating costs—lower figures are synonymous with eating up a small chunk of . Conversely, a ratio above one implies that the company isn’t breaking even and generating enough money to cover its costs. \n\n### Important: \n\nA ratio of one means a company’s annual gross income is equal to its total expenditure, so anything below that implies the company is able to recover operating costs, whereas anything above reflects its inability to do so.\n\n## Example of the Working Ratio \n\nXYZ Inc. has been making widgets since the 1900s and is seen in the industry as a somewhat antiquated brand. XYZ hasn't spent very much money overhauling its machinery over the years and is still using old technology to manufacture its end product. \n\nManagement argues that not upgrading to the latest model has saved it money that can be better spent elsewhere. The problem is the equipment it uses is power-intensive and expensive to run and relative to newer versions. This means that continuing to use the old technology actually works out to be more expensive in the long-run. \n\nTo make matters worse, XYZ is also losing every year to its more modern competitors. Sales are falling and costs are rising, leading to a progressively higher working ratio. Recently it rose above one, the tipping point, and analysts fear it will continue to climb—putting the business in danger of reneging on payments—unless drastic changes are soon made to slash costs and catch up with the competition. \n\n## Limitations of the Working Ratio \n\nThe working ratio is not perfect and cannot be fully relied on to determine a company’s and ability to cover expenses with the money it brings in. \n\nOne issue is that it does not take into consideration. This oversight can lead to misleading results, particularly as most companies borrow money to fund growth and are required to pay back these loans, together with , punctually. \n\nThe ratio also does not account for projected changes in operating expenses. In some industries, operating costs have a tendency to fluctuate from year to year and in certain periods can be uncharacteristically low or high for a good reason. \n\nIf the company has cash tucked away to bankroll extra costs, and is poised to generate extra off them in the future, its current high working ratio shouldn’t necessarily be a cause for alarm. \n\n## Special Considerations \n\nWhen applying ratios, investors are advised to not always take the num\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_701", "name": "Basket of Goods", "short_description": "Calculate a weighted index for a basket of goods using CPI data. This function computes the weighted index based on the prices and associated weights of various items in a basket of goods. It is useful for constructing a consumer price index (CPI) to measure inflation.", "domain": "financial_markets", "topic": "inflation_measurement", "topic_extension": true, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-701", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-748", "question_id": "test-1242", "difficulty": 2.6390573296152584, "level": "medium", "execution_smoke_ok": false, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "execution_smoke_error": "Weights must sum to 1.", "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "ba601ad37acd458cc381096b6ddc1a9d5b0baaef918ed77ae11722001f0eda9c", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["CPI", "Consumer Price Index", "weighted index", "basket of goods", "inflation measurement", "price index", "economic indicator"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "output_scale", "ambiguity_type": "unit_scale", "trigger_signal": "the computed index can be interpreted as a raw value or a scaled percentage", "clarification_question": "Should the weighted index be expressed as a raw numerical value (e.g., 1.73) or scaled to represent a percentage (e.g., 173%)?", "options": [{"label": "Raw numerical value (e.g., 1.73) - DEFAULT", "value": "raw_value", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Percentage representation (e.g., 173.0 for 173%)", "value": "percentage_representation", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "result * 100.0", "max_expr_nodes": 6, "invariant": "result_new == result_old * 100.0", "affected_inputs": []}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Raw numerical value (e.g., 1.73)", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "prices", "type": "array[number]", "required": true, "description": "A list of current prices of items in the basket.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "weights", "type": "array[number]", "required": true, "description": "A list of weights representing the significance of each item's price in the overall basket. These should sum to 1.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "weighted_index", "type": "number", "unit": null, "description": "The calculated weighted index."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    prices = inputs['prices']\n    weights = inputs['weights']\n    if len(prices) != len(weights):\n        raise ValueError('The length of prices and weights must be the same.')\n    if not 0.999 <= sum(weights) <= 1.001:\n        raise ValueError('Weights must sum to 1.')\n    weighted_index = sum((price * weight for price, weight in zip(prices, weights)))\n    return weighted_index", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "prices_input_type", "name": "Prices Input Type Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['prices'], list)", "applies_to": ["prices"], "description": "The 'prices' input must be a list of numerical values."}, {"rule_id": "weights_input_type", "name": "Weights Input Type Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['weights'], list)", "applies_to": ["weights"], "description": "The 'weights' input must be a list of numerical values."}, {"rule_id": "prices_elements_numeric", "name": "Prices Elements Numeric Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "all(isinstance(p, (int, float)) for p in inputs['prices'])", "applies_to": ["prices"], "description": "All elements in the 'prices' list must be numbers (integers or floats)."}, {"rule_id": "weights_elements_numeric", "name": "Weights Elements Numeric Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "all(isinstance(w, (int, float)) for w in inputs['weights'])", "applies_to": ["weights"], "description": "All elements in the 'weights' list must be numbers (integers or floats)."}, {"rule_id": "length_mismatch", "name": "Prices and Weights Length Mismatch", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "len(inputs['prices']) != len(inputs['weights'])", "applies_to": ["prices", "weights"], "description": "The number of prices must exactly match the number of weights."}, {"rule_id": "weights_sum_to_one", "name": "Weights Sum to One Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "abs(sum(inputs['weights']) - 1.0) > 0.001", "applies_to": ["weights"], "description": "The sum of all weights must be equal to 1, allowing for minor floating-point errors."}, {"rule_id": "non_negative_prices", "name": "Non-Negative Prices Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "any(p < 0 for p in inputs['prices'])", "applies_to": ["prices"], "description": "All prices must be non-negative values."}, {"rule_id": "non_negative_weights", "name": "Non-Negative Weights Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "any(w < 0 for w in inputs['weights'])", "applies_to": ["weights"], "description": "All weights must be non-negative values."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": false, "error": "Weights must sum to 1.", "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    prices = inputs['prices']\n    weights = inputs['weights']\n    if len(prices) != len(weights):\n        raise ValueError('The length of prices and weights must be the same.')\n    if not 0.999 <= sum(weights) <= 1.001:\n        raise ValueError('Weights must sum to 1.')\n    weighted_index = sum((price * weight for price, weight in zip(prices, weights)))\n    return weighted_index"}, "article_title": "Basket of Goods", "article_doc_id": 1298, "article_content_excerpt": "# Basket of Goods: Definition, CPI Calculation, and Example\n\nDefinition\n\nA basket of goods is a set of consumer goods and services whose prices are used to measure inflation.\n\n## What Is a Basket of Goods? \n\nA basket of goods is a collection of items that represent consumer spending patterns. It is made up of a fixed set of goods and services whose prices are used to measure inflation. These prices are monitored each month by federal governments so they can set and make changes to their . For example, the , a common measure of inflation, measures the price change over time for a basket of goods and services. The Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS) tracks this basket of goods in the United States. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * A basket of goods represents consumer spending and is used to track changes in the prices of consumer goods and services over time.\n * The Bureau of Labor Statistics tracks 80,000 prices monthly to assess inflation for more than 200 categories of products and services\n * The U.S. CPI basket includes a 36.1% weighting for shelter costs derived mostly from rents and owners' equivalents.\n * CPI calculations factor in consumer substitution of items rising in price with alternatives and filter out price increases reflecting product improvements. \n\n## Understanding a Basket of Goods \n\nThe concept of a basket of goods is central to understanding economic and measuring . By tracking a representative sample of items, economists can gauge changes in the cost of living and consumer prices over time. \n\nThe composition of this basket can vary by country and can be influenced by numerous factors, including technological advancements, government policies, and shifts in consumer behavior. This can also change over time; we'll look at this more closely in the article. \n\nThe basket of goods can also highlight the interconnection between various . For example, changes in transportation costs can affect food prices due to shipping expenses, while fluctuations in utility costs can influence housing affordability. \n\nPolicymakers rely on these types of relationships to better understand the implications of the policies they consider implementing. \n\n## Basket of Goods Deconstructed \n\nWith 80,000 prices sampled monthly, the is using a huge basket, because its goal is to get an accurate measure of price changes for consumer goods and services across the U.S. economy.\n\nBroad categories like food, energy, apparel, and services include subcategories tracking inflation for everything from apples and premium unleaded gasoline to men's underwear and funerals.\n\nThe prices of goods and services are gathered mostly from visits by BLS data collectors to some 23,000 retail and service outlets in 75 urban areas.\n\nItems for sampling at each outlet are selected randomly based on odds proportional to how much spending they attract relative to category alternatives in terms of brand, variety, and size or weight. Items remain in the sample for four years.\n\n## How the Government Calculates CPI \n\nAfter the prices are collected, BLS product specialists make adjustments to ensure the price changes are measuring inflation rather than the cost of product improvements in items such as autos, consumer appliances, and electronics. \n\nThe prices are used to calculate basic indexes for 211 goods, services, and housing item categories for 32 geographic areas subdividing all U.S. urban areas. The BLS then calculates more than 7,776 item-area combination basic indexes in a way that factors in the substitution of cheaper items for more expensive ones within and between spending categories.\n\nAll those item-area indexes are then weighed based on recent two-year results from a detailed survey to calculate two versions of the consumer price index:\n\n * The reflects the spending patterns of roughly 93% of the U.S. population living in areas where the BLS collects price data. It is the basis of the headlines about the rate of change in consumer prices, or the inflation rate.\n *\n...[truncated]"}
