 the period.", "unit": null, "aliases": ["lost_customers", "churned_subscribers", "cancelled_subscriptions"]}, {"name": "total_subscribers", "type": "integer", "required": true, "description": "The total number of subscribers at the beginning of the period.", "unit": null, "aliases": ["starting_subscribers", "initial_subscribers", "base_subscribers"]}], "output": {"name": "net_growth_rate", "type": "number", "unit": "percent", "description": "The net growth rate expressed as a percentage."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    new_subscribers = inputs['new_subscribers']\n    subscribers_lost = inputs['subscribers_lost']\n    total_subscribers = inputs['total_subscribers']\n    growth_rate = new_subscribers / total_subscribers * 100\n    churn_rate = subscribers_lost / total_subscribers * 100\n    net_growth_rate = growth_rate - churn_rate\n    return net_growth_rate", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "input_type_new_subscribers", "name": "New subscribers must be an integer", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['new_subscribers'], int)", "applies_to": ["new_subscribers"], "description": "The 'new_subscribers' input must be an integer to ensure correct calculation."}, {"rule_id": "input_type_subscribers_lost", "name": "Subscribers lost must be an integer", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['subscribers_lost'], int)", "applies_to": ["subscribers_lost"], "description": "The 'subscribers_lost' input must be an integer to ensure correct calculation."}, {"rule_id": "input_type_total_subscribers", "name": "Total subscribers must be an integer", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['total_subscribers'], int)", "applies_to": ["total_subscribers"], "description": "The 'total_subscribers' input must be an integer to ensure correct calculation."}, {"rule_id": "total_subscribers_positive", "name": "Total subscribers must be greater than zero", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "inputs['total_subscribers'] > 0", "applies_to": ["total_subscribers"], "description": "The 'total_subscribers' must be greater than zero as it forms the denominator in rate calculations, preventing division by zero and ensuring a meaningful base."}, {"rule_id": "new_subscribers_non_negative", "name": "New subscribers cannot be negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "inputs['new_subscribers'] >= 0", "applies_to": ["new_subscribers"], "description": "The number of 'new_subscribers' cannot logically be negative."}, {"rule_id": "subscribers_lost_non_negative", "name": "Subscribers lost cannot be negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "inputs['subscribers_lost'] >= 0", "applies_to": ["subscribers_lost"], "description": "The number of 'subscribers_lost' cannot logically be negative."}, {"rule_id": "subscribers_lost_less_than_total", "name": "Subscribers lost cannot exceed total subscribers", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "inputs['subscribers_lost'] <= inputs['total_subscribers']", "applies_to": ["subscribers_lost", "total_subscribers"], "description": "It is not possible to lose more subscribers than the total number of subscribers at the beginning of the period."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    new_subscribers = inputs['new_subscribers']\n    subscribers_lost = inputs['subscribers_lost']\n    total_subscribers = inputs['total_subscribers']\n    growth_rate = new_subscribers / total_subscribers * 100\n    churn_rate = subscribers_lost / total_subscribers * 100\n    net_growth_rate = growth_rate - churn_rate\n    return net_growth_rate"}, "article_title": "Churn Rate", "article_doc_id": 146, "article_content_excerpt": "# Churn Rate: What It Means, Examples, and Calculations\n\n## What Is the Churn Rate? \n\nThe churn rate, also known as the rate of attrition or customer churn, is the rate at which customers stop doing business with an entity. It is most commonly expressed as the percentage of service subscribers who discontinue their within a given time period. It is also the rate at which employees leave their jobs within a certain period. For a company to expand its clientele, its growth rate (measured by the number of new customers) must exceed its churn rate. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * The churn rate measures a company's loss of subscribers for a given period of time.\n * Churn rates can be applied to subscription-based businesses as well as to the number of employees that leave a firm.\n * Churn rate is the opposite of growth rate, which measures the acquisition of customers.****\n * For a company to experience growth it must ensure that its new subscriptions are higher than its lost subscriptions in a given period.\n * Each industry will have a different average churn rate that companies can compare themselves with to understand their competitiveness.\n\n## Understanding the Churn Rate \n\nChurn rate reflects the rate at which a company loses customers or subscribers. A high churn rate could adversely affect and impede growth. What is considered a good or bad churn rate can vary from industry to industry. \n\nThe churn rate not only includes when customers switch providers but also includes when customers terminate service without switching. This measurement is most valuable in subscriber-based businesses in which subscription fees comprise most of the . \n\n### Important: \n\n \nThe churn rate of a company is particularly meaningful in industries where customers can easily switch from one provider to another, such as telecommunications or streaming services.\n\n## Churn Rate vs. Growth Rate \n\nWhile the churn rate tracks lost customers, the growth rate tracks new customers. A company can compare its new subscribers to its loss of subscribers to determine both its churn rate and growth rate. The difference between the two shows whether there was overall growth or loss in a specific time period. \n\nIf the growth rate was higher than the churn rate, the company experienced growth. If the churn rate was higher than the growth rate, the company experienced a loss in its customer base. \n\nFor example, if in one quarter a company added 100 new subscribers but lost 110 subscribers, the net loss would be 10. There was no growth for the company this but rather a loss. This would be a negative growth rate and a positive churn rate. \n\n### Tip: \n\nIt's important to pay attention to customer acquisition costs. If most customers churn before you have made back the money spent on acquiring that customer, then your customer acquisition costs are too high for your business model.\n\nIt is critical for a company to ensure that its growth rate is higher than its churn rate otherwise it will experience declining revenues and profits with the eventual scenario of having to close the business. \n\n## Advantages and Disadvantages of the Churn Rate \n\n### Benefits of Using the Churn Rate \n\nThe advantage of calculating a company's churn rate is that it provides clarity on how well the business is retaining customers, which is a reflection on the quality of the service the business is providing, as well as its usefulness. \n\nIf a company sees that its churn rate is increasing from period to period, this can show that a fundamental component of how it is running its business is flawed. This can indicate a few potential problems: \n\n * Faulty product(s)\n * Poor customer service\n * Cost is higher than to customers\n\nThe churn rate will indicate to a company that it needs to understand why its clients are leaving and where to fix its business. The cost of acquiring new customers is much higher than it is to retain current customers, so working to lower the churn rate can save a business money in the\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_2659", "name": "Strangle", "short_description": "Calculate the profit or loss for a long strangle strategy given an asset's final price.", "domain": "financial_markets", "topic": "option_pricing", "topic_extension": false, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-2659", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-230", "question_id": "test-1941", "difficulty": 3.9120230054281464, "level": "medium", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "f5010a84f2a5e2bea3071b83e5e26e17650c38ec4a87d3a0bca4450edad8d4d4", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["options trading", "strangle strategy", "profit loss calculation", "price swings", "volatility"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "profit_loss_basis", "ambiguity_type": "calculation_basis", "trigger_signal": "profit or loss calculation often implies tax considerations", "clarification_question": "Should the profit/loss be considered before or after taxes?", "options": [{"label": "Before taxes (DEFAULT)", "value": "before_tax", "is_default": true}, {"label": "After taxes (requires tax_rate input)", "value": "after_tax", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "result * (1 - tax_rate)", "max_expr_nodes": 10, "invariant": "result_new == result_old * (1 - tax_rate)", "affected_inputs": ["tax_rate"]}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Before taxes", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "stock_price", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The final trading price of the underlying asset.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "call_strike", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The strike price of the call option.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "call_premium", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The premium paid for the call option.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "put_strike", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The strike price of the put option.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "put_premium", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The premium paid for the put option.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "profit_loss", "type": "number", "unit": "dollars", "description": "The profit or loss from the strangle strategy. A positive value indicates a profit, while a negative value indicates a loss."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    stock_price = inputs['stock_price']\n    call_strike = inputs['call_strike']\n    call_premium = inputs['call_premium']\n    put_strike = inputs['put_strike']\n    put_premium = inputs['put_premium']\n    total_premium = call_premium + put_premium\n    call_value = max(0, stock_price - call_strike)\n    put_value = max(0, put_strike - stock_price)\n    profit_loss = call_value + put_value - total_premium\n    return profit_loss", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "strangle_input_presence", "name": "All required inputs must be provided.", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not all(k in inputs for k in ['stock_price', 'call_strike', 'call_premium', 'put_strike', 'put_premium'])", "applies_to": ["stock_price", "call_strike", "call_premium", "put_strike", "put_premium"], "description": "Ensures all necessary inputs for calculating strangle profit/loss are present."}, {"rule_id": "strangle_input_numeric_type", "name": "All inputs must be numeric.", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not all(isinstance(inputs[k], (int, float)) for k in ['stock_price', 'call_strike', 'call_premium', 'put_strike', 'put_premium'])", "applies_to": ["stock_price", "call_strike", "call_premium", "put_strike", "put_premium"], "description": "Verifies that all input values are valid numbers (integers or floats)."}, {"rule_id": "strangle_premiums_non_negative", "name": "Option premiums must be non-negative.", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['call_premium'] < 0 or inputs['put_premium'] < 0", "applies_to": ["call_premium", "put_premium"], "description": "The premiums paid for call and put options should not be negative."}, {"rule_id": "strangle_strikes_non_negative", "name": "Strike prices must be non-negative.", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['call_strike'] < 0 or inputs['put_strike'] < 0", "applies_to": ["call_strike", "put_strike"], "description": "Strike prices for options must be non-negative values."}, {"rule_id": "strangle_stock_price_non_negative", "name": "Stock price must be non-negative.", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['stock_price'] < 0", "applies_to": ["stock_price"], "description": "The final trading price of the underlying asset must be non-negative."}, {"rule_id": "strangle_strike_order", "name": "For a long strangle, call strike must be greater than put strike.", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['call_strike'] <= inputs['put_strike']", "applies_to": ["call_strike", "put_strike"], "description": "A long strangle strategy typically involves purchasing an out-of-the-money call (higher strike) and an out-of-the-money put (lower strike)."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    stock_price = inputs['stock_price']\n    call_strike = inputs['call_strike']\n    call_premium = inputs['call_premium']\n    put_strike = inputs['put_strike']\n    put_premium = inputs['put_premium']\n    total_premium = call_premium + put_premium\n    call_value = max(0, stock_price - call_strike)\n    put_value = max(0, put_strike - stock_price)\n    profit_loss = call_value + put_value - total_premium\n    return profit_loss"}, "article_title": "Strangle", "article_doc_id": 5359, "article_content_excerpt": "# Strangle: How This Options Strategy Works, with an Example\n\nDefinition\n\nA strangle is an options trading strategy that profits from big price swings by simultaneously holding call and put options with different strike prices on the same asset.\n\nA strangle is an options trading strategy that aims to profit from significant price moves in a stock or other asset, whether the move is up or down. \n\nA classic case where you might use this strategy is before an expected U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA) announcement about a pharmaceutical company’s drug. If it’s approved, you can expect the company’s stock price to soar; if it’s rejected, the drug's profit potential is gone and share prices will likely drop like a stone. \n\nThe strategy involves simultaneously purchasing two types of options on the same asset: a (the right to buy) with a strike price above the current market price and a (the right to sell) with a strike price below the current market price—both with the same expiration date. This combination gives you a safety net to capture profits whether the asset’s price soars or plunges. \n\nBelow, we explain how to set up a strangle, calculate your maximum risk, and determine when this strategy makes the most sense. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * A strangle combines a call option above the current market price and a put option below it, with both having the same expiration date.\n * The strategy profits when an asset makes a significant price move in either direction, making it a good choice for traders who expect volatility but are unsure of which direction.\n * The most you can lose is the total cost of both option premiums, while, theoretically, at least, the potential profits are unlimited on the upside.\n * Strangles are generally cheaper than similar options strategies like straddles because they use out-of-the-money options.\n * Success depends on the asset making a move large enough to offset the cost of both options before they expire.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/strangle-Final-12984203025d4a6181f069fca09fe437.jpg)\n\nTheresa Chiechi / Investopedia\n\n## When to Consider a Strangle Strategy \n\nStrangles are particularly worthwhile during events or market conditions that typically generate significant price . Here are key situations when traders might consider it: \n\n**Earnings announcements** : Companies, especially in the tech and growth sectors, often see dramatic price swings after quarterly earnings reports. Investors tend to respond to tech earnings reports like people to eating pizza with pineapple on top or wearing Crocs: They either love or hate it; there’s no moderate reaction. \n\nFor example, in February 2023, Meta Platforms Inc. () dropped 26% in a single day, losing $232 billion in market value. This beat the previous largest single-day loss—an ignoble record Apple Inc. () set only 17 months earlier. Meta shares had risen for five straight days before an earnings report fell well short of analyst expectations, sending investors scrambling for the exits. \n\n**Merger and acquisition activity** : When companies are rumored to be targets or involved in major deals, their stock prices often become volatile. A strangle could enable you to profit whether a deal goes through at a premium or falls apart, setting off a price decline. \n\n### Fast Fact: \n\nReminder: Calls give the buyer the right, but not the obligation, to buy a stock at a specific price within a given time frame, while puts give the right to sell. Investors use calls when they expect prices to rise and puts when they expect a decline.\n\n**FDA drug approvals** : As we noted above, biotech and pharmaceutical companies often see massive price movements when the FDA makes decisions about their drugs. These binary events can send stocks soaring on approval or plunging on rejection. \n\nFor example, in June 2021, Biogen Inc.’s () stock surged over 38% in a single day following the FDA’s controversial approval of its Alzheimer’s drug, Aduhelm—one of the biggest price\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_2452", "name": "Weighted Average Cost of Capital (WACC)", "short_description": "Calculate the Weighted Average Cost of Capital (WACC) for a company. This function computes the WACC, which represents a company's average after-tax cost of capital from all sources, including equity and debt. It combines the cost of both equity and debt, weighted by their respective proportions in the total capital used by the company.", "domain": "corporate_finance", "topic": "wacc", "topic_extension": false, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-2452", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-179", "question_id": "test-2022", "difficulty": 4.276666119016055, "level": "hard", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "b34a65e8491710b46516dbb4866935dbbe55bf5587d3be69891244b8a4a995e8", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["cost of capital", "financing cost", "discount rate", "investment evaluation", "capital structure"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "output_scale", "ambiguity_type": "unit_scale", "trigger_signal": "question asks for percentage, FIC outputs decimal (or vice versa)", "clarification_question": "Should the answer be expressed as a decimal (e.g., 0.08) or a percentage (e.g., 8.0%)?", "options": [{"label": "Decimal (e.g., 0.08) — DEFAULT", "value": "decimal", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Percentage (e.g., 8.0%)", "value": "percent", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "result * 100.0", "max_expr_nodes": 6, "invariant": "result_new == result_old * 100.0", "affected_inputs": []}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Decimal", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "equity_market_value", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "Market value of the firm's equity.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "debt_market_value", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "Market value of the firm's debt.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "cost_of_equity", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "Cost of equity, representing the required rate of return for equity investors.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "cost_of_debt", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "Cost of debt, representing the effective rate paid on the company's issued debt.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "tax_rate", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "Corporate tax rate, used to calculate the after-tax cost of debt.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "wacc", "type": "number", "unit": null, "description": "The calculated Weighted Average Cost of Capital (WACC)."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    equity_market_value = inputs['equity_market_value']\n    debt_market_value = inputs['debt_market_value']\n    cost_of_equity = inputs['cost_of_equity']\n    cost_of_debt = inputs['cost_of_debt']\n    tax_rate = inputs['tax_rate']\n    total_value = equity_market_value + debt_market_value\n    equity_weight = equity_market_value / total_value\n    debt_weight = debt_market_value / total_value\n    after_tax_cost_of_debt = cost_of_debt * (1 - tax_rate)\n    wacc = equity_weight * cost_of_equity + debt_weight * after_tax_cost_of_debt\n    return wacc", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "wacc_001", "name": "Equity Market Value Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['equity_market_value'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Equity market value must be a positive number."}, {"rule_id": "wacc_002", "name": "Debt Market Value Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['debt_market_value'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Debt market value must be a positive number."}, {"rule_id": "wacc_003", "name": "Cost of Equity Range", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (0 <= inputs['cost_of_equity'] <= 1)", "applies_to": [], "description": "Cost of equity must be a rate between 0 and 1 (0% to 100%)."}, {"rule_id": "wacc_004", "name": "Cost of Debt Range", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (0 <= inputs['cost_of_debt'] <= 1)", "applies_to": [], "description": "Cost of debt must be a rate between 0 and 1 (0% to 100%)."}, {"rule_id": "wacc_005", "name": "Tax Rate Range", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (0 <= inputs['tax_rate'] < 1)", "applies_to": [], "description": "Corporate tax rate must be between 0 and 1 (0% to less than 100%)."}, {"rule_id": "wacc_006", "name": "Total Market Value Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['equity_market_value'] + inputs['debt_market_value'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The sum of equity and debt market values must be positive to calculate weights."}, {"rule_id": "wacc_007", "name": "WACC Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "compute(inputs) < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Weighted Average Cost of Capital (WACC) should not be negative under normal circumstances."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    equity_market_value = inputs['equity_market_value']\n    debt_market_value = inputs['debt_market_value']\n    cost_of_equity = inputs['cost_of_equity']\n    cost_of_debt = inputs['cost_of_debt']\n    tax_rate = inputs['tax_rate']\n    total_value = equity_market_value + debt_market_value\n    equity_weight = equity_market_value / total_value\n    debt_weight = debt_market_value / total_value\n    after_tax_cost_of_debt = cost_of_debt * (1 - tax_rate)\n    wacc = equity_weight * cost_of_equity + debt_weight * after_tax_cost_of_debt\n    return wacc"}, "article_title": "Weighted Average Cost of Capital (WACC)", "article_doc_id": 4843, "article_content_excerpt": "# Weighted Average Cost of Capital (WACC): Definition and Formula\n\n## What Is Weighted Average Cost of Capital (WACC)? \n\nWeighted average cost of capital (WACC) is a company's average after-tax from all sources, including common stock, preferred stock, bonds, and other forms of debt. It represents the average rate that a company expects to pay to finance its business. \n\nWACC is a common way to determine the because it expresses, in a single number, the return that bondholders and shareholders demand in return for providing the company with . A company's WACC is likely to be higher if its is relatively volatile or if its debt is considered risky because investors will want greater returns to compensate them for the level of risk. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Weighted average cost of capital (WACC) represents a company's cost of capital, with each category of capital (debt and equity) proportionately weighted.\n * WACC can be calculated by multiplying the cost of each capital source by its relevant weight in terms of market value, then adding the results together to determine the total. \n * WACC is commonly used as a against which companies and investors can gauge the desirability of a given project or acquisition.\n * WACC is also used as the discount rate for future cash flows in discounted cash flow analysis.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/TermDefinitions_wacc_final-626b8af9bfc741d6a9792fe0568242cd.png)\n\nJessica Olah / Investopedia\n\n## Understanding WACC \n\nCalculating a company's WACC is useful for investors and stock analysts, as well company management. Each group will use WACC for different purposes. \n\nIn corporate finance, determining a company's cost of capital can be important for several reasons. For instance, WACC can be used as the for estimating the of a project or acquisition. \n\nIf the company believes that a merger, for example, will generate a return higher than its cost of capital, then it's likely a good choice for the company. However, if it anticipates a return lower than its investors are expecting, there might be better uses for that capital. \n\nTo investors, WACC is an important tool in assessing a company's potential for profitability. In most cases, a lower WACC indicates a healthy business that's able to attract money from investors at a lower cost. A higher WACC usually coincides with businesses that are seen as riskier and need to compensate investors with higher returns to offset the level of volatility. \n\nIf a company only obtains financing through one source—say, common stock—then calculating its cost of capital would be relatively simple. If investors expected a of 10% on their , the company's cost of capital would be the same as its cost of equity: 10%. \n\nThe same would be true if the company only used debt financing. For example, if the company paid an average yield of 5% on its bonds, its pre-tax cost of debt would be 5%. However, because interest payments are tax-deductible, the after-tax cost of debt would be lower, calculated as 5% × (1 - tax rate). This after-tax cost of debt would also represent the company's cost of capital in this scenario, since all the capital is debt. \n\nHowever, many companies use both debt and equity financing in various proportions. This is where the calculation for WACC becomes valuable. \n\n## WACC Formula and Calculation \n\nWACC is found by determining the proportions of debt and equity financing that a company uses to determine the total cost of capital. The equation is: \n\n\\begin{aligned} &\\text{WACC} = \\left ( \\frac{ E }{ V} \\times Re \\right ) + \\left ( \\frac{ D }{ V} \\times Rd \\times ( 1 - Tc ) \\right ) \\\\\\ &\\textbf{where:} \\\\\\ &E = \\text{Market value of the firm's equity} \\\\\\ &D = \\text{Market value of the firm's debt} \\\\\\ &V = E + D \\\\\\ &Re = \\text{Cost of equity} \\\\\\ &Rd = \\text{Cost of debt} \\\\\\ &Tc = \\text{Corporate tax rate} \\\\\\ \\end{aligned}\n\nWACC is calculated by multiplying the cost of each capital source (debt and equity) by its relevant weight and then ad\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_1400", "name": "Purchasing Managers' Index (PMI)", "short_description": "Calculates the Purchasing Managers' Index (PMI) based on survey responses indicating improvement, no change, or deterioration, providing an indicator of economic trends in manufacturing and service sectors.", "domain": "financial_markets", "topic": "economic_indicators", "topic_extension": true, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-1400", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-551", "question_id": "test-1710", "difficulty": 3.2188758248682006, "level": "medium", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "5e4d7c653d18b71f3e53e3804c3cc7b7b96e8415df671213d65b702017f33d43", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["Purchasing Managers' Index", "PMI", "economic indicator", "manufacturing trends", "service sector trends", "business conditions", "survey index"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "pmi_output_scale", "ambiguity_type": "unit_scale", "trigger_signal": "PMI is an index from 0-100, but often discussed in percentage terms, causing potential confusion on whether 50 means 0.50 or 50.0", "clarification_question": "Should the PMI output be interpreted as a value from 0 to 100 (e.g., 57.5), or scaled down to a decimal between 0 and 1 (e.g., 0.575)?", "options": [{"label": "Value from 0-100 (Default PMI reporting convention)", "value": "0_100_scale", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Scaled to a decimal from 0-1", "value": "0_1_scale", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "result / 100.0", "max_expr_nodes": 6, "invariant": "result_new == result_old / 100.0", "affected_inputs": []}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Value from 0 to 100", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "p1", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The percentage of survey answers reporting an improvement in business conditions.", "unit": "percent", "aliases": []}, {"name": "p2", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The percentage of survey answers reporting no change in business conditions.", "unit": "percent", "aliases": []}, {"name": "p3", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The percentage of survey answers reporting a deterioration in business conditions.", "unit": "percent", "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "pmi", "type": "number", "unit": "index_points", "description": "The calculated Purchasing Managers' Index (PMI) value, ranging from 0 to 100."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    p1 = inputs['p1']\n    p2 = inputs['p2']\n    p3 = inputs['p3']\n    pmi = p1 * 1 + p2 * 0.5 + p3 * 0\n    return round(pmi, 1)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "pmi_input_non_negative", "name": "Input percentages must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['p1'] < 0 or inputs['p2'] < 0 or inputs['p3'] < 0", "applies_to": ["p1", "p2", "p3"], "description": "The percentages of survey responses (improvement, no change, deterioration) cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "pmi_input_sum_100", "name": "Sum of percentages must equal 100%", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "abs(inputs['p1'] + inputs['p2'] + inputs['p3'] - 100) > 1e-6", "applies_to": ["p1", "p2", "p3"], "description": "The sum of percentages for improvement, no change, and deterioration must equal 100% to represent all survey responses."}, {"rule_id": "pmi_input_not_exceed_100", "name": "Input percentages must not exceed 100%", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['p1'] > 100 or inputs['p2'] > 100 or inputs['p3'] > 100", "applies_to": ["p1", "p2", "p3"], "description": "Individual percentages for survey responses cannot exceed 100%."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    p1 = inputs['p1']\n    p2 = inputs['p2']\n    p3 = inputs['p3']\n    pmi = p1 * 1 + p2 * 0.5 + p3 * 0\n    return round(pmi, 1)"}, "article_title": "Purchasing Managers' Index (PMI)", "article_doc_id": 2763, "article_content_excerpt": "# Purchasing Managers' Index (PMI) Definition and How It Works\n\n## What Is the Purchasing Managers' Index (PMI)? \n\nThe Purchasing Managers' Index (PMI) is an indicator of the prevailing direction of economic trends in the manufacturing and service sectors. The indicator is compiled and released monthly by the , a nonprofit supply management organization. \n\nIt is a that summarizes whether market conditions are expanding, staying the same, or contracting, as viewed by purchasing managers. The purpose of the PMI is to provide information about current and future business conditions to company decision-makers, analysts, and investors. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * The Purchasing Managers' Index (PMI) is a measure of the prevailing direction of economic trends in manufacturing.\n * The PMI is based on a monthly survey of supply chain managers across 19 industries, covering both upstream and downstream activity.\n * The value of the PMI and its movements can provide useful insight to business decision makers, market analysts, and investors.\n * The PMI is a leading indicator of overall economic activity in the U.S.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/PMI--f77e0dc1e4fe49b5985b22d1f5494bc0.jpg)\n\nInvestopedia / Zoe Hansen\n\n## Formula and Calculation of the Purchasing Managers' Index (PMI) \n\nThe PMI is calculated as follows: \n\n> PMI = (P1 * 1) + (P2 * 0.5) + (P3 * 0) \n\nWhere: \n\n * P1 = percentage of answers reporting an improvement \n * P2 = percentage of answers reporting no change \n * P3 = percentage of answers reporting a deterioration \n\nThe survey-based indicator is compiled and released each month by ISM. Other companies also produce PMI numbers, including IHS Markit Group, which puts out the PMI for various countries outside the U.S. \n\n## How the PMI Works \n\nThe PMI is a key economic tool and is among the most reliable leading indicators of the U.S. economy. The index is reported by manufacturing and services. The index sheds insight into the business environment and also helps companies get a grasp on where the economy is headed. \n\nThe PMI is calculated based on responses to a survey sent to senior executives at more than 400 companies in 19 primary industries, which are weighted by their contribution to U.S. . \n\nThe surveys include questions about business conditions, whether or not they are changing, and whether they are improving or deteriorating. The PMI is based on five major survey areas—each of which is weighted equally: \n\n * New orders\n * Inventory levels\n * Production\n * Supplier deliveries\n * Employment \n\nThe headline PMI is a number from 0 to 100. A PMI above 50 represents an when compared with the previous month. A PMI reading under 50 represents a while a reading at 50 indicates no change. The further away from 50, the greater the level of change. \n\n### Important: \n\nThe PMI results are released on the first Monday of every month.\n\n## Using the PMI \n\nThe PMI and relevant data produced from the monthly surveys by the ISM are critical decision-making tools for a variety of areas, including management, suppliers, and investors. \n\n### Corporate Managers \n\nManagement can use the monthly PMI results to make key decisions about their own businesses. For instance, an automobile manufacturer makes production decisions based on the new orders it expects from customers in future months. \n\nThose new orders drive the purchasing decisions of its leadership about dozens of component parts and raw materials, such as steel and plastic. Existing inventory balances also drive the amount of production the manufacturer needs to complete to fill new orders and to keep some inventory on hand at the end of the month. \n\n### Suppliers \n\nSuppliers also make decisions based on the PMI. A parts supplier for a manufacturer follows the PMI to estimate the amount of future demand for its products. The supplier also wants to know how much inventory its customers have on hand, which also affects the amount of production its clients must generate. \n\nPMI informat\n...[truncated]"}
