ion' provided as a direct multiplier (e.g., 1.25 for 25% appreciation) or as a percentage change (e.g., 0.25 for 25% appreciation)?", "options": [{"label": "Direct multiplier (e.g., 1.25 for 25% appreciation) - DEFAULT", "value": "direct_multiplier", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Percentage change (e.g., 0.25 for 25% appreciation)", "value": "percentage_change", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "(result - (borrowed_funds * stock_appreciation_as_percentage_change * time_period)) / (1 + stock_appreciation_as_percentage_change) * stock_appreciation_as_percentage_change", "max_expr_nodes": 26, "invariant": "False", "affected_inputs": ["borrowed_funds", "investment", "interest_rate", "time_period"]}}], "i_level": "hard", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Direct multiplier (1 + percentage_change_as_decimal)", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}, {"id": "interest_rate_period_basis", "ambiguity_type": "rate_period", "trigger_signal": "interest rate period not explicitly stated (annual vs monthly)", "clarification_question": "Is the 'interest_rate' provided as an annual rate or a monthly rate?", "options": [{"label": "Annual rate (DEFAULT)", "value": "annual", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Monthly rate (will be annualized for calculation)", "value": "monthly", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "result - borrowed_funds * ( (1 + interest_rate) ** 12 - (1 + interest_rate) ) * time_period", "max_expr_nodes": 28, "invariant": "False", "affected_inputs": ["borrowed_funds", "interest_rate", "time_period"]}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Annual rate", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}], "inputs": [{"name": "investment", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The initial amount of money invested by the trader.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "borrowed_funds", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The amount of money borrowed from the broker.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "stock_appreciation", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The multiplier of stock price change (e.g., 2.0 if the stock doubled, 0.5 if it halved).", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "interest_rate", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The annual interest rate charged on the borrowed funds as a decimal (e.g., 0.10 for 10%).", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "time_period", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The period in years for which the money was borrowed.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "net_profit_or_loss", "type": "number", "unit": "currency", "description": "The net profit or loss after accounting for stock appreciation and interest paid."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    investment = inputs['investment']\n    borrowed_funds = inputs['borrowed_funds']\n    stock_appreciation = inputs['stock_appreciation']\n    interest_rate = inputs['interest_rate']\n    time_period = inputs['time_period']\n    stock_value_at_sale = (investment + borrowed_funds) * stock_appreciation\n    interest_paid = borrowed_funds * interest_rate * time_period\n    net_profit_or_loss = stock_value_at_sale - investment - borrowed_funds - interest_paid\n    return net_profit_or_loss", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "input_investment_positive", "name": "Investment must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['investment'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The initial investment amount must be a positive value."}, {"rule_id": "input_borrowed_funds_non_negative", "name": "Borrowed funds must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['borrowed_funds'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The amount of money borrowed cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "input_stock_appreciation_positive", "name": "Stock appreciation multiplier must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['stock_appreciation'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The stock appreciation multiplier must be greater than zero, as stock price cannot be zero or negative."}, {"rule_id": "input_interest_rate_non_negative", "name": "Interest rate must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['interest_rate'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The annual interest rate on borrowed funds cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "input_time_period_positive", "name": "Time period must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['time_period'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The time period for which the money was borrowed must be a positive value."}, {"rule_id": "input_interest_rate_plausibility", "name": "Plausible annual interest rate", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['interest_rate'] > 1.0", "applies_to": [], "description": "An annual interest rate greater than 100% (1.0) is unusually high and might indicate an input error."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    investment = inputs['investment']\n    borrowed_funds = inputs['borrowed_funds']\n    stock_appreciation = inputs['stock_appreciation']\n    interest_rate = inputs['interest_rate']\n    time_period = inputs['time_period']\n    stock_value_at_sale = (investment + borrowed_funds) * stock_appreciation\n    interest_paid = borrowed_funds * interest_rate * time_period\n    net_profit_or_loss = stock_value_at_sale - investment - borrowed_funds - interest_paid\n    return net_profit_or_loss"}, "article_title": "Margin Account", "article_doc_id": 1555, "article_content_excerpt": "# Margin Account: Definition, How It Works, and Example \n\n## What Is a Margin Account? \n\nThe term margin account refers to a in which an investor's broker-dealer lends them cash to purchase stocks or other financial products. The margin account and the securities held within it are used as collateral for the loan. \n\nIt comes with a that the investor must pay to keep it active. Borrowing money from a broker-dealer through a margin account allows investors to increase their purchasing and trading power. Investing with margin accounts means using , which increases the chance of magnifying an investor's profits and losses. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * A margin account allows a trader to borrow funds from a broker without needing to put up the entire value of a trade.\n * A margin account typically allows an investor to trade other financial products, such as futures and options (if approved and available with that broker), as well as stocks.\n * Margin increases the profit and loss potential of the trader's capital.\n * When trading stocks, a margin fee or interest is charged on borrowed funds.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/marginaccount.asp-final-e5093f288a7348ad9bbb1943538d9dbe.png)\n\nInvestopedia / Julie Bang\n\n## How a Margin Account Works \n\nIf an investor purchases securities with margin funds and those securities appreciate in value beyond the interest rate charged on the funds, the investor will earn a better total return than if they had only purchased securities with their own cash. This is the advantage of using margin funds. \n\nOn the downside, the brokerage firm charges interest on the margin funds for as long as the loan is outstanding, increasing the investor’s cost of buying the securities. If the securities decline in value, the investor will be and will have to pay interest to the broker on top of that. \n\nIf a margin account’s equity drops below the level, the brokerage firm will make a to the investor. Within a specified number of days—typically within three days, although in some situations it may be less—the investor must deposit more cash or all or a portion of the difference between the security’s price and the maintenance margin. \n\n### Warning: \n\nThe investor has the potential to lose more money than the funds deposited in the account. For this reason, a margin account is only suitable for a sophisticated investor with a thorough understanding of the additional investment risks and requirements of .\n\nA brokerage firm has the right to ask a customer to increase the amount of they have in a margin account, sell the investor’s securities if the broker feels their own funds are at risk, or sue the investor if they don't fulfill a margin call or if they are carrying a negative balance in their account. \n\nA margin account may not be used for buying stocks on margin in an , a trust, or other fiduciary accounts. In addition, a margin account can't be used with stock trading accounts of less than $2,000, in most cases.\n\n## Margin on Other Financial Products \n\nFinancial products, other than stocks, can be purchased on margin. traders also frequently use margin, for example. \n\nWith other financial products, the initial margin and maintenance margin will vary. Exchanges or other regulatory bodies set the minimum margin requirements, although certain brokers may increase these margin requirements. \n\nThat means the margin may vary by broker. The required for futures is typically much lower than for stocks. While stock investors must put up 50% of the value of a trade, futures traders may only be required to put up between 3% to 12%.\n\n### Tip: \n\nMargin accounts are required for most trading strategies.\n\n## Example of a Margin Account \n\nAssume an investor with $2,500 in a margin account wants to buy a stock for $5 per share. The customer could use additional margin funds of up to $2,500 supplied by the broker to purchase $5,000 worth of stock, or 1,000 shares. \n\nIf the stock appreciates to $10 per share, the investor can sell th\n...[truncated]"}
