, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "debt_to_cap_ratio", "type": "number", "unit": "ratio", "description": "The debt-to-capitalization ratio, expressed as a decimal."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    short_term_debt = inputs['short_term_debt']\n    long_term_debt = inputs['long_term_debt']\n    shareholders_equity = inputs['shareholders_equity']\n    total_debt = short_term_debt + long_term_debt\n    total_capital = total_debt + shareholders_equity\n    if total_capital == 0:\n        raise ValueError(\"The sum of debts and shareholders' equity must not be zero.\")\n    debt_to_cap_ratio = total_debt / total_capital\n    return debt_to_cap_ratio", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "debt_term_debt_positive", "name": "Short-term debt must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['short_term_debt'] < 0", "applies_to": ["short_term_debt"], "description": "Short-term debt cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "long_term_debt_positive", "name": "Long-term debt must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['long_term_debt'] < 0", "applies_to": ["long_term_debt"], "description": "Long-term debt cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "shareholders_equity_plausibility", "name": "Shareholders' equity should typically be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['shareholders_equity'] < 0", "applies_to": ["shareholders_equity"], "description": "While equity can technically be negative, for standard leverage ratio calculations, a non-negative value is typically expected."}, {"rule_id": "total_capital_not_zero", "name": "Total capitalization must not be zero", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['short_term_debt'] + inputs['long_term_debt'] + inputs['shareholders_equity'] == 0", "applies_to": ["short_term_debt", "long_term_debt", "shareholders_equity"], "description": "The sum of short-term debt, long-term debt, and shareholders' equity (total capitalization) cannot be zero to avoid division by zero."}, {"rule_id": "ratio_within_bounds", "name": "Debt-to-capitalization ratio must be between 0 and 1", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "compute(inputs) < 0 or compute(inputs) > 1", "applies_to": ["debt_to_cap_ratio"], "description": "The debt-to-capitalization ratio, representing a proportion of capital, should naturally fall between 0 and 1 (inclusive)."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    short_term_debt = inputs['short_term_debt']\n    long_term_debt = inputs['long_term_debt']\n    shareholders_equity = inputs['shareholders_equity']\n    total_debt = short_term_debt + long_term_debt\n    total_capital = total_debt + shareholders_equity\n    if total_capital == 0:\n        raise ValueError(\"The sum of debts and shareholders' equity must not be zero.\")\n    debt_to_cap_ratio = total_debt / total_capital\n    return debt_to_cap_ratio"}, "article_title": "Leverage Ratio", "article_doc_id": 4126, "article_content_excerpt": "# Leverage Ratio: What It Is, What It Tells You, How to Calculate\n\n## What Is a Leverage Ratio? \n\nA leverage ratio is a type of financial measurement used in finance, business, and economics to evaluate the level of debt relative to another financial metric. It can be used to measure how much comes in the form of debt (loans) or assess the ability of a company to meet its financial obligations. \n\nCommon leverage ratios include the , equity multiplier, , , consumer leverage ratio, debt to capital ratio, leverage ratio, debt-to-EBITDAX ratio, interest coverage ratio, and fixed-charge coverage ratio. \n\nIn business, finance, and economics, leverage ratios are important because companies and institutions rely on a mixture of and to finance their operations, and knowing the amount of debt held is useful in evaluating whether it can be paid off as it comes due. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * A leverage ratio is a type of financial measurement used in finance, business, and economics to evaluate the level of debt relative to another financial metric.\n * There are many different types of leverage ratios which can be used to assess the ability of a company, institution, or individual to meet their financial obligations.\n * A leverage ratio may also be used to measure a company’s mix of operating expenses to get an idea of how changes in output will affect operating income.\n * Common leverage ratios include the debt-equity ratio, equity multiplier, degree of financial leverage, and consumer leverage ratio.\n * Banks have regulatory oversight on the level of leverage they can hold.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/leverageratio-3039fd72c0e44663bce328f13eef2fb8.png)\n\nLaura Porter / Investopedia\n\n## What Does a Leverage Ratio Tell You? \n\nIn most cases, leverage ratios assess the ability of a company, institution, or individual to meet their financial obligations. For example, too much debt can be dangerous for a company and its investors. However, if a company’s operations can generate a higher rate of return than the interest rate on its loans, then the debt may help to fuel growth. \n\nUncontrolled debt levels can lead to credit downgrades or worse. On the other hand, too few debts can also raise questions. A reluctance or inability to borrow may indicate that operating margins are tight. \n\n### Important: \n\nSeveral different ratios may be categorized as leverage ratios. The main factors considered are debt, equity, assets, and .\n\nA leverage ratio may also be used to measure a company’s mix of to get an idea of how changes in output will affect operating income. Fixed and variable costs are the two types of operating costs; depending on the company and the industry, the mix will differ. \n\nAnother leverage ratio is the consumer leverage ratio. This ratio looks at the level of consumer debt compared to disposable income and is used in economic analysis and by policymakers. \n\n### Tip: \n\nUnderstanding how debt amplifies returns is the key to understanding leverage. Debt is not necessarily a bad thing, particularly if the debt is taken on to invest in projects that will generate positive returns. Leverage can thus multiply returns, although it can also magnify losses if returns turn out to be negative.\n\n## Banks and Leverage Ratios \n\nBanks are among the most leveraged institutions in the United States. The combination of fractional-reserve banking and protection has produced a banking environment with limited lending risks. \n\nTo compensate for this, three separate regulatory bodies—the FDIC, the , and the —review and restrict the leverage ratios for American banks. These bodies restrict how much money a bank can lend relative to how much capital the bank devotes to its own assets. The level of capital is important because banks can “” the capital portion of their assets if total asset values drop. Assets financed by debt cannot be written down because the bank’s bondholders and depositors are owed those funds. \n\nBanking regulations for leverage ratios\n...[truncated]"}
