ses": []}, {"name": "months_passed", "type": "integer", "required": true, "description": "The number of months that have passed in the current year.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "annual_yield", "type": "number", "unit": "%", "description": "The annualized yield as a percentage."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    initial_value = inputs['initial_value']\n    current_value = inputs['current_value']\n    months_passed = inputs['months_passed']\n    ytd_growth = current_value / initial_value\n    annual_yield = (ytd_growth ** (12 / months_passed) - 1) * 100\n    return round(annual_yield, 2)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "initial_value_type_check", "name": "Initial Value Type Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('initial_value'), (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "The initial value must be a number (integer or float)."}, {"rule_id": "current_value_type_check", "name": "Current Value Type Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('current_value'), (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "The current value must be a number (integer or float)."}, {"rule_id": "months_passed_type_check", "name": "Months Passed Type Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('months_passed'), int)", "applies_to": [], "description": "Months passed must be an integer."}, {"rule_id": "initial_value_positive", "name": "Initial Value Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['initial_value'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The initial investment value must be greater than zero to calculate yield meaningfully."}, {"rule_id": "months_passed_range", "name": "Months Passed Range Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (1 <= inputs['months_passed'] <= 12)", "applies_to": [], "description": "The number of months passed must be between 1 and 12, inclusive."}, {"rule_id": "current_value_non_negative", "name": "Current Value Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['current_value'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "An investment's current value is typically not negative; this may indicate an input error."}, {"rule_id": "extreme_annualized_yield", "name": "Extreme Annualized Yield Alert", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "abs(compute(inputs)) > 500.0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The annualized yield is extremely high (above 500%) or low (below -500%), which may indicate an input error or highly volatile investment."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    initial_value = inputs['initial_value']\n    current_value = inputs['current_value']\n    months_passed = inputs['months_passed']\n    ytd_growth = current_value / initial_value\n    annual_yield = (ytd_growth ** (12 / months_passed) - 1) * 100\n    return round(annual_yield, 2)"}, "article_title": "Year to Date (YTD)", "article_doc_id": 12, "article_content_excerpt": "# Year to Date (YTD): What It Means and How to Use It\n\nDefinition\n\nYear to date is the period of time that begins at the first day of a fiscal or calendar year and ends at the current date.\n\n## What Is Year to Date? \n\nYear to date (YTD) refers to the period beginning on the first day of the current or up to the current date. YTD information is useful for analyzing business trends over time or comparing performance data to competitors or peers in the same industry. The acronym is often seen in references to investment returns, , and net pay. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * YTD refers to a period beginning the first day of the current calendar year or fiscal year up to the current date.\n * Some governmental agencies and organizations have fiscal years that begin on a date other than the first day of January.\n * YTD analysis is useful for managers when reviewing interim financial statements in comparison to historical YTD financial statements.\n * Calculating YTD is a simple process.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/YTD-V2-2a43c52527b840ee946b51e2efeb1a4c.jpg)\n\nInvestopedia / Matthew Collins\n\n## Understanding Year to Date \n\nSomeone who's using YTD for a calendar year reference would be referring to the period from Jan. 1 of the current year through the current date. They would mean the period between the first day of the fiscal year in question and the current date if they were using YTD for a fiscal year reference. \n\nA fiscal year is a period lasting one year but not necessarily beginning on the first of January. It's used by governments, corporations, and other organizations for accounting and external purposes. \n\nThe federal government observes its fiscal year from Oct. 1 to Sept. 30. Microsoft's fiscal year is from July 1 to June 30. It's common for to have a fiscal year of July 1 to June 30. \n\nCurrent YTD are routinely analyzed against historical YTD financial statements for the equivalent period. A three-month YTD financial statement would run through Sept. 30 and would be compared to previous years' July through September statements if a company's fiscal year begins on July 1. \n\nThis comparison can help to identify seasonal trends or abnormalities. \n\n### Important: \n\nYTD financial information is useful for management because it's a good way to check in on the financial health of a company on an interim basis rather than waiting until the end of the fiscal or calendar year.\n\n## Types of Year to Date \n\nYTD financial information can be created and classified in various ways. \n\n### Year to Date Return \n\nYTD return refers to the amount of that's made by an investment since the first day of the current year. Investors and analysts use YTD return information to assess the performance of investments and portfolios. \n\nCalculate a YTD by subtracting its value on the first day of the current year from its current value. Then divide the difference by the value on the first day and multiply the product by 100 to convert it to a percentage. A portfolio's YTD return would be 50% if it was worth $100,000 on Jan. 1 and it's worth $150,000 on the present date. \n\n### Year to Date Earnings \n\nYTD earnings refer to the amount of money an individual has earned from Jan. 1 to the current date. This amount typically appears on an employee's pay stub along with information about and withholdings and payments. \n\nYTD earnings may also describe the amount of money an or business has earned since the beginning of the year. This amount consists of revenue minus expenses. Small-business owners use YTD earnings to track financial goals and estimate quarterly tax payments. \n\n### Year to Date Net Pay \n\nNet pay is the difference between an employee's earnings and the withholdings from those earnings. An employee can calculate net pay by subtracting the tax and other withholdings from their gross pay. YTD net pay appears on many paycheck stubs and this figure includes all the money earned since Jan. 1 of the current year minus all the tax and other benefit amounts\n...[truncated]"}
