on": "The price of the underlying asset at expiration.", "unit": "$", "aliases": ["stock_price_at_expiry"]}, {"name": "is_long_call", "type": "boolean", "required": true, "description": "True if calculating for a long call butterfly spread, False for a short call butterfly spread.", "unit": null, "aliases": ["long_position", "call_spread_type"]}], "output": {"name": "profit_or_loss", "type": "number", "unit": "$", "description": "The calculated profit or loss of the butterfly spread position."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    lower_strike = inputs['lower_strike']\n    middle_strike = inputs['middle_strike']\n    upper_strike = inputs['upper_strike']\n    premium_cost = inputs['premium_cost']\n    underlying_price = inputs['underlying_price']\n    is_long_call = inputs['is_long_call']\n    if is_long_call:\n        if underlying_price == middle_strike:\n            profit_or_loss = middle_strike - lower_strike - premium_cost\n        else:\n            profit_or_loss = -premium_cost\n    elif underlying_price <= lower_strike or underlying_price >= upper_strike:\n        profit_or_loss = premium_cost\n    else:\n        profit_or_loss = lower_strike - upper_strike + premium_cost\n    return round(profit_or_loss, 2)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "strike_order", "name": "Strike Price Order Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (inputs['lower_strike'] < inputs['middle_strike'] and inputs['middle_strike'] < inputs['upper_strike'])", "applies_to": [], "description": "The strike prices must be in ascending order: lower_strike < middle_strike < upper_strike."}, {"rule_id": "strike_equidistance", "name": "Strike Price Equidistance Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "abs((inputs['middle_strike'] - inputs['lower_strike']) - (inputs['upper_strike'] - inputs['middle_strike'])) > 1e-6", "applies_to": [], "description": "The lower and upper strike prices must be equidistant from the middle strike price for a standard butterfly spread."}, {"rule_id": "positive_strikes", "name": "Positive Strike Prices Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['lower_strike'] <= 0 or inputs['middle_strike'] <= 0 or inputs['upper_strike'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "All strike prices (lower, middle, upper) must be positive values."}, {"rule_id": "positive_premium", "name": "Positive Net Premium Cost Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['premium_cost'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The net premium cost must be a positive value representing a debit for long positions or the absolute credit received for short positions."}, {"rule_id": "positive_underlying_price", "name": "Positive Underlying Price Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['underlying_price'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The underlying asset price at expiration must be a non-negative value."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    lower_strike = inputs['lower_strike']\n    middle_strike = inputs['middle_strike']\n    upper_strike = inputs['upper_strike']\n    premium_cost = inputs['premium_cost']\n    underlying_price = inputs['underlying_price']\n    is_long_call = inputs['is_long_call']\n    if is_long_call:\n        if underlying_price == middle_strike:\n            profit_or_loss = middle_strike - lower_strike - premium_cost\n        else:\n            profit_or_loss = -premium_cost\n    elif underlying_price <= lower_strike or underlying_price >= upper_strike:\n        profit_or_loss = premium_cost\n    else:\n        profit_or_loss = lower_strike - upper_strike + premium_cost\n    return round(profit_or_loss, 2)"}, "article_title": "Butterfly Spread", "article_doc_id": 1505, "article_content_excerpt": "# Butterfly Spread: What It Is, With Types Explained & Example\n\n## What Is a Butterfly Spread? \n\nThe term butterfly spread refers to an strategy that combines and with a fixed risk and capped profit. These spreads are intended as a market-neutral strategy and pay off the most if the underlying asset does not move prior to option expiration. They involve either four calls, four puts, or a combination of puts and calls with three strike prices. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * A butterfly spread is an options strategy that combines both bull and bear spreads.\n * These are neutral strategies that come with a fixed risk and capped profits and losses.\n * Butterfly spreads pay off the most if the underlying asset doesn't move before the option expires.\n * These spreads use four options and three different strike prices.\n * The upper and lower strike prices are equal distance from the middle, or at-the-money, strike price.\n\n## Understanding Butterfly Spreads \n\nButterfly spreads are strategies used by options traders. Remember that an option is a financial instrument that is based on the value of an , such as a stock or a commodity. Options contracts allow buyers to buy or sell the underlying asset by a specific expiration or exercise date.\n\nAs noted above, a butterfly spread . This is a neutral strategy that uses four options contracts with the same expiration but three different : \n\n * A higher strike price\n * An strike price\n * A lower strike price\n\nThe options with the higher and lower strike prices are the same distance from the at-the-money options. If the at-the-money options have a strike price of $60, the upper and lower options should have strike prices equal dollar amounts above and below $60. At $55 and $65, for example, these strikes are both $5 away from $60. \n\n or can be used for a butterfly spread. Combining the options in various ways will create different types of butterfly spreads, each designed to either profit from or low volatility. \n\n### Important: \n\nA spread strategy can be characterized by its payoff or the visualizations of its profit-loss profile.\n\n## Types of Butterfly Spreads \n\n### Long Call Butterfly Spread \n\nThe long butterfly call spread is created by buying one in-the-money call option with a low strike price, two at-the-money call options, and buying one call option with a higher strike price. Net is created when entering the trade. \n\nThe maximum profit is achieved if the price of the underlying at is the same as the written calls. The max profit is equal to the strike of the written option, less the strike of the lower call, premiums, and commissions paid. The maximum loss is the initial cost of the premiums paid, plus commissions. \n\n### Short Call Butterfly Spread \n\nThe short butterfly spread is created by selling one call option with a lower strike price, buying two at-the-money call options, and selling an out-of-the-money call option at a higher strike price. A net is created when entering the position. This position maximizes its profit if the price of the is above or the upper strike or below the lower strike at expiry. \n\nThe maximum profit is equal to the initial premium received, less the price of commissions. The maximum loss is the strike price of the bought call minus the lower strike price, less the premiums received. \n\n### Long Put Butterfly Spread \n\nThe long put butterfly spread is created by buying one put with a lower strike price, selling two at-the-money puts, and buying a put with a higher strike price. is created when entering the position. Like the long call butterfly, this position has a maximum profit when the underlying stays at the strike price of the middle options. \n\nThe maximum profit is equal to the higher strike price minus the strike of the sold put, less the premium paid. The maximum loss of the trade is limited to the initial premiums and commissions paid. \n\n### Short Put Butterfly Spread \n\nThe short put butterfly spread is created by writing one out-of-the-money put option wi\n...[truncated]"}
