 null, "aliases": ["returns", "components"]}, {"name": "weights", "type": "array[number]", "required": true, "description": "A list of weights corresponding to each value, reflecting its importance. The sum of weights is used for normalization.", "unit": null, "aliases": ["proportions", "allocations"]}], "output": {"name": "weighted_average", "type": "number", "unit": "%", "description": "The calculated weighted average value, expressed as a number representing a percentage."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    values = inputs['values']\n    weights = inputs['weights']\n    if len(values) != len(weights):\n        raise ValueError('The length of values and weights must match.')\n    if len(weights) == 0 or sum(weights) == 0:\n        raise ValueError('Sum of weights must be non-zero.')\n    weighted_sum = sum((value * weight for value, weight in zip(values, weights)))\n    total_weight = sum(weights)\n    weighted_average = weighted_sum / total_weight\n    return weighted_average", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "input_values_type", "name": "Values input type check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('values'), list)", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'values' input must be a list of numbers."}, {"rule_id": "input_weights_type", "name": "Weights input type check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('weights'), list)", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'weights' input must be a list of numbers."}, {"rule_id": "values_elements_numeric", "name": "Values elements numeric check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "all(isinstance(v, (int, float)) for v in inputs.get('values', []))", "applies_to": [], "description": "All elements in the 'values' list must be numbers."}, {"rule_id": "weights_elements_numeric", "name": "Weights elements numeric check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "all(isinstance(w, (int, float)) for w in inputs.get('weights', []))", "applies_to": [], "description": "All elements in the 'weights' list must be numbers."}, {"rule_id": "length_mismatch", "name": "Input list length check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "len(inputs.get('values', [])) != len(inputs.get('weights', []))", "applies_to": [], "description": "The length of 'values' and 'weights' lists must be identical."}, {"rule_id": "sum_weights_nonzero", "name": "Sum of weights check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "len(inputs.get('weights', [])) == 0 or sum(inputs.get('weights', [])) == 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'weights' list cannot be empty and the sum of weights must be non-zero to avoid division by zero."}, {"rule_id": "non_negative_weights", "name": "Non-negative weights check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "any(w < 0 for w in inputs.get('weights', []))", "applies_to": [], "description": "Weights should typically be non-negative. Negative weights might indicate a special scenario or an error."}, {"rule_id": "weights_normalization", "name": "Weights normalization check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "abs(sum(inputs.get('weights', [])) - 1.0) > 1e-6 and abs(sum(inputs.get('weights', [])) - 100.0) > 1e-6", "applies_to": [], "description": "Weights often sum to 1 (for decimals) or 100 (for percentages). Confirm if your weights are scaled correctly if they do not match these common sums."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    values = inputs['values']\n    weights = inputs['weights']\n    if len(values) != len(weights):\n        raise ValueError('The length of values and weights must match.')\n    if len(weights) == 0 or sum(weights) == 0:\n        raise ValueError('Sum of weights must be non-zero.')\n    weighted_sum = sum((value * weight for value, weight in zip(values, weights)))\n    total_weight = sum(weights)\n    weighted_average = weighted_sum / total_weight\n    return weighted_average"}, "article_title": "Weighted", "article_doc_id": 4840, "article_content_excerpt": "# Weighted: What It Means and How It Works\n\n## What is Weighted \n\nWeighted is a description of adjustments to a figure to reflect different proportions or \"weights\" of components that make up that figure. A , for example, takes into account the proportional relevance of each component instead of measuring each individual component equally. The is a price-weighted average that compares each security based on the stock's price relative to the sum of all the stocks' prices. The S&P 500 Index and , on the other hand, are based on market capitalization, where each company is measured relative to its . \n\nWhere the DJIA and indexes utilize weighting in their calculation to more closely approximate the effect that changing stock prices will have on the overall market, weighting can also be used to help evaluate the past and current prices of individual instruments through . \n\n## BREAKING DOWN Weighted \n\nEmphasis can be placed on the more pertinent data through weighting; this method is used frequently in the investing and accounting world. A weighted , for example, places additional emphasis on the most recent data, thereby providing a better view of current market activity. Similarly, a measures how much a stock has risen or fallen over a certain period, placing more emphasis on recent activity. Since more focus is placed on the current period, the calculation provides a more relevant measure for short-term analysis. Other weighted metrics include (WACC), weighted average coupon, and time weighted average annual rate of return. \n\n## Paying Attention to Index Weights \n\n, or index investing, has many cheerleaders. Investing in an index is held out as the \"best\" way to participate in the stock market. For many investors who do not have the time, aptitude or inclination to follow the stock market, this may be true. For others, though, who care about balance in an index, periodic checks of sector weightings are useful. The S&P 500 Index, the most common market index upon which several passive investment vehicles are formed, can become overweighted in certain sectors such as information technology if the market caps of these constituents grow disproportionately relative to the other sectors. If an investor is uncomfortable with too much weight in a particular sector, an index fund may not be the right choice."}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_2286", "name": "Adjusted Present Value (APV)", "short_description": "Calculates the Adjusted Present Value (APV) of a firm or project by summing the unlevered firm value with the present value of the tax shield from debt financing. APV separates a firm's value into its all-equity value and the present value of financing effects like tax shields.", "domain": "corporate_finance", "topic": "capital_structure", "topic_extension": false, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-2286", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-128", "question_id": "test-2098", "difficulty": 4.595119850134591, "level": "hard", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "b79a0472bc292748d55b702eb8b46b6e83b657fef335a91eeeec403b6e74864e", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["Adjusted Present Value", "APV", "Project Valuation", "Firm Valuation", "Tax Shield", "Debt Financing Impact"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "tax_rate_scale", "ambiguity_type": "unit_scale", "trigger_signal": "tax rate value not explicitly stated as decimal or percentage", "clarification_question": "Is the tax rate provided as a decimal (e.g., 0.28 for 28%) or a percentage (e.g., 28 for 28%)?", "options": [{"label": "Decimal (e.g., 0.28 for 28%) - DEFAULT", "value": "decimal", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Percentage (e.g., 28 for 28%)", "value": "percentage", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "The tax rate is provided as a decimal (e.g., 0.28 for 28%).", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}, {"id": "interest_rate_scale", "ambiguity_type": "unit_scale", "trigger_signal": "interest rate value not explicitly stated as decimal or percentage", "clarification_question": "Is the interest rate provided as a decimal (e.g., 0.05 for 5%) or a percentage (e.g., 5 for 5%)?", "options": [{"label": "Decimal (e.g., 0.05 for 5%) - DEFAULT", "value": "decimal", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Percentage (e.g., 5 for 5%)", "value": "percentage", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "The interest rate is provided as a decimal (e.g., 0.05 for 5%).", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}, {"id": "financing_effects_scope", "ambiguity_type": "scope_of_calculation", "trigger_signal": "APV calculation requested; article mentions 'other financing effects' beyond tax shields", "clarification_question": "Does the APV calculation need to consider only the tax shield benefit, or should other financing effects (e.g., costs of financial distress) also be included?", "options": [{"label": "Only the present value of tax shields - DEFAULT", "value": "tax_shields_only", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Includes other financing effects (not modeled by this function)", "value": "all_financing_effects", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Only the present value of tax shields is included in the calculation.", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "unlevered_firm_value", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The value of the firm if financed entirely by equity (base case NPV).", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "tax_rate", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The corporate tax rate applicable to the firm (as a decimal).", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "debt", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The total amount of debt financing used by the firm or project.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "interest_rate", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The interest rate on the debt financing (as a decimal).", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "periods", "type": "integer", "required": true, "description": "The number of years over which the tax shield applies.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "apv", "type": "number", "unit": "USD", "description": "The adjusted present value, incorporating the benefits of the tax shield."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    unlevered_firm_value = inputs['unlevered_firm_value']\n    tax_rate = inputs['tax_rate']\n    debt = inputs['debt']\n    interest_rate = inputs['interest_rate']\n    periods = inputs['periods']\n    annual_interest = debt * interest_rate\n    annual_tax_shield = annual_interest * tax_rate\n    if interest_rate == 0:\n        pv_tax_shield = annual_tax_shield * periods\n    else:\n        pv_tax_shield = annual_tax_shield * (1 - 1 / (1 + interest_rate) ** periods) / interest_rate\n    apv = unlevered_firm_value + pv_tax_shield\n    return apv", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "apv_001", "name": "Unlevered Firm Value Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['unlevered_firm_value'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["unlevered_firm_value"], "description": "The unlevered firm value must be a positive number, representing the intrinsic value of the firm."}, {"rule_id": "apv_002", "name": "Tax Rate Range", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (0 <= inputs['tax_rate'] <= 1)", "applies_to": ["tax_rate"], "description": "The tax rate must be a decimal between 0 and 1 (inclusive), representing 0% to 100%."}, {"rule_id": "apv_003", "name": "Debt Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['debt'] < 0", "applies_to": ["debt"], "description": "The amount of debt financing cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "apv_004", "name": "Interest Rate Range", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (0 <= inputs['interest_rate'] <= 1)", "applies_to": ["interest_rate"], "description": "The interest rate must be a decimal between 0 and 1 (inclusive), representing 0% to 100%."}, {"rule_id": "apv_005", "name": "Periods Positive Integer", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (isinstance(inputs['periods'], int) and inputs['periods'] > 0)", "applies_to": ["periods"], "description": "The number of periods must be a positive integer."}, {"rule_id": "apv_006", "name": "Non-Zero Interest Rate for Standard PV", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['interest_rate'] == 0", "applies_to": ["interest_rate"], "description": "An interest rate of zero can lead to an undefined present value calculation in some standard formulas. While handled in this implementation, a non-zero rate is typically expected for PV calculations."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    unlevered_firm_value = inputs['unlevered_firm_value']\n    tax_rate = inputs['tax_rate']\n    debt = inputs['debt']\n    interest_rate = inputs['interest_rate']\n    periods = inputs['periods']\n    annual_interest = debt * interest_rate\n    annual_tax_shield = annual_interest * tax_rate\n    if interest_rate == 0:\n        pv_tax_shield = annual_tax_shield * periods\n    else:\n        pv_tax_shield = annual_tax_shield * (1 - 1 / (1 + interest_rate) ** periods) / interest_rate\n    apv = unlevered_firm_value + pv_tax_shield\n    return apv"}, "article_title": "Adjusted Present Value (APV)", "article_doc_id": 4418, "article_content_excerpt": "# Adjusted Present Value (APV): Overview, Formula, and Example\n\nDefinition\n\nAdjusted present value separates a firm's value into two components: its value if financed entirely by equity, and the present value of tax shields and other financing effects.\n\nAdjusted present value (APV) is a sophisticated method for assessing a company or project's worth compared with traditional techniques. APV separates the valuation process into two components: the first treats the company as if it were financed wholly by equity, and the second takes account of its debt financing.\n\nSuppose you're thinking about buying a house. The basic value of the house comes from its location, size, condition, and so on. That's like the core value of a business: what it's worth based on its operations alone. But when you buy a house, you usually take out a mortgage, right? That mortgage changes things since you can deduct the interest from your taxes, which saves you money. Meanwhile, if you borrow too much, you might struggle with payments and risk foreclosure. These financial effects change the overall value of your house-buying decision. \n\nAPV is a way for businesses to look at their value in a similar way. It starts by figuring out what a company is worth just based on its business operations—as if it had no debt at all. Then, it adds or subtracts value based on how the company is financed. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Adjusted present value (APV) separates a firm's operational value from its financing.\n * It requires a two-step process to calculate the firm's all-equity value and then add or subtract financing impacts like tax shields and debt costs.\n * APV is best for scenarios with shifting capital structures, such as leveraged buyouts or major restructurings.\n * By isolating the effects of financing, the APV enables one to evaluate firms with intricate debt arrangements or those operating across multiple tax jurisdictions.\n * APV is a project or company's net present value (NPV) if financed solely by equity plus the present value (PV) of financing benefits.\n\nThis is important for a few reasons: \n\n 1. It helps businesses make smarter decisions about how much to take on. They can see clearly how different levels of borrowing will affect the company's value.\n 2. For investors, it gives a fuller picture of what a company is worth. They can understand how well the business is doing and how its financial choices affect its value.\n 3. In big financial deals, such as when one company buys another, it helps everyone involved understand the value being exchanged, especially if the agreement changes how much debt the company has.\n\nTo get the APV, you first calculate the base case value, which is the of the company or project as if it were financed entirely with equity. This is the fundamental value of the business operations without considering any effects of debt financing. The second part of APV accounts for the PV of all financial side effects resulting from the company or project's debt. These effects primarily include tax shields, which are the tax savings generated by the tax deductibility of interest payments on debt. \n\nHowever, it also considers the potential costs of financial distress that might arise from high levels of debt, as well as other financing-related impacts like subsidies or . \n\n### Tip: \n\nNet present value (NPV) is the difference between the PV of the cash coming in and going out of a firm in a given period. NPV is used in capital budgeting and investment planning to analyze the profitability of an investment or project.\n\n \n\nThis allows you to better understand how different capital structure choices affect the company's value. It's particularly useful when a company's is expected to change significantly over time or when complex financing is involved. \n\nAPV can provide a more nuanced approach to valuation than methods like (DCF) analysis. APV is particularly valuable in situations where a company's capital structure is expected to change signi\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_510", "name": "Kijun-Sen (Base Line)", "short_description": "Calculates the Kijun-sen (base line), a component of the Ichimoku Kinko Hyo method of technical analysis, which is the midpoint of the period's high and low prices. It helps in assessing trend direction over the specified period.", "domain": "financial_markets", "topic": "stock_market_analysis", "topic_extension": false, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-510", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-431", "question_id": "test-1747", "difficulty": 3.332204510175204, "level": "medium", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "39e80a32cb167eba28374d85f7f44ba3efca1c1210a2b0579c917b4f27f33312", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["Kijun-sen", "Base Line", "Ichimoku Cloud", "Technical Analysis", "Trend Indicator", "High-Low Midpoint", "Ichimoku Kinko Hyo"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "calculation_period", "ambiguity_type": "parameter_choice", "trigger_signal": "period value not explicitly specified or differing from common defaults", "clarification_question": "What period length should be used for the Kijun-sen calculation?", "options": [{"label": "26 periods (Standard) - DEFAULT", "value": "26", "is_default": true}, {"label": "9 periods (often used for Tenkan-sen, a shorter period)", "value": "9", "is_default": false}, {"label": "15 periods (a shorter period for closer tracking)", "value": "15", "is_default": false}, {"label": "45 periods (a longer period for broader trend view)", "value": "45", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "The standard period of 26 will be used.", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}], "inputs": [{"name": "highs", "type": "array[number]", "required": true, "description": "A list of high prices over the periods. The list should contain at least 'period' number of values from the most recent to the oldest.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "lows", "type": "array[number]", "required": true, "description": "A list of low prices over the periods. The list should contain at least 'period' number of values from the most recent to the oldest.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "period", "type": "integer", "required": false, "description": "The number of periods to consider for the Kijun-sen calculation. Defaults to 26.", "unit": "periods", "aliases": ["n_periods", "lookback_period"]}], "output": {"name": "kijun_sen", "type": "number", "unit": null, "description": "The calculated Kijun-sen (base line) value, representing the midpoint of the high and low prices over the specified period."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    highs = inputs['highs']\n    lows = inputs['lows']\n    period = inputs.get('period', 26)\n    period_high = max(highs[-period:])\n    period_low = min(lows[-period:])\n    kijun_sen = (period_high + period_low) / 2\n    return kijun_sen", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "f001", "name": "Missing highs input", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "'highs' not in inputs", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'highs' input is required for calculating the Kijun-sen."}, {"rule_id": "f002", "name": "Missing lows input", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "'lows' not in inputs", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'lows' input is required for calculating the Kijun-sen."}, {"rule_id": "f003", "name": "Invalid highs type", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not isinstance(inputs.get('highs'), list)", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'highs' input must be a list."}, {"rule_id": "f004", "name": "Invalid lows type", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not isinstance(inputs.get('lows'), list)", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'lows' input must be a list."}, {"rule_id": "e001", "name": "Period must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs.get('period', 26) <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'period' for Kijun-sen calculation must be a positive integer."}, {"rule_id": "e002", "name": "Highs and Lows list length mismatch", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "len(inputs.get('highs', [])) != len(inputs.get('lows', []))", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'highs' and 'lows' lists must have the same number of elements."}, {"rule_id": "e003", "name": "Insufficient data for period", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "len(inputs.get('highs', [])) < inputs.get('period', 26) or len(inputs.get('lows', [])) < inputs.get('period', 26)", "applies_to": [], "description": "The length of the 'highs' and 'lows' lists must be at least equal to the specified 'period'."}, {"rule_id": "e004", "name": "Non-positive prices", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "any(h <= 0 for h in inputs.get('highs', [])) or any(l <= 0 for l in inputs.get('lows', []))", "applies_to": [], "description": "High and low prices in the input lists must be positive."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    highs = inputs['highs']\n    lows = inputs['lows']\n    period = inputs.get('period', 26)\n    period_high = max(highs[-period:])\n    period_low = min(lows[-period:])\n    kijun_sen = (period_high + period_low) / 2\n    return kijun_sen"}, "article_title": "Kijun-Sen (Base Line)", "article_doc_id": 888, "article_content_excerpt": "# Kijun-Sen (Base Line): Overview, Formulas, Calculations\n\n## What Is the Kijun-Sen (Base Line)? \n\nThe Kijun-sen, or base line, is an indicator and important component of the method of technical analysis, which is also known as the Ichimoku cloud. \n\nThe Kijun-sen is the midpoint price of the last 26-periods, and therefore an indicator of short- to medium-term price . The indicator aids in assessing the trend, and can also be useful for identifying trading opportunities when combined with the other components of the Ichimoku cloud. \n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/Kijun-Sen-5c894489c9e77c0001f2ad67.png)\n\nTradingView.\n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Kijun-sen also means \"base line\" and is the mid-point of the 26-period high and low.\n * Kijun-sen is typically used in conjunction with Tenkan-sen (conversion line)—the 9-period midpoint price—to generate trade signals when they cross.\n * Kijun-sen is typically used in conjunction with the other Ichimoku indicators.\n * When the price is above Kijun-sen then short- to medium-term price momentum is up. If the price is below Kijun-sen then price momentum is down.\n\n## The Formula for the Kijun-Sen (Base Line) is \n\n﻿\\begin{aligned} &\\text{Kijun-sen (base line)}=\\frac{1}{2} \\left( \\text{26-period high}+\\text{26-period low} \\right ) \\end{aligned}﻿ \n\n### How to Calculate the Kijun-Sen (Base Line) \n\n 1. Find the highest price reached over the last 26 periods.\n 2. Find the lowest price reached over the last 26 periods.\n 3. Sum these two numbers together and then divide by two.\n\n## What Does the Kijun-Sen (Base Line) Tell You? \n\nOn its own, Kijun-sen shows the midpoint price for the last 26 periods. Similar to a , when the price is above the base line it indicates the price is above the midpoint and therefore short-term price momentum is up. This is further confirmed if the Kijun-sen line is angled upwards. \n\nWhen the price is below the base line, and especially if Kijun-sen is angled downwards, that indicates price momentum is to the downside as the price is below the 26-period midpoint. While 26-periods is typically used for this calculation, this can be altered to suit individual preference. A smaller number of periods, such as 15, will track the price more closely. A larger number of periods, such as 45, will not track the price as closely. \n\nThe Kijun-sen is nearly always used alongside the (conversion line) to help gauge direction changes in price and to generate trade signals. Tenkan-sen is the 9-period price midpoint. Since it is a short-term indicator it tracks price more closely and responds quicker to price changes. Therefore, when Tenkan-sen crosses above Kijun-sen it indicates that price momentum is picking up steam to the upside. Some traders use this as a buy signal. This is a crossover. \n\n * When Tenkan-sen crosses down through Kijun-sen it indicates the price is dropping, and some traders use this as a sell signal. This is a crossover.\n * When Tenkan-sen and Kijun-sen are intertwined or crossing back and forth that means the price is lacking a trend or moving in a fashion. Crossover signals are not as reliable during such times.\n\nWhen gauging the trend or using , the information provided should be used within the context of the entire Ichimoku cloud indicator. For example, if the price is above the \"\", a bearish crossover may still be used to sell a long position, but it likely wouldn't be used to enter a position. \n\n## The Difference Between Kijun-sen (Base Line) and a Simple Moving Average (SMA) \n\nThe Kijun-sen is a midpoint of the high and low price over the last 26-periods. This is not an average. A is an average price over a set number of periods, calculated by adding up the closing prices of those periods and then dividing the total by the number of periods. \n\nA 26-period base line and a 26-period SMA will produce different values and thus provide different information to the trader. \n\n## The Limitations of Using Kijun-sen (Base Line) \n\nUnless there's a lot of recent price mov\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_571", "name": "Fixed Asset Turnover Ratio", "short_description": "Calculate the Fixed Asset Turnover (FAT) ratio, measuring a company's ability to generate net sales from its fixed asset investments. It is calculated by dividing net sales by the average balance of fixed assets over a period.", "domain": "financial_ratios", "topic": "effratio", "topic_extension": false, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-571", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-955", "question_id": "test-1028", "difficulty": 2.4849066497880004, "level": "medium", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "8d28424ad362d01e5539f4f8407e203aece2c75922b7fe0b63ce12a7cfbf97bf", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["fixed asset turnover", "FAT ratio", "efficiency ratio", "asset utilization", "sales generation from assets", "capital intensity"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "output_scale", "ambiguity_type": "unit_scale", "trigger_signal": "output is a ratio, user might expect percentage", "clarification_question": "Should the Fixed Asset Turnover ratio be expressed as a decimal (e.g., 2.27) or a percentage (e.g., 227%)?", "options": [{"label": "Decimal — DEFAULT", "value": "decimal", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Percentage", "value": "percent", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "result * 100.0", "max_expr_nodes": 6, "invariant": "result_new == result_old * 100.0", "affected_inputs": []}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Decimal", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "net_sales", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The net sales amount, calculated as gross sales minus returns and allowances.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "beginning_fixed_assets", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The balance of fixed assets at the beginning of the period.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "ending_fixed_assets", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The balance of fixed assets at the end of the period.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "fixed_asset_turnover_ratio", "type": "number", "unit": null, "description": "The calculated Fixed Asset Turnover ratio."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    net_sales = inputs['net_sales']\n    beginning_fixed_assets = inputs['beginning_fixed_assets']\n    ending_fixed_assets = inputs['ending_fixed_assets']\n    average_fixed_assets = (beginning_fixed_assets + ending_fixed_assets) / 2\n    fixed_asset_turnover_ratio = net_sales / average_fixed_assets\n    return fixed_asset_turnover_ratio", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "net_sales_non_negative", "name": "Net Sales must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['net_sales'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Net sales cannot be negative. Please provide a non-negative value."}, {"rule_id": "beginning_fixed_assets_non_negative", "name": "Beginning Fixed Assets must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['beginning_fixed_assets'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Beginning fixed assets cannot be negative. Please provide a non-negative value."}, {"rule_id": "ending_fixed_assets_non_negative", "name": "Ending Fixed Assets must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['ending_fixed_assets'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Ending fixed assets cannot be negative. Please provide a non-negative value."}, {"rule_id": "average_fixed_assets_not_zero", "name": "Average Fixed Assets must be non-zero", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "(inputs['beginning_fixed_assets'] + inputs['ending_fixed_assets']) == 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The average fixed assets, calculated as the sum of beginning and ending fixed assets divided by two, cannot be zero, as it would lead to division by zero in the ratio calculation."}, {"rule_id": "fat_ratio_plausibility_upper_bound", "name": "Fixed Asset Turnover Ratio plausibility check (upper bound)", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "compute(inputs) > 10.0", "applies_to": [], "description": "An extremely high Fixed Asset Turnover Ratio (e.g., >10) might indicate data entry errors or that the company operates in an exceptionally capital-light manner, making this ratio less informative for comparison with capital-intensive industries. Consider if inputs are correct or if a different metric is more suitable."}, {"rule_id": "fat_ratio_plausibility_lower_bound", "name": "Fixed Asset Turnover Ratio plausibility check (lower bound)", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "compute(inputs) < 0.1 and inputs['net_sales'] > 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "A very low Fixed Asset Turnover Ratio (e.g., <0.1) suggests inefficient asset utilization or potentially idle assets, assuming positive net sales. Verify the input figures for accuracy."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    net_sales = inputs['net_sales']\n    beginning_fixed_assets = inputs['beginning_fixed_assets']\n    ending_fixed_assets = inputs['ending_fixed_assets']\n    average_fixed_assets = (beginning_fixed_assets + ending_fixed_assets) / 2\n    fixed_asset_turnover_ratio = net_sales / average_fixed_assets\n    return fixed_asset_turnover_ratio"}, "article_title": "Fixed Asset Turnover Ratio", "article_doc_id": 1046, "article_content_excerpt": "# What Is the Fixed Asset Turnover Ratio?\n\nDefinition\n\nThe Fixed Asset Turnover Ratio (FAT) is found by dividing net sales by the average balance of fixed assets.\n\n \n\n## What Is the Fixed Asset Turnover Ratio? \n\nThe fixed asset (FAT) measures operating performance. This ratio compares net sales displayed on the income statement to fixed assets on the balance sheet. \n\nFAT measures a company's ability to generate net sales from its fixed-asset investments, namely (PP&E). A higher fixed asset turnover ratio indicates that a company has effectively used investments in fixed assets to generate sales. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * The fixed asset turnover ratio reveals how efficiently a company generates sales from its existing fixed assets.\n * FAT is calculated by dividing net sales by the average balance in fixed assets.\n * A higher ratio means management is using its fixed assets more effectively.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/TermDefinitions_Fixed_Asset_Turnover_Ratio_-d269a3bf50b040dcb50552ac0ac79e4f.jpg)\n\nInvestopedia / Crea Taylor\n\n## Fixed Asset Turnover Ratio Formula \n\n \n\n\\begin{aligned}&\\text{FAT}=\\frac{\\text{Net Sales}}{\\text{Average Fixed Assets}}\\\\\\&\\textbf{where:}\\\\\\&\\text{Net Sales}=\\text{Gross sales}-\\text{Returns and allowances}\\\\\\&\\text{Average Fixed Assets}=\\frac{\\text{Beginning Fixed Assets}+\\text{Ending Fixed Assets}}{2}\\end{aligned}\n\nThe ratio is commonly used as a metric in industries that make substantial purchases of PP&E to increase output. Investors monitor this ratio in subsequent years to see if the company's new fixed assets reward it with increased sales.\n\nInvestments in fixed assets tend to represent the largest component of a company’s total assets. The FAT ratio, calculated annually, is constructed to reflect how efficiently a company uses these substantial assets to generate revenue for the firm. \n\n### Important: \n\nThe fixed asset balance is used as a net of accumulated .\n\n## Interpreting FAT \n\nA higher turnover ratio indicates greater efficiency in managing fixed-asset investments. Analysts and investors often compare a company’s most recent ratio to historical ratios, ratio values from peer companies, or average ratios for the company's industry. \n\nFixed assets vary drastically from one company type to the next. A technology company like Meta has a significantly smaller fixed asset base than a manufacturing giant like Caterpillar. In this example, Caterpillar’s fixed asset turnover ratio is more relevant and should hold more weight for analysts than Meta’s FAT ratio. \n\n## Fixed Asset Turnover Ratio vs. Asset Turnover Ratio \n\nThe asset turnover ratio uses total assets instead of focusing only on fixed assets. Using total assets reflects management’s decisions on all and other assets. \n\nA company's asset turnover ratio will be smaller than its fixed asset turnover ratio because the denominator in the equation is larger while the numerator stays the same. It also makes conceptual sense that there is a wider gap between the amount of sales and total assets compared to the amount of sales and a subset of assets. \n\nManufacturing companies often favor the FAT ratio over the asset turnover ratio to determine how well capital investments perform. Companies with fewer fixed assets such as retailers may be less interested in the FAT compared to how other assets such as inventory are utilized. \n\n## Limitations of the FAT \n\nCompanies with cyclical sales may have low ratios in slow periods, so the ratio should be analyzed over several periods. Additionally, management may outsource production to reduce reliance on assets and improve its FAT ratio, while still struggling to maintain stable cash flows and other business fundamentals. \n\nCompanies with strong ratios may review all aspects that generate solid profits or healthy cash flow. FAT only looks at net sales and fixed assets; company-wide expenses are not factored into the equation. In addition, there may be differences in the cash flow between when net sal\n...[truncated]"}
