id interest added to current principal (negative amortization) - DEFAULT", "value": "negative_amortization", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Retroactively applied to original balance if not paid off (credit card style)", "value": "retroactive_original_balance", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "hard", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Unpaid interest is added to the current principal (negative amortization style).", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "initial_balance", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The original balance of the loan.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "min_payment", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The minimum payment made each month.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "interest_rate", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The annual interest rate as a decimal (e.g., 0.072 for 7.2%).", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "num_months", "type": "integer", "required": true, "description": "The number of months after which the balance is evaluated.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "updated_balance", "type": "number", "unit": null, "description": "The updated loan balance after considering deferred interest."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    initial_balance = inputs['initial_balance']\n    min_payment = inputs['min_payment']\n    interest_rate = inputs['interest_rate']\n    num_months = inputs['num_months']\n    monthly_interest_rate = interest_rate / 12\n    updated_balance = initial_balance\n    for _ in range(num_months):\n        interest_for_month = updated_balance * monthly_interest_rate\n        deferred_interest = interest_for_month - min_payment\n        updated_balance += deferred_interest\n    return updated_balance", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "input_type_check", "name": "Input Type Validation", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('initial_balance'), (float, int)) and isinstance(inputs.get('min_payment'), (float, int)) and isinstance(inputs.get('interest_rate'), (float, int)) and isinstance(inputs.get('num_months'), int)", "applies_to": ["initial_balance", "min_payment", "interest_rate", "num_months"], "description": "Ensures all inputs are of the correct numeric type."}, {"rule_id": "initial_balance_positive", "name": "Initial Balance Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "inputs['initial_balance'] > 0", "applies_to": ["initial_balance"], "description": "The initial loan balance must be a positive value."}, {"rule_id": "min_payment_non_negative", "name": "Minimum Payment Must Be Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "inputs['min_payment'] >= 0", "applies_to": ["min_payment"], "description": "The minimum payment cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "interest_rate_bounds", "name": "Annual Interest Rate Plausibility", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "0 <= inputs['interest_rate'] <= 1.0", "applies_to": ["interest_rate"], "description": "The annual interest rate, as a decimal, must be between 0 and 1 (inclusive)."}, {"rule_id": "num_months_positive_integer", "name": "Number of Months Must Be Positive Integer", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "inputs['num_months'] > 0", "applies_to": ["num_months"], "description": "The number of months for evaluation must be a positive integer."}, {"rule_id": "deferred_interest_scenario_check", "name": "Minimum Payment Adequacy for Deferred Interest", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['min_payment'] >= inputs['initial_balance'] * (inputs['interest_rate'] / 12)", "applies_to": ["initial_balance", "min_payment", "interest_rate"], "description": "If the minimum payment covers or exceeds the monthly interest accrual, then no interest is effectively 'deferred' and added to the principal. The loan balance would decrease or stay flat, which may not align with the typical deferred interest scenario implied by the function name."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    initial_balance = inputs['initial_balance']\n    min_payment = inputs['min_payment']\n    interest_rate = inputs['interest_rate']\n    num_months = inputs['num_months']\n    monthly_interest_rate = interest_rate / 12\n    updated_balance = initial_balance\n    for _ in range(num_months):\n        interest_for_month = updated_balance * monthly_interest_rate\n        deferred_interest = interest_for_month - min_payment\n        updated_balance += deferred_interest\n    return updated_balance"}, "article_title": "Deferred Interest", "article_doc_id": 3227, "article_content_excerpt": "# Deferred Interest: Definition, How It Works, Examples\n\n## What Is Deferred Interest? \n\nDeferred interest is when payments are deferred on a loan during a specific period of time. You will not pay any interest as long as your entire balance on the loan is paid off before this period ends. If you do not pay off the loan balance before this period ends, then interest charges start accruing. \n\nDeferred interest options are also available on mortgages, known as a deferred interest mortgage or a . \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * A deferred interest loan postpones interest payments till after a certain period of time.\n * If the loan is not paid off by the specified time, interest starts accruing.\n * The interest paid can sometimes be backdated to the entire loan balance and include high-interest rates.\n * Deferred interest loans are typically found on credit cards or offered by retailers.\n * Mortgages can also include deferred interest options, in which the unpaid interest is added to the principal balance of the loan, also known as negative amortization.\n * Generally, deferred interest loans are not considered a financially prudent means of financing.\n\n## Understanding Deferred Interest \n\nDeferred interest options are usually provided by retailers on big-ticket items, such as furniture and home appliances. It makes it easier and more attractive for a consumer to buy these items than if they had to pay upfront in full or take out a loan with interest, increasing the cost of the purchase. \n\nDeferred interest options usually last for a specific period of time where no interest is charged. Once this period is over and if the loan balance has not been paid, then interest charges start accruing, sometimes at very high rates. It's important for a consumer to be aware of the deferred interest period as well as any fine print laying out the terms of the offer. They should also, of course, ensure that they can pay off the loan before the interest-free period is over. Retailers offer deferred interest or \"no interest\" items through their retail credit card or other options. \n\nDeferred interest loans can also be offered on credit cards. Typically as a marketing scheme to lure in consumers to sign up for a card, credit card companies offer deferred interest or no interest credit cards. These credit cards work in the same way as a deferred interest loan with a retailer, in that they offer no interest charges on the balance of the credit card for a specific period of time. Once that period is over, interest starts being charged on the remaining balance or any balance going forward. If you're considering switching from your current card to one with with a deferred interest rate (or no interest rate), make sure it's one of the best balance transfer cards currently available. \n\nTypically, on deferred interest loans, if the balance is not fully paid off before the period ends, interest is backdated and charged on the entire, original balance, regardless of how much of the balance is left. \n\nMortgages that include deferred interest features work in a slightly different way. The amount of interest that is not paid on a mortgage's monthly payment is then added to the principal balance of the loan. When a loan's principal balance increases because of deferred interest, it is known as . For example, , a type of adjustable-rate mortgage, and fixed-rate mortgages with a deferrable interest feature, carry the risk of the monthly payments increasing substantially at some point over the term of the mortgage. \n\n## Deferred Interest on Mortgages \n\nBefore the mortgage crisis of 2008, programs such as payment option ARMs had low introductory payments for the first 2-3 years, which payments increased significantly afterwards. Mortgagors could choose a 30-year or 15-year payment, an covering interest but not reducing the principal balance, or a that wouldn't even cover the interest due. The difference between the minimum payment and the interest due was the deferred intere\n...[truncated]"}
