es_to": [], "description": "The list of 'cash_flows' cannot be empty; at least one cash flow must be provided."}, {"rule_id": "cf_003", "name": "Each cash flow must be a number", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "all(isinstance(cf, (int, float)) for cf in inputs['cash_flows'])", "applies_to": [], "description": "Each item in the 'cash_flows' list must be a numerical value."}, {"rule_id": "dr_001", "name": "Discount rate must be a number", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['discount_rate'], (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'discount_rate' must be a numerical value."}, {"rule_id": "dr_002", "name": "Discount rate must be greater than -1", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['discount_rate'] <= -1", "applies_to": [], "description": "The discount rate must be greater than -1. A rate of -1 or less would imply infinite or negative present value, which is typically not financially meaningful in this context."}, {"rule_id": "dcf_001", "name": "Discounted value is positive if all cash flows are positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "all(cf > 0 for cf in inputs['cash_flows']) and compute(inputs) <= 0", "applies_to": ["cash_flows", "discount_rate"], "description": "If all provided cash flows are positive, the calculated discounted cash flow (present value) is expected to be positive. A non-positive result may indicate an issue with inputs or assumptions."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    cash_flows = inputs['cash_flows']\n    discount_rate = inputs['discount_rate']\n    if discount_rate <= -1:\n        raise ValueError('Discount rate must be greater than -1.')\n    discounted_value = sum((cf / (1 + discount_rate) ** (i + 1) for i, cf in enumerate(cash_flows)))\n    return round(discounted_value)"}, "article_title": "Valuation", "article_doc_id": 354, "article_content_excerpt": "# What Is Valuation? How It Works and Methods Used\n\nDefinition\n\nValuation is the analytical process of determining the current (or projected) worth of an asset or a company.\n\n## What Is Valuation? \n\nValuation is the analytical process of determining the current or projected worth of an asset or company. Many techniques are used for doing a valuation. Among other metrics, an analyst placing a value on a company looks at the business's management, the composition of its , the prospect of future earnings, and the of its assets. \n\n is often employed in valuation although several other methods may be employed such as the (CAPM) or the (DDM). \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Valuation is a quantitative process of determining the fair value of an asset, investment, or firm.\n * A company can generally be valued on its own on an absolute basis or a relative basis compared to other similar companies or assets.\n * Several methods and techniques can be used to arrive at a valuation, each of which may produce a different value.\n * Valuations can be quickly impacted by corporate earnings or economic events that force analysts to retool their valuation models.\n * Valuation is quantitative in nature but it often involves some degree of subjective input or assumptions.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/valuation.asp-final-4ef03f976ffd45c681a5fe107a5e6e93.png)\n\nInvestopedia / Mira Norian\n\n## Understanding Valuation \n\nA valuation can be useful when you're trying to determine the of a security determined by what a buyer is willing to pay a seller assuming that both parties enter the transaction willingly. Buyers and sellers determine the of a stock or bond when a security trades on an exchange. \n\nThe concept of refers to the perceived value of a security based on future earnings or some other company attribute. It's unrelated to the market price of a security and this is where valuation comes into play. Analysts do a valuation to determine whether a company or asset is by the market. \n\n## Types of Valuation Models \n\n * **Absolute valuation models** attempt to find the intrinsic or \"true\" value of an investment based only on fundamentals. You would focus only on things such as dividends, cash flow, and the growth rate for a single company. You wouldn't worry about any other companies. Valuation models that fall into this category include the dividend discount model, discounted cash flow model, residual income model, and asset-based model.\n * ** models **operate by comparing the company in question to other similar companies. These methods involve calculating multiples and ratios such as the price-to-earnings multiple and comparing them to the multiples of similar companies.\n\nThe original company might be considered undervalued if the P/E is lower than the P/E multiple of a comparable company. The relative valuation model is typically a lot easier and quicker to calculate than the absolute model. This is why many investors and analysts begin their analysis with this model. \n\n## Types of Valuation Methods \n\nYou can do a valuation in various ways. \n\n### Comparables Method \n\nThe looks at companies that are in size and industry and how they trade to determine a fair value for a company or asset. The past transaction method looks at past transactions of similar companies to determine an appropriate value. There's also the asset-based valuation method which adds up all the company's asset values to get the intrinsic value assuming that they were sold at fair market value. \n\n### Fast Fact: \n\nA comparables approach is often synonymous with in investments.\n\nSometimes doing all these and then weighing each is appropriate to calculate intrinsic value but some methods are more appropriate for certain industries. You wouldn't use an asset-based valuation approach to valuing a consulting company that has few assets. An earnings-based approach like the DCF would be more appropriate. \n\n### Discounted Cash Flow Method \n\nAnalysts also place a value on an asset or investmen\n...[truncated]"}
