puts['total_assets']\n    adjusted_net_income = net_income + interest_expense * (1 - tax_rate)\n    adjusted_roa = adjusted_net_income / total_assets * 100\n    return adjusted_roa", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "dc001", "name": "Total Assets Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['total_assets'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["total_assets"], "description": "Total assets must be a positive value to ensure a meaningful ROA calculation."}, {"rule_id": "dc002", "name": "Tax Rate Must Be Between 0 and 1", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (0 <= inputs['tax_rate'] <= 1)", "applies_to": ["tax_rate"], "description": "The tax rate must be a decimal value between 0 and 1 (inclusive)."}, {"rule_id": "dc003", "name": "Net Income Plausibility", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['net_income'] < -10000000000", "applies_to": ["net_income"], "description": "Extremely large negative net income values may indicate data entry errors or unusual financial circumstances."}, {"rule_id": "dc004", "name": "Interest Expense Plausibility", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['interest_expense'] < 0", "applies_to": ["interest_expense"], "description": "Negative interest expense suggests interest income, which might require a different treatment or clarification."}, {"rule_id": "dc005", "name": "Adjusted ROA Plausibility", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "compute(inputs) < -100.0 or compute(inputs) > 1000.0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Adjusted ROA values typically fall within a reasonable range; extreme values may indicate input errors or exceptional performance."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    net_income = inputs['net_income']\n    interest_expense = inputs['interest_expense']\n    tax_rate = inputs['tax_rate']\n    total_assets = inputs['total_assets']\n    adjusted_net_income = net_income + interest_expense * (1 - tax_rate)\n    adjusted_roa = adjusted_net_income / total_assets * 100\n    return adjusted_roa"}, "article_title": "Return on Assets (ROA)", "article_doc_id": 3027, "article_content_excerpt": "# Return on Assets (ROA) Ratio: Formula and \"Good\" ROA Defined\n\n## What Is the Return on Assets (ROA) Ratio? \n\nReturn on assets (ROA) is a financial ratio that indicates how profitable a company is relative to its total . Corporate management, analysts, and investors can use the return on assets ratio to determine how efficiently a company uses its resources to generate a profit. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Return on assets (ROA) is a ratio that indicates a company’s profitability relative to its total assets.\n * ROA can be used by management, analysts, and investors to determine whether a company uses its assets efficiently to generate a profit.\n * You can calculate a company’s ROA by dividing its net income by its total assets.\n * It’s always best to compare the ROA of companies within the same industry because they share the same asset base.\n * ROA factors in a company’s debt. Return on equity does not.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/returnonassets-c50f81631ab546988626b29279e956b9.jpg)\n\nTheresa Chiechi / Investopedia\n\n## Understanding Return on Assets (ROA) Ratio \n\nThe return on assets ratio is commonly expressed as a percentage using a company’s net income and average assets. A higher ROA means a company is more efficient and productive at managing its balance sheet to generate profits. A lower ROA indicates there's room for improvement. \n\nBusinesses are about . Comparing profits to revenue is a useful operational metric but comparing them to the resources a company used to earn them displays the feasibility of that company’s existence. Return on assets is the simplest of these corporate bang-for-the-buck measures. It reveals what earnings are generated from or assets. \n\nROA for can vary substantially and are highly dependent on the industry in which they function. The ROA for a tech company won’t necessarily correspond to that of a food and beverage company. It's best to compare a company's ROA against its previous ROA numbers or a similar company’s ROA when using it as a comparative measure. \n\nThe ROA figure gives investors an idea of how effective the company is in converting the money it invests into . The higher the ROA number, the better because the company can earn more money with a smaller investment. A higher ROA means more asset efficiency. \n\nA similar valuation concept is a which uses the average value of assets instead of the current value of the item. Financial institutions often use ROAA to gauge financial performance. \n\n## Return on Assets Ratio: Formula and Calculation \n\nThe return on assets ratio is by dividing a company’s net income by its total assets. It’s expressed as a formula like this:\n\n> Return\\ on\\ Assets = \\frac{Net\\ Income}{Total\\ Assets}\n\nLet's say that Sam and Milan both start hot dog stands. Sam spends $1,500 on a bare-bones metal cart. Milan spends $15,000 on a zombie apocalypse-themed unit, complete with costume.\n\nLet’s assume that those were the only assets each firm deployed. Milan would have the more valuable business but Sam would have the more efficient one if Sam earned $150 and Milan earned $1,200 over a given period. Sam’s simplified ROA is $150 ÷ $1,500 = 10% using the above formula. Milan’s simplified ROA is $1,200 ÷ $15,000 = 8%. \n\n## Special Considerations \n\nTotal assets are also the sum of its total liabilities and because of the balance sheet . Both types of financing are used to fund a company’s operations. A company’s assets are either funded by debt or equity so some analysts and investors disregard the cost of acquiring the asset by adding back in the formula for ROA. \n\nThe impact of taking more debt is negated by adding back the cost of borrowing to the net income and using the average assets in a given period as the denominator. Interest expense is added because the net income amount on the excludes interest expense. \n\n### Tip: \n\nROA shouldn’t be the only determining factor when it comes to making your investment decisions. It’s just one of the many metrics available to\n...[truncated]"}
