required": true, "description": "Total cash collected from customers.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "cash_paid_to_suppliers", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "Cash paid to vendors and suppliers.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "cash_paid_for_operating_expenses", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "Total cash paid for operating expenses like salaries.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "cash_paid_for_interest", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "Total cash paid for interest.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "cash_paid_for_taxes", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "Total cash paid for income taxes.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "other_cash_payments", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "Other assorted cash payments made during the operating period.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "cash_flow_direct", "type": "number", "unit": null, "description": "The calculated cash flow from operating activities."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    cash_collected_from_customers = inputs['cash_collected_from_customers']\n    cash_paid_to_suppliers = inputs['cash_paid_to_suppliers']\n    cash_paid_for_operating_expenses = inputs['cash_paid_for_operating_expenses']\n    cash_paid_for_interest = inputs['cash_paid_for_interest']\n    cash_paid_for_taxes = inputs['cash_paid_for_taxes']\n    other_cash_payments = inputs['other_cash_payments']\n    cash_outflows = cash_paid_to_suppliers + cash_paid_for_operating_expenses + cash_paid_for_interest + cash_paid_for_taxes + other_cash_payments\n    cash_flow_direct = cash_collected_from_customers - cash_outflows\n    return cash_flow_direct", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "input_type_cash_collected_from_customers", "name": "Cash Collected from Customers Type Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('cash_collected_from_customers'), (int, float))", "applies_to": ["cash_collected_from_customers"], "description": "Ensures 'cash_collected_from_customers' is a valid number (integer or float)."}, {"rule_id": "input_type_cash_paid_to_suppliers", "name": "Cash Paid to Suppliers Type Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('cash_paid_to_suppliers'), (int, float))", "applies_to": ["cash_paid_to_suppliers"], "description": "Ensures 'cash_paid_to_suppliers' is a valid number (integer or float)."}, {"rule_id": "input_type_cash_paid_for_operating_expenses", "name": "Cash Paid for Operating Expenses Type Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('cash_paid_for_operating_expenses'), (int, float))", "applies_to": ["cash_paid_for_operating_expenses"], "description": "Ensures 'cash_paid_for_operating_expenses' is a valid number (integer or float)."}, {"rule_id": "input_type_cash_paid_for_interest", "name": "Cash Paid for Interest Type Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('cash_paid_for_interest'), (int, float))", "applies_to": ["cash_paid_for_interest"], "description": "Ensures 'cash_paid_for_interest' is a valid number (integer or float)."}, {"rule_id": "input_type_cash_paid_for_taxes", "name": "Cash Paid for Taxes Type Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('cash_paid_for_taxes'), (int, float))", "applies_to": ["cash_paid_for_taxes"], "description": "Ensures 'cash_paid_for_taxes' is a valid number (integer or float)."}, {"rule_id": "input_type_other_cash_payments", "name": "Other Cash Payments Type Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('other_cash_payments'), (int, float))", "applies_to": ["other_cash_payments"], "description": "Ensures 'other_cash_payments' is a valid number (integer or float)."}, {"rule_id": "non_negative_cash_flow_inputs", "name": "Non-Negative Cash Flow Input Values Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "any(inputs.get(k, 0) < 0 for k in ['cash_collected_from_customers', 'cash_paid_to_suppliers', 'cash_paid_for_operating_expenses', 'cash_paid_for_interest', 'cash_paid_for_taxes', 'other_cash_payments'])", "applies_to": ["cash_collected_from_customers", "cash_paid_to_suppliers", "cash_paid_for_operating_expenses", "cash_paid_for_interest", "cash_paid_for_taxes", "other_cash_payments"], "description": "Ensures all specified cash flow input values are non-negative, as they represent absolute amounts paid or collected."}, {"rule_id": "negative_cfo_alert", "name": "Negative Cash Flow from Operations Alert", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "compute(inputs) < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Alerts if the calculated Cash Flow from Operating Activities (CFO) is negative, which may indicate operational challenges."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    cash_collected_from_customers = inputs['cash_collected_from_customers']\n    cash_paid_to_suppliers = inputs['cash_paid_to_suppliers']\n    cash_paid_for_operating_expenses = inputs['cash_paid_for_operating_expenses']\n    cash_paid_for_interest = inputs['cash_paid_for_interest']\n    cash_paid_for_taxes = inputs['cash_paid_for_taxes']\n    other_cash_payments = inputs['other_cash_payments']\n    cash_outflows = cash_paid_to_suppliers + cash_paid_for_operating_expenses + cash_paid_for_interest + cash_paid_for_taxes + other_cash_payments\n    cash_flow_direct = cash_collected_from_customers - cash_outflows\n    return cash_flow_direct"}, "article_title": "Cash Flow from Operating Activities (CFO)", "article_doc_id": 104, "article_content_excerpt": "# Cash Flow From Operating Activities (CFO) Defined, With Formulas\n\n## What Is Cash Flow From Operating Activities (CFO)? \n\nCash flow from operating activities (CFO) indicates the amount of money a company brings in from its ongoing, regular business activities, such as manufacturing and selling goods or providing a service to customers. It is the first section depicted on a company's . \n\nCash flow from operating activities does not include long-term or investment revenue and expense. CFO focuses only on the core business, and is also known as operating cash flow (OCF) or net cash from operating activities. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Cash flow from operating activities is an important benchmark to determine the financial success of a company's core business activities.\n * Cash flow from operating activities is the first section depicted on a cash flow statement, which also includes cash from investing and financing activities. \n * There are two methods for depicting cash from operating activities on a cash flow statement: the indirect method and the direct method.\n * The indirect method begins with net income from the income statement then adds back noncash items to arrive at a cash basis figure.\n * The direct method tracks all transactions in a period on a cash basis and uses actual cash inflows and outflows on the cash flow statement.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/terms_c_cash-flow-from-operating-activities_FINAL-e4025a9df8de40059fc1b585394c4b8b.jpg)\n\nInvestopedia / Daniel Fishel\n\n## Understanding Cash Flow From Operating Activities (CFO) \n\n forms one of the most important parts of business operations and accounts for the total amount of money being transferred into and out of a business. Since it affects the company's , it has significance for multiple reasons. It allows business owners and operators check where the money is coming from and going to, it helps them take steps to generate and maintain sufficient cash necessary for operational efficiency and other necessary needs, and it helps in making key and efficient financing decisions. \n\nThe details about the cash flow of a company are available in its cash flow statement, which is part of a company's quarterly and . The cash flow from operating activities depicts the cash-generating abilities of a company's core business activities. It typically includes from the and adjustments to modify net income from an basis to a basis. \n\nCash availability allows a business the option to expand, build and launch new products, shares to affirm their strong financial position, pay out to reward and bolster shareholder confidence, or reduce debt to save on interest payments. Investors attempt to look for companies whose share prices are lower and cash flow from operations is showing an upward trend over recent quarters. The disparity indicates that the company has increasing levels of cash flow which, if better utilized, can lead to higher share prices in near future. \n\nPositive (and increasing) cash flow from operating activities indicates that the core business activities of the company are thriving. It provides as additional measure/indicator of profitability potential of a company, in addition to the traditional ones like net income or . \n\n## Cash Flow Statement \n\nThe cash flow statement is one of the three main required in standard financial reporting- in addition to the income statement and . The cash flow statement is divided into three sections—cash flow from operating activities, , and . Collectively, all three sections provide a picture of where the company's cash comes from, how it is spent, and the net change in cash resulting from the firm's activities during a given accounting period. \n\nThe cash flow from investing section shows the cash used to purchase fixed and long-term assets, such as , as well as any proceeds from the sale of these assets. The cash flow from financing section shows the source of a company's financing and as well as its servicing and payments on\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_2817", "name": "Excess Return", "short_description": "Calculate Jensen's Alpha for a portfolio or investment. Jensen's Alpha measures the return of an investment beyond the return expected given its risk as per the Capital Asset Pricing Model (CAPM).", "domain": "investment_analysis", "topic": "portfolio_performance", "topic_extension": true, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-2817", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-585", "question_id": "test-1424", "difficulty": 2.772588722239781, "level": "medium", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "5cd06ed02aa326396a69f2ef02b1d58c7971212eb0a2bc6e3166311840875542", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["Jensen's Alpha", "alpha", "risk-adjusted return", "CAPM", "excess return", "portfolio performance", "investment analysis"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "output_scale", "ambiguity_type": "unit_scale", "trigger_signal": "output result is a rate or return, user might expect percentage or decimal", "clarification_question": "Should the calculated Jensen's Alpha be expressed as a decimal (e.g., 0.006) or a percentage (e.g., 0.6%)?", "options": [{"label": "Percentage (e.g., 0.6%) \n DEFAULT", "value": "percent", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Decimal (e.g., 0.006)", "value": "decimal", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "result / 100.0", "max_expr_nodes": 6, "invariant": "result_new == result_old / 100.0", "affected_inputs": []}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Percentage (e.g., 0.6%)", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}, {"id": "benchmark_choice", "ambiguity_type": "input_binding", "trigger_signal": "benchmark or market return source not explicitly specified", "clarification_question": "Which benchmark is being used for 'market_return'? Is it a broad market index (e.g., S&P 500) or a more specific comparable benchmark?", "options": [{"label": "Broad market index as provided \n DEFAULT", "value": "as_given", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Specific comparable benchmark", "value": "alternative_benchmark", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Market return is based on a broad market index, as commonly used for CAPM.", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}, {"id": "risk_free_rate_source", "ambiguity_type": "input_binding", "trigger_signal": "source or maturity of risk-free rate not specified", "clarification_question": "What is the source or maturity of the risk-free rate? Is it a short-term T-bill, a longer-term Treasury, or another low-risk instrument?", "options": [{"label": "Treasury yield matching investment horizon \n DEFAULT", "value": "treasury_matching_horizon", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Short-term T-bill rate", "value": "short_term_t_bill", "is_default": false}, {"label": "Other specified low-risk rate", "value": "other_low_risk_rate", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "The risk-free rate represents the yield of a Treasury instrument with a maturity comparable to the investment horizon.", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}], "inputs": [{"name": "realized_return", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The actual return of the portfolio or investment.", "unit": "%", "aliases": []}, {"name": "risk_free_rate", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The risk-free rate of return.", "unit": "%", "aliases": []}, {"name": "beta", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The beta value of the portfolio with respect to the market.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "market_return", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The return of the market index.", "unit": "%", "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "jensens_alpha", "type": "number", "unit": "%", "description": "The calculated Jensen's Alpha value."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    realized_return = inputs['realized_return']\n    risk_free_rate = inputs['risk_free_rate']\n    beta = inputs['beta']\n    market_return = inputs['market_return']\n    expected_return_based_on_risk = risk_free_rate + beta * (market_return - risk_free_rate)\n    jensens_alpha = realized_return - expected_return_based_on_risk\n    return round(jensens_alpha, 2)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "rate_non_negative", "name": "All rates must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['realized_return'] < 0 or inputs['risk_free_rate'] < 0 or inputs['market_return'] < 0", "applies_to": ["realized_return", "risk_free_rate", "market_return"], "description": "Realized return, risk-free rate, and market return are typically expected to be non-negative values for a meaningful calculation in this context."}, {"rule_id": "beta_non_negative", "name": "Beta must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['beta'] < 0", "applies_to": ["beta"], "description": "Beta values are typically non-negative, representing the directional sensitivity of an asset to market movements. Negative beta assets are rare and typically imply special circumstances."}, {"rule_id": "risk_free_less_than_market", "name": "Risk-free rate should generally be less than market return", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['risk_free_rate'] > inputs['market_return']", "applies_to": ["risk_free_rate", "market_return"], "description": "For the Capital Asset Pricing Model (CAPM) to hold true, the market risk premium (market_return - risk_free_rate) is typically positive. A negative premium would imply an irrational market or an unusual economic environment."}, {"rule_id": "beta_plausibility", "name": "Beta value is outside typical range", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['beta'] < 0.0 or inputs['beta'] > 2.0", "applies_to": ["beta"], "description": "While beta can theoretically be any value, most common investments have betas between 0 (risk-free) and 2 (twice as volatile as market). Values outside this range may indicate highly unusual assets or data entry errors."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    realized_return = inputs['realized_return']\n    risk_free_rate = inputs['risk_free_rate']\n    beta = inputs['beta']\n    market_return = inputs['market_return']\n    expected_return_based_on_risk = risk_free_rate + beta * (market_return - risk_free_rate)\n    jensens_alpha = realized_return - expected_return_based_on_risk\n    return round(jensens_alpha, 2)"}, "article_title": "Excess Return", "article_doc_id": 5659, "article_content_excerpt": "# Excess Returns Meaning, Risk, and Formulas\n\n## What Are Excess Returns? \n\nExcess returns are returns achieved above and beyond the return of a proxy. Excess returns will depend on a designated comparison for analysis. Some of the most basic return comparisons include a riskless rate and benchmarks with similar levels of risk to the investment being analyzed. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Excess returns are returns achieved above and beyond the return of a proxy.\n * Excess returns will depend on a designated investment return comparison for analysis.\n * The riskless rate and benchmarks with similar levels of risk to the investment being analyzed are commonly used in calculating excess return.\n * Alpha is a type of excess return metric that focuses on performance return in excess of a closely comparable benchmark.\n * Excess return is an important consideration when using modern portfolio theory which seeks to invest with an optimized portfolio. \n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/ExcessReturnsFinal2-8265b37153224aa8818d77fc6f8a5200.jpg)\n\nInvestopedia / Matthew Collins\n\n## Understanding Excess Returns \n\nExcess returns are an important metric that helps an investor to gauge performance in comparison to other investment alternatives. In general, all investors hope for positive excess return because it provides an investor with more money than they could have achieved by investing elsewhere. \n\nExcess return is identified by subtracting the return of one investment from the total return percentage achieved in another investment. When calculating excess return, multiple return measures can be used. Some investors may wish to see excess return as the difference in their investment over a risk-free rate. \n\nOther times, an excess return may be calculated in comparison to a closely comparable benchmark with similar risk and return characteristics. Using closely comparable benchmarks is a return calculation that results in an excess return measure known as alpha. \n\nIn general, return comparisons may be either positive or negative. A positive excess return shows that an investment outperformed its comparison, while a negative difference in returns occurs when an investment underperforms. Investors should keep in mind that purely to a benchmark provides an excess return that does not necessarily take into consideration all of the potential trading costs of a comparable proxy. \n\nFor example, using the S&P 500 as a benchmark provides an excess return calculation that does not typically take into consideration the actual costs required to invest in all 500 stocks in the Index or management fees for investing in an S&P 500 managed fund. \n\n## Excess Return vs. Riskless Rates \n\nRiskless and low risk investments are often used by investors seeking to preserve capital for various goals. U.S. Treasuries are typically considered the most basic form of riskless securities. Investors can buy U.S. Treasuries with maturities of one month, two months, three months, six months, one year, two years, three years, five years, seven years, 10-years, 20-years, and 30-years.\n\nEach maturity will have a different expected return found along the U.S. Treasury yield curve. Other types of low risk investments include certificates of deposits, money market accounts, and municipal bonds. \n\nInvestors can determine excess return levels based on comparisons to risk free securities. For example, if the one year Treasury has returned 2.0% and the technology stock Meta (formerly Facebook) has returned 15%, then the excess return achieved for investing in Meta is 13%. \n\n### Alpha \n\nOftentimes, an investor will want to look at a more closely comparable investment when determining excess return. That’s where alpha comes in. Alpha is the result of a more narrowly focused calculation that includes only a benchmark with comparable risk and return characteristics to an investment. Alpha is commonly calculated in investment fund management as the excess return a fund manager achieves ov\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_61", "name": "Capital Market Line (CML)", "short_description": "Calculates the expected return of a portfolio that lies on the Capital Market Line (CML), optimally combining a risk-free asset and the market portfolio.", "domain": "investment_analysis", "topic": "capital_market_line", "topic_extension": true, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-61", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-518", "question_id": "test-1555", "difficulty": 2.995732273553991, "level": "medium", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "6c0636333e9ec9ce98c898a1298056015d547c1ed1db15d309c95245a7e45efe", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["Capital Market Line", "CML", "Portfolio Return", "Risk and Return Optimization", "CAPM", "Sharpe Ratio"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "output_scale", "ambiguity_type": "unit_scale", "trigger_signal": "Question asks for percentage, FIC outputs decimal (or vice versa)", "clarification_question": "Should the answer be expressed as a decimal (0.08) or percent (8.0)?", "options": [{"label": "Decimal - DEFAULT", "value": "decimal", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Percent", "value": "percent", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "result * 100.0", "max_expr_nodes": 6, "invariant": "result_new == result_old * 100.0", "affected_inputs": []}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Decimal", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "risk_free_rate", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The risk-free rate of return.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "market_return", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The expected return of the market portfolio.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "market_std_dev", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The standard deviation of market returns.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "portfolio_std_dev", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The standard deviation of portfolio returns.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "portfolio_return", "type": "number", "unit": null, "description": "The expected return of the portfolio on the CML."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    risk_free_rate = inputs['risk_free_rate']\n    market_return = inputs['market_return']\n    market_std_dev = inputs['market_std_dev']\n    portfolio_std_dev = inputs['portfolio_std_dev']\n    portfolio_return = risk_free_rate + (market_return - risk_free_rate) / market_std_dev * portfolio_std_dev\n    return portfolio_return", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "rfr_001", "name": "Risk-Free Rate Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['risk_free_rate'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The risk-free rate should generally not be negative in standard financial models. A negative value may indicate a data error or an unusual market condition."}, {"rule_id": "msd_001", "name": "Market Standard Deviation Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['market_std_dev'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Standard deviation cannot be negative. Please provide a non-negative value for market standard deviation."}, {"rule_id": "msd_002", "name": "Market Standard Deviation Non-Zero", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['market_std_dev'] == 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Market standard deviation cannot be zero as it would lead to division by zero in the CML formula. This implies no risk in the market, which is unrealistic."}, {"rule_id": "psd_001", "name": "Portfolio Standard Deviation Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['portfolio_std_dev'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Standard deviation cannot be negative. Please provide a non-negative value for portfolio standard deviation."}, {"rule_id": "mr_rfr_001", "name": "Market Return Exceeds Risk-Free Rate", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['market_return'] <= inputs['risk_free_rate']", "applies_to": [], "description": "In efficient markets and under CAPM assumptions, the market return is typically expected to be greater than the risk-free rate. If not, it suggests an unusual market condition or an arbitrage opportunity."}, {"rule_id": "rates_001", "name": "Rate Input Scale Plausibility", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['risk_free_rate'] > 1.0 or inputs['market_return'] > 1.0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Rates are expected as decimals (e.g., 0.05 for 5%). Values greater than 1.0 might indicate they were entered as percentages (e.g., 5.0 for 5%) and require normalization."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    risk_free_rate = inputs['risk_free_rate']\n    market_return = inputs['market_return']\n    market_std_dev = inputs['market_std_dev']\n    portfolio_std_dev = inputs['portfolio_std_dev']\n    portfolio_return = risk_free_rate + (market_return - risk_free_rate) / market_std_dev * portfolio_std_dev\n    return portfolio_return"}, "article_title": "Capital Market Line (CML)", "article_doc_id": 72, "article_content_excerpt": "# Understanding Capital Market Line (CML) and How to Calculate It\n\n## What Is the Capital Market Line (CML)? \n\nThe capital market line (CML) represents portfolios that optimally combine risk and return. It is a theoretical concept that represents all the portfolios that optimally combine the and the market portfolio of risky assets. Under the (CAPM), all investors will choose a position on the capital market line, in equilibrium, by borrowing or lending at the risk-free rate, since this maximizes return for a given level of risk. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * The capital market line (CML) represents portfolios that optimally combine risk and return.\n * CML is a special case of the capital allocation line (CAL) where the risk portfolio is the market portfolio. Thus, the slope of the CML is the Sharpe ratio of the market portfolio.\n * The intercept point of CML and efficient frontier would result in the most efficient portfolio called the tangency portfolio.\n * As a generalization, buy assets if Sharpe ratio is above CML and sell if Sharpe ratio is below CML.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/DDM_INV_CML-Final-a50f290fb65849cdab26156c236777a5.jpg)\n\nInvestopedia / Eliana Rodgers\n\n## Formula and Calculation of the Capital Market Line (CML) \n\nCalculating the capital market line is done as follows: \n\n\\begin{aligned} &R_p = r_f + \\frac { R_T - r_f }{ \\sigma_T } \\sigma_p \\\\\\ &\\textbf{where:} \\\\\\ &R_p = \\text{portfolio return} \\\\\\ &r_f = \\text{risk free rate} \\\\\\ &R_T = \\text{market return} \\\\\\ &\\sigma_T = \\text{standard deviation of market returns} \\\\\\ &\\sigma_p = \\text{standard deviation of portfolio returns} \\\\\\ \\end{aligned}\n\n## What the CML Can Tell You \n\nPortfolios that fall on the capital market line (CML), in theory, optimize the risk/return relationship, thereby maximizing performance. The (CAL) makes up the allotment of risk-free assets and risky portfolios for an investor. \n\nCML is a special case of the CAL where the risk portfolio is the market portfolio. Thus, the slope of the CML is the of the market portfolio. As a generalization, buy assets if the Sharpe ratio is above the CML and sell if the Sharpe ratio is below the CML. \n\n### Important: \n\nCML differs from the more popular in that it includes risk-free investments. The intercept point of CML and efficient frontier would result in the most efficient portfolio, called the tangency portfolio.\n\nMean-variance analysis was pioneered by Harry Markowitz and . The efficient frontier of optimal portfolios was identified by Markowitz in 1952, and James Tobin included the risk-free rate to in 1958. William Sharpe then developed the CAPM in the 1960s, and won a Nobel prize for his work in 1990, along with Markowitz and Merton Miller.\n\nThe CAPM is the line that connects the risk-free rate of return with the tangency point on the efficient frontier of optimal portfolios that offer the highest , or the lowest risk for a given level of expected return. \n\nThe portfolios with the best trade-off between expected returns and variance (risk) lie on this line. The tangency point is the optimal portfolio of risky assets, known as the market portfolio. Under the assumptions of —that investors seek to maximize their expected return for a given amount of variance risk, and that there is a risk-free rate of return—all investors will select portfolios that lie on the CML. \n\nAccording to Tobin's separation theorem, finding the market portfolio and the best combination of that market portfolio and the risk-free asset are separate problems. Individual investors will either hold just the risk-free asset or some combination of the risk-free asset and the market portfolio, depending on their risk-aversion. \n\nAs an investor moves up the CML, the overall portfolio risk and returns increase. Risk-averse investors will select portfolios close to the risk-free asset, preferring low variance to higher returns. Less risk-averse investors will prefer portfolios higher up on the CML, with a higher expected return,\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_2093", "name": "Labor Productivity", "short_description": "Calculates the percentage growth in labor productivity between two periods, given the GDP per labor hour for the new and old periods.", "domain": "corporate_finance", "topic": "labor_productivity", "topic_extension": true, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-2093", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-1078", "question_id": "test-1097", "difficulty": 2.4849066497880004, "level": "medium", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "bfe3cc44e93b5add5aaf050183f0405d75b1b888c8a7175d35ab2e77371777ba", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["labor productivity", "productivity growth", "economic output per labor hour", "GDP per hour", "workforce productivity growth"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "output_scale", "ambiguity_type": "unit_scale", "trigger_signal": "output value is a rate or percentage, unit not explicitly stated in user query", "clarification_question": "Should the growth rate be expressed as a percentage (e.g., 8%) or as a decimal (e.g., 0.08)?", "options": [{"label": "Percentage (default)", "value": "percentage", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Decimal", "value": "decimal", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "result / 100.0", "max_expr_nodes": 6, "invariant": "result_new == result_old / 100.0", "affected_inputs": []}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Percentage (e.g., 8%)", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "new_gdp_per_hour", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The GDP per labor hour for the newer period.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "old_gdp_per_hour", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The GDP per labor hour for the older period.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "growth_percentage", "type": "number", "unit": "%", "description": "The percentage growth in labor productivity."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    new_gdp_per_hour = inputs['new_gdp_per_hour']\n    old_gdp_per_hour = inputs['old_gdp_per_hour']\n    growth_percentage = (new_gdp_per_hour - old_gdp_per_hour) / old_gdp_per_hour * 100\n    return growth_percentage", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "input_type_new_gdp_per_hour", "name": "New GDP per hour type check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['new_gdp_per_hour'], (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'new_gdp_per_hour' must be a number (integer or float)."}, {"rule_id": "input_type_old_gdp_per_hour", "name": "Old GDP per hour type check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['old_gdp_per_hour'], (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'old_gdp_per_hour' must be a number (integer or float)."}, {"rule_id": "old_gdp_per_hour_positive", "name": "Old GDP per hour must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['old_gdp_per_hour'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["old_gdp_per_hour"], "description": "The 'old_gdp_per_hour' must be strictly greater than zero to avoid mathematical errors and ensure a meaningful growth calculation."}, {"rule_id": "new_gdp_per_hour_non_negative", "name": "New GDP per hour must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['new_gdp_per_hour'] < 0", "applies_to": ["new_gdp_per_hour"], "description": "The 'new_gdp_per_hour' should be non-negative, as negative GDP per hour values are highly unusual and may indicate data entry errors."}, {"rule_id": "extreme_growth_alert", "name": "Unusually high or low growth rate", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "abs(compute(inputs)) > 500", "applies_to": ["new_gdp_per_hour", "old_gdp_per_hour"], "description": "A labor productivity growth rate exceeding 500% or dropping below -500% is unusually large and may indicate an anomaly or data input error."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    new_gdp_per_hour = inputs['new_gdp_per_hour']\n    old_gdp_per_hour = inputs['old_gdp_per_hour']\n    growth_percentage = (new_gdp_per_hour - old_gdp_per_hour) / old_gdp_per_hour * 100\n    return growth_percentage"}, "article_title": "Labor Productivity", "article_doc_id": 4032, "article_content_excerpt": "# Labor Productivity: What It Is, Calculation, and How to Improve It\n\n## What Is Labor Productivity? \n\nLabor productivity is a measure that compares economic output against the amount of labor required to produce that output. \n\nLabor productivity is often used to calculate the amount of (GDP) produced by an hour of labor. Growth in labor productivity depends on three main factors: savings and investment in new technology, and human capital. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Labor productivity calculates economic output based on labor.\n * The most common measure of labor productivity is real gross domestic product per hour of labor.\n * Labor productivity is largely driven by investment in capital, technological progress, and human capital development.\n * Businesses and governments can increase labor productivity by investing in technology, physical capital, or human capital.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/labor-productivity.asp-final-2c0d23a4f3544122969aacf8ef94ed49.png)\n\nInvestopedia / Paige McLaughlin\n\n## Understanding Labor Productivity \n\nLabor productivity measures economic output for a given amount of labor. Growth in labor productivity is measured by the change in economic output per unit of time over a defined period. \n\nLabor productivity is also known as workforce productivity. Labor productivity should not be confused with , which is a measure of an individual worker's output. \n\n## How to Calculate Labor Productivity \n\nTo calculate a country's labor productivity, you would divide the total output by . \n\nFor example, suppose the real GDP of an economy is $10 trillion and the aggregate hours of labor in the country is 300 billion. The labor productivity would be $10 trillion divided by 300 billion, equaling about $33 per labor hour. If the real GDP of the same economy grows to $20 trillion the next year and its labor hours increase to 350 billion, the economy's growth in labor productivity would be 72 percent. \n\nThe growth number is derived by dividing the new real GDP of $57 by the previous real GDP of $33. Growth in this labor productivity number can sometimes be interpreted as improved in the country, assuming it keeps pace with labor's share of total income. \n\n## The Importance of Measuring Labor Productivity \n\nLabor productivity is directly linked to improved standards of living in the form of higher consumption. As an economy's labor productivity grows, it produces more goods and services for the same amount of relative work. This increase in output makes it possible to consume more of the goods and services for an increasingly reasonable price. \n\nGrowth in labor productivity is directly attributable to fluctuations in physical capital, new technology, and human capital. If labor productivity is growing, it can usually be traced back to growth in one of these three areas. \n\nPhysical capital includes the tools, equipment, and facilities that workers have available to use to produce goods. New technologies are methods of combining inputs to produce more output, such as assembly lines or automation. Human capital represents the increase in education and of the workforce. Measuring labor productivity gives an estimate of the combined effects of these underlying trends. \n\nLabor productivity can also indicate short-term and cyclical changes in an economy, possibly even . If the output is increasing while labor hours remains static, it signals that the labor force has become more productive. In addition to the three traditional factors outlined above, this is also seen during economic , as workers increase their labor effort when unemployment rises and the threat of lay-offs looms.\n\n## Policies to Improve Labor Productivity \n\nThere are a number of ways that governments and companies can improve labor productivity. \n\n * **Investment in physical capital** : Increasing the investment in capital goods including from governments and the private sector can help productivity while lowering the cost of doing business.\n * **Quality of\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_593", "name": "Foregone Earnings", "short_description": "Calculates the difference in foregone earnings between two funds with different fee percentages based on an initial investment amount. It assesses how much earnings are foregone when investing in a fund with higher fees as opposed to a fund with lower fees.", "domain": "investment_analysis", "topic": "investment_fees", "topic_extension": true, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-593", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-472", "question_id": "test-1786", "difficulty": 3.401197381662155, "level": "medium", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "592bb351e26fc5ecaa1877af914c6621a25e0569cbabfe76fb551f219956d469", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["foregone earnings", "investment fees", "fund fees", "management fees", "sales charges", "expense ratio", "investment comparison", "fee difference"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "fee_input_scale", "ambiguity_type": "unit_scale", "trigger_signal": "fee percentages provided without explicit indication of scale (0-1 or 0-100)", "clarification_question": "Are the fee percentages (fee1_percent, fee2_percent) provided as whole numbers (e.g., 1.5 for 1.5%) or as decimals (e.g., 0.015 for 1.5%)?", "options": [{"label": "Whole number percentage (0-100) - DEFAULT", "value": "whole_number_percent", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Decimal (0-1)", "value": "decimal_percent", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "result * 100.0", "max_expr_nodes": 6, "invariant": "result_new == result_old * 100.0", "affected_inputs": []}}], "i_level": "hard", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Whole number percentage (0-100)", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}], "inputs": [{"name": "investment", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The initial amount invested.", "unit": "dollar", "aliases": []}, {"name": "fee1_percent", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The fee percentage for the first fund. Expected between 0 and 100.", "unit": "percent", "aliases": []}, {"name": "fee2_percent", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The fee percentage for the second fund. Expected between 0 and 100.", "unit": "percent", "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "foregone_earnings_due_to_fees", "type": "number", "unit": "dollar", "description": "The foregone earnings due to higher fees in the second fund."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    investment = inputs['investment']\n    fee1_percent = inputs['fee1_percent']\n    fee2_percent = inputs['fee2_percent']\n    fee1_cost = investment * (fee1_percent / 100)\n    fee2_cost = investment * (fee2_percent / 100)\n    foregone_earnings_due_to_fees = fee2_cost - fee1_cost\n    return foregone_earnings_due_to_fees", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "fe001", "name": "Investment Amount Must Be Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "inputs['investment'] >= 0", "applies_to": ["investment"], "description": "The initial investment amount must be a non-negative value."}, {"rule_id": "fe002", "name": "Fee 1 Percentage Must Be Between 0 and 100", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "0 <= inputs['fee1_percent'] <= 100", "applies_to": ["fee1_percent"], "description": "The fee percentage for the first fund must be between 0 and 100 (inclusive)."}, {"rule_id": "fe003", "name": "Fee 2 Percentage Must Be Between 0 and 100", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "0 <= inputs['fee2_percent'] <= 100", "applies_to": ["fee2_percent"], "description": "The fee percentage for the second fund must be between 0 and 100 (inclusive)."}, {"rule_id": "fe004", "name": "Fee 2 Should Be Greater Than or Equal to Fee 1 for Foregone Earnings", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['fee2_percent'] < inputs['fee1_percent']", "applies_to": ["fee1_percent", "fee2_percent"], "description": "The concept of 'foregone earnings' implies a higher cost in the comparison fund (Fund B). If Fund B's fee (fee2_percent) is lower than Fund A's (fee1_percent), the result will be 'earnings gained' rather than 'foregone earnings'. This is an alert for potential misinterpretation of the output's meaning."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    investment = inputs['investment']\n    fee1_percent = inputs['fee1_percent']\n    fee2_percent = inputs['fee2_percent']\n    fee1_cost = investment * (fee1_percent / 100)\n    fee2_cost = investment * (fee2_percent / 100)\n    foregone_earnings_due_to_fees = fee2_cost - fee1_cost\n    return foregone_earnings_due_to_fees"}, "article_title": "Foregone Earnings", "article_doc_id": 1086, "article_content_excerpt": "# Foregone Earnings: Meaning, Overview, Examples\n\n## What Are Foregone Earnings? \n\nForegone earnings represent the difference between actually achieved and the earnings that could have been achieved with the absence of fees, expenses, or lost time. As such, a large portion of foregone is represented by the amount that the investor spent on investment fees, which often make up a sizable percentage of investment earnings. \n\nThe assumption is that if the investor had been exposed to lower fees, they would have automatically earned a better return. The concept of foregone earnings is typically used when referring to sales charges, management fees, or total expenses paid to funds. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Foregone earnings represent the difference between an investment's actual earnings and the earnings that could have been realized had there been no fees.\n * Foregone earnings, therefore, are the investment capital that the investor spent on investment fees.\n * The concept of foregone earnings assumes that investors exposed to lower fees earn better returns in the market.\n * Sales charges and operating fees, incurred by an investor in a mutual fund, are examples of investment fees that lead to foregone earnings. \n\n## Understanding Foregone Earnings \n\nForegone earnings, as they relate to investment performance, can cause a big drag on the of assets and investments. Fees are usually charged to investors for access to , (ETFs), and other pooled . Mutual funds are actively managed funds, meaning they're a collection of securities bought and sold by a portfolio manager. ETFs are passively managed funds, meaning they typically track an index such as the S&P 500 and, therefore, have lower fees than mutual funds. \n\nSomething as seemingly innocent as a or a 1% can cost thousands of dollars as the years pile up, thanks to the wonders of . Investors must research the costs associated with each investment to limit foregone earnings. \n\n### Tip: \n\nForegone earnings are a type of , or the cost of missing out on a better choice or opportunity, thus leaving money on the table.\n\n## Examples of Foregone Earnings: Mutual Funds \n\n### Sales Charges \n\nSales charges can be a significant expense for investors. The (FINRA) provides the following schedule, which outlines potential front-end load sales charges for investing in mutual funds. The table below shows the hypothetical as examples where mutual fund sales charges might be reduced based on the amount of funds invested. \n \n<table> \n<tr> \n<th>\n\nPossible Breakpoint Discounts\n</th> </tr> \n<tr> \n<th>\n\n**Investment Amount**\n</th> \n<th>\n\n**Sales Charge**\n</th> </tr> \n<tr> \n<td>\n\nLess than $25,000\n</td> \n<td>\n\n5.00%\n</td> </tr> \n<tr> \n<td>\n\nAt least $25,000 but less than $50,000\n</td> \n<td>\n\n4.25%\n</td> </tr> \n<tr> \n<td>\n\nAt least $50,000 but less than $100,000\n</td> \n<td>\n\n3.75%\n</td> </tr> \n<tr> \n<td>\n\nAt least $100,000 but less than $250,000\n</td> \n<td>\n\n3.25%\n</td> </tr> \n<tr> \n<td>\n\nAt least $250,000 but less than $500,000\n</td> \n<td>\n\n2.75%\n</td> </tr> \n<tr> \n<td>\n\nAt least $500,000 but less than $1,000,000\n</td> \n<td>\n\n2.00%\n</td> </tr> \n<tr> \n<td>\n\n$1 million or more\n</td> \n<td>\n\nNo sales charge\n</td> </tr> </table>\n\nSales charges can occur at various points in the investment process. Sales charges are commissions charged by distributors that compensate the broker for sales. \n\nBelow are three examples of the types of sales charges and when they occur:\n\n * sales charges are calculated as a percentage of the amount or initial investment at the time of the purchase. Typically, class A shares have front-end sales charges associated with them.\n * sales charges are calculated as a percentage of the notional amount at the time of selling the investment. Typically, a fund's B-shares are charged back-end sales charges.\n * sales charges are back-end sales charges that are reduced gradually as long as the investment remains in the fund. The charges can be reduced to zero eventually. Deferred charges are also call\n...[truncated]"}
