expression": "inputs['revenue'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Revenue must be a positive value."}, {"rule_id": "niat_dc_002", "name": "Non-negative Expenses Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "any(inputs[exp] < 0 for exp in ['cogs', 'depreciation', 'charge_offs', 'interest_expense', 'taxes', 'overhead_costs', 'research_and_development'])", "applies_to": [], "description": "All expense items (COGS, depreciation, charge-offs, interest expense, taxes, overhead costs, R&D) must be non-negative."}, {"rule_id": "niat_dc_003", "name": "Taxes vs. Pre-Tax Income Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "(inputs['revenue'] - (inputs['cogs'] + inputs['depreciation'] + inputs['charge_offs'] + inputs['interest_expense'] + inputs['overhead_costs'] + inputs['research_and_development'])) < inputs['taxes']", "applies_to": [], "description": "Taxes paid should not exceed the company's pre-tax income."}, {"rule_id": "niat_dc_004", "name": "Total Expenses vs. Revenue Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "(inputs['cogs'] + inputs['depreciation'] + inputs['charge_offs'] + inputs['interest_expense'] + inputs['taxes'] + inputs['overhead_costs'] + inputs['research_and_development']) > inputs['revenue']", "applies_to": [], "description": "The sum of all expenses (COGS, depreciation, charge-offs, interest expense, taxes, overhead costs, R&D) should not exceed total revenue."}, {"rule_id": "niat_dc_005", "name": "Plausible NIAT Output Range", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "compute(inputs) < -inputs['revenue'] * 2", "applies_to": [], "description": "Net Income After Taxes (NIAT) is unusually low, indicating potential input errors or extreme financial distress."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    revenue = inputs['revenue']\n    cogs = inputs['cogs']\n    depreciation = inputs['depreciation']\n    charge_offs = inputs['charge_offs']\n    interest_expense = inputs['interest_expense']\n    taxes = inputs['taxes']\n    overhead_costs = inputs['overhead_costs']\n    research_and_development = inputs['research_and_development']\n    total_expenses = cogs + depreciation + charge_offs + interest_expense + taxes + overhead_costs + research_and_development\n    niat = revenue - total_expenses\n    return niat"}, "article_title": "Net Income After Taxes (NIAT)", "article_doc_id": 5830, "article_content_excerpt": "# Net Income After Taxes (NIAT): Definition, Calculation, Example\n\n## What Is Net Income After Taxes? \n\nNet income after taxes (NIAT) is a financial term used to describe a company's profit after all taxes have been paid. Net income after taxes is an accounting term and is most often found in a company's quarterly and annual financial reports. Net income after taxes represents the profit or earnings after all expense have been deducted from revenue. Net income after taxes calculation can be shown as both a total dollar amount and a per-share calculation. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Net income after taxes (NIAT) is a financial term used to describe a company's profit after all taxes have been paid.\n * Net income after taxes represents the profit or earnings after all expense have been deducted from revenue.\n * Companies that increase net income have more cash to invest in the company's future, pay dividends, and buyback stock.\n\n## Understanding Net Income After Taxes (NIAT) \n\nNet income after taxes (NIAT) is the of a business less all taxes. In other words, NIAT is the sum of all revenues generated from the sale of the company's products and services minus the costs to run it. Companies and analysts can also use the calculation to determine the value of revenue after the subtraction of taxes. \n\n and sales are sometimes used interchangeably by companies. Also, retail companies often use the term _net revenue_ or _net sales_ because they often have returned merchandise by customers. The total amount of rebates to customers from returns is deducted from the revenue total for the period. \n\nRegardless of the term used by a company to describe its total revenue earned from sales, revenue is always located at the top of the income statement. As a result, revenue is the figure that all costs and expenses are deducted from that ultimately leads to net income, which rests at the bottom of the income statement. This is why revenue is referred to as the , while net income is called the . \n\nNet income after taxes is calculated by taking revenue and subtracting all of a company's expenses and costs, including the following: \n\n * , which represents the costs involved in production including direct labor and direct materials or inventory\n * , which is the process of expensing or spreading out the cost of fixed assets over their useful life\n * , which can be one-time write-offs or losses\n * on any debt including short-term debt and the interest portion for that period for long-term debt, such as bonds issued\n * Taxes paid to the government\n * , which include the staff and building for the corporate office are listed on the income statement as \n * Research and development spending\n\nAlthough net income after taxes is essentially the same as net income, it is used in financial statements to differentiate between and income after taxes. The two figures can also be described as pre-tax income and after-tax income. \n\n## Interpreting Net Income After Taxes \n\nNet income after taxes is one of the most analyzed figures on a company’s financial statements. The amount recorded provides an indication of the profitability of a company, which determines whether the firm can compensate its investors and shareholders through dividends and share buybacks. are rewards–usually in cash–paid to shareholders while are share repurchases by a company. \n\nAn increase in profits over multiple periods typically leads to an increase in the company's stock price since investors would have a favorable view of the business. As a company generates additional net income, they have more cash to invest in the company's future, which can include purchasing new equipment, technologies, or expanding their operations and sales. A company with positive net income growth is also in a better financial position to pay down debt or make an to boost their competitiveness and total revenue. \n\nA company with a net income figure that is negative or below average can be the result of a firm experie\n...[truncated]"}
