bel": "Decimal (e.g., 0.0408) - DEFAULT", "value": "decimal", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Percentage (e.g., 4.08%)", "value": "percent", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "result * 100.0", "max_expr_nodes": 6, "invariant": "result_new == result_old * 100.0", "affected_inputs": []}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Decimal", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}, {"id": "yield_type_clarification", "ambiguity_type": "output_interpretation", "trigger_signal": "User might be looking for money market yield instead of bank discount yield as mentioned in article", "clarification_question": "Are you looking for the Bank Discount Yield (calculated by default) or the Money Market Yield (a related measure)?", "options": [{"label": "Bank Discount Yield - DEFAULT", "value": "bank_discount_yield", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Money Market Yield", "value": "money_market_yield", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "result * (face_value / purchase_price)", "max_expr_nodes": 11, "invariant": "result_new == result_old * (face_value / purchase_price)", "affected_inputs": ["face_value", "purchase_price"]}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Bank Discount Yield", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "face_value", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The face value of the security.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "purchase_price", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The purchase price of the security.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "time_to_maturity", "type": "integer", "required": true, "description": "The time to maturity of the security in days.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "bank_discount_yield", "type": "number", "unit": null, "description": "The bank discount yield expressed as a decimal."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    face_value = inputs['face_value']\n    purchase_price = inputs['purchase_price']\n    time_to_maturity = inputs['time_to_maturity']\n    bank_discount_yield = (face_value - purchase_price) / face_value * (360 / time_to_maturity)\n    return bank_discount_yield", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "face_value_positive", "name": "Face Value Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['face_value'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["face_value"], "description": "The face value of the security must be a positive number."}, {"rule_id": "purchase_price_positive", "name": "Purchase Price Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['purchase_price'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["purchase_price"], "description": "The purchase price of the security must be a positive number."}, {"rule_id": "purchase_price_less_than_face_value", "name": "Purchase Price Less Than Face Value", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['purchase_price'] >= inputs['face_value']", "applies_to": ["purchase_price", "face_value"], "description": "For a discount instrument, the purchase price must be strictly less than the face value."}, {"rule_id": "time_to_maturity_positive", "name": "Time to Maturity Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['time_to_maturity'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["time_to_maturity"], "description": "The time to maturity must be a positive number of days."}, {"rule_id": "time_to_maturity_less_than_year", "name": "Time to Maturity For Money Market Instruments", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['time_to_maturity'] > 365", "applies_to": ["time_to_maturity"], "description": "Money market instruments typically have maturities of less than one year (365 days)."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    face_value = inputs['face_value']\n    purchase_price = inputs['purchase_price']\n    time_to_maturity = inputs['time_to_maturity']\n    bank_discount_yield = (face_value - purchase_price) / face_value * (360 / time_to_maturity)\n    return bank_discount_yield"}, "article_title": "Money Market Yield", "article_doc_id": 1753, "article_content_excerpt": "# Money Market Yield: Definition, Calculation, and Example\n\n## What Is the Money Market Yield? \n\nThe money market yield is the interest rate earned by investing in securities with high liquidity and maturities of less than one year, such as , U.S. Treasury bills, and municipal notes. Money market yield is calculated by taking the holding period yield and multiplying it by a 360-day bank year divided by days to maturity. It can also be calculated using a . \n\nThe money market yield is closely related to the CD-equivalent yield and the (BEY). \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * The money market yield is what money market instruments are expected to return to investors.\n * The money market involves the purchase and sale of large volumes of very short-term debt products, such as overnight reserves or commercial paper.\n * An individual may invest in the money market by purchasing a money market mutual fund, buying a Treasury bill, or opening a money market account at a bank.\n\n## Understanding the Money Market Yield \n\nThe is the part of the broader financial markets that deals with highly liquid and short-term financial securities. The market links borrowers and lenders who are looking to transact in short-term instruments overnight or for some days, weeks, or months, but always less than a year. \n\nActive participants in this market include banks, , brokers, and dealers. Examples of money market securities include (CD), (T-bills), commercial paper, municipal notes, short-term asset-backed securities, Eurodollar deposits, and . \n\nTo earn a money market yield, it is thus necessary to have a . Banks, for example, offer money market accounts because they need to borrow funds on a short-term basis to meet and to participate in interbank lending. \n\nMoney market investors receive compensation for lending funds to entities that need to fulfill their short-term debt obligations. This compensation is typically in the form of variable interest rates determined by the current interest rate in the economy. \n\nSince money market securities are considered to have low , the money market yield will be but higher than the interest rates on standard savings accounts. \n\n## Calculating the Money Market Yield \n\nAlthough interest rates are quoted annually, the quoted interest may actually be compounded semi-annually, quarterly, monthly, or even daily. The money market yield is calculated using the (BEY) based on a 360-day year, which helps an investor compare the return of a bond that pays a coupon on an annual basis with a bond that pays semi-annual, quarterly, or any other coupons. \n\nThe formula for the money market yield is: \n\n> Money market yield = x (360/Time to maturity) \n\n> Money market yield = [(Face value – Purchase price)/Purchase price] x (360/Time to maturity) \n\nFor example, a T-bill with a $100,000 is issued for $98,000 and is due to mature in 180 days. The money market yield is: \n\n * = ($100,000 - $98,000)/$98,000 x (360/180)\n * = 0.0204 x 2\n * = 0.0408, or 4.08%\n\nThe money market yield differs slightly from the yield, which is computed on the face value, not the purchase price; however, the money market yield can also be calculated using the bank discount yield as seen in this formula: \n\n> Money market yield = Bank discount yield x (Face value/Purchase price) \n\n> Money market yield = Bank discount yield / [1 – (Face value – Purchase price/Face value)] \n\nWhere bank discount yield = (Face value – Purchase price)/Face value x (360/Time to maturity) \n\n## What Is a Typical Money Market Yield?\n\nMoney market accounts and instruments typically yield between 0.01% and 4%. This depends on the amount of money deposited, as some institutions require a higher deposit to earn the higher interest rate.\n\n## What Is the 7-Day Yield on the Money Market?\n\nThe 7-day yield on the money market is a method of estimating the return of money market instruments on an annual basis. It takes the difference between the price today and the price seven days ago and multiplies that by\n...[truncated]"}
