on, it's a significant financial status. Ensure this aligns with your investment strategy or data expectations. This diagnostic provides context for the calculated intrinsic value, especially when it results in zero. It helps in understanding the current profitability (or lack thereof) of exercising the option. Review your market data to confirm the current price relationship. This status is common for many options and indicates they are only holding time value. Please acknowledge this status to proceed. If you expected an in-the-money put option, double-check the 'market_price' and 'exercise_price' inputs for accuracy. This alert helps to confirm that the calculated intrinsic value of zero is consistent with the option's current out-of-the-money status. It's a key piece of information for evaluating the option's current profitability. Verify that the market price is not mistakenly higher than the exercise price if you anticipated an ITM option. This alert is purely informational, highlighting the option's current market position relative to its exercise price."}, {"rule_id": "numeric_prices", "name": "Exercise and Market Price Must Be Numeric", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['exercise_price'], (int, float)) and isinstance(inputs['market_price'], (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "Exercise price and market price must be numeric values. Received: exercise_price={inputs.get('exercise_price')}, market_price={inputs.get('market_price')}. Please ensure that both inputs are provided as valid numbers (integers or floats) to allow for correct calculation. Non-numeric values cannot be processed and will result in an error. Verify that there are no text characters, symbols, or incorrect data types for these fields. If the values are derived from other systems, confirm that they are cast or converted to numeric types before being passed to this function. For example, '120.0' or 120 are valid, while '$120' or 'one hundred twenty' are not. This check is crucial for the fundamental operation of the calculation, as mathematical operations require numeric inputs. Correcting the data type will resolve this issue. If the input is missing, please provide a value. Otherwise, ensure it's a number. This diagnostic is critical for preventing fundamental data type mismatches. Providing numerical values for prices is a basic requirement for any financial calculation. Please correct these inputs to be valid numbers."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    option_type = inputs['option_type']\n    exercise_price = inputs['exercise_price']\n    market_price = inputs['market_price']\n    if option_type == 'call':\n        intrinsic_value = max(0.0, market_price - exercise_price)\n    else:\n        intrinsic_value = max(0.0, exercise_price - market_price)\n    return intrinsic_value"}, "article_title": "Exercise Price: Overview, Put and Calls, In and Out of The Money", "article_doc_id": 5681, "article_content_excerpt": "# Exercise Price: Overview, Put and Calls, In and Out of The Money\n\n## What Is an Exercise Price? \n\nThe exercise price is the price at which an can be purchased or sold when trading a call or put , respectively. It is also referred to as the strike price and is known when an investor initiates the trade. \n\nAn option gets its value from the difference between the fixed exercise price and the of the underlying security. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * An option's exercise price is the price the underlying security can be either bought or sold for.\n * Both call and put options have an exercise price.\n * Investors also refer to the exercise price as the strike price.\n * The difference between the exercise price and the underlying security’s price determines if an option is “in the money” or “out of the money.\"\n\n## Understanding Exercise Prices \n\n\"Exercise price\" is a term used in trading. A derivative is a financial instrument based on an underlying asset. Options are derivatives, while the stock, for example, refers to the underlying security. \n\nIn options trading, there are calls and puts and the exercise price can be (ITM) or (OTM). A call option would be ITM if the exercise price is below the underlying security’s price and OTM if the exercise price is above the underlying security’s price. The converse would hold for a put option. \n\n### Calls vs Puts \n\nA gives investors the right, but not the obligation, to sell a stock in the future. Investors buy puts if they think the stock is going down or if they own the stock and want to against a possible price decline. They buy puts because it allows them to sell the stock at the strike price of the option, even if the stock falls dramatically. \n\nA , meanwhile, gives investors the right, but not the obligation, to buy a stock in the future. Investors buy calls if they think the stock is going up in the future or if they sold the stock and want to hedge against a possible surge in price. Calls give them the right to buy at the strike price even if the stock price rallies aggressively. \n\nTypically, put option investors only their right to sell their shares at the exercise price if the price of the underlying is below the . Likewise, call options are usually only exercised if the price of the underlying is trading above the strike price. \n\n## Exercise Price Example \n\nLet’s assume that Sam owns call options for Wells Fargo & Company with an exercise price of $45, and the underlying stock is trading at $50. This means the call options are trading ITM—the exercise price is lower than the price at which the stock is currently trading—by $5. \n\nThe call options give Sam the right to buy the stock at $45 even though it's trading at $50, allowing him to make $5 per share by exercising the option. Sam's profit would be $5 less the or cost he paid for the option. \n\nIf, on the other hand, Wells Fargo is trading at $50, and the strike price of Sam's call option is $55, that option is OTM. It would not be beneficial for Sam to exercise that option because there is no need to pay $55 (using the option) when he can currently buy the stock for $50. \n\n**Example of the Exercise Price / Strike Price in Wells Fargo Options Table**\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/optionstableWFC-5c89e0e246e0fb00010f11d8.GIF)\n\nYahoo! Finance.\n\nThe further OTM an option moves, the less valuable it gets. It only has , or value based on the possibility that the price of the underlying _could_ move through the strike price. Meanwhile, the further ITM an option is, the more value it has, giving Sam a better price than what is available in the stock market—or another underlying market."}
