ity.", "unit": "dollar", "aliases": []}, {"name": "option_type", "type": "string", "required": true, "description": "The type of the option, either 'call' or 'put'.", "unit": null, "aliases": ["type", "option_kind", "option_type"]}], "output": {"name": "intrinsic_value", "type": "number", "unit": "dollar", "description": "The intrinsic value of the option, which is a non-negative number, rounded to the nearest integer as requested."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    strike_price = inputs['strike_price']\n    market_price = inputs['market_price']\n    option_type = inputs['option_type']\n    if option_type == 'call':\n        intrinsic_value = max(0, market_price - strike_price)\n    else:\n        intrinsic_value = max(0, strike_price - market_price)\n    return round(intrinsic_value)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "dc001", "name": "Strike Price Type Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('strike_price'), (int, float))", "applies_to": ["strike_price"], "description": "The 'strike_price' input must be a numeric value (integer or float)."}, {"rule_id": "dc002", "name": "Market Price Type Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('market_price'), (int, float))", "applies_to": ["market_price"], "description": "The 'market_price' input must be a numeric value (integer or float)."}, {"rule_id": "dc003", "name": "Option Type String Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('option_type'), str)", "applies_to": ["option_type"], "description": "The 'option_type' input must be a string."}, {"rule_id": "dc004", "name": "Positive Strike Price Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['strike_price'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["strike_price"], "description": "The strike price must be a positive value."}, {"rule_id": "dc005", "name": "Positive Market Price Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['market_price'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["market_price"], "description": "The market price of the underlying security must be a positive value."}, {"rule_id": "dc006", "name": "Valid Option Type", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['option_type'] not in ['call', 'put']", "applies_to": ["option_type"], "description": "The option type must be either 'call' or 'put'."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    strike_price = inputs['strike_price']\n    market_price = inputs['market_price']\n    option_type = inputs['option_type']\n    if option_type == 'call':\n        intrinsic_value = max(0, market_price - strike_price)\n    else:\n        intrinsic_value = max(0, strike_price - market_price)\n    return round(intrinsic_value)"}, "article_title": "Time Decay", "article_doc_id": 3591, "article_content_excerpt": "# What Is Time Decay? How It Works, Impact, and Example\n\n## What Is Time Decay? \n\nTime decay is a measure of the rate of decline in the value of an options contract due to the passage of time. Time decay accelerates as an draws closer since there's less time to realize a profit from the trade. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Time decay is the rate of change in value to an option's price as it nears expiration.\n * Depending on whether an option is in-the-money (ITM), time decay accelerates in the last month before expiration.\n * The more time left until expiry, the slower the time decay while the closer to expiry, the more time decay increases. \n\n## How Time Decay Works \n\nTime decay is the reduction in the value of an option as the time to the approaches. An option's is how much time plays into the value—or the premium—for the option. The time value declines or time decay accelerates as the expiration date gets closer because there's less time for an investor to earn a profit from the option. \n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/dotdash_Final_Time_Decay_Apr_2020-01-a2824c7ac5ad47ed9082ea52f9ace031.jpg)\n\nImage by Sabrina Jiang © Investopedia 2020\n\nThis figure, when calculated, will always be negative, as time only moves in one direction. The countdown for time decay begins as soon as the option is initially bought and continues until expiration. \n\n### Important: \n\nTime decay is also called theta and is known as one of the . Other Greeks include delta, gamma, vega, and rho, and these formulas help you assess the risks inherent with an options trade.\n\n## Special Considerations \n\nTo understand how , we must first review what makes up the value of an option. Options contracts give investors the right to buy or sell securities, such as stocks, at a specific price and time. The is the price at which the options contract changes to shares of the underlying security if the option is exercised. \n\nEach option has a attached to it, which is the value and often the cost of purchasing the option. However, there are a few other components that also drive the value of the premium. These factors include intrinsic value, extrinsic value, interest rate changes, and the volatility the underlying asset may exhibit. \n\n### Intrinsic Value \n\n is the difference between the market price of the underlying security—such as a stock—and the strike price of the option. A call option with a strike price of $20, while the underlying stock is trading at $20, would have no intrinsic value since there's no profit. \n\nHowever, a call option with a strike price of $20, while the underlying stock is trading at $30, would have a $10 intrinsic value. In other words, the intrinsic value is the minimum profit that's built into the option given the prevailing market price and the strike. Of course, the intrinsic value can change as the stock's price fluctuates, but the strike price remains fixed throughout the contract. \n\n### Extrinsic Value \n\nThe is more abstract than the intrinsic value, and it's more difficult to measure. The extrinsic value of options factors in the amount of time left before expiration and the rate of time decay leading up to the expiry. If an investor buys a call option with a few months until expiry, the option will have a greater value than an option that expires in a few days. \n\nThe time value of an option with little time left until expiry is less since there's a lower probability of an investor making money by buying the option. As a result, the option's price or premium declines. \n\nThe option with a few months until expiry will have an increased amount of time value and slow time decay since there's a reasonable probability that an option buyer could earn a profit. However, as time passes and the option isn't yet profitable, time decay accelerates, particularly in the last 30 days before expiration. As a result, the option's value declines as the expiry approaches, and more so if it's not yet profitable. \n\n## Time Decay vs. Moneyness \n\n is the level o\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_886", "name": "Markup", "short_description": "Calculate the markdown percentage from an original price to a reduced price. This function calculates the percentage markdown, which indicates the reduction in price from the original selling price to a lower price. It is typically used in retail to reflect discounts or promotions.", "domain": "corporate_finance", "topic": "pricing_and_discounts", "topic_extension": true, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-886", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-1017", "question_id": "test-1067", "difficulty": 2.4849066497880004, "level": "medium", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "8e76e40ba38dac2abe0e8a59d9aeff7e284a05db067e1ce0f59d383e3995bddf", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["markdown percentage", "discount percentage", "price reduction", "retail sale", "promotional discount", "price markdown", "original price", "reduced price"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "output_scale", "ambiguity_type": "unit_scale", "trigger_signal": "question implies a percentage or decimal representation, but not explicitly stated", "clarification_question": "Should the markdown be expressed as a percentage (e.g., 25.0) or as a decimal (e.g., 0.25)?", "options": [{"label": "Percentage (e.g., 25.0) — DEFAULT", "value": "percentage_output", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Decimal (e.g., 0.25)", "value": "decimal_output", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "result / 100.0", "max_expr_nodes": 6, "invariant": "result_new == result_old / 100.0", "affected_inputs": []}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Percentage (multiplied by 100)", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "original_price", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The initial selling price of the product.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "reduced_price", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The new selling price after the markdown.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "markdown_percentage", "type": "number", "unit": "%", "description": "The markdown expressed as a percentage of the original price."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    original_price = inputs['original_price']\n    reduced_price = inputs['reduced_price']\n    markdown_percentage = (original_price - reduced_price) / original_price * 100\n    return round(markdown_percentage, 2)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "original_price_type", "name": "Original Price Type Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('original_price'), (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'original_price' must be a numeric value (integer or float). If missing or not a number, it cannot be processed."}, {"rule_id": "reduced_price_type", "name": "Reduced Price Type Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('reduced_price'), (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'reduced_price' must be a numeric value (integer or float). If missing or not a number, it cannot be processed."}, {"rule_id": "original_price_positive", "name": "Original Price Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['original_price'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The original price must be greater than 0 to calculate a meaningful markdown percentage."}, {"rule_id": "price_reduction_logic", "name": "Original Price Must Be Greater Than Reduced Price", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['original_price'] < inputs['reduced_price']", "applies_to": [], "description": "For a markdown to occur, the original price must be greater than the reduced price. If not, it suggests a markup or invalid input."}, {"rule_id": "reduced_price_non_negative", "name": "Reduced Price Cannot Be Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['reduced_price'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "A product's reduced price is typically not negative; this might indicate an erroneous input."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    original_price = inputs['original_price']\n    reduced_price = inputs['reduced_price']\n    markdown_percentage = (original_price - reduced_price) / original_price * 100\n    return round(markdown_percentage, 2)"}, "article_title": "Markup", "article_doc_id": 1626, "article_content_excerpt": "# What Is a Markup in Investing and Retailing?\n\n## What Is a Markup? \n\nA markup is the difference between an investment's lowest current among broker-dealers and the price charged to the customer for said investment. Markups occur when brokers act as principals, buying and selling securities from their own accounts at their own risk rather than receiving a fee for facilitating a transaction. Most dealers are brokers, and vice versa, and so the term is common. \n\nMarkups also appear in retail settings, where retailers mark-up the selling price of merchandise by a certain amount or percentage in order to earn a profit. A pricing method whereby a retailer establishes a selling price by adding a markup to total variable costs is called the method. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * A markup is the difference between the market price of a security personally held by a broker-dealer and the price paid by a customer.\n * Markups are a legitimate way for broker-dealers to make a profit on the sale of securities.\n * Dealers, however, are not always required to disclose the markup to customers.\n * In retail settings, markups occur when retailers increase the selling price of merchandise by a certain amount or percentage in order to earn a profit.\n\n## Understanding Markups \n\nMarkups occur when certain are available for purchase by retail investors from dealers who sell the securities directly from their own accounts. The dealer's only compensation comes in the form of the markup, the difference between the security's purchase price and the price the dealer charges to the retail investor. The dealer assumes some risk as the market price of the security could drop before being sold to investors. \n\nIn business, the markup is the between the cost to produce a good or service and its selling price. In order to ensure a profit and recover the costs to create a product or service, producers must add a markup to their total costs. They will express the markup as either a fixed amount or a percentage over the cost. \n\n## Markups vs. Markdowns \n\nA , on the other hand, occurs when a broker purchases a security from a customer at a price lower than its market value. Markdowns also occur when a dealer charges a customer a lower price for a security than the current bid price among dealers. Dealers might offer lower prices to customers in order to stimulate additional buying, which will offset their initial losses by earning them extra commissions. \n\nFor retailers, a price markdown is a deliberate reduction in the selling price of a good. There are several reasons why a retailer may decide to markdown its goods. For , the retailer may be eager to clear the shelves of old merchandise to make room for the next season's goods. They may slash prices to do so, even if it means they take a loss on the sale. Some manufacturers may come out with new models of products each year or every few years, in which case they will offer markdowns on older products rather than risk being stuck with . \n\n## Benefits of Markups \n\nMarkups are a legitimate way for broker-dealers to make a profit on the sale of securities. Securities, such as bonds, bought or sold on the market are offered with a spread. The spread is determined by the bid price, what someone is willing to pay for the bonds, and the ask price, which is what someone is willing to accept for the bonds. \n\nWhen a dealer acts a principal in the transaction, he can mark up the bid price, which creates a wider . The difference between the market spread and the dealer’s marked-up spread is the profit. \n\n### Important: \n\nIn lieu of charging a flat fee, brokers acting as principals can be compensated from the markup (gross profits) of securities held and later sold to customers.\n\n## Special Considerations for Markups \n\nThe dealer is only required to disclose the , which is typically a nominal cost. In doing so, the buyer isn’t privy to the dealer’s original transaction or the markup. From the buyer’s perspective, the only cost for t\n...[truncated]"}
