   if taxable_income > previous_limit:\n            income_in_bracket = min(taxable_income, upper_limit) - previous_limit\n            total_tax_liability += income_in_bracket * rate\n            previous_limit = upper_limit\n        else:\n            break\n    return total_tax_liability", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "i_neg_01", "name": "Non-negative Income", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['income'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Income cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "sd_neg_01", "name": "Non-negative Standard Deduction", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['standard_deduction'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Standard deduction cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "tb_type_01", "name": "Tax Brackets is List", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['tax_brackets'], list)", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'tax_brackets' input must be a list."}, {"rule_id": "tb_elem_structure_01", "name": "Tax Bracket Entry Structure", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "all(isinstance(item, (list, tuple)) and len(item) == 2 for item in inputs['tax_brackets'])", "applies_to": [], "description": "Each entry in 'tax_brackets' must be a list or tuple of two elements (upper limit, rate)."}, {"rule_id": "tb_rate_range_01", "name": "Tax Rate Range", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "any(not (0 <= rate <= 1) for upper_limit, rate in inputs['tax_brackets'])", "applies_to": [], "description": "Tax rates must be between 0 (0%) and 1 (100%)."}, {"rule_id": "tb_order_limit_01", "name": "Tax Bracket Order and Limits", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "any(inputs['tax_brackets'][i][0] >= inputs['tax_brackets'][i+1][0] for i in range(len(inputs['tax_brackets']) - 1)) or any(upper_limit < 0 for upper_limit, rate in inputs['tax_brackets'])", "applies_to": [], "description": "Tax bracket upper limits must be non-negative and strictly increasing."}, {"rule_id": "tax_lia_excess_01", "name": "Tax Liability Exceeds Income", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "compute(inputs) > inputs['income']", "applies_to": [], "description": "Calculated tax liability cannot exceed the total income."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    income = inputs['income']\n    standard_deduction = inputs['standard_deduction']\n    tax_brackets = inputs['tax_brackets']\n    taxable_income = max(0, income - standard_deduction)\n    total_tax_liability = 0.0\n    previous_limit = 0\n    for upper_limit, rate in tax_brackets:\n        if taxable_income > previous_limit:\n            income_in_bracket = min(taxable_income, upper_limit) - previous_limit\n            total_tax_liability += income_in_bracket * rate\n            previous_limit = upper_limit\n        else:\n            break\n    return total_tax_liability"}, "article_title": "Tax Liability", "article_doc_id": 3495, "article_content_excerpt": "# Tax Liability: Definition, Calculation, and Example\n\n## What Is Tax Liability? \n\nA federal tax liability is an amount that's owed to the government in taxes. It can include income taxes on earnings and capital gains taxes on assets. Both are based on brackets, a percentage of the money earned, and brackets are determined by various factors. \n\nA liability can be owed by an individual, business, or other entity. It can be owed to a state or local tax authority as well as to the federal government. \n\nYou generally have a tax liability when you earn income or generate profits by selling an investment or other asset. It's possible to have no tax liability if you don't meet the income requirements or brackets to file taxes. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Tax liability is the amount of tax debt owed to a government by an individual, corporation, or other entity.\n * Income taxes, sales tax, and capital gains tax are all forms of tax liabilities.\n * Taxes are imposed by various taxing authorities including federal, state, and local governments. \n * Taxes generate the funds necessary to pay for services such as repairing roads and maintaining a military.\n * You can lower your tax liabilities by claiming deductions, exemptions, and tax credits.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/taxliability.asp-final-a8ea9ba48a1f40149767a30961b171e6.png)\n\nInvestopedia / NoNo Flores\n\n## Understanding Tax Liability \n\nFederal, state, and local governments impose taxes and use the money that's raised to pay for services such as repairing roads, funding social programs, and maintaining a military. \n\nCompanies withhold income taxes, taxes, and from employees' wages and send the money to the government to cover their tax liabilities. \n\n### Important: \n\nSocial Security and Medicare are taxed at a flat rate that's more or less applicable to all taxpayers but U.S. federal income tax rates are . A higher income will put you in a higher tax bracket on your top-earned dollars. The percentage owed for taxes and your federal tax liability will become greater if you earn more.\n\nYour tax liability doesn't just include your income and earnings in the current year. It factors in any past years for which taxes are owed. Any unpaid taxes from previous years are also added to your federal. tax liability if back taxes are due. \n\n## How to Calculate Your Tax Liability \n\nThe most common federal tax liability for Americans is the tax on earned income. You can use the and standard deductions issued by the Internal Revenue Service (IRS) to get an idea of what yours will be for a given year. \n\nThe standard deductions for 2024 are: \n\n * $14,600 for single filers\n * $14,600 for married couples filing separately\n * $21,900 for heads of households\n * $29,200 for married couples filing jointly\n\nStandard deductions for 2025 are: \n\n * $15,000 for single filers\n * $15,000 for married couples filing separately\n * $22,500 for heads of households\n * $30,000 for married couples filing jointly\n\nThese standard deduction amounts are subtracted from the total of your earned income and you're only taxed on the remaining balance. The amount you can deduct depends on your filing status. You also have the option of itemizing your deductions instead of claiming the standard deduction, but you can't do both. Many filers find that their standard deductions are larger than the amount of itemized deductions they're eligible to claim. \n\nTax bracket income ranges are adjusted annually to keep pace with inflation so they're slightly more generous in 2025 than they were in 2024: \n \n \n<table> \n<tr> \n<th>\n\n2024 Tax Brackets\n</th> </tr> \n<tr> \n<th>\n\n**Tax Rate**\n</th> \n<th>\n\n**Single Filer in 2024**\n</th> \n<th>\n\n**Married Filing Separately in 2024**\n</th> \n<th>\n\n**Married Filing Jointly in 2024**\n</th> \n<th>\n\n**Head of Household in 2024**\n</th> </tr> \n<tr> \n<td>\n\n10%\n</td> \n<td>\n\n$11,600 or less\n</td> \n<td>\n\n$11,600 or less\n</td> \n<td>\n\n$23,200 or less\n</td> \n<td>\n\n$16,550 or less\n</td> </tr> \n<tr> \n<td>\n\n12% \n</td>\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_51", "name": "Capital Expenditure", "short_description": "Calculates the Free Cash Flow to Equity (FCFE) based on earnings, capital expenditures, depreciation, debt ratio, and change in net working capital.", "domain": "corporate_finance", "topic": "free_cash_flow", "topic_extension": true, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-51", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-358", "question_id": "test-1825", "difficulty": 3.5553480614894135, "level": "medium", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "3ec5769e97db3a6aedd27ebb86c490da6a94d83f2536cad1f54454486e97b7b9", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["Free Cash Flow to Equity", "FCFE", "equity valuation", "cash flow analysis", "company performance", "earnings", "capital expenditures", "depreciation", "debt ratio", "net working capital"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "capex_definition", "ambiguity_type": "input_definition", "trigger_signal": "capital expenditures not explicitly qualified as long-term assets", "clarification_question": "Are the provided 'capital expenditures' strictly for assets with a useful life exceeding one year (CapEx), or do they include shorter-term expenses (OpEx)?", "options": [{"label": "Strictly CapEx (useful life > 1 year) - DEFAULT", "value": "capex_only", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Includes OpEx (useful life < 1 year)", "value": "includes_opex", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Capital expenditures refer strictly to long-term assets (CapEx) with a useful life exceeding one year.", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}, {"id": "debt_ratio_basis", "ambiguity_type": "input_definition", "trigger_signal": "debt ratio not explicitly defined as total debt to total capital", "clarification_question": "Does the debt ratio represent Total Debt to Total Assets, or Total Debt to Total Capital (Debt + Equity)?", "options": [{"label": "Total Debt to Total Capital (Debt + Equity) - DEFAULT", "value": "debt_to_capital", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Total Debt to Total Assets", "value": "debt_to_assets", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "The debt ratio represents Total Debt to Total Capital (Debt + Equity).", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}], "inputs": [{"name": "earnings_to_equity", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "Earnings available to equity shareholders.", "unit": null, "aliases": ["ep"]}, {"name": "capital_expenditures", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "Capital expenditures.", "unit": null, "aliases": ["ce"]}, {"name": "depreciation", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "Depreciation.", "unit": null, "aliases": ["d"]}, {"name": "debt_ratio", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "Debt ratio.", "unit": null, "aliases": ["dr"]}, {"name": "change_in_net_working_capital", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "Change in net working capital.", "unit": null, "aliases": ["delta_c"]}], "output": {"name": "fcfe", "type": "number", "unit": "dollar", "description": "The calculated free cash flow to equity."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    ep = inputs['earnings_to_equity']\n    ce = inputs['capital_expenditures']\n    d = inputs['depreciation']\n    dr = inputs['debt_ratio']\n    delta_c = inputs['change_in_net_working_capital']\n    fcfe = ep - (ce - d) * (1 - dr) - delta_c * (1 - dr)\n    return fcfe", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "input_types_numeric", "name": "All inputs must be numeric", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['earnings_to_equity'], (int, float)) and isinstance(inputs['capital_expenditures'], (int, float)) and isinstance(inputs['depreciation'], (int, float)) and isinstance(inputs['debt_ratio'], (int, float)) and isinstance(inputs['change_in_net_working_capital'], (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "All financial inputs (earnings, capital expenditures, depreciation, debt ratio, and change in net working capital) must be provided as numbers."}, {"rule_id": "debt_ratio_range", "name": "Debt Ratio must be between 0 and 1", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (0 <= inputs['debt_ratio'] <= 1)", "applies_to": [], "description": "The debt ratio must be a value between 0 and 1, representing a proportion of debt in the capital structure. If a percentage (e.g., 40) was intended, convert it to a decimal (0.40)."}, {"rule_id": "non_negative_capex_and_depreciation", "name": "Capital Expenditures and Depreciation must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['capital_expenditures'] < 0 or inputs['depreciation'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Capital expenditures and depreciation cannot be negative values as they represent outflows or asset consumption."}, {"rule_id": "capex_greater_than_depreciation", "name": "Capital Expenditures should ideally exceed Depreciation", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['capital_expenditures'] < inputs['depreciation']", "applies_to": [], "description": "For a growing or stable company, capital expenditures typically exceed or equal depreciation, indicating reinvestment. If CapEx is less than depreciation, it might signal underinvestment, which could affect future cash flows and FCFE."}, {"rule_id": "earnings_non_negative", "name": "Earnings available to equity shareholders should be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['earnings_to_equity'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "While possible, negative earnings available to equity shareholders can significantly impact FCFE and should be reviewed."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    ep = inputs['earnings_to_equity']\n    ce = inputs['capital_expenditures']\n    d = inputs['depreciation']\n    dr = inputs['debt_ratio']\n    delta_c = inputs['change_in_net_working_capital']\n    fcfe = ep - (ce - d) * (1 - dr) - delta_c * (1 - dr)\n    return fcfe"}, "article_title": "Capital Expenditure", "article_doc_id": 63, "article_content_excerpt": "# Capital Expenditure (CapEx) Definition, Formula, and Examples\n\n## What Are Capital Expenditures (CapEx)? \n\nCapital expenditures (CapEx) are funds used by a company to acquire, upgrade, and maintain physical assets such as property, plants, buildings, technology, or equipment. CapEx is often used to by a company. Making capital expenditures on fixed assets can include repairing a roof if the useful life of the roof is extended, purchasing a piece of equipment, or building a new factory. \n\nThis type of financial outlay is made by companies in an effort to increase the scope of their operations or to add some future to the operation. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Capital expenditures are payments that are made for goods or services that are recorded or capitalized on a company's balance sheet rather than expensed on the income statement.\n * Spending is important for companies to maintain existing property and equipment and to invest in new technology and other assets for growth.\n * An item must be expensed on the income statement rather than capitalized if it has a useful life of less than one year so it isn't considered CapEx.\n * Operating expenses (OpEx) are shorter-term expenses used for the day-to-day operations of a business, unlike CapEx. \n * Examples of CapEx include the purchase of land, vehicles, buildings, or heavy machinery.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/capitalexpenditure-b2aaeae25f3648f9929b8e86061eff63.png)\n\nInvestopedia / Laura Porter\n\n## Understanding Capital Expenditures (CapEx) \n\nCapEx can tell you how much a company invests in existing and new fixed assets to maintain or grow its business. It's any type of expense that a company capitalizes or shows on its balance sheet as an investment rather than on its income statement as an expenditure. Capitalizing an asset requires that the company spread the cost of the expenditure over the useful life of the asset. \n\nThe amount of capital expenditures a company is likely to have depends on its industry. Some of the most capital-intensive industries have the highest levels of capital expenditures. They include oil exploration and production, telecommunications, manufacturing, and utility industries. \n\nCapEx can be found in the cash flow from investing activities in a company's cash flow statement. Companies can highlight CapEx in various ways. You may see it listed as capital spending, purchases of (PP&E), or acquisition expenses. \n\nYou can also calculate capital expenditures using data from a company's income statement and balance sheet. Find the amount of expense recorded for the current period on the income statement. Locate the current period's property, plant, and equipment line-item balance on the balance sheet. \n\nFind the company's PP&E balance from the prior period. Take the difference between the two to find the change in the company's PP&E balance. Add the change in PP&E to the depreciation expense for the current period to arrive at the company's current-period CapEx spending. \n\n## Types of CapEx \n\nMany types of assets can attribute long-term value to a company. Several types of purchases may be considered CapEx. \n\n * **Buildings** may be used for office space, manufacturing of goods, storage of inventory, or other purposes.\n * **Land** may be used for further development. Accounting treatment can vary for land that's specifically held as a speculative long-term investment.\n * **Equipment** and machinery may be used to manufacture goods and convert into final products for sale.\n * **Computers** or **servers** may be used to support a company's operational aspects, including the logistics, reporting, and communication of operations. Software may also be treated as CapEx in certain circumstances.\n * **Furniture** can be used to furnish an office building, making the space usable by staff, clients, and customers.\n * **Vehicles** may be used to transport goods and pick up clients or by staff for business purposes.\n * **Patents** can hold long-term value if the r\n...[truncated]"}
