required": true, "description": "The highest price of the asset for the period.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "low", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The lowest price of the asset for the period.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "volume", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The traded volume of the asset for the period.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "previous_ad", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The Accumulation/Distribution (A/D) value from the previous period.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "updated_ad_value", "type": "number", "unit": "shares", "description": "The updated Accumulation/Distribution (A/D) line value for the current period, rounded to the nearest integer."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    close_price = inputs['close']\n    high_price = inputs['high']\n    low_price = inputs['low']\n    volume = inputs['volume']\n    previous_ad_value = inputs['previous_ad']\n    if high_price == low_price:\n        mfm = 0.0\n    else:\n        mfm = (close_price - low_price - (high_price - close_price)) / (high_price - low_price)\n    money_flow_volume = mfm * volume\n    updated_ad_value = previous_ad_value + money_flow_volume\n    return round(updated_ad_value)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "ad_001", "name": "HighGreaterThanLow", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['high'] < inputs['low']", "applies_to": [], "description": "The high price must be greater than or equal to the low price. If high equals low, the Money Flow Multiplier will be 0, as handled by the formula."}, {"rule_id": "ad_002", "name": "NonNegativePrices", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['close'] < 0 or inputs['high'] < 0 or inputs['low'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Closing, high, and low prices must be non-negative values."}, {"rule_id": "ad_003", "name": "ClosePriceWithinRange", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['close'] < inputs['low'] or inputs['close'] > inputs['high']", "applies_to": [], "description": "The closing price must be within or equal to the low and high prices for the period."}, {"rule_id": "ad_004", "name": "NonNegativeVolume", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['volume'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Trading volume must be a non-negative value."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    close_price = inputs['close']\n    high_price = inputs['high']\n    low_price = inputs['low']\n    volume = inputs['volume']\n    previous_ad_value = inputs['previous_ad']\n    if high_price == low_price:\n        mfm = 0.0\n    else:\n        mfm = (close_price - low_price - (high_price - close_price)) / (high_price - low_price)\n    money_flow_volume = mfm * volume\n    updated_ad_value = previous_ad_value + money_flow_volume\n    return round(updated_ad_value)"}, "article_title": "Accumulation/Distribution Indicator (A/D)", "article_doc_id": 4387, "article_content_excerpt": "# Accumulation/Distribution Indicator (A/D): What it Tells You\n\n## What Is the Accumulation/Distribution Indicator (A/D)? \n\nThe accumulation/distribution indicator (A/D) is a cumulative indicator that uses and price to assess whether a stock is being accumulated or distributed. The A/D measure seeks to identify between the stock price and the volume flow. This provides insight into how strong a trend is. If the price is rising but the indicator is falling, then it suggests that buying or accumulation volume may not be enough to support the price rise and a price decline could be forthcoming. \n\n### Key Takeways\n\n * The accumulation/distribution (A/D) line gauges supply and demand of an asset or security by looking at where the price closed within the period’s range and then multiplying that by volume.\n * The A/D indicator is cumulative, meaning one period’s value is added or subtracted from the last.\n * In general, a rising A/D line helps confirm a rising price trend, while a falling A/D line helps confirm a price downtrend.\n\n## The Accumulation/Distribution Indicator (A/D) Formula \n\n\\begin{aligned}&\\text{MFM} = \\frac {(\\text{Close} - \\text{Low} ) - ( \\text{High} - \\text{Close} ) } {\\text{High} - \\text{Low} } \\\\\\&\\textbf{where:}\\\\\\&\\text{MFM} = \\text{Money Flow Multiplier} \\\\\\&\\text{Close} = \\text{Closing price} \\\\\\&\\text{Low} = \\text{Low price for the period} \\\\\\&\\text{High} = \\text{High price for the period} \\\\\\ \\end{aligned}\n\n\\begin{aligned}&\\text{Money Flow Volume} = \\text{MFM} \\times \\text{Period Volume} \\\\\\ \\end{aligned}\n\n\\begin{aligned}&\\text{A/D} = \\text{Previous A/D} + \\text{CMFV}\\\\\\&\\textbf{where:}\\\\\\&\\text{CMFV} = \\text{Current period money flow volume} \\\\\\ \\end{aligned}\n\nHow to Calculate the A/D Line \n\n 1. Start by calculating the multiplier. Note the most recent period’s , high, and low to calculate.\n 2. Use the multiplier and the current period’s volume to calculate the volume.\n 3. Add the money flow volume to the last A/D value. For the first calculation, use money flow volume as the first value.\n 4. Repeat the process as each period ends, adding/subtracting the new money flow volume to/from the prior total. This is A/D.\n\n## What Does the Accumulation/Distribution Indicator (A/D) Tell You? \n\nThe A/D line helps to show how factors are influencing price. A/D can move in the same direction as price changes or in the opposite direction. \n\nThe multiplier in the calculation provides a gauge for how strong the buying or selling was during a particular period. It does this by determining whether the price closed in the upper or lower portion of its . This is then multiplied by the volume. Therefore, when a stock closes near the high of the period’s range and has high volume, it will result in a large A/D jump. Alternatively, if the price finishes near the high of the range but volume is low, or if the volume is high but the price finishes more toward the middle of the range, then the A/D will not move up as much. \n\nThe same concepts apply when the price closes in the lower portion of the period’s price range. Both volume and where the price closes within the period’s range determine how much the A/D will decline. \n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/dotdash_INV-final-Accumulation-Distribution-Indicator-A-D-Apr-2021-01-b3e86084a45649438b410115afe16139.jpg)\n\nImage by Sabrina Jiang © Investopedia 2021\n\nThe and potentially spot forthcoming reversals. If a price is in a while the A/D line is in an uptrend, then the indicator shows there may be buying pressure and the security’s price may reverse to the upside. Conversely, if a security’s price is in an uptrend while the A/D line is in a downtrend, then the indicator shows there may be selling pressure, or higher distribution. This warns that the price may be due for a decline. \n\nIn both cases, the steepness of the A/D line provides insight into the . A strongly rising A/D line confirms a strongly rising price. Similarly, if the price is falling and the A/D is also falling, th\n...[truncated]"}
