ratio", "type": "number", "unit": "%", "description": "The retention ratio expressed as a percentage."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    total_dividends = inputs['total_dividends']\n    net_income = inputs['net_income']\n    if net_income <= 0:\n        raise ValueError('Net income must be greater than zero.')\n    payout_ratio = total_dividends / net_income * 100\n    retention_ratio = 100 - payout_ratio\n    return round(retention_ratio, 2)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "ni_001", "name": "Net Income Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['net_income'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["net_income"], "description": "Net income must be a positive value to ensure a meaningful retention ratio calculation."}, {"rule_id": "td_001", "name": "Total Dividends Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['total_dividends'] < 0", "applies_to": ["total_dividends"], "description": "Total dividends paid cannot be a negative value."}, {"rule_id": "td_ni_001", "name": "Dividends vs. Net Income Plausibility", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['total_dividends'] > inputs['net_income'] and inputs['net_income'] > 0", "applies_to": ["total_dividends", "net_income"], "description": "A company paying more in dividends than its net income suggests an unsustainable practice. While possible, it warrants an alert."}, {"rule_id": "type_td", "name": "Total Dividends Type Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['total_dividends'], (int, float))", "applies_to": ["total_dividends"], "description": "total_dividends must be a numeric value."}, {"rule_id": "type_ni", "name": "Net Income Type Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['net_income'], (int, float))", "applies_to": ["net_income"], "description": "net_income must be a numeric value."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    total_dividends = inputs['total_dividends']\n    net_income = inputs['net_income']\n    if net_income <= 0:\n        raise ValueError('Net income must be greater than zero.')\n    payout_ratio = total_dividends / net_income * 100\n    retention_ratio = 100 - payout_ratio\n    return round(retention_ratio, 2)"}, "article_title": "Payout Ratio", "article_doc_id": 2523, "article_content_excerpt": "# Payout Ratio: What It Is, How to Use It, and How to Calculate It\n\n## What Is the Payout Ratio? \n\nThe payout ratio is a financial metric that shows the proportion of earnings a company pays its shareholders in the form of . It's expressed as a percentage of the company’s total but it can refer to the dividends paid out as a percentage of a company’s cash flow in some cases. The payout ratio is also known as the dividend payout ratio. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * The payout ratio is also known as the dividend payout ratio.\n * It shows the percentage of a company’s earnings that are paid out as dividends to shareholders.\n * A low payout ratio can signal that a company is reinvesting the bulk of its earnings into expanding operations.\n * A payout ratio over 100% indicates that the company is paying out more in dividends than its earnings can support and this could be an unsustainable practice.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/DDM_INV_payout-ratio_final-112322-03f9cc3452714cf49b380d9fe74d9700.jpg)\n\nEliana Rodgers / Investopedia\n\n## Understanding the Payout Ratio \n\nThe payout ratio is a key financial metric that's used to of a company’s dividend payment program. It's the amount of dividends paid to shareholders relative to the total net income of a company.\n\nThe payout ratio is an important metric for determining the sustainability of a company’s dividend payment program but other factors should be considered as well. There's no single number that defines an ideal payout ratio because the adequacy largely depends on the in which a given company operates. \n\nCompanies in such as utilities, pipelines, and telecommunications tend to boast stable earnings and that can support high payouts over the long haul. Income-driven investors have been advised to look for a ratio in the neighborhood of 60%, however. Even 35% to 55% is considered strong.\n\nCompanies in cyclical industries typically make less reliable payouts because their profits are vulnerable to macroeconomic fluctuations. \n\n### Important: \n\nPeople spend less of their incomes on new cars, entertainment, and luxury goods in times of economic hardship. Companies in these sectors consequently tend to experience earnings peaks and valleys that fall in line with economic cycles.\n\n## Example of the Payout Ratio \n\nLet’s assume Company A has earnings per share of $1 and pays dividends per share of $0.60. The payout ratio would be 60% (0.6 ÷ 1). Let’s further assume that Company Z has earnings per share of $2 and dividends per share of $1.50. The payout ratio is 75% (1.5 ÷ 2) in this scenario. \n\nCompany A pays out a smaller percentage of its earnings to shareholders as dividends, giving it a more sustainable payout ratio than Company Z. \n\n## Payout Ratio Formula \n\n\\begin{aligned} &DPR=\\dfrac{\\textit{Total dividends}}{\\textit{Net income}} \\\\\\ &\\textbf{where:} \\\\\\ &DPR = \\text{Divided payout ratio (or simply payout ratio)}\\\\\\ \\end{aligned}\n\nSome companies pay out all their earnings to shareholders. Others dole out just a portion and funnel the remaining assets back into their businesses. The measure of retained earnings is known as the retention ratio. The higher the retention ratio, the lower the payout ratio.\n\nThe payout ratio would be $25,000 ÷ $100,000 = 25% if a company reports a net income of $100,000 and issues $25,000 in dividends. This implies that the company boasts a 75% retention ratio. It records the remaining $75,000 of its income for the period in its financial statements as retained earnings. This appears in the equity section of the company’s the following year.\n\nCompanies with the best long-term records of dividend payments generally have stable payout ratios over many years. But a payout ratio greater than 100% suggests that a company is paying out more in dividends than its earnings can support. This might be cause for concern regarding sustainability. \n\n## What Does the Payout Ratio Tell You?\n\nThe payout ratio is a key financial metric used to determine the sustainability\n...[truncated]"}
