he number of years the investment was held.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "annualized_hpr", "type": "number", "unit": "%", "description": "The annualized holding period return as a percentage."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    initial_value = inputs['initial_value']\n    final_value = inputs['final_value']\n    years = inputs['years']\n    holding_period_return = (final_value - initial_value) / initial_value\n    annualized_hpr = (1 + holding_period_return) ** (1 / years) - 1\n    return annualized_hpr * 100", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "initial_value_type_check", "name": "Initial Value Type Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('initial_value'), (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'initial_value' input must be a number (integer or float)."}, {"rule_id": "final_value_type_check", "name": "Final Value Type Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('final_value'), (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'final_value' input must be a number (integer or float)."}, {"rule_id": "years_type_check", "name": "Years Type Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('years'), (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'years' input must be a number (integer or float)."}, {"rule_id": "initial_value_positive", "name": "Initial investment must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['initial_value'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The initial investment value must be a positive number."}, {"rule_id": "years_positive", "name": "Years held must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['years'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The number of years the investment was held must be a positive number."}, {"rule_id": "holding_period_return_lower_bound", "name": "Holding Period Return cannot be less than -100%", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "(inputs['final_value'] - inputs['initial_value']) / inputs['initial_value'] <= -1.0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The total holding period return cannot be less than -1.0 (-100%), meaning the final value cannot be less than or equal to zero for a positive initial investment. This ensures the term (1+HPR) is non-negative for the power calculation."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    initial_value = inputs['initial_value']\n    final_value = inputs['final_value']\n    years = inputs['years']\n    holding_period_return = (final_value - initial_value) / initial_value\n    annualized_hpr = (1 + holding_period_return) ** (1 / years) - 1\n    return annualized_hpr * 100"}, "article_title": "Holding Period Return (Yield)", "article_doc_id": 2051, "article_content_excerpt": "# Holding Period Return/Yield: Definition, Formula, and Example\n\n## What Is the Holding Period Return/Yield? \n\nHolding period return is the received from holding an asset or of assets over a period of time, known as the . It is generally expressed as a percentage and is particularly useful for comparing returns on investments purchased at different periods in time. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Holding period return (or yield) is the total return earned on an investment during the time that it has been held.\n * A holding period is the amount of time the investment is held by an investor, or the period between the purchase and sale of a security.\n * Holding period return is useful for making like comparisons between returns on investments purchased at different periods in time.\n\n## Understanding Holding Period Return \n\nHolding period return is calculated on the (income plus changes in value). It is particularly useful for comparing returns between investments . \n\nStarting on the day after the security's acquisition and continuing until the day of its disposal or sale, the holding period determines tax implications. For example, Sarah bought 100 shares of stock on Jan. 2, 2023. When determining her holding period, she begins counting on Jan. 3, 2023. The third day of each month after that counts as the start of a new month, regardless of how many days each month contains. \n\nIf Sarah sold her stock on Dec. 23, 2023, she would realize a short-term capital gain or because her holding period is less than one year. If she sells her stock on Jan. 3, 2024, she would realize a long-term capital gain or loss because her holding period is more than one year.\n\n## Calculating Holding Period Return \n\nHolding Period Return (HPR) and annualized HPR for returns over multiple years can be calculated as follows:\n\n\\begin{aligned}&\\textit{Holding Period Return}\\\\\\&\\qquad=\\frac{\\textit{Income }+(\\textit{End Of Period Value }-\\textit{ Initial Value})}{\\textit{Initial Value}} \\end{aligned}\n\nReturns computed for regular time periods such as quarters or years can be converted to a holding period return as well. \n\n## Example of Holding Period Return/Yield \n\nThe following are some examples of calculating holding period return:\n\n1\\. What is the HPR for an who bought a stock a year ago at $50 and received $5 in over the year if the stock is now trading at $60?\n\n\\begin{aligned}HPR=\\frac{5+(60-50)}{50}=30\\%\\end{aligned}\n\n2\\. Which investment performed better: X, which was held for three years and appreciated from $100 to $150, providing $5 in distributions, or Mutual Fund B, which went from $200 to $320 and generated $10 in over four years?\n\n\\begin{aligned}&\\textit{HPR for Fund X}=\\frac{5+(150-100)}{100}=55\\%\\\\\\\\[+.010pt]&\\textit{HPR for Fund B}=\\frac{10+(320-200)}{200}=65\\%\\end{aligned}\n\nNote: Fund B had the higher HPR, but it was held for four years, as opposed to the three years for which Fund X was held. Since the time periods are different, this requires annualized HPR to be calculated, as shown below.\n\n3\\. Calculation of annualized HPR:\n\n\\begin{aligned}&\\textit{Annualized HPR for Fund X}\\\\\\&\\qquad=(0.55+1)^{1/3}-1=15.73\\%\\\\\\&\\textit{Annualized HPR for Fund B}\\\\\\&\\qquad=(0.65+1)^{1/4}-1=13.34\\%\\end{aligned}\n\nThus, despite having the lower HPR, Fund X was the superior investment.\n\n4\\. Your stock portfolio had the following returns in the four quarters of a given year: +8%, -5%, +6%, +4%. How did it compare against the index, which had total returns of 12% over the year?\n\n\\begin{aligned}&\\textit{HPR for your stock portfolio}\\\\\\&\\qquad=[(1+0.08)\\times(1-0.05)\\times(1+0.06)\\times(1+0.04)]\\\\\\&\\qquad\\quad-1=13.1\\%\\end{aligned}\n\nYour portfolio, therefore, outperformed the index by more than a percentage point. (However, the risk of the portfolio should also be compared to that of the index to evaluate if the added return was generated by taking significantly higher risk.) \n\n## Is Holding Period Return the Same as Rate of Return?\n\nPretty much, yes. The rate of return\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_961", "name": "Moving Average (MA)", "short_description": "Calculate the simple moving average (SMA) of a list of prices over a specified period. This function computes the simple moving average for financial market analysis to help smooth out price data by taking the arithmetic mean of a set of prices.", "domain": "financial_markets", "topic": "moving_average", "topic_extension": true, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-961", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-752", "question_id": "test-1597", "difficulty": 2.995732273553991, "level": "medium", "execution_smoke_ok": false, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "execution_smoke_error": "name 'calculate_simple_moving_average_series' is not defined", "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "5dd7bab5a9c5e3876850721081319a1267b4e76a5239cfdd16c75af1e5f8ff96", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["Simple Moving Average", "SMA", "technical analysis", "stock indicator", "smooth price data", "trend identification", "market analysis", "stock prices", "average price"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "moving_average_type", "ambiguity_type": "calculation_method", "trigger_signal": "moving average mentioned without specifying simple or exponential", "clarification_question": "Are you calculating a Simple Moving Average (SMA) or an Exponential Moving Average (EMA)?", "options": [{"label": "Simple Moving Average (SMA) - DEFAULT", "value": "simple_moving_average", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Exponential Moving Average (EMA)", "value": "exponential_moving_average", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "hard", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Simple Moving Average (SMA)", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}, {"id": "output_precision", "ambiguity_type": "precision", "trigger_signal": "output rounding not explicitly specified", "clarification_question": "To what decimal precision should the final Simple Moving Average be rounded?", "options": [{"label": "Round to two decimal places - DEFAULT", "value": "two_decimal_places", "is_default": true}, {"label": "No rounding", "value": "no_rounding", "is_default": false}, {"label": "Round to one decimal place", "value": "one_decimal_place", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Round to two decimal places", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "prices", "type": "array[number]", "required": true, "description": "A list of prices (e.g., daily closing prices of a stock).", "unit": null, "aliases": ["stock_prices", "closing_prices", "price_series"]}, {"name": "period", "type": "integer", "required": true, "description": "The number of periods over which to calculate the SMA.", "unit": null, "aliases": ["sma_period", "window_size"]}, {"name": "sma_index", "type": "integer", "required": true, "description": "The index (0-based) of the specific Simple Moving Average value to retrieve from the calculated series.", "unit": null, "aliases": ["index_of_sma"]}], "output": {"name": "simple_moving_average", "type": "number", "unit": null, "description": "The requested Simple Moving Average value, rounded to two decimal places."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def calculate_simple_moving_average_series(prices: list, period: int) -> list:\n    if not (isinstance(prices, list) and all((isinstance(p, (int, float)) for p in prices))):\n        raise ValueError('Prices must be a list of numbers.')\n    if not (isinstance(period, int) and period > 0 and (period <= len(prices))):\n        raise ValueError('Period must be a positive integer and not exceed the length of the prices list.')\n    sma_series = []\n    for i in range(len(prices) - period + 1):\n        sma_series.append(sum(prices[i:i + period]) / period)\n    return sma_series\n\ndef compute(inputs):\n    prices = inputs['prices']\n    period = inputs['period']\n    sma_index = inputs['sma_index']\n    all_smas = calculate_simple_moving_average_series(prices, period)\n    if not (isinstance(sma_index, int) and 0 <= sma_index < len(all_smas)):\n        raise IndexError(f'SMA index {sma_index} is out of bounds for the calculated SMA series of length {len(all_smas)}.')\n    result = all_smas[sma_index]\n    return round(result, 2)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "sma_001", "name": "Prices list structural integrity", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['prices'], list) and all(isinstance(p, (int, float)) for p in inputs['prices'])", "applies_to": ["prices"], "description": "The 'prices' input must be a list where all elements are numbers (integers or floats)."}, {"rule_id": "sma_002", "name": "Prices list non-empty", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "len(inputs['prices']) > 0", "applies_to": ["prices"], "description": "The 'prices' list cannot be empty."}, {"rule_id": "sma_003", "name": "Period type check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['period'], int)", "applies_to": ["period"], "description": "The 'period' input must be an integer."}, {"rule_id": "sma_004", "name": "Period value bounds", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "inputs['period'] > 0 and inputs['period'] <= len(inputs['prices'])", "applies_to": ["period", "prices"], "description": "The 'period' must be a positive integer and cannot exceed the number of prices provided."}, {"rule_id": "sma_005", "name": "SMA Index type check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['sma_index'], int)", "applies_to": ["sma_index"], "description": "The 'sma_index' input must be an integer."}, {"rule_id": "sma_006", "name": "SMA Index value bounds", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "inputs['sma_index'] >= 0 and inputs['sma_index'] < (len(inputs['prices']) - inputs['period'] + 1)", "applies_to": ["sma_index", "prices", "period"], "description": "The 'sma_index' must be a non-negative integer and within the valid range of calculated SMA values. This range is determined by the length of prices and the period."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": false, "error": "name 'calculate_simple_moving_average_series' is not defined", "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def calculate_simple_moving_average_series(prices: list, period: int) -> list:\n    if not (isinstance(prices, list) and all((isinstance(p, (int, float)) for p in prices))):\n        raise ValueError('Prices must be a list of numbers.')\n    if not (isinstance(period, int) and period > 0 and (period <= len(prices))):\n        raise ValueError('Period must be a positive integer and not exceed the length of the prices list.')\n    sma_series = []\n    for i in range(len(prices) - period + 1):\n        sma_series.append(sum(prices[i:i + period]) / period)\n    return sma_series\n\ndef compute(inputs):\n    prices = inputs['prices']\n    period = inputs['period']\n    sma_index = inputs['sma_index']\n    all_smas = calculate_simple_moving_average_series(prices, period)\n    if not (isinstance(sma_index, int) and 0 <= sma_index < len(all_smas)):\n        raise IndexError(f'SMA index {sma_index} is out of bounds for the calculated SMA series of length {len(all_smas)}.')\n    result = all_smas[sma_index]\n    return round(result, 2)"}, "article_title": "Moving Average (MA)", "article_doc_id": 1793, "article_content_excerpt": "# Moving Average (MA): Purpose, Uses, Formula, and Examples\n\n## What Is a Moving Average (MA)? \n\nIn finance, a moving average (MA) is a stock indicator commonly used in . The reason for calculating the moving average of a stock is to help smooth out the price data by creating a constantly updated . \n\nBy calculating the moving average, the impacts of random, short-term fluctuations on the price of a stock over a specified time frame are mitigated. Simple moving averages (SMAs) use a simple arithmetic average of prices over some timespan, while exponential moving averages (EMAs) place greater weight on more recent prices than older ones over the time period. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * A moving average (MA) is a stock indicator commonly used in technical analysis.\n * The moving average helps to level the price data over a specified period by creating a constantly updated average price.\n * A simple moving average (SMA) is a calculation that takes the arithmetic mean of a given set of prices over a specific number of days in the past.\n * An exponential moving average (EMA) is a weighted average that gives greater importance to the price of a stock in more recent days, making it an indicator that is more responsive to new information.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/MOVING-AVERAGE-FINAL-21674874615f49c19444bbd9d2086c51.jpg)\n\nInvestopedia / Yurle Villegas\n\n## Understanding a Moving Average (MA) \n\nMoving averages are calculated to identify the or to determine its support and resistance levels. It is a trend-following or lagging indicator because it is based on past prices. \n\nThe longer the period for the moving average, the greater the lag. A 200-day moving average will have a much greater degree of lag than a 20-day MA because it contains prices for the past 200 days. Fifty-day and 200-day moving average figures are widely followed by investors and traders and are considered to be important . \n\nInvestors may choose different periods of varying lengths to calculate moving averages based on their trading objectives. Shorter moving averages are typically used for short-term trading, while longer-term moving averages are more suited for long-term investors. \n\nWhile it is impossible to predict the future movement of a specific stock, using technical analysis and research can help make better predictions. A rising moving average indicates that the security is in an uptrend, while a declining moving average indicates that it is in a downtrend. \n\nSimilarly, upward momentum is confirmed with a bullish , which occurs when a short-term moving average crosses above a longer-term moving average. Conversely, downward momentum is confirmed with a bearish crossover, which occurs when a short-term moving average crosses below a longer-term moving average. \n\n## Types of Moving Averages \n\n### Simple Moving Average \n\nA (SMA) is calculated by taking the arithmetic mean of a given set of values over a specified period. A set of numbers, or prices of stocks, are added together and then divided by the number of prices in the set. The formula for calculating the simple moving average of a security is as follows:\n\n\\begin{aligned} &SMA = \\frac{ A_1 + A_2 + \\dotso + A_n }{ n } \\\\\\ &\\textbf{where:} \\\\\\ &A = \\text{Average in period } n \\\\\\ &n = \\text{Number of time periods} \\\\\\ \\end{aligned}\n\nCharting stock prices over 50 days using a simple moving average may look like this: \n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/dotdash_INV-final-Simple-Moving-Average-SMA-May-2021-01-98751e52a2d844a795d8d11434852d7c.jpg)\n\nCharting a 50-Day Simple Moving Average.\n\nImage by Sabrina Jiang © Investopedia 2021\n\n### Exponential Moving Average (EMA) \n\nThe gives more weight to recent prices in an attempt to make them more responsive to new information. To , the simple moving average (SMA) over a particular period is calculated first. \n\nThen calculate the multiplier for weighting the EMA, known as the \"smoothing factor,\" which typically follows the formula: [2/(selected time period + 1)]\n...[truncated]"}
