ired": true, "description": "The number of option contracts written (typically 1 contract = 100 shares).", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "premium_received", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The premium received per share from writing the option.", "unit": "currency", "aliases": []}, {"name": "strike_price", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The strike price at which the option can be exercised.", "unit": "currency", "aliases": []}, {"name": "market_price", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The current market price of the underlying security.", "unit": "currency", "aliases": []}, {"name": "covered", "type": "boolean", "required": true, "description": "Indicates whether the option position is covered (e.g., the writer owns the underlying shares for a call).", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "shares_bought_price", "type": "number", "required": false, "description": "The price at which the underlying shares were bought if the position is covered. Assumed 0 if not provided.", "unit": "currency", "aliases": ["cost_basis_of_shares"]}], "output": {"name": "profit_or_loss", "type": "number", "unit": "currency", "description": "The total profit or loss of the option writing position."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    contracts = inputs['contracts']\n    premium_received = inputs['premium_received']\n    strike_price = inputs['strike_price']\n    market_price = inputs['market_price']\n    covered = inputs['covered']\n    shares_bought_price = inputs.get('shares_bought_price', 0)\n    shares = contracts * 100\n    total_premium_received = premium_received * shares\n    if covered:\n        intrinsic_value = max(0, market_price - strike_price)\n        profit_or_loss = total_premium_received - intrinsic_value * shares + (market_price - shares_bought_price) * shares\n    else:\n        intrinsic_value = min(0, market_price - strike_price)\n        profit_or_loss = total_premium_received + intrinsic_value * shares\n    return round(profit_or_loss)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "contracts_type_check", "name": "Contracts must be an integer", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not isinstance(inputs['contracts'], int)", "applies_to": [], "description": "The number of option contracts must be an integer for accurate calculation."}, {"rule_id": "contracts_positive_check", "name": "Contracts must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['contracts'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The number of option contracts must be greater than zero."}, {"rule_id": "premium_received_non_negative_check", "name": "Premium received must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['premium_received'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The premium received per share from writing the option cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "strike_price_non_negative_check", "name": "Strike price must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['strike_price'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The strike price at which the option can be exercised cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "market_price_non_negative_check", "name": "Market price must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['market_price'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The current market price of the underlying security cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "shares_bought_price_plausibility", "name": "Shares bought price for covered position plausibility", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['covered'] and inputs['shares_bought_price'] < 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "For a covered position, the shares bought price is typically non-negative. A negative value suggests an unusual scenario or data entry error."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    contracts = inputs['contracts']\n    premium_received = inputs['premium_received']\n    strike_price = inputs['strike_price']\n    market_price = inputs['market_price']\n    covered = inputs['covered']\n    shares_bought_price = inputs.get('shares_bought_price', 0)\n    shares = contracts * 100\n    total_premium_received = premium_received * shares\n    if covered:\n        intrinsic_value = max(0, market_price - strike_price)\n        profit_or_loss = total_premium_received - intrinsic_value * shares + (market_price - shares_bought_price) * shares\n    else:\n        intrinsic_value = min(0, market_price - strike_price)\n        profit_or_loss = total_premium_received + intrinsic_value * shares\n    return round(profit_or_loss)"}, "article_title": "Writer", "article_doc_id": 5013, "article_content_excerpt": "# Option Writer: Overview of Long and Short Strategies\n\n## What Is an Option Writer? \n\nA writer (sometimes referred to as a ) is the seller of an option who opens a position to collect a payment from the buyer. Writers can sell call or put options that are covered or uncovered. An uncovered position is also referred to as a . For example, the owner of 100 shares of stock can sell a on those shares to collect a premium from the buyer of the option; the position is covered because the writer owns the stock that underlies the option and has agreed to sell those shares at the of the contract. A covered put option would involve being short the shares and writing a put on them. If an option is not covered the option writer theoretically faces the risk of very large losses if the underlying moves against them. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Option writers collect a premium in exchange for giving the buyer the right to buy or sell the underlying at an agreed price within an agreed period of time.\n * A put or call can be covered or uncovered, with uncovered positions carrying much greater risk.\n * Option writers prefer if options expire worthless and out-of-the-money, so they get to keep the entire premium. Option buyers want the options to expire in-the-money.\n\n## Understanding the Writer \n\nOption buyers are given the right to buy or sell an underlying security, within a certain time frame, at a specified price by the option seller or writer. For this right, the option has a cost, called the premium. The premium is what option writers are after. They get paid upfront, but face high risk (if uncovered) if the option becomes very valuable to the buyer. For example, a put writer is hoping an underlying stock won't drop below the strike price, the buyer is hoping it will.The further below the put's strike price the underlying falls, the larger the loss for the writer, and the bigger the profit for the put buyer. \n\nAn option is uncovered when the writer does not have an offsetting position in the account. For example, the writer of a , who agrees to buy shares at the contract’s strike price, is uncovered if there is not a corresponding in their account to offset the risk of buying shares. \n\nThe writer faces potentially large losses if the options they write are uncovered. That means they don't own shares they write calls on, or don't hold short shares in the options they write puts on. The large losses can result from an adverse move in the underlying's price. With a call, for example, the writer is agreeing to sell shares to the buyer at the strike price, say $50. But assume that the stock, currently trading at $45, is offered a by another company for $70 per share. The underlying instantly launch to $65 and oscillates there. It doesn't go to $70 because there is a chance the deal won't go through. The writer of the option now needs to buy shares at $65 to sell them at $50 to the option buyer, if the buyer the option. Even if the option hasn't expired yet, the option writer is still facing a large loss, since they will need to buy the option back for roughly $15 more ($65 - $50) than they wrote it for to close out the position. \n\nThe primary objective for option writers is to generate income by collecting premiums when contracts are sold to open a position. The largest gains occur when contracts that have been sold expire . For call writers, options expire out-of-the-money when the closes below the strike price of the contract. Out-of-the-money puts expire when the price of the underlying shares closes above the strike price. In both situations, the writer keeps the entire premium received for the sale of the contracts. \n\nWhen the option moves , the write faces a potential loss because they need to buy the option back for more than they received. \n\n is considered to be a conservative strategy for generating income. Uncovered or naked option writing is highly speculative because of the potential for unlimited losses. \n\n## Call Writing \n\nSome trad\n...[truncated]"}
