ownside risk (e.g., as in PMPT)?", "options": [{"label": "Standard Deviation (Volatility) — DEFAULT", "value": "standard_deviation", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Downside Risk (e.g., Sortino Ratio components)", "value": "downside_risk", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Standard deviation (volatility)", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "weights", "type": "array[number]", "required": true, "description": "A list of weights representing the proportion of the total portfolio value that is invested in each asset.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "variances", "type": "array[number]", "required": true, "description": "A list of variances for each asset in the portfolio.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "correlations", "type": "array[array[number]]", "required": true, "description": "A JSON array-of-arrays representing the numeric correlation matrix.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "portfolio_risk", "type": "number", "unit": null, "description": "The standard deviation of the portfolio, representing its risk."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    weights = inputs['weights']\n    variances = inputs['variances']\n    correlations = inputs['correlations']\n    num_assets = len(weights)\n    portfolio_variance = 0.0\n    for i in range(num_assets):\n        for j in range(num_assets):\n            portfolio_variance += weights[i] * weights[j] * correlations[i][j] * variances[i] ** 0.5 * variances[j] ** 0.5\n    portfolio_risk = portfolio_variance ** 0.5\n    return round(portfolio_risk, 4)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "dimension_consistency", "name": "Input Dimension Consistency Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "len(inputs['variances']) != len(inputs['weights']) or len(inputs['correlations']) != len(inputs['weights']) or any(len(row) != len(inputs['weights']) for row in inputs['correlations'])", "applies_to": ["weights", "variances", "correlations"], "description": "Ensures that the number of assets implied by weights, variances, and the correlation matrix are consistent."}, {"rule_id": "weights_sum_to_one", "name": "Portfolio Weights Sum to One Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "abs(sum(inputs['weights']) - 1.0) > 1e-6", "applies_to": ["weights"], "description": "Verifies that the sum of all portfolio weights is approximately equal to 1 (100%)."}, {"rule_id": "non_negative_weights", "name": "Non-Negative Weights Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "any(w < 0 for w in inputs['weights'])", "applies_to": ["weights"], "description": "Ensures that all portfolio weights are non-negative, implying no short selling for this calculation context."}, {"rule_id": "non_negative_variances", "name": "Non-Negative Variances Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "any(v < 0 for v in inputs['variances'])", "applies_to": ["variances"], "description": "Ensures that all asset variances are non-negative, as variance cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "correlation_diagonal_ones", "name": "Correlation Matrix Diagonal Ones Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "any(inputs['correlations'][i][i] != 1 for i in range(len(inputs['weights'])))", "applies_to": ["correlations"], "description": "Verifies that all diagonal elements of the correlation matrix are exactly 1, representing an asset's correlation with itself."}, {"rule_id": "correlation_bounds", "name": "Correlation Values Bounds Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "any(val < -1 or val > 1 for row in inputs['correlations'] for val in row)", "applies_to": ["correlations"], "description": "Ensures that all correlation coefficients are within the valid range of -1 to +1."}, {"rule_id": "weights_structure", "name": "Weights List Structure Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['weights'], list) and all(isinstance(x, (int, float)) for x in inputs['weights'])", "applies_to": ["weights"], "description": "Verifies that 'weights' is a list and all its elements are numbers."}, {"rule_id": "correlations_structure", "name": "Correlation Matrix Structure Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['correlations'], list) and all(isinstance(row, list) and all(isinstance(x, (int, float)) for x in row) for row in inputs['correlations'])", "applies_to": ["correlations"], "description": "Verifies that 'correlations' is a list of lists and all its elements are numbers, forming a valid matrix structure."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    weights = inputs['weights']\n    variances = inputs['variances']\n    correlations = inputs['correlations']\n    num_assets = len(weights)\n    portfolio_variance = 0.0\n    for i in range(num_assets):\n        for j in range(num_assets):\n            portfolio_variance += weights[i] * weights[j] * correlations[i][j] * variances[i] ** 0.5 * variances[j] ** 0.5\n    portfolio_risk = portfolio_variance ** 0.5\n    return round(portfolio_risk, 4)"}, "article_title": "Modern Portfolio Theory (MPT)", "article_doc_id": 1719, "article_content_excerpt": "# Modern Portfolio Theory: What MPT Is and How Investors Use It \n\n## What Is the Modern Portfolio Theory (MPT)? \n\nThe modern portfolio theory (MPT) is a practical method for selecting investments in order to maximize their overall returns within an acceptable level of risk. This mathematical framework is used to build a portfolio of investments that maximize the amount of expected return for the collective given level of risk. \n\nAmerican economist pioneered this theory in his paper \"Portfolio Selection,\" which was published in the Journal of Finance in 1952. He was later awarded a Nobel Prize for his work on modern portfolio theory.\n\nA key component of the MPT theory is diversification. Most investments are either high risk and high return or low risk and low return. that investors could achieve their best results by choosing an optimal mix of the two based on an assessment of their individual tolerance to risk. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * The modern portfolio theory (MPT) is a method that can be used by risk-averse investors to construct diversified portfolios that maximize their returns without unacceptable levels of risk.\n * The modern portfolio theory can be useful to investors trying to construct efficient and diversified portfolios using ETFs.\n * Investors who are more concerned with downside risk might prefer the post-modern portfolio theory (PMPT) to MPT.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/Modern-Portfolio-V2-9a0e2a7c92764f0cb194615eaedcdd76.jpg)\n\nInvestopedia / Matthew Collins\n\n## Understanding the Modern Portfolio Theory (MPT) \n\nThe modern portfolio theory argues that any given investment's risk and return characteristics should not be viewed alone but should be evaluated by how it affects the overall portfolio's risk and return. That is, an investor can construct a portfolio of multiple assets that will result in greater returns without a higher level of risk. \n\nAs an alternative, starting with a desired level of expected return, the investor can construct a portfolio with the lowest possible risk that is capable of producing that return. \n\nBased on statistical measures such as and , a single investment's performance is less important than how it impacts the entire portfolio. \n\n### Acceptable Risk \n\nThe MPT assumes that investors are risk-averse, meaning they prefer a less risky portfolio to a riskier one for a given level of return. As a practical matter, risk aversion implies that most people should invest in multiple . \n\nThe expected return of the portfolio is calculated as a sum of the returns of the individual assets. If a portfolio contained four equally weighted assets with expected returns of 4%, 6%, 10%, and 14%, the portfolio's expected return would be: \n\n * (4% x 25%) + (6% x 25%) + (10% x 25%) + (14% x 25%) = 8.5%\n\nThe portfolio's risk is a function of the variances of each asset and the correlations of each pair of assets. To calculate the risk of a four-asset portfolio, an investor needs each of the four assets' variances and six correlation values, since there are six possible two-asset combinations with four assets. Because of the asset correlations, the total portfolio risk, or , is lower than what would be calculated by a weighted sum. \n\n## Benefits of the MPT \n\nThe who are trying to build diversified portfolios. In fact, the growth of exchange-traded funds (ETFs) made the MPT more relevant by giving investors easier access to a broader range of asset classes. \n\nFor example, stock investors can reduce risk by putting a portion of their portfolios in . The variance of the portfolio will be significantly lower because government bonds have a negative correlation with stocks. Adding a small investment in Treasuries to a stock portfolio will not have a large impact on expected returns because of this loss-reducing effect. \n\n### Looking for Negative Correlation \n\nSimilarly, the MPT can be used to reduce the volatility of a U.S. Treasury portfolio by putting 10% in a or ETF. Although small-cap value stocks\n