it": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "low_prices", "type": "array[number]", "required": true, "description": "A list of the lowest prices for the security over the specified periods.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "high_prices", "type": "array[number]", "required": true, "description": "A list of the highest prices for the security over the specified periods.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "period", "type": "integer", "required": true, "description": "The number of periods to consider for calculating the stochastic oscillator. Default is 14.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "stochastic_oscillator_value", "type": "number", "unit": "%", "description": "The calculated stochastic oscillator value, expressed as a percentage, indicating momentum and potential overbought/oversold conditions."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    closing_prices = inputs['closing_prices']\n    low_prices = inputs['low_prices']\n    high_prices = inputs['high_prices']\n    period = inputs['period']\n    if len(closing_prices) < period or len(low_prices) < period or len(high_prices) < period:\n        raise ValueError(\"Price lists must contain at least 'period' number of elements.\")\n    recent_close = closing_prices[period - 1]\n    period_low = min(low_prices[:period])\n    period_high = max(high_prices[:period])\n    if period_high - period_low == 0:\n        stochastic_value = 0.0\n    else:\n        stochastic_value = (recent_close - period_low) / (period_high - period_low) * 100.0\n    return stochastic_value", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "prices_list_type_and_non_empty", "name": "Price list format and emptiness check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['closing_prices'], list) and len(inputs['closing_prices']) > 0 and isinstance(inputs['low_prices'], list) and len(inputs['low_prices']) > 0 and isinstance(inputs['high_prices'], list) and len(inputs['high_prices']) > 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "Closing, low, and high prices must be provided as non-empty lists."}, {"rule_id": "period_type_and_positive", "name": "Period parameter validation", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['period'], int) and inputs['period'] > 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'period' must be a positive integer."}, {"rule_id": "price_lists_length_consistency", "name": "Consistent price list lengths", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "len(inputs['closing_prices']) != len(inputs['low_prices']) or len(inputs['closing_prices']) != len(inputs['high_prices'])", "applies_to": [], "description": "All price lists (closing, low, high) must have the same number of elements."}, {"rule_id": "period_within_list_bounds", "name": "Period within data range", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['period'] > len(inputs['closing_prices'])", "applies_to": [], "description": "The specified 'period' must not exceed the length of the provided price lists."}, {"rule_id": "prices_non_negative", "name": "Non-negative prices check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "any(p < 0 for p in inputs['closing_prices']) or any(p < 0 for p in inputs['low_prices']) or any(p < 0 for p in inputs['high_prices'])", "applies_to": [], "description": "All prices (closing, low, high) should be non-negative values."}, {"rule_id": "stochastic_oscillator_range", "name": "Stochastic oscillator output range check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "0 <= compute(inputs) <= 100", "applies_to": [], "description": "The calculated stochastic oscillator value must be within the expected range of 0 to 100."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    closing_prices = inputs['closing_prices']\n    low_prices = inputs['low_prices']\n    high_prices = inputs['high_prices']\n    period = inputs['period']\n    if len(closing_prices) < period or len(low_prices) < period or len(high_prices) < period:\n        raise ValueError(\"Price lists must contain at least 'period' number of elements.\")\n    recent_close = closing_prices[period - 1]\n    period_low = min(low_prices[:period])\n    period_high = max(high_prices[:period])\n    if period_high - period_low == 0:\n        stochastic_value = 0.0\n    else:\n        stochastic_value = (recent_close - period_low) / (period_high - period_low) * 100.0\n    return stochastic_value"}, "article_title": "Stochastic Oscillator", "article_doc_id": 5332, "article_content_excerpt": "# Stochastic Oscillator: What It Is, How It Works, How To Calculate\n\nDefinition\n\nA stochastic oscillator is a momentum indicator that compares a security's closing price to a range of its prices over a certain time period.\n\n## What Is a Stochastic Oscillator? \n\nA stochastic oscillator is a momentum indicator comparing a particular of a security to a range of its prices over a certain period of time. The sensitivity of the oscillator to market movements is reducible by adjusting that time period or by taking a of the result. It is used to generate and oversold trading signals, utilizing a 0–100 bounded range of values. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * A stochastic oscillator is a popular technical indicator for generating overbought and oversold signals.\n * It is a popular momentum indicator, first developed in the 1950s.\n * Stochastic oscillators tend to vary around some mean price level since they rely on an asset's price history.\n * Stochastic oscillators measure the momentum of an asset's price to determine trends and predict reversals.\n * Stochastic oscillators measure recent prices on a scale of 0 to 100, with measurements above 80 indicating that an asset is overbought and measurements below 20 indicating that it is oversold.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/Term-Definitions_stochasticoscillator-Final-0ac691d6dead495fb4bfc908a011747c.jpg)\n\nInvestopedia / Jessica Olah\n\n## Understanding the Stochastic Oscillator \n\nThe stochastic oscillator is range-bound, meaning it is always between 0 and 100. This makes it a useful indicator of overbought and oversold conditions. \n\nTraditionally, readings over 80 are considered in the overbought range, and readings under 20 are considered oversold. However, these are not always indicative of impending reversal; very strong trends can maintain overbought or oversold conditions for an extended period. Instead, traders should look to changes in the stochastic oscillator for clues about future trend shifts. \n\nStochastic oscillator charting generally consists of two lines: one reflecting the actual value of the oscillator for each session and one reflecting its three-day simple moving average. Because price is thought to follow , the intersection of these two lines is considered to be a signal that a reversal may be in the works, as it indicates a large shift in momentum from day to day. \n\nDivergence between the stochastic oscillator and trending price action is also seen as an important reversal signal. For example, when a bearish trend reaches a new lower low, but the oscillator prints a higher low, it may be an indicator that bears are exhausting their momentum, and a bullish reversal is brewing. \n\nThe stochastic oscillator is only one of several to time entry and exit points. \n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/dotdash_INV-final-Stochastic-Oscillator-Jun-2021-01-0580390daa1c44ffaac8c7ffcbb96f6a.jpg)\n\nImage by Sabrina Jiang © Investopedia 2021\n\n## Formula for the Stochastic Oscillator \n\n\\begin{aligned} &\\text{\\%K}=\\left(\\frac{\\text{C} - \\text{L14}}{\\text{H14} - \\text{L14}}\\right)\\times100\\\\\\ &\\textbf{where:}\\\\\\ &\\text{C = The most recent closing price}\\\\\\ &\\text{L14 = The lowest price traded of the 14 previous}\\\\\\ &\\text{trading sessions}\\\\\\ &\\text{H14 = The highest price traded during the same}\\\\\\ &\\text{14-day period}\\\\\\ &\\text{\\%K = The current value of the stochastic indicator}\\\\\\ \\end{aligned}\n\nNotably, %K is referred to sometimes as the indicator. The \"slow\" stochastic indicator is taken as %D = 3-period moving average of %K. \n\nThe general theory serving as the foundation for this indicator is that in a market trending upward, prices will close near the high, and in a market trending downward, prices close near the low. Transaction signals are created when the %K crosses through a three-period moving average, which is called the %D. \n\nThe difference between the slow and fast Stochastic Oscillator is the Slow %K incorporates a %K slowing period of 3 that controls the internal smoothing of\n...[truncated]"}
