ding value of the investment.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "number_of_periods", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The number of periods (e.g., years) over which the investment grows.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "cagr", "type": "number", "unit": "%", "description": "The compound annual growth rate as a percentage."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    beginning_value = inputs['beginning_value']\n    ending_value = inputs['ending_value']\n    number_of_periods = inputs['number_of_periods']\n    cagr = ((ending_value / beginning_value) ** (1 / number_of_periods) - 1) * 100\n    return cagr", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "bv_type_missing", "name": "Beginning Value Type and Presence Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('beginning_value'), (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "Beginning value must be provided and be a numeric type (integer or float)."}, {"rule_id": "ev_type_missing", "name": "Ending Value Type and Presence Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('ending_value'), (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "Ending value must be provided and be a numeric type (integer or float)."}, {"rule_id": "nop_type_missing", "name": "Number of Periods Type and Presence Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('number_of_periods'), (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "Number of periods must be provided and be a numeric type (integer or float)."}, {"rule_id": "bv_positive", "name": "Beginning Value Positive Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['beginning_value'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The beginning value must be a positive number greater than zero, as a zero or negative starting value makes CAGR undefined or nonsensical."}, {"rule_id": "ev_positive", "name": "Ending Value Positive Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['ending_value'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The ending value must be a positive number greater than zero."}, {"rule_id": "nop_positive", "name": "Number of Periods Positive Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['number_of_periods'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The number of periods must be a positive number greater than zero."}, {"rule_id": "cagr_plausibility_alert", "name": "CAGR Plausibility Range Alert", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "compute(inputs) < -99 or compute(inputs) > 5000", "applies_to": [], "description": "Calculated CAGR is extremely high or indicates near-total loss, which might suggest input error or an exceptional scenario. Review if this is intended."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    beginning_value = inputs['beginning_value']\n    ending_value = inputs['ending_value']\n    number_of_periods = inputs['number_of_periods']\n    cagr = ((ending_value / beginning_value) ** (1 / number_of_periods) - 1) * 100\n    return cagr"}, "article_title": "Compound Annual Growth Rate (CAGR)", "article_doc_id": 203, "article_content_excerpt": "# Compound Annual Growth Rate (CAGR) Formula and Calculation\n\n## What Is the Compound Annual Growth Rate (CAGR)? \n\nThe compound annual growth rate is the that an investment would need to have every year in order to grow from its beginning balance to its ending balance, over a given time interval. The CAGR assumes that any profits were reinvested at the end of each period of the investment’s life span. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * The compounded annual growth rate (CAGR) is one of the most accurate ways to calculate and determine returns for anything that can rise or fall in value over time.\n * It measures a smoothed rate of return.\n * Investors can compare the CAGR of two or more alternatives to evaluate how well one stock performed against other stocks in a peer group or a market index.\n * CAGR is thus a good way to evaluate how different investments have performed over time, or against a benchmark.\n * The CAGR does not, however, reflect investment risk.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/CAGR_final-67bb17a264264824b7a3ef6b121b89b9.png)\n\nInvestopedia / Alex Dos Diaz\n\n## How to Calculate Compound Annual Growth Rate (CAGR) \n\n\\begin{aligned}&CAGR=\\left(\\left(\\frac{EV}{BV}\\right)^{\\frac1n}-1\\right)\\times100\\\\\\&\\textbf{where:}\\\\\\&EV=\\text{Ending value}\\\\\\&BV=\\text{Beginning value}\\\\\\&n=\\text{Number of years}\\end{aligned}\n\nTo calculate the CAGR of an investment:\n\n 1. Divide the value of an investment at the end of the period by its value at the beginning of that period.\n 2. Raise the result to an exponent of one divided by the number of years.\n 3. Subtract one from the subsequent result.\n 4. Multiply by 100 to convert the answer into a percentage.\n\nThe CAGR formula gives an annualized rate of return, which is useful for comparing the performance of different investments over time. \n\n## What the CAGR Can Tell You \n\nThe compound annual growth rate isn’t a true return rate, but rather a representational figure. It is essentially a number that describes the rate at which an investment would have grown if it had grown at the same rate every year and the profits were reinvested at the end of each year. For stock market investors, this can be particularly useful in comparing the performance of different stocks. The CAGR does not take into account the discount rate, which is critical in assessing the present value of future returns. \n\nIn reality, this sort of performance is unlikely. However, the CAGR can be used to smooth returns so that they may be more easily understood and compared to alternative methods. \n\n## Example of How to Use CAGR \n\nImagine you invested $10,000 in a portfolio with the returns outlined below: \n\n * From Jan. 1, 2018, to Jan. 1, 2019, your portfolio grew to $13,000 (or 30% in year one).\n * On Jan. 1, 2020, the portfolio was $14,000 (or 7.69% from January 2019 to January 2020).\n * On Jan. 1, 2021, the portfolio ended with $19,000 (or 35.71% from January 2020 to January 2021).\n\nWe can see that on an annual basis, the year-to-year growth rates of the investment portfolio were quite different as shown in the parentheses. \n\nOn the other hand, the compound annual growth rate smooths the investment’s performance and ignores the fact that 2018 and 2020 were vastly different from 2019. The CAGR over that period was 23.86% and can be calculated as follows: \n\nCAGR=\\left(\\frac{\\$19,000}{\\$10,000}\\right )^{\\frac{1}{3}}-1\\times100=23.86\\%\n\nThe CAGR of 23.86% over the three-year investment period can help an investor compare alternatives for their capital or make forecasts of future values. For example, imagine an investor is comparing the performance of two uncorrelated investments. \n\nIn any given year during the period, one investment may be rising while the other falls. This could be the case when comparing high-yield to , or a real estate investment to emerging markets. Using CAGR would smooth the annual return over the period so the two alternatives would be easier to compare. \n\nAs another example, let’s say an investor bought 55\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_1520", "name": "Residual Income", "short_description": "Estimate the intrinsic value of a company's stock using the residual income model. This function calculates the intrinsic value by summing the book value of the company and the present value of expected future residual incomes, taking into account the cost of capital.", "domain": "investment_analysis", "topic": "stock_valuation_models", "topic_extension": true, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-1520", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-386", "question_id": "test-1826", "difficulty": 3.5553480614894135, "level": "medium", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "3d1591ee333bab0aa99bf7ae32ed2d80de0eef998e2f709ba76115682f152d07", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["stock valuation", "residual income model", "intrinsic value", "company valuation", "cost of capital"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "residual_income_context", "ambiguity_type": "definition_context", "trigger_signal": "residual income term without explicit context (personal vs. corporate/valuation)", "clarification_question": "Which context of 'residual income' applies to the provided figures?", "options": [{"label": "Corporate Finance / Stock Valuation (as used in this model) - DEFAULT", "value": "corporate_finance_valuation", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Personal Finance / Disposable Income", "value": "personal_finance_disposable", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "hard", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Corporate Finance / Stock Valuation", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}, {"id": "discount_rate_type", "ambiguity_type": "rate_type", "trigger_signal": "discount rate without specifying real/nominal or specific cost of capital", "clarification_question": "What is the intended basis for the 'discount_rate'?", "options": [{"label": "Nominal rate of return - DEFAULT", "value": "nominal", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Real rate of return (adjust for inflation)", "value": "real", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Nominal rate of return", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}, {"id": "discount_rate_scale", "ambiguity_type": "unit_scale", "trigger_signal": "discount_rate is a rate or percentage", "clarification_question": "Is the 'discount_rate' provided as a decimal (e.g., 0.08 for 8%) or a percentage (e.g., 8 for 8%)?", "options": [{"label": "Decimal (e.g., 0.08) - DEFAULT", "value": "decimal", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Percentage (e.g., 8 means 8%)", "value": "percentage", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Decimal", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}], "inputs": [{"name": "book_value", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The current book value of the company's equity.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "future_residual_incomes", "type": "array[number]", "required": true, "description": "A list of expected future residual incomes.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "discount_rate", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The discount rate used to calculate the present value of future incomes.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "intrinsic_value", "type": "number", "unit": "currency", "description": "The estimated intrinsic value of the company's stock."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    book_value = inputs['book_value']\n    future_residual_incomes = inputs['future_residual_incomes']\n    discount_rate = inputs['discount_rate']\n    present_value_residual_incomes = sum((ri / (1 + discount_rate) ** (i + 1) for i, ri in enumerate(future_residual_incomes)))\n    intrinsic_value = book_value + present_value_residual_incomes\n    return intrinsic_value", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "bv001", "name": "Book Value must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['book_value'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["book_value"], "description": "The book value of equity must be a positive number for meaningful stock valuation."}, {"rule_id": "fri001", "name": "Future Residual Incomes must be a list", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not isinstance(inputs['future_residual_incomes'], (list, tuple))", "applies_to": ["future_residual_incomes"], "description": "The 'future_residual_incomes' must be provided as a list of numerical values."}, {"rule_id": "fri002", "name": "Future Residual Incomes elements must be non-negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "any(ri < 0 for ri in inputs['future_residual_incomes'])", "applies_to": ["future_residual_incomes"], "description": "Individual future residual income figures are typically expected to be non-negative."}, {"rule_id": "dr001", "name": "Discount Rate must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['discount_rate'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["discount_rate"], "description": "The discount rate must be positive for valid present value calculations."}, {"rule_id": "dr002", "name": "Discount Rate plausibility check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['discount_rate'] > 1.0", "applies_to": ["discount_rate"], "description": "A discount rate typically does not exceed 100% (1.0 in decimal form); ensure it's not provided as a percentage (e.g., 8 for 8%)."}, {"rule_id": "fri003", "name": "Future Residual Incomes cannot be empty", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not inputs['future_residual_incomes']", "applies_to": ["future_residual_incomes"], "description": "The list of future residual incomes should not be empty for a meaningful valuation."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    book_value = inputs['book_value']\n    future_residual_incomes = inputs['future_residual_incomes']\n    discount_rate = inputs['discount_rate']\n    present_value_residual_incomes = sum((ri / (1 + discount_rate) ** (i + 1) for i, ri in enumerate(future_residual_incomes)))\n    intrinsic_value = book_value + present_value_residual_incomes\n    return intrinsic_value"}, "article_title": "Residual Income", "article_doc_id": 2997, "article_content_excerpt": "# Residual Income: What It Is, Types, and How to Make It\n\n## What Is Residual Income? \n\nResidual income is the money that continues to flow after an initial investment of time and resources has been completed. Examples of residual income include artist royalties, rental income, interest income, and dividend payments. \n\nThe term residual income is used in other contexts: \n\n * In personal finance, residual income can refer to an individual's , or the total amount of money left over after paying all personal debts and obligations.\n * In corporate finance, residual income is a measurement of corporate performance that reflects the total income generated after paying all relevant costs of capital.\n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Personal residual income is not generated by hourly wages. Rather, it requires an initial investment of money, time, or both with the primary objective of earning ongoing revenue.\n * Residual income is often referred to as passive income. \n * Sources of residual income include real estate investing, stocks, bonds, and royalties.\n * Corporate residual income is leftover profit after paying all costs of capital. \n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/Residualincome-Final-aa06a1d8e8c24cadb8fad5b3da5de6ae.jpg)\n\nInvestopedia / Michela Buttignol\n\n## How Residual Income Works \n\nResidual income broadly speaking is a measurement of tangential profits earned after subtracting all costs of capital related to generating that income. Other terms for residual income include , , and abnormal earnings. \n\n### Important: \n\nAlthough residual income is sometimes known as passive income, side hustles can be used to boost personal residual income. \n\n## Types of Residual Income \n\n### Stock Valuation \n\nResidual income is also a valuation method for estimating the intrinsic value of a company's common stock. It accounts for the , meaning the combination of debt and equity expended to finance the company's operations. \n\nThe residual income valuation model values a company as the sum of book value and the present value of expected future residual income. Residual income in this case is the profit remaining after the deduction of for all sources of capital. \n\nResidual income is calculated as net income less a charge for the cost of capital. This is known as the equity charge and is calculated as the value of equity capital multiplied by the cost of equity or the required rate of return on equity. \n\nThe formula is: \n\n**Residual Income = Net Income - Equity Charge**\n\nGiven the opportunity cost of equity, a company can have positive net income but negative residual income. \n\n### Corporate Finance \n\nManagerial accounting defines residual income for a company as the amount of leftover operating profit after paying all costs of capital used to generate the revenues. It is also considered the company's net operating income or the amount of profit that exceeds its . \n\nResidual income in this case may be used to assess the performance of a capital investment, a team, a department, or a business unit. \n\nThe calculation of residual income is as follows: Residual income = operating income - (minimum required return x operating assets). \n\n### Personal Finance \n\nIn personal finance, residual income is synonymous with monthly disposable income. It is the total income that remains after paying all monthly debts. \n\nThus, residual income is often a key factor when a lender considers a loan application. An adequate amount of residual income indicates that the borrower can cover the monthly loan payment. \n\n## How to Generate Residual Income \n\nMost sources of residual income require an upfront investment of money, sweat equity, or both. Some examples: \n\n * Buy bonds. Once the bonds are purchased, the owner has a stream of cash available until the bonds reach their maturity.\n * Buy a rental property. Renting out a second home or investment property is a sound way to add to your income without much effort after the initial investment. If you lack the seed money, consi\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_2738", "name": "Economic Value of Equity (EVE)", "short_description": "Calculate the Economic Value of Equity (EVE) for a bank's balance sheet by taking the present value of all asset cash flows and subtracting the present value of all liability cash flows. EVE is used to assess the bank's sensitivity to interest rate changes and manage asset-liability balance.", "domain": "risk_management", "topic": "interest_rate_risk", "topic_extension": true, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-2738", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-130", "question_id": "test-2143", "difficulty": 4.836281906951478, "level": "hard", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "91abe4071c774ca538f5d344879a9130b51505613c5dbec764a57fc0bf8372a9", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["Economic Value of Equity", "EVE", "Asset Liability Management", "Bank Valuation", "Present Value", "Cash Flow", "Interest Rate Sensitivity"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "cash_flow_timing", "ambiguity_type": "time_basis", "trigger_signal": "cash flow timing not explicitly stated or assumed end-of-period", "clarification_question": "Are the cash flows assumed to occur at the END of each period or the BEGINNING of each period?", "options": [{"label": "End of period (Ordinary Annuity) - DEFAULT", "value": "end_of_period", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Beginning of period (Annuity-Due)", "value": "beginning_of_period", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "result * (1 + discount_rate)", "max_expr_nodes": 10, "invariant": "result_new == result_old * (1 + discount_rate)", "affected_inputs": ["discount_rate"]}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "End of period (Ordinary Annuity)", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "asset_cash_flows", "type": "array[number]", "required": true, "description": "A list of expected future cash flows from assets.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "liability_cash_flows", "type": "array[number]", "required": true, "description": "A list of expected future cash flows from liabilities.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "discount_rate", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The discount rate used to present value the cash flows, representing the interest rate risk.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "eve", "type": "number", "unit": null, "description": "The economic value of equity."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    asset_cash_flows = inputs['asset_cash_flows']\n    liability_cash_flows = inputs['liability_cash_flows']\n    discount_rate = inputs['discount_rate']\n    present_value_assets = sum((cf / (1 + discount_rate) ** (i + 1) for i, cf in enumerate(asset_cash_flows)))\n    present_value_liabilities = sum((cf / (1 + discount_rate) ** (i + 1) for i, cf in enumerate(liability_cash_flows)))\n    eve = present_value_assets - present_value_liabilities\n    return eve", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "dr001", "name": "Discount Rate Type Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['discount_rate'], (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "The discount rate must be a numeric value (integer or float)."}, {"rule_id": "dr002", "name": "Discount Rate Value Constraint", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "inputs['discount_rate'] > -1", "applies_to": [], "description": "The discount rate must be greater than -1 to ensure a valid present value calculation."}, {"rule_id": "dr003", "name": "Asset Cash Flows List Type and Non-empty", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['asset_cash_flows'], list) and len(inputs['asset_cash_flows']) > 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The asset cash flows must be provided as a non-empty list."}, {"rule_id": "dr004", "name": "Liability Cash Flows List Type and Non-empty", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs['liability_cash_flows'], list) and len(inputs['liability_cash_flows']) > 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The liability cash flows must be provided as a non-empty list."}, {"rule_id": "dr005", "name": "Asset Cash Flows Elements Numeric", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "all(isinstance(cf, (int, float)) for cf in inputs['asset_cash_flows'])", "applies_to": [], "description": "All elements in the asset cash flows list must be numeric."}, {"rule_id": "dr006", "name": "Liability Cash Flows Elements Numeric", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "all(isinstance(cf, (int, float)) for cf in inputs['liability_cash_flows'])", "applies_to": [], "description": "All elements in the liability cash flows list must be numeric."}, {"rule_id": "dr007", "name": "Asset Cash Flows Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "any(cf < 0 for cf in inputs['asset_cash_flows'])", "applies_to": [], "description": "Asset cash flows are typically non-negative. Negative values may indicate an unusual situation or error."}, {"rule_id": "dr008", "name": "Liability Cash Flows Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "any(cf < 0 for cf in inputs['liability_cash_flows'])", "applies_to": [], "description": "Liability cash flows are typically non-negative. Negative values may indicate an unusual situation or error."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    asset_cash_flows = inputs['asset_cash_flows']\n    liability_cash_flows = inputs['liability_cash_flows']\n    discount_rate = inputs['discount_rate']\n    present_value_assets = sum((cf / (1 + discount_rate) ** (i + 1) for i, cf in enumerate(asset_cash_flows)))\n    present_value_liabilities = sum((cf / (1 + discount_rate) ** (i + 1) for i, cf in enumerate(liability_cash_flows)))\n    eve = present_value_assets - present_value_liabilities\n    return eve"}, "article_title": "Economic Value of Equity (EVE)", "article_doc_id": 5488, "article_content_excerpt": "# Economic Value of Equity (EVE) Definition, Limitations\n\n## What Is the Economic Value of Equity (EVE)? \n\nThe economic value of equity (EVE) is a cash flow calculation that takes the present value of all asset cash flows and subtracts the present value of all liability cash flows. Unlike earnings at risk and value at risk (), a bank uses the economic value of equity to manage its assets and liabilities. This is a long-term economic measure used to assess the degree of exposure—as opposed to net-interest income (NII), which reflects short-term interest rate risk. \n\nThe simplest definition of EVE is the (NPV) of a bank's balance sheet's cash flows. This calculation is used for to measure changes in the economic value of the bank. \n\n### Important: \n\nEVE risk is defined as a bank's value sensitivity to changes in market rates.\n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * The economic value of equity (EVE) is a cash flow calculation that takes the present value of all asset cash flows and subtracts the present value of all liability cash flows.\n * Unlike earnings at risk and value at risk (VAR), a bank uses the economic value of equity to manage its assets and liabilities. This is a long-term economic measure used to assess the degree of interest rate risk exposure.\n * Financial regulators require banks to conduct periodic EVE calculations.\n\n## Understanding EVE \n\nThe economic value of equity is a cash flow calculation that subtracts the present value of the expected cash flows on liabilities from the present value of all expected asset cash flows. This value is used as an estimate of total capital when evaluating the sensitivity of total capital to fluctuations in interest rates. A bank may use this measure to create models that indicate how interest rate changes will affect its total capital. \n\nThe fair market values of a bank's assets and liabilities are directly linked to interest rates. A bank constructs models with all constituent assets and liabilities that show the effect of different interest rate changes on its total capital. This is a key tool that allows banks to prepare against constantly changing interest rates and to perform stress tests. \n\nAn internationally accepted standard for determining interest rate risk is to _stress-test_ EVE. The Basel Committee on Banking Supervision recommends a plus and minus 2% stress test on all interest rates and US bank regulations require regular analysis of EVE.\n\nThe economic value of equity should not be confused with the earnings profile of a bank. A general rise in interest rates may boost earnings of a bank, but it would normally cause a decrease in the economic value of equity because of the basic inverse relationship between asset values and interest rates and direct relationship (same direction) between values of liabilities and interest rates. However, EVE and bank earnings do bear a relationship in that the higher the EVE, the greater the potential for increased future earnings generated from the base. \n\n### Important: \n\nBank regulators require banks to conduct periodic EVE calculations.\n\n## Limitations of EVE \n\nWhile the net present value of a bond can be calculated quite easily, future cash flows can be difficult to quantify for deposit accounts and other financial instruments that have no maturity because these types of products have uncertain duration and uneven cash flows. EVE modelers must make assumptions for certain liabilities, which may deviate from reality. In addition—because EVE is a comprehensive calculation—complex products with embedded options are not easily modeled and leave wide room for interpretation and subjective judgement of the modelers or their supervisors."}
