ross exercise gain (only gain from price difference)", "value": "gross_gain", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "result + option_cost", "max_expr_nodes": 7, "invariant": "result_new == result_old + option_cost", "affected_inputs": ["option_cost"]}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Net profit, accounting for the option cost", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "stock_price", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The current market price of the underlying stock.", "unit": null, "aliases": ["market_price"]}, {"name": "strike_price", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The strike price of the Bermuda option.", "unit": null, "aliases": ["exercise_price"]}, {"name": "option_cost", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The cost of the Bermuda option contract.", "unit": null, "aliases": ["premium_paid"]}, {"name": "shares_per_contract", "type": "integer", "required": true, "description": "The number of shares represented by one option contract. Default is 100.", "unit": null, "aliases": ["contract_size"]}], "output": {"name": "profit", "type": "number", "unit": "USD", "description": "The profit from exercising the Bermuda option early, rounded to the nearest dollar."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    stock_price = inputs['stock_price']\n    strike_price = inputs['strike_price']\n    option_cost = inputs['option_cost']\n    shares_per_contract = inputs['shares_per_contract']\n    if stock_price >= strike_price:\n        return -option_cost\n    exercise_profit = (strike_price - stock_price) * shares_per_contract\n    profit = exercise_profit - option_cost\n    return round(profit)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "sp001", "name": "Stock Price Type Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('stock_price'), (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'stock_price' input must be a numeric value."}, {"rule_id": "sp002", "name": "Strike Price Type Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('strike_price'), (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'strike_price' input must be a numeric value."}, {"rule_id": "oc001", "name": "Option Cost Type Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('option_cost'), (int, float))", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'option_cost' input must be a numeric value."}, {"rule_id": "spc001", "name": "Shares Per Contract Type Check", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('shares_per_contract'), int)", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'shares_per_contract' input must be an integer."}, {"rule_id": "spv001", "name": "Stock Price Positive Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['stock_price'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["stock_price"], "description": "The stock price must be a positive value."}, {"rule_id": "spv002", "name": "Strike Price Positive Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['strike_price'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["strike_price"], "description": "The strike price must be a positive value."}, {"rule_id": "ocv001", "name": "Option Cost Non-Negative Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['option_cost'] < 0", "applies_to": ["option_cost"], "description": "The option cost must be a non-negative value."}, {"rule_id": "spcv001", "name": "Shares Per Contract Positive Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['shares_per_contract'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["shares_per_contract"], "description": "The number of shares per contract must be a positive integer."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    stock_price = inputs['stock_price']\n    strike_price = inputs['strike_price']\n    option_cost = inputs['option_cost']\n    shares_per_contract = inputs['shares_per_contract']\n    if stock_price >= strike_price:\n        return -option_cost\n    exercise_profit = (strike_price - stock_price) * shares_per_contract\n    profit = exercise_profit - option_cost\n    return round(profit)"}, "article_title": "Bermuda Option", "article_doc_id": 1327, "article_content_excerpt": "# Bermuda Option: What They Are, Examples, Pros and Cons\n\n## What Is a Bermuda Option? \n\nA Bermuda option is a type of contract that can only be exercised on predetermined dates—often on one day each month. \n\nA spin on , which permit holders to exercise early at any time, Bermudian options allow investors to buy or sell a security or at a preset price on a set of specific dates as well as the option's expiration date. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * A Bermuda option can be exercised early, but only on a set of specific dates before its expiration.\n * These exercise dates are often set in one-month increments.\n * Premiums for Bermuda options are typically lower than those of American options, which can be exercised any time before expiry.\n\n## Understanding Bermuda Options \n\nOptions contracts are financial that provide the buyer the right—but not the obligation—to transact in an underlying asset, such as shares of stock, at a distinct price—the —on or before a specified future date. \n\nAn option to buy an underlying asset is a . An option to sell an underlying asset is a . At the option's expiration, the contracts can be converted to shares, known as , of the asset at the predetermined price. \n\nThere are two main types or styles of options, American and European options. American options are exercisable at any time between the purchase date and the date of expiration. , however, are exercised only at the date of expiration. Bermuda options are a restricted form of the American option that allows for early exercise but only at set dates. \n\nThe early exercise feature of Bermuda options allows for an investor to use the option and convert it to shares on specific dates before . The dates—contained in the contract's terms—are known upfront during the purchasing of the option. \n\n## Special Considerations \n\nSome Bermuda options might allow an investor to exercise the option on the first business day of the month. So, if an investor's call option's strike price is lower than the underlying stock's market price on the first of the month, the investor can exercise and buy shares for the lower strike price. Conversely, if the investor's put option strike price is higher than the market price of the stock, the investor can sell at the strike and pick up the shares at the lower market price. Most times, the net difference is . \n\nHowever, some Bermuda options have early expiration date restrictions. For example, a Bermuda option might have the features of a European option where it cannot be exercised until the early exercise date. Following the early exercise date, the option converts to American-style options and can be exercised at any time. \n\nThe ability to exercise an option early is a benefit to the holder, and this feature adds value to the contract. The (price) on a Bermuda option will often be higher than a option with the same terms, and lower than an American option due to its limitations on early exercise. \n\n## Bermuda Options: Advantages and Disadvantages \n\nThere are several advantages and disadvantages to Bermuda options. Unlike American and European options, Bermuda options give investors the ability to create and purchase a hybrid contract. In other words, investors are given more control over when the options can be exercised. \n\nPremiums for Bermuda options are typically lower than those of American options. However, Bermuda options don't have the flexibility of exercising at any time. As a result, American options are the most expensive, while European options are the cheapest since they offer the least flexibility. The cost of Bermuda options falls somewhere in between their American and European counterparts. \n\nA possible drawback to a Bermuda option can happen if an investor doesn't exercise until the option's expiration date. In this case, the investor would have been better off buying the cheaper European option instead. Also, the additional exercise dates of a Bermuda option may not necessarily represent the best times to exer\n...[truncated]"}
