e = floor_rate - floating_rate\n    payout = loan_amount * interest_difference * (days_to_maturity / days_in_period)\n    return round(payout)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "loan_amount_non_negative", "name": "Loan Amount Must Be Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['loan_amount'] < 0", "applies_to": ["loan_amount"], "description": "The principal loan amount cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "floor_rate_non_negative", "name": "Floor Rate Must Be Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['floor_rate'] < 0", "applies_to": ["floor_rate"], "description": "The interest rate floor cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "floating_rate_non_negative", "name": "Floating Rate Must Be Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['floating_rate'] < 0", "applies_to": ["floating_rate"], "description": "The current floating interest rate cannot be negative."}, {"rule_id": "days_to_maturity_positive", "name": "Days to Maturity Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['days_to_maturity'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["days_to_maturity"], "description": "The number of days to maturity must be a positive value."}, {"rule_id": "days_in_period_positive", "name": "Days in Period Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['days_in_period'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["days_in_period"], "description": "The number of days in the interest calculation period must be a positive value."}, {"rule_id": "rate_value_plausibility", "name": "Rate Value Scale Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['floor_rate'] > 1.0 or inputs['floating_rate'] > 1.0", "applies_to": ["floor_rate", "floating_rate"], "description": "One or both of the interest rates (floor_rate, floating_rate) are greater than 1.0, which might indicate they were entered as percentages (e.g., 5 for 5%) instead of decimals (0.05). Please confirm the rate scale."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    loan_amount = inputs['loan_amount']\n    floor_rate = inputs['floor_rate']\n    floating_rate = inputs['floating_rate']\n    days_to_maturity = inputs.get('days_to_maturity', 1)\n    days_in_period = inputs.get('days_in_period', 365)\n    if floating_rate >= floor_rate:\n        return 0.0\n    interest_difference = floor_rate - floating_rate\n    payout = loan_amount * interest_difference * (days_to_maturity / days_in_period)\n    return round(payout)"}, "article_title": "Interest Rate Floor", "article_doc_id": 709, "article_content_excerpt": "# What Is an Interest Rate Floor and How Is It Used With a Loan?\n\n## What Is an Interest Rate Floor? \n\nAn interest rate floor is an agreed-upon rate in the lower range of rates associated with a floating rate loan product. Interest rate floors are utilized in derivative contracts and loan agreements. This is in contrast to an (or cap). \n\nInterest rate floors are often used in the (ARM) market. Often, this minimum is designed to cover any costs associated with processing and servicing the loan. An interest rate floor is often present through the issuing of an ARM, as it prevents interest rates from adjusting below a preset level. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Contracts and loan agreements often include interest rate floors.\n * Interest rate floors are in contrast to interest rate ceilings or caps.\n * There are three common interest rate derivative contracts, with interest rate floors being just one.\n * If a variable rate falls below the interest rate floor, the floor is triggered and will be the prevailing rate for the period.\n * A variable-rate floor is meant to protect a lender by ensuring a minimum interest assessment can be collected each month even if adjustable rates reach 0%.\n\n## Understanding Interest Rate Floors \n\nInterest rate floors and interest rate caps are levels used by varying market participants to risks associated with floating-rate loan products. In both products, the buyer of the contract seeks to obtain a payout based on a negotiated rate. In the case of an interest rate floor, the buyer of an interest rate floor contract seeks compensation when the floating rate falls below the contract’s floor. This buyer is buying protection from lost interest income paid by the borrower when the floating rate falls. \n\nInterest rate floor contracts are one of three common contracts, the other two being interest rate caps and . Interest rate floor contracts and interest rate cap contracts are derivative products typically bought on market exchanges similar to put and call options. \n\nInterest rate swaps require two separate entities to agree on the swapping of an asset, typically involving the exchanging of fixed-rate debt for floating-rate debt. Interest rate floor and interest rate cap contracts can provide a different alternative to the exchanging of balance sheet assets in an interest rate swap. \n\n## Real-World Example of an Interest Rate Floor \n\nAs a hypothetical example, assume that a is securing a floating rate loan and is looking for protection against lost income that would arise if were to decline. Suppose the lender buys an interest rate floor contract with an interest rate floor of 8%. The floating rate on the $1 million negotiated loan then falls to 7%. The interest rate floor derivative contract purchased by the lender results in a payout of $10,000 = (($1 million *.08) - ($1 million*.07)). \n\nThe payout to the holder of the contract is also adjusted based on days to maturity or days to reset which is determined by the details of the contract. \n\n### Advisor Insight: \n\nAn interest rate floor is carefully calculated based on future market expectations. The lender imposing the floor doesn't want to include this unfavorable loan term to the borrower only for the floor to never be met.\n\n## The Use of Floors in Adjustable Rate Loan Contracts \n\nAn interest rate floor can also be an agreed-upon rate in an adjustable-rate loan contract, such as an adjustable mortgage. The lender’s lending terms structure the contract with an interest rate floor provision, which means that the rate is adjustable based on the agreed-upon market rate until it reaches the interest rate floor. A loan with an interest rate floor provision has a minimum rate that must be paid by the borrower to protect the income for the lender. \n\n## How Does an Interest Rate Floor Apply to My Loan?\n\nAn interest rate floor impacts your loan by creating a minimum interest rate. Even if prevalent market rates drop to 0%, you will still be subject to a rate equal to a\n...[truncated]"}
