ases": []}, {"name": "seeking_work", "type": "integer", "required": true, "description": "The number of people actively seeking work.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "non_institutional_population", "type": "integer", "required": true, "description": "The total civilian non-institutional population aged 16 and over.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "participation_rate", "type": "number", "unit": "percent", "description": "The labor force participation rate expressed as a percentage."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    employed = inputs['employed']\n    seeking_work = inputs['seeking_work']\n    non_institutional_population = inputs['non_institutional_population']\n    if non_institutional_population <= 0:\n        raise ValueError('Non-institutional population must be greater than zero.')\n    labor_force = employed + seeking_work\n    participation_rate = labor_force / non_institutional_population * 100\n    return participation_rate", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "input_employed_missing", "name": "Missing 'employed' input", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs.get('employed') is None", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'employed' input is required but was not provided."}, {"rule_id": "input_seeking_work_missing", "name": "Missing 'seeking_work' input", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs.get('seeking_work') is None", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'seeking_work' input is required but was not provided."}, {"rule_id": "input_non_institutional_population_missing", "name": "Missing 'non_institutional_population' input", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs.get('non_institutional_population') is None", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'non_institutional_population' input is required but was not provided."}, {"rule_id": "input_non_negative", "name": "Non-negative Input Values", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (inputs['employed'] >= 0 and inputs['seeking_work'] >= 0 and inputs['non_institutional_population'] >= 0)", "applies_to": [], "description": "All input values (employed, seeking_work, non_institutional_population) must be non-negative."}, {"rule_id": "non_institutional_population_positive", "name": "Population Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['non_institutional_population'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'non_institutional_population' must be greater than zero to calculate a meaningful participation rate."}, {"rule_id": "labor_force_less_than_population", "name": "Labor Force Exceeds Total Population", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "(inputs['employed'] + inputs['seeking_work']) > inputs['non_institutional_population']", "applies_to": [], "description": "The sum of employed and seeking work individuals (labor force) cannot exceed the total non-institutional population."}, {"rule_id": "participation_rate_plausible_range", "name": "Participation Rate Plausibility", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "compute(inputs) < 0 or compute(inputs) > 100", "applies_to": [], "description": "The calculated labor force participation rate should typically be between 0% and 100%."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": false, "error": "Non-institutional population must be greater than zero.", "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    employed = inputs['employed']\n    seeking_work = inputs['seeking_work']\n    non_institutional_population = inputs['non_institutional_population']\n    if non_institutional_population <= 0:\n        raise ValueError('Non-institutional population must be greater than zero.')\n    labor_force = employed + seeking_work\n    participation_rate = labor_force / non_institutional_population * 100\n    return participation_rate"}, "article_title": "Participation Rate", "article_doc_id": 2502, "article_content_excerpt": "# Labor Force Participation Rate: Purpose, Formula, and Trends\n\n## What Is the Labor Force Participation Rate? \n\nThe labor force participation rate is an estimate of an economy’s active workforce. The U.S. government's labor force participation rate formula is the number of people ages 16 and older who are employed or actively seeking employment, divided by the total non-institutionalized, civilian working-age population. \n\nIn the 12 months ending October 2024, the U.S. labor force participation rate was 62.6%, according to the , which publishes the figures monthly.\n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * The labor force participation rate indicates the percentage of working-age people who are employed or are actively seeking work.\n * In conjunction with the unemployment numbers, it offers some perspective into the state of the economy.\n * Social, demographic, and economic trends cause the rate to fluctuate from month to month.\n * Global labor force participation has shown a steady decline since 1990.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/Investopedia_LaborForceParticipationRate-6589f46752cc48ef9a8af59ea4179bdf.jpg)\n\nInvestopedia / Sydney Burns\n\n## Understanding the Labor Force Participation Rate \n\nThe labor force participation rate is an important metric to use when analyzing employment and data because it measures the number of people who are actively job-hunting as well as those who are currently employed. \n\nIt includes all other people aged 16 or older and compares the proportion of those who are working or seeking work outside the home to those who are neither working nor seeking work outside the home. It omits institutionalized people, such as individuals in prisons, nursing homes, mental health facilities, and members of the military.\n\nThe labor force participation rate is considered to be somewhat more reliable than the unemployment rate because it accounts for people who have given up looking for work. The unemployment numbers do not take into account those who have given up looking for work.\n\nSome economists argue that the should be considered together to better understand an economy’s real employment status. \n\n## Labor Force Participation Rate Formula \n\nThe formula for labor force participation is:\n\n\\begin{aligned}&\\frac{ ( \\text{Number Employed} + \\text{Number Seeking Work} ) \\times 100 }{ \\text{Civilian Non-Institutional Population} } \\\\\\\\\\end{aligned}\n\nThis applies to all members of the population at age 16 or older. \n\n## Factors That Affect the Participation Rate \n\nLabor force participation is affected by numerous social, economic, and demographic factors. As these factors change, labor force participation goes up or down. These changes can happen quickly or slowly. They might have a short-term impact on labor force participation, or they might create long-term change. \n\n### Economic Factors \n\nShort- and long-term economic trends influence the labor force participation rate. In the long run, industrialization and the accumulation of wealth can have an impact. \n\nIndustrialization tends to increase participation by creating employment opportunities. High levels of accumulated wealth can reduce participation because wealthier people simply have less need to work for a living. \n\nIn the short term, and unemployment rates influence the participation rate. During an economic recession, the labor force participation rate tends to fall because many laid-off workers become discouraged and give up looking for jobs. Economic policies such as heavy labor market regulation and generous social benefit programs may tend to decrease labor force participation. \n\n### Social Factors \n\nSocial expectations and changes to those expectations affect who is available to participate in the workforce. As different groups are expected to work or not, the labor force participation rate will go up or down. \n\nFor example, if married men are considered responsible for supporting their families, while married women are encouraged to stay home, women will stop work\n...[truncated]"}
