alculate APR."}, {"rule_id": "days_in_term_positive", "name": "Loan Term Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['days_in_loan_term'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["days_in_loan_term"], "description": "The number of days in the loan term must be a positive integer."}, {"rule_id": "fees_non_negative", "name": "Fees Must Be Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['fees'] < 0", "applies_to": ["fees"], "description": "The total fees associated with the loan should not be negative."}, {"rule_id": "interest_non_negative", "name": "Interest Must Be Non-Negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['interest'] < 0", "applies_to": ["interest"], "description": "The total interest paid over the life of the loan should not be negative."}, {"rule_id": "apr_reasonable_range", "name": "Plausible Annual Percentage Rate", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "compute(inputs) > 500.0", "applies_to": ["fees", "interest", "principal", "days_in_loan_term"], "description": "The calculated Annual Percentage Rate (APR) appears unusually high (greater than 500%), suggesting a potential input error or extreme loan conditions."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    fees = inputs['fees']\n    interest = inputs['interest']\n    principal = inputs['principal']\n    days_in_loan_term = inputs['days_in_loan_term']\n    total_cost = fees + interest\n    periodic_rate = total_cost / principal\n    apr = periodic_rate / days_in_loan_term * 365 * 100\n    return apr"}, "article_title": "Annual Percentage Rate (APR)", "article_doc_id": 4495, "article_content_excerpt": "# Annual Percentage Rate (APR): What It Means and How It Works\n\n## What Is Annual Percentage Rate (APR)? \n\nAnnual percentage rate (APR) refers to the yearly interest generated by a sum that's charged to borrowers or paid to investors. APR is expressed as a percentage that represents the actual yearly over the term of a loan or income earned on an investment. This includes any fees or additional costs associated with the transaction but does not take into account. The APR provides consumers with a bottom-line number they can compare among lenders, credit cards, or investment products. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * An annual percentage rate (APR) is the yearly rate charged for a loan or earned by an investment and includes interest and fees.\n * Financial institutions must disclose a financial instrument’s APR before any agreement is signed.\n * The APR provides a consistent basis for presenting annual interest rate information in order to protect consumers from misleading advertising.\n * An APR may not reflect the actual cost of borrowing because lenders have a fair amount of leeway in calculating it, excluding certain fees.\n * APR shouldn't be confused with APY (annual percentage yield), a calculation that takes the compounding of interest into account.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/Annual_Percentage_Rate-0c5e018f6e1148a29c55c0a356c2a411.png)\n\nInvestopedia / Lara Antal\n\n## How the Annual Percentage Rate (APR) Works \n\nAn annual percentage rate is expressed as an . It calculates what percentage of the principal you’ll pay each year by taking things such as monthly payments and fees into account. APR is also the annual rate of interest paid on investments without accounting for the compounding of interest within that year. \n\nThe of 1968 mandates that the APR they charge to borrowers. Credit card companies are allowed to advertise interest rates on a monthly basis, but they must clearly report the APR to customers before they sign an agreement.\n\n### Important: \n\nCredit card companies can increase your interest rate for new purchases, but not existing balances if they provide you with 45 days' notice first.\n\n### How Is APR Calculated? \n\n by multiplying the by the number of periods in a year in which it was applied. It does not indicate how many times the rate is actually applied to the balance.\n\n\\begin{aligned} &\\text{APR} = \\left ( \\left ( \\frac{ \\frac{ \\text{Fees} + \\text{Interest} }{ \\text {Principal} } }{ n } \\right ) \\times 365 \\right ) \\times 100 \\\\\\ &\\textbf{where:} \\\\\\ &\\text{Interest} = \\text{Total interest paid over life of the loan} \\\\\\ &\\text{Principal} = \\text{Loan amount} \\\\\\ &n = \\text{Number of days in loan term} \\\\\\ \\end{aligned}\n\n## Types of APRs \n\nCredit card APRs vary based on the type of charge. The credit card issuer may charge one APR for purchases, another for , and yet another for from another card. Issuers also charge high-rate penalty APRs to customers for late payments or violating other terms of the cardholder agreement. There’s also the introductory APR—a low or 0% rate—with which many credit card companies try to entice new customers to sign up for a card. \n\nBank loans generally come with . A fixed APR loan has an interest rate that is guaranteed not to change during the life of the loan or credit facility. A variable APR loan has an interest rate that may change at any time. \n\nThe APR borrowers are charged also depends on their credit. The rates offered to those with excellent credit are significantly lower than those offered to . \n\n### Compound Interest or Simple Interest?\n\nAPR does not take into account the compounding of interest within a specific year: It is based only on .\n\n## APR vs. Annual Percentage Yield (APY) \n\nThough an APR only accounts for simple interest, the takes compound interest into account. As a result, a loan’s APY is higher than its APR. The higher the interest rate—and to a lesser extent, the smaller the compounding periods—the greater the difference between the APR and APY. \n\nIm\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_1395", "name": "Protective Put", "short_description": "Calculate the net profit of a protective put strategy.\n\nThis function computes the net profit from a protective put strategy, taking into\nconsideration the price at which the stock is sold, the initial purchase price,\nand the premium paid for the put option.", "domain": "financial_markets", "topic": "option_pricing", "topic_extension": false, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-1395", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-526", "question_id": "test-1559", "difficulty": 2.995732273553991, "level": "medium", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "aabce400b2a793fedbd8088d7f84164c5e64f3f88aa05fefd78cc2bc1347aece", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["protective put", "net profit", "stock sales price", "stock purchase price", "put option premium", "shares quantity", "hedging strategy", "options contract"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "output_unit_scale", "ambiguity_type": "unit_scale", "trigger_signal": "Output represents a total monetary profit, but a per-share value might be expected.", "clarification_question": "Should the output represent the total net profit for all shares, or the net profit per share?", "options": [{"label": "Total Net Profit (Default)", "value": "total_profit", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Net Profit Per Share", "value": "per_share_profit", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "result / quantity", "max_expr_nodes": 7, "invariant": "result_new * quantity == result_old", "affected_inputs": ["quantity"]}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Total net profit for all shares.", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "stock_sales_price", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The sale price of the stock.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "stock_purchase_price", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The initial purchase price of the stock.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "premium", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The premium paid for the put option per share.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "quantity", "type": "integer", "required": false, "description": "The number of shares. Defaults to 100 shares, corresponding to one option contract.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "net_profit", "type": "number", "unit": null, "description": "The net profit realized after selling the stock and accounting for the premium."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    stock_sales_price = inputs['stock_sales_price']\n    stock_purchase_price = inputs['stock_purchase_price']\n    premium = inputs['premium']\n    quantity = inputs.get('quantity', 100)\n    profit_per_share = stock_sales_price - stock_purchase_price\n    net_profit = profit_per_share * quantity - premium * quantity\n    return net_profit", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "check_stock_sales_price_type", "name": "Stock Sales Price Type Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('stock_sales_price'), (float, int))", "applies_to": ["stock_sales_price"], "description": "Stock sales price must be a numeric value."}, {"rule_id": "check_stock_purchase_price_type", "name": "Stock Purchase Price Type Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('stock_purchase_price'), (float, int))", "applies_to": ["stock_purchase_price"], "description": "Stock purchase price must be a numeric value."}, {"rule_id": "check_premium_type", "name": "Premium Type Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "isinstance(inputs.get('premium'), (float, int))", "applies_to": ["premium"], "description": "Premium must be a numeric value."}, {"rule_id": "check_quantity_type", "name": "Quantity Type Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "validity", "expression": "inputs.get('quantity') is None or isinstance(inputs.get('quantity'), int)", "applies_to": ["quantity"], "description": "Quantity, if provided, must be an integer."}, {"rule_id": "check_positive_sales_price", "name": "Positive Stock Sales Price Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['stock_sales_price'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["stock_sales_price"], "description": "Stock sales price must be greater than zero."}, {"rule_id": "check_positive_purchase_price", "name": "Positive Stock Purchase Price Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['stock_purchase_price'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["stock_purchase_price"], "description": "Stock purchase price must be greater than zero."}, {"rule_id": "check_non_negative_premium", "name": "Non-negative Premium Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['premium'] < 0", "applies_to": ["premium"], "description": "Premium paid for the put option should not be negative."}, {"rule_id": "check_positive_quantity", "name": "Positive Quantity Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs.get('quantity', 100) <= 0", "applies_to": ["quantity"], "description": "Quantity of shares must be a positive integer."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    stock_sales_price = inputs['stock_sales_price']\n    stock_purchase_price = inputs['stock_purchase_price']\n    premium = inputs['premium']\n    quantity = inputs.get('quantity', 100)\n    profit_per_share = stock_sales_price - stock_purchase_price\n    net_profit = profit_per_share * quantity - premium * quantity\n    return net_profit"}, "article_title": "Protective Put", "article_doc_id": 2746, "article_content_excerpt": "# Protective Put: What It Is, How It Works, and Examples\n\n## What Is a Protective Put? \n\nA protective put is a risk-management strategy using options contracts that investors employ to guard against the loss of owning a stock or asset. The hedging strategy involves an investor buying a for a fee, called a premium. \n\nPuts by themselves are a bearish strategy where the trader believes the price of the asset will decline in the future. However, a protective put is typically used when an investor is still on a stock but wishes to hedge against potential losses and uncertainty. \n\nProtective puts may be placed on stocks, currencies, commodities, and indexes and give some protection to the downside. A protective put acts as an insurance policy by providing downside protection in the event the price of the asset declines. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * A protective put is a risk-management strategy using options contracts that investors employ to guard against a loss in a stock or other asset.\n * For the cost of the premium, protective puts act as an insurance policy by providing downside protection from an asset's price declines.\n * Protective puts offer unlimited potential for gains since the put buyer also owns shares of the underlying asset.\n * When a protective put covers the entire long position of the underlying, it is called a married put.\n\n## How a Protective Put Works \n\nProtective puts are commonly utilized when an investor is or purchases shares of stock or other assets that they intend to hold in their portfolio. Typically, an investor who owns stock has the risk of taking a loss on the investment if the stock price declines below the purchase price. By purchasing a put option, any losses on the stock are limited or capped. \n\nThe protective put sets a known floor price below which the investor will not continue to lose any added money even as the underlying asset's price continues to fall. \n\nA put option is a contract that gives the owner the ability to sell a specific amount of the at a set price before or by a specified date. Unlike futures contracts, the options contract does not obligate the holder to sell the asset and only allows them to sell if they should choose to do so. The set price of the contract is known as the strike price, and the specified date is the expiration date or expiry. One option contract equates to 100 shares of the underlying asset. \n\nAlso, just like all things in life, put options are not free. The fee on an option contract is known as the premium. This price has a including the current price of the underlying asset, the time until expiration, and the (IV)—how likely the price is going to change—of the asset. \n\n## Strike Prices and Premiums \n\nA protective put option contract can be bought at any time. Some investors will buy these at the same time and when they purchase the stock. Others may wait and buy the contract at a later date. Whenever they buy the option, the relationship between the price of the underlying asset and the strike price can place the contract into one of three categories—known as the . These categories include: \n\n 1. At-the-money (ATM) where strike and market are equal\n 2. Out-of-the-money (OTM) where the strike is below the market\n 3. In-the-money (ITM) where the strike is above the market\n\nInvestors looking to hedge losses on a holding primarily focus on the ATM and OTM option offerings. \n\nShould the price of the asset and the strike price be the same, the contract is considered (ATM). An at-the-money put option provides an investor with 100% protection until the option expires. Many times, a protective put will be at-the-money if it was bought at the same time the underlying asset is purchased. \n\nAn investor can also buy an (OTM) put option. Out-of-the-money happens when the strike price is below the price of the stock or asset. An OTM put option does not provide 100% protection on the downside but instead caps the losses to the difference between the purchased stock price and\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_2208", "name": "Luhn Algorithm", "short_description": "Validate an identification number (such as a credit card or Social Security number) using the Luhn algorithm to check its authenticity and detect potential data entry errors.", "domain": "fintech", "topic": "payment_technologies", "topic_extension": false, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-2208", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-362", "question_id": "test-2059", "difficulty": 4.430816798843313, "level": "hard", "execution_smoke_ok": false, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "execution_smoke_error": "invalid literal for int() with base 10: 'x'", "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "491c68747ac05056fd6c4cb2dbb90e89854c756bfefce3146a836d47a1e1a6a4", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["Luhn Algorithm", "credit card validation", "identity verification", "payment processing", "fraud detection", "check digit", "number authenticity"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "number_type_context", "ambiguity_type": "data_type_context", "trigger_signal": "the term 'identification number' is generic", "clarification_question": "What type of identification number are you validating?", "options": [{"label": "Credit Card Number (default, as in example)", "value": "credit_card_number", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Social Security Number", "value": "social_security_number", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "Credit Card Number", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}], "inputs": [{"name": "number", "type": "string", "required": true, "description": "The identification number to be validated as a string, which should only contain digits.", "unit": null, "aliases": ["id_number", "card_number"]}], "output": {"name": "is_valid", "type": "boolean", "unit": null, "description": "True if the number is valid according to the Luhn check, False otherwise."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    number = inputs['number']\n    total = 0\n    num_digits = len(number)\n    parity = num_digits % 2\n    for i, digit in enumerate(number):\n        n = int(digit)\n        if i % 2 == parity:\n            n *= 2\n            if n > 9:\n                n -= 9\n        total += n\n    is_valid = total % 10 == 0\n    return is_valid", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "missing_number", "name": "Identification number input missing", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs.get('number') is None", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'number' input, representing the identification number, is required for validation."}, {"rule_id": "number_type_mismatch", "name": "Identification number input type must be string", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not isinstance(inputs.get('number'), str)", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'number' input must be a string."}, {"rule_id": "number_contains_non_digits", "name": "Identification number contains non-digit characters", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not inputs.get('number', '').isdigit()", "applies_to": [], "description": "The identification number must contain only digit characters."}, {"rule_id": "number_length_plausibility_credit_card", "name": "Credit card number length plausibility", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not (13 <= len(inputs.get('number', '')) <= 19)", "applies_to": [], "description": "The length of the identification number is outside the typical range for credit cards (13-19 digits). This check applies if the number is assumed to be a credit card number."}, {"rule_id": "number_not_empty", "name": "Identification number cannot be empty", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "len(inputs.get('number', '')) == 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The identification number cannot be an empty string."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": false, "error": "invalid literal for int() with base 10: 'x'", "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    number = inputs['number']\n    total = 0\n    num_digits = len(number)\n    parity = num_digits % 2\n    for i, digit in enumerate(number):\n        n = int(digit)\n        if i % 2 == parity:\n            n *= 2\n            if n > 9:\n                n -= 9\n        total += n\n    is_valid = total % 10 == 0\n    return is_valid"}, "article_title": "Luhn Algorithm", "article_doc_id": 4324, "article_content_excerpt": "# Luhn Algorithm: Uses in Identity Verification for Credit Cards\n\n## What Is the Luhn Algorithm? \n\nThe Luhn algorithm—also known as the “Modulus 10 algorithm”—is a formula that is used to determine whether the identification number provided by a user is accurate. The formula is widely used in validating numbers, as well as other number sequences such as government . \n\nToday, the Luhn algorithm is an essential component in the electronic payments system and is used by all major credit cards. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * The Luhn algorithm is a mathematical formula developed in the late 1950s.\n * The Luhn algorithm is widely used to validate the authenticity of identification numbers, such as Social Security numbers.\n * In finance, the Luhn algorithm facilitates electronic payments by rapidly identifying mis-entered credit card numbers.\n * Whether buying something online or at a store's point of sale (POS) terminal, the Luhn algorithm identifies the card number within the payment processing system.\n\n## How the Luhn Algorithm Works \n\nThe Luhn algorithm is widely used to validate the authenticity of identification numbers, such as Social Security and credit card numbers. \n\n### History of the Luhn Algorithm \n\nThe Luhn formula algorithm was developed by a German Computer Scientist named Hans Peter Luhn in 1954 while working as a researcher at IBM. The exact workings of the are based on modular arithmetic, a mathematical technique developed by Carl Friedrich Gauss in the early 19th century. Although its detailed workings are rather complex, it is best known for allowing computers to quickly assess whether the credit card numbers provided by customers are accurate.\n\n### Luhn Algorithm Process \n\nThe Luhn algorithm applies a series of computations to the credit card number given, adding up the results of those computations, and checking whether the resulting number matches the expected result. If it matches, the credit number is deemed valid. If it's an incorrect match, the algorithm will reject the credit card number, indicating the user made an error when inputting the number.\n\n### How the Luhn Algorithm Is Used \n\nFrom a customer’s perspective, we frequently use the Luhn algorithm when placing orders online or using a merchant’s . The computer system can quickly tell when we have input the incorrect credit card information since the Luhn algorithm has been incorporated into those systems’ programming. \n\nWithout it, we would need to wait until the entire purchase order is submitted before realizing the transaction was approved. In other words, the Luhn algorithm helps us quickly identify user errors, thereby speeding up the pace of transactions. \n\n## Real-World Examples of the Luhn Algorithm \n\nOne of the central concepts within the Luhn algorithm is the use of so-called “check digits.” These digits consist of numbers that are inserted into the broader number sequence in order to help verify, or “check,” whether the whole number is authentic. \n\nFor credit cards, the check digit consists of a single digit printed at the end of the credit card number. Rather than being specifically chosen by the credit card company, the check digit is automatically determined by the Luhn algorithm based on the preceding numbers in the sequence. When users enter their credit card numbers to complete a payment, the credit card processing software can use the Luhn algorithm to detect whether the specified number is accurate, based in part on its check digit. \n\nToday, the Luhn algorithm is integrated into popular programming languages and code libraries, making it relatively easy to include Luhn-based identification number verification in new software applications. \n\n### Tip: \n\nBe sure to monitor your credit and request copies of your credit reports to determine if there are any errors or unauthorized activity, such as a new credit card opened without your permission. You can obtain a free credit report every year from each of the three credit reporting companies\n...[truncated]"}
{"fic_id": "fic_article_705", "name": "Bear Market", "short_description": "Calculates the percentage decline between an initial and final value, typically used for assessing market downturns.", "domain": "financial_markets", "topic": "stock_market_analysis", "topic_extension": false, "version": "v2", "source_meta": {"function_id": "article-705", "source": "FinanceReasoning-test-1013", "question_id": "test-1063", "difficulty": 2.4849066497880004, "level": "medium", "execution_smoke_ok": true, "execution_autofix_applied": false, "normalization_version": "ast_v1_docstring_strip", "code_sanity_ok": true, "ast_exact_hash": "42bee783945ac5043c58625b79a4028ac5e0da62dc92d6373c3b4e9c6d4c07b8", "is_duplicate_kernel": false, "duplicate_of": null}, "selection_hints": ["percentage decline", "market downturn", "asset price drop", "bear market", "stock prices fall", "house prices decline"], "semantic_hints": [{"id": "output_scale", "ambiguity_type": "unit_scale", "trigger_signal": "output is a percentage, but could be interpreted as a decimal (or vice versa)", "clarification_question": "Should the answer be expressed as a decimal (e.g., 0.08) or a percentage (e.g., 8.0)?", "options": [{"label": "Percentage (e.g., 8.0) — DEFAULT", "value": "percent", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Decimal (e.g., 0.08)", "value": "decimal", "is_default": false, "transform_spec": {"patch_type": "result_postprocess", "result_expr": "result / 100.0", "max_expr_nodes": 6, "invariant": "result_new == result_old / 100.0", "affected_inputs": []}}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "The result is expressed as a percentage.", "impact_scope": "output_interpretation"}], "inputs": [{"name": "initial_value", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The original, higher value of the asset or index.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}, {"name": "final_value", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The decreased value of the asset or index after a decline.", "unit": null, "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "percentage_decline", "type": "number", "unit": "%", "description": "The calculated percentage decline from the initial to the final value."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    initial_value = inputs['initial_value']\n    final_value = inputs['final_value']\n    percentage_decline = (initial_value - final_value) / initial_value * 100\n    return round(percentage_decline, 2)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "input_initial_value_positive", "name": "Initial Value Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['initial_value'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'initial_value' must be a positive number for a meaningful percentage decline calculation."}, {"rule_id": "input_final_value_positive", "name": "Final Value Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['final_value'] <= 0", "applies_to": [], "description": "The 'final_value' must be a positive number for a meaningful percentage decline calculation."}, {"rule_id": "decline_initial_greater_than_final", "name": "Initial Value Must Be Greater Than Final for Decline", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['initial_value'] <= inputs['final_value']", "applies_to": [], "description": "For a valid 'decline' calculation, the 'initial_value' is expected to be greater than the 'final_value'. If not, the calculation represents an increase or no change."}, {"rule_id": "bear_market_threshold_alert", "name": "Decline Below Bear Market Threshold", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "compute(inputs) < 20.0", "applies_to": [], "description": "According to common definitions, a 'bear market' or significant downturn often involves a decline of 20% or more. This check alerts if the calculated decline is less than this threshold."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    initial_value = inputs['initial_value']\n    final_value = inputs['final_value']\n    percentage_decline = (initial_value - final_value) / initial_value * 100\n    return round(percentage_decline, 2)"}, "article_title": "Bear Market", "article_doc_id": 1307, "article_content_excerpt": "# Bear Market Guide: Definition, Phases, Examples & How to Invest During One\n\nDefinition\n\nA bear market is a prolonged decline in stock prices with the major indices falling by 20% or more from their highs.\n\nA bear market is a financial market experiencing prolonged price declines, generally of 20% or more. A bear market usually occurs along with widespread investor pessimism, large-scale liquidation of securities and other assets, and a weakening economy. \n\nBear markets are often associated with like the S&P 500, but individual securities or commodities can also be considered to be in a bear market if they experience a decline of 20% or more over a sustained period of time, typically two months or more. Bear markets also may accompany general economic downturns such as a recession. Bear markets are seen as the opposite of upward-trending . \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Bear markets occur when prices in a market decline by more than 20%, often accompanied by negative investor sentiment and a weakening economy.\n * Bear markets can be cyclical or longer-term. The former lasts for several weeks or a couple of months and the latter can last for several years or even decades.\n * Short selling, put options, and inverse ETFs are some ways that investors can make money during a bear market as prices fall.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/terms_b_bearmarket_Final-93d086d074d44dadb9958f01f3d0ec05.jpg)\n\nInvestopedia / Daniel Fishel\n\n## Understanding Bear Markets \n\nStock prices generally reflect how investors expect companies to perform. If a company has lower-than-expected profits, or experiences less growth than analysts predicted, investors may respond by selling the company's stock, which makes the overall price decline. The combination of herd behavior and fear can create a rush to minimize losses, which in turn can lead to prolonged periods of depressed asset prices. \n\nOne definition of a bear market says markets are in bear territory when stocks, on average, fall at least 20% off their high. But 20% is an arbitrary number, just as a 10% decline is an arbitrary benchmark for a correction. Another definition of a bear market is when than risk-seeking. This kind of bear market can last for months or years as investors shun speculation in favor of boring, sure bets. \n\nThe causes of a bear market often vary, but in general, a weak or , bursting market bubbles, pandemics, wars, geopolitical crises, and drastic paradigm shifts in the economy such as shifting to an online economy, are all factors that might cause a bear market. The signs of a weak or slowing economy are typically: \n\n * Low employment\n * Low disposable income\n * Weak productivity\n * Drop in business profits\n\nGovernment interventions in the economy can also trigger a bear market. For example, changes in the tax rate or the can lead to a bear market. Similarly, a drop in investor confidence may also signal the onset of a bear market. When investors believe something is about to happen, they will take action—in the case of an imminent bear market, selling off shares to avoid losses. \n\nBear markets can last for multiple years or just several weeks. A bear market can last anywhere from 10 to 20 years and is characterized by below-average returns on a sustained basis. There may be rallies within secular bear markets where stocks or indexes rally for a period, but the gains are not sustained, and prices revert to lower levels. A bear market, on the other hand, can last anywhere from a few weeks to several months. \n\n### Recent Bear Markets \n\nThe U.S. major market indexes were close to bear market territory on December 24, 2018, falling just shy of a 20% drawdown. More recently, major indexes including the S&P 500 and Dow Jones Industrial Average (DJIA) fell sharply into bear market territory between March 11 and March 12, 2020. Prior to that, the last prolonged bear market in the United States occurred between 2007 and 2009 during and lasted for roughly 17 months. The S&P 500 lost 50%\n...[truncated]"}
