nstance(periods, int) or periods <= 0:\n        raise ValueError('Periods must be a positive integer.')\n    if start_value <= 0:\n        raise ValueError('Start value must be positive.')\n    cagr = (end_value / start_value) ** (1 / periods) - 1\n    return cagr", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "cagr_input_start_value_positive", "name": "Start Value Must Be Positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['start_value'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["start_value"], "description": "The initial value (start_value) must be a positive number for CAGR to be meaningfully calculated."}, {"rule_id": "cagr_input_periods_positive_integer", "name": "Periods Must Be Positive Integer", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not isinstance(inputs['periods'], int) or inputs['periods'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["periods"], "description": "The number of periods (periods) must be a positive integer."}, {"rule_id": "cagr_input_end_value_non_negative_alert", "name": "End Value Should Be Non-Negative for Growth Analysis", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['end_value'] < 0 and inputs['start_value'] > 0", "applies_to": ["end_value"], "description": "If the start value is positive, a negative end value indicates a complete or more than complete loss, which might warrant review in typical growth scenarios."}, {"rule_id": "cagr_implied_significant_loss_alert", "name": "CAGR Indicates Significant Loss", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "compute(inputs) < -0.9999", "applies_to": ["start_value", "end_value", "periods"], "description": "A CAGR indicating a loss of nearly 100% or more implies a significant or complete loss of value, which might warrant review."}, {"rule_id": "cagr_zero_growth_consistency", "name": "Zero Growth Consistency Check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "abs(inputs['start_value'] - inputs['end_value']) < 1e-9 and abs(compute(inputs)) > 1e-9", "applies_to": ["start_value", "end_value", "periods"], "description": "If the start and end values are approximately equal, the CAGR should be approximately zero. This check flags inconsistencies."}, {"rule_id": "cagr_input_start_end_value_type_check", "name": "Start and End Values Must Be Numeric", "check_type": "normalization", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "not isinstance(inputs.get('start_value'), (int, float)) or not isinstance(inputs.get('end_value'), (int, float))", "applies_to": ["start_value", "end_value"], "description": "Start and end values must be numeric (integer or float) and properly provided."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    start_value = inputs['start_value']\n    end_value = inputs['end_value']\n    periods = inputs['periods']\n    if not isinstance(periods, int) or periods <= 0:\n        raise ValueError('Periods must be a positive integer.')\n    if start_value <= 0:\n        raise ValueError('Start value must be positive.')\n    cagr = (end_value / start_value) ** (1 / periods) - 1\n    return cagr"}, "article_title": "Growth Rates", "article_doc_id": 2443, "article_content_excerpt": "# Growth Rates: Definition, Formula, and How to Calculate\n\n## What Are Growth Rates? \n\nGrowth rates refer to the percentage change of a specific variable within a specific time period. Growth rates can be positive or negative, depending on whether the size of the variable is increasing or decreasing over time. Growth rates were first used by biologists studying population sizes, but they have since been brought into use in studying economic activity, corporate management, or investment returns. \n\nFor investors, growth rates typically represent the compounded of growth of an investment, or a company’s revenues, earnings, or dividends. Growth rates are also applied to more macro concepts, such as and unemployment. Expected forward-looking or growth rates are two common kinds of growth rates used for analysis. \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Growth rates are used to express the annual change in a variable as a percentage.\n * A positive growth rate indicates a variable is increasing over time; a negative growth rate indicates that it is decreasing. \n\n * Growth rates can be beneficial in assessing a company’s performance and predicting future performance.\n * Growth rates are computed by dividing the difference between the ending and starting values for the period being analyzed and dividing that by the starting value.\n * Time periods used for growth rates are most often annually, quarterly, monthly, and weekly.\n\n:max_bytes\\(150000\\):strip_icc\\(\\)/Growth-Rates-Final-155cb3b2a9394257af9570a2756d50f0.jpg)\n\nInvestopedia / Xiaojie Liu\n\n## ﻿Understanding Growth Rates \n\nAt their most basic level, growth rates are used to express the annual change in a variable as a percentage. For example, an economy’s growth rate is derived as the annual rate of change at which a country’s GDP increases or decreases. This rate of growth is used to measure an economy’s recession or expansion. If the income within a country declines for two consecutive quarters, it is considered to be in a . \n\nConversely, if the country has grown its income for two consecutive quarters, it is considered to be expanding. \n\n## How to Calculate Growth Rates \n\nGrowth rates can be calculated in several ways, depending on what the figure is intended to convey. A simple growth measurement simply divides the difference between the ending and starting value by the beginning value, or (EV-BV)/BV. The can thus be computed as:\n\n\\begin{aligned} &\\text{Economic Growth} = \\frac { \\text{GDP}_2 - \\text{GDP}_1 }{ \\text{GDP}_1 } \\\\\\ &\\textbf{where:} \\\\\\ &\\text{GDP} = \\text{Gross domestic product of nation} \\\\\\ \\end{aligned}\n\nThis approach, however, may be overly simplistic. \n\n### Compound Annual Growth Rate (CAGR) \n\nThe is a variation on the growth rate that is often used to assess an investment’s or company’s performance. The CAGR, which is not a true return rate, but rather a representation that describes the rate at which an investment would have grown if it had grown at the same rate every year and the profits were reinvested at the end of each year. The formula for calculating CAGR is: \n\n\\begin{aligned} &CAGR= \\left ( \\frac{EV}{BV} \\right ) ^{\\frac{1}{n}}-1\\\\\\ &\\textbf{where:}\\\\\\ &EV = \\text{Ending value}\\\\\\ &BV = \\text{Beginning value}\\\\\\ &n = \\text{Number of years} \\end{aligned}\n\nThe CAGR calculation assumes that growth is steady over a specified period of time. CAGR is a widely used metric due to its simplicity and flexibility, and many firms will use it to report and forecast earnings growth. \n\n### Dividend Growth and Securities Valuation \n\nFinancial theory suggests that a company’s shares can be fairly valued using a , based on the hypothesis that present-day price is worth the sum of all of its future payments when back to its present value. As a result, dividend growth rates are important for valuing stocks. \n\nThe is a popular approach used to determine the intrinsic value of a stock based on a future series of dividends that grow at a constant rate. This is assumed to be positive as mat\n...[truncated]"}
