or 2%) a percentage or already a decimal (e.g. 0.02)?", "options": [{"label": "Decimal (e.g., 0.02) - DEFAULT", "value": "decimal", "is_default": true}, {"label": "Percentage (e.g., 2)", "value": "percent", "is_default": false}], "i_level": "soft", "assumption_if_not_clarified": "The interest rate is provided as a decimal.", "impact_scope": "input_binding"}], "inputs": [{"name": "balance", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The current account balance.", "unit": "currency", "aliases": []}, {"name": "interest_rate", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The annual interest rate (expressed as a decimal, e.g., 0.015 for 1.5%).", "unit": "decimal_rate", "aliases": []}, {"name": "life_expectancy", "type": "number", "required": true, "description": "The account holder's life expectancy used for the amortization.", "unit": "years", "aliases": []}], "output": {"name": "annual_payment", "type": "number", "unit": "currency", "description": "The calculated annual fixed payment amount."}, "execution": {"language": "python", "entrypoint": "compute", "code": "def compute(inputs):\n    balance = inputs['balance']\n    interest_rate = inputs['interest_rate']\n    life_expectancy = inputs['life_expectancy']\n    annual_payment = balance * interest_rate / (1 - (1 + interest_rate) ** (-life_expectancy))\n    return round(annual_payment)", "deterministic": true}, "diagnostic_checks": [{"rule_id": "balance_missing", "name": "Account balance is required", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "'balance' not in inputs or inputs['balance'] is None", "applies_to": ["balance"], "description": "The current account balance must be provided."}, {"rule_id": "interest_rate_missing", "name": "Interest rate is required", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "'interest_rate' not in inputs or inputs['interest_rate'] is None", "applies_to": ["interest_rate"], "description": "The annual interest rate must be provided."}, {"rule_id": "life_expectancy_missing", "name": "Life expectancy is required", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "F", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "'life_expectancy' not in inputs or inputs['life_expectancy'] is None", "applies_to": ["life_expectancy"], "description": "The life expectancy for amortization must be provided."}, {"rule_id": "balance_positive", "name": "Account balance must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['balance'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["balance"], "description": "The account balance must be a positive value."}, {"rule_id": "interest_rate_non_negative", "name": "Interest rate cannot be negative", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['interest_rate'] < 0", "applies_to": ["interest_rate"], "description": "The annual interest rate must be non-negative."}, {"rule_id": "interest_rate_plausibility", "name": "Interest rate plausibility check", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['interest_rate'] > 0.5", "applies_to": ["interest_rate"], "description": "An interest rate above 50% is unusually high and might indicate an error in input (e.g., percentage instead of decimal)."}, {"rule_id": "life_expectancy_positive", "name": "Life expectancy must be positive", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "error", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['life_expectancy'] <= 0", "applies_to": ["life_expectancy"], "description": "Life expectancy must be a positive number of years."}, {"rule_id": "life_expectancy_range", "name": "Life expectancy must be within a reasonable range", "check_type": "deterministic", "diagnostic_type": "E", "severity": "alert", "predicate_mode": "violation", "expression": "inputs['life_expectancy'] < 1 or inputs['life_expectancy'] > 120", "applies_to": ["life_expectancy"], "description": "Life expectancy should typically be between 1 and 120 years."}], "execution_smoke_test": {"ok": true, "error": null, "autofix_applied": false, "lint_fixes": [], "effective_code": "def compute(inputs):\n    balance = inputs['balance']\n    interest_rate = inputs['interest_rate']\n    life_expectancy = inputs['life_expectancy']\n    annual_payment = balance * interest_rate / (1 - (1 + interest_rate) ** (-life_expectancy))\n    return round(annual_payment)"}, "article_title": "Rule 72(t)", "article_doc_id": 3135, "article_content_excerpt": "# 72(t) Rule: Definition, Calculation, and Example\n\n## What Is Rule 72(t)? \n\nRule 72(t) allows for penalty-free withdrawals from and other retirement accounts like and plans. It is issued by the . \n\nThis rule allows account holders to benefit from their retirement savings before retirement age through early withdrawals without the otherwise required 10% penalty. The IRS still subjects the withdrawals to the account holder’s normal . \n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n * Rule 72(t) allows you to take penalty-free, early withdrawals from your IRA, 401(k), or 403(b).\n * There are other IRS exemptions that can be used for medical expenses, purchasing a home, and more.\n * Rule 72(t) withdrawals should be considered as a last resort when all other options for reducing financial pressure (creditor negotiation, debt consolidation, bankruptcy, etc.) have been exhausted.\n\n## Understanding Rule 72(t) \n\nRule 72(t) refers to code 72(t), section 2, which specifies exceptions to the . These exceptions allow investors to withdraw funds from their retirement accounts before age 59½, as long as certain qualifications are met. \n\nTo take advantage of this rule, the owner of the retirement account must take at least five (SEPPs). The amount of the payments depends on the owner’s as calculated through IRS-approved methods. You must also withdraw these funds according to a specific schedule. The IRS offers three different methods for calculating your specific withdrawal schedule. You must adhere to the payment schedule for five years or until you reach age 59 1/2, whichever comes later (unless you are disabled or die). \n\n## Calculation for Payment Amounts Under Rule 72(t) \n\nThe amounts an account holder receives in the periodic payments enabled by rule 72(t) depend on life expectancy, which can be calculated through one of three IRS-approved methods: \n\n * The amortization method\n * The minimum distribution or the life expectancy method\n * The annuitization method\n\nThe determines yearly payment amounts by amortizing the balance of an investor’s account over single or joint life expectancy. This method develops the largest and most reasonable amount an individual can remove, and the amount is fixed annually. \n\nThe minimum distribution method takes a dividing factor from the IRS’s single or joint life expectancy table, using it to divide the retirement account’s balance. The key difference between this method and the amortization method is the resulting payments with the minimum distribution method, as the name implies, are the lowest possible amounts that can be withdrawn. \n\n### Fast Fact: \n\nThe minimum distribution method is nearly the opposite of the amortization method, as the annual early withdrawal payments are likely to vary from year to year, though not substantially.\n\nThe final IRS-approved calculation is the annuitization method, which uses an provided by the IRS to determine equivalent or nearly equivalent payments in accordance with the SEPP regulation. This method offers account holders a fixed annual payout, with the amount typically falling somewhere between the highest and lowest amount the account owner can withdraw. \n\n## What Is the Downside of 72(t)?\n\nWithdrawing money from a retirement account is a financial last resort. Using rule 72(t) will deplete your retirement savings, potentially putting the stability of your financial future in jeopardy.\n\n## Is 72(t) a Good Idea?\n\nFor many situations, using rule 72(t) is not a good idea. The risk to your future retirement may be too great to justify taking money out now. In some rare cases, however, it may be worth it.\n\n## What Is an Example of Withdrawing Money Early with Rule 72(t)?\n\nAs an example, assume a 53-year-old investor who has an IRA earning 1.5% annually with a balance of $250,000 wishes to withdraw money early under rule 72(t). Using the amortization method, they would receive approximately $10,042 in yearly payments. With the minimum distribution method, they would receive around $7,962 annu\n...[truncated]"}
